<SLUG> BC-NY-TURKEY-MUSLIMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRAYERS AND DONATIONS FOR TURKEY'S QUAKE VICTIMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
(ko) 
 By KIT R. ROANE    c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ They are natives of Syria, Lebanon, Somalia, Egypt,
England and the United States. But on Friday, they all gathered to
pray amid the exposed wiring and unfinished walls of a house of
worship that they had scrimped and saved to build in midtown
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   As they thanked Allah for their own good fortune, their prayers
were for others a continent away in Turkey, a land devastated by a
huge earthquake that has taken the lives of more than 10,000 people
and left rescue workers searching through rubble for tens of
thousands more.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all brothers, and should one of our brothers suffer, be
they in Egypt, Turkey or here, be they Muslim or just of the human
race, our heart should be soft and we must help,'' said Mohammed
Ali Abdelaal, the director of the Uthman Ben Affan Mosque on East
55th Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is the answer,'' he said. ``There is no other.''
</P>
<P>
   Similar calls were being broadcast from mosques across New York
and the rest of the country during the Friday khutba, or sermon.
With relief workers toiling against time to find survivors of
Tuesday's earthquake, and worrying about the spread of disease,
officials said billions of dollars would be needed to right the
situation once all the bodies could be pulled from the rubble and
buried.
</P>
<P>
   Several Turkish banks and Muslim organizations have set up
accounts where donations can be routed. Other groups and hospitals
are collecting medical supplies, construction equipment, mobile
toilets and tents.
</P>
<P>
   Alper Tutus, a businessman from Great Neck, N.Y., drove all the
way to the Fatih Mosque on the eastern edge of Bay Ridge to donate
to the cause. Saying he is not a religious man and never goes to
the mosque to pray, Tutus spoke through tears about the devastation
in his homeland as he dropped bills onto a donation table.
</P>
<P>
   ``My heart is bleeding,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Aly Abuzaakouk, the director of the American Muslim Council,
noted that even the Greek government, which historically has had a
fractious relationship with Turkey, has sent aid.
</P>
<P>
   ``This disaster has helped show that, despite animosities and
adversities, we are all of one human race,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That was also the message Friday at the Uthman Ben Affan Mosque.
More than 100 Sunni Muslims, members of Islam's main branch,
kneeled before Abdelaal. While implicit in Abdelaal's sermon was
the idea that such disasters are an act of God, he urged his
congregation not to think that the Turkish people had been singled
out for punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Many Muslims have been opposed to both the secular nature of the
Turkish government and its close ties with Israel. But while the
disaster might bring secular Turkey closer to its Muslim brothers,
Abdelaal said, that was not a subject to be debated now.
</P>
<P>
   The congregation understood what was being asked: Put aside your
differences and open your wallets and hearts in an act of
salvation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot say we don't care, that the government of Turkey is
corrupt, that they are too close with Israel, that they fight their
Muslim brothers, that this is thousands of miles away,'' Abdelaal
said. ``We Muslims are like a great brick wall and if you take one
brick from the wall, we will all fall down.''
</P>
<P>
   The mosque, also known as the Islamic Society of Mid-Manhattan,
has itself benefited from the generosity of others. After nine
years renting a basement space on West 44th Street, the society
collected enough donations and financing to buy and begin
renovating a new home on East 55th Street. The society moved into
its new home two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Services are held amid exposed beams and snarled wiring, a bit
of which caught fire because of a short circuit during the
director's sermon Friday. More money will be needed to complete the
mosque. But on Friday, its members did not shy from offering what
they had to their brethren in Turkey, dropping 5, 10, and 20-dollar
bills into a special case marked for the effort.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the day, more than $1,000 had been collected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now the relief agencies say they can only take money,
but I also will give clothes if necessary,'' said Darosh Karim, a
30-year-old computer engineer who immigrated from India.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, we sent money to help in the floods in China,'' he
added. ``But wherever such disaster happens we will help. It does
not matter who is in need.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
