<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-TWINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES TAKE EXTRA BATTING PRACTICE, BEAT TWINS, 9-3 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Nearly the entire roster of the Yankees' position
players inhabited the otherwise empty Metrodome early Friday
afternoon for extra and optional batting practice, the echoes of
ball meeting bat pinballing around the place.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Jeter was there, trying to conquer his recent slump. Tino
Martinez took his turn, attempting to correct his lurching
approach. Chili Davis was the last to hit, searching for the swing
he lost a few weeks ago. Ricky Ledee and Bernie Williams were the
only members of the starting lineup who did not attend. No matter.
Hours later, they drove in all but two of the runs as the Yankees
defeated the Twins, 9-3.
</P>
<P>
   Hideki Irabu (10-4) pitched into the eighth inning and once
again, the Yankees could feel good about themselves, after
improving their record to 74-47 and finally collecting enough hits
and runs to support the strong pitching they have been getting.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of their 4-1 loss to Kansas City on Thursday, the
Yankees' batting coach, Chris Chambliss, mentioned to manager Joe
Torre that Davis wanted to take extra batting practice Friday.
Torre thought about it and mused that there probably would be a lot
of Yankees showing up.
</P>
<P>
   They had scored a total of 14 runs in the six games coming into
Friday night's, with two home runs, and while they practiced their
hitting in the afternoon, there was very little talk. The batting
cage usually is a place of laughter and joking, lots of shouting
and teasing. Not Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``They all had something to work on,'' Torre said. ``They all
had a purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees then attacked the Twins' Brad Radke with the same
singlemindedness in the first inning. Chuck Knoblauch grounded a
single through the left side, Jeter rolled a hit up the middle, and
even after Paul O'Neill hit into a double play, Williams singled
and drove in a run.
</P>
<P>
   Radke typically has great control _ he had allowed only 27 walks
in 165 innings _ but Martinez drew a five-pitch walk, and when
Davis also walked, the bases were loaded. Ledee took two pitches
out of the strike zone; now Radke had to throw a strike.
</P>
<P>
   He fired a fastball, Ledee turned on it, his front leg
straightening as he threw his bat at the ball, and soon the
Minnesota right fielder Marty Cordova was staring upward, watching
Ledee's home run fly over the giant blue tarpaulin that serves as
the top of the wall.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees had scored only one run in their previous 20
innings, and now they had five in the first.
</P>
<P>
   Williams singled home another run in the second _ Knoblauch
started the inning with a walk _ and Irabu took it from there,
striking out seven before being lifted in the eight. The Yankees
took a first step toward breaking out of their slump, but they
still have problems to address.
</P>
<P>
   One is Jeter, who went two for five Friday night and scored his
100th run of the season in the ninth. But his average is .348, down
from .371 at the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   As he has acknowledged, Jeter has tried to pull the ball to the
left side of the field too much, rather than do what he does best:
spray the ball from line to line.
</P>
<P>
   Pitchers have always tried jamming Jeter, down and inside or up
and inside, but lately, they have been particularly effective
pitching him down and in.
</P>
<P>
   In his last 30 games, Jeter has four doubles and five homers,
after accumulating 46 extra-base hits in his first 89 games.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem involves Paul O'Neill's run production, which
has dipped significantly because of those slumping in front of him
_ including the No. 9 hitter Scott Brosius. O'Neill has three runs
batted in in his last 12 games.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, the cleanup batter, returned to the starting lineup
Friday night after missing three games with a stomach virus. ``I
feel a lot better than yesterday,'' Williams said, while picking at
some soup.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez tripled home two runs in the ninth Friday night, but he
has had a poor season, considering all the RBI chances he has had.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, Martinez has had a tendency to chase pitches low and
inside and out of the strike zone _ Minnesota and Kansas City
consistently pitched him this way during the recently completed
homestand _ and over the last 25 games, he has drawn only five
walks.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, the designated hitter, has not hit a home run in his last
13 games, and his batting average has dipped steadily. Torre is
convinced that Davis is simply tired _ maybe he should have been
rested more, Torre said _ and Davis will likely be rested
consistently in the last weeks of the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   With a single in Thursday's game against Kansas City, Brosius
ended a string of 28 hitless at-bats, the longest streak by a
Yankee since Kevin Maas went 0 for 29 in 1991. Brosius went 0-for-5
Friday night, with terrible at-bats that prompted him to flip his
bat and helmet away after the fourth one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
