<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-FUNDRAISER-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON, IN ROLE REVERSAL, HELPS HIS WIFE AS FUND-RAISER
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ADDS 4th and 5th grafs with details of president's speech.)  (rk) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDGARTOWN, Mass. _ For the first time in the strange odyssey of
a sitting president whose wife is seeking public office, President
Clinton stepped into the role of supportive spouse Friday night to
help Hillary Rodham Clinton build up a war chest for her likely
Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   At a Nantucket dinner that cost $1,000 a ticket, Mrs. Clinton
pulled in more than $100,000 in the first of numerous fund-raising
events that she plans to attend in the next two weeks during the
couple's summer vacation. She is expected to raise about $600,000
toward the more than $20 million she needs for her all-but-declared
candidacy for the Senate from New York.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 7, President Clinton started stumping for his vice
president, Al Gore, introducing him to small clutches of
fund-raisers and crowds of others. Friday night he began the same
supportive duty for his wife.
</P>
<P>
   The president regaled his audience with reminiscences of meeting
Hillary Rodham in the early 1970s at Yale Law School, where she
introduced herself to him after they had caught each other's eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``This woman has initiative,'' Clinton said Friday night, adding
that this was the first reason Clinton would be a good senator. He
also said he was grateful that she had put her career on hold for
him.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton was the star of the show as 140 people gathered at
the Nantucket home of Smith and Elizabeth Bagley, longtime
Democratic donors. Bagley is an heir to the R.J. Reynolds tobacco
fortune, and Mrs. Bagley is a former ambassador to Portugal.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's the draw,'' Mrs. Bagley said in an interview before
serving her guests a buffet dinner of chicken, Portuguese sausage,
mussels and clams at their spacious, weathered cedar-shingled home.
``There are people calling like crazy. We promised we'd help in any
way we could.''
</P>
<P>
   The guests included Sen. John Kerry of Massachusetts, as well as
those with lower profiles, like several longtime island residents,
like Chuck Lenhart, an architect, Martin McGowan, a gardener, and
Paula Gonfrader, who owns a hairdressing salon. But most, Mrs.
Bagley said, are longtime Democratic donors.
</P>
<P>
   The buffet, which was closed to the press, came after the couple
spent the first full day of their vacation by flying to Nantucket
from Martha's Vineyard, where they are based for the next two
weeks. After the couple landed on Nantucket in the smaller DC-9
version of Air Force One, Mrs. Clinton's four-vehicle motorcade
broke off from the president's, and they pursued separate
schedules.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton spent a secluded day golfing at the Nantucket
Golf Club, where some club members were miffed that his arrival
might interfere with their tournament tee times. He played with
Kerry and two major Democratic contributors, Wayne Rogers and Jack
Manning.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton spent the morning helping to raise money to rebuild
the 176-year-old United Methodist Church as part of her program to
help preserve national historical sites. She received a standing
ovation from the 80 people inside the church and cheers and
applause from the 250 people outside.
</P>
<P>
   She then went on a tour of Nantucket's historic, cobblestoned
downtown, trailed by many of the 250 people who had gathered
outside the church, and repeatedly hopped out of her car to chat.
She inspected the Dane Gallery and its New England crafts and
stopped in at Nantucket Loom, whose owner, Elizabeth Winship, had
sent Mrs. Clinton a throw-rug.
</P>
<P>
   ``She wasn't shopping,'' Ms. Winship said later. ``She was
learning the history of Nantucket.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the afternoon, the Clintons reunited at the Bagley
house before a brief outing to help raise money for the American
Ireland Fund, which promotes peace in Northern Ireland, at the
Nantucket home of Bob Matthews, a New England real estate
developer.
</P>
<P>
   The dinner honored Tim Russert, the NBC newsman, and raised more
than $90,000 for a program called ``Vital Voices,'' which brings
Catholic and Protestant women together. The money is being
contributed in Mrs. Clinton's name. Both Clintons spoke and
afterward, the crowd of more than 100 people, which included actor
Ben Stiller, sang ``Happy Birthday'' in honor of Clinton's 53rd
birthday, which was on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   They returned to the Bagley's ocean-front house, which like much
of Nantucket was festooned with both Irish and American flags, for
the fund-raising dinner for Mrs. Clinton.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
