<SLUG> BC-CENTENARIAN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMAN HAS WATCHED THE WORLD CHANGE DRAMATICALLY IN HER 107 YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JUDI HUNT  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Olufina Gjertina Duesund Andvik is frail, her skin is cellophane
thin and she is cold most of the time.
</P>
<P>
   But 107 years have not dimmed many memories of her long tenure
on Earth or blunted her mental sharpness. She has strong opinions
and doesn't hesitate to voice them.
</P>
<P>
   Andvik has watched the world change dramatically since her birth
Sept. 8, 1891, in Masfjord, Norway, a town about 60 miles north of
Bergen.
</P>
<P>
   She doesn't like many of the changes, especially in the United
States where she has lived since 1924. ``So much has changed for
the worse,'' she flatly declares, her bright blue eyes flashing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess the worst that's happened is there's nothing that's
wrong anymore. There is no morality, no rules. Nothing is right or
wrong these days.''
</P>
<P>
   She blames greed and materialism, people grabbing for everything
without concern for other people.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have too many things. They think these make them happy,
but they don't,'' she said. ``Happiness comes from living a good
life, caring about their family and neighbors and most of all,
being kind.''
</P>
<P>
   Andvik grew up on a modest Norwegian farm that was big enough
for a few cows, sheep and goats.
</P>
<P>
   She went to school in the winter, rowing across the fjord to
classes held in private homes. In the summers she and the other
village girls took the livestock into the mountains where they
lived in primitive cabins, tending the animals, making goat cheese
and churning butter.
</P>
<P>
   She married her husband in 1922, when she was 31 years old. ``He
was a nice man,'' she said. ``The marriage wasn't always smooth and
sometimes I cried when my feelings were hurt, but we never talked
about divorce once.''
</P>
<P>
   Farming proved too difficult in Norway, so the couple came to
Seattle in 1924. By that time the family included their first son
Bjarne, who was followed over the next few years by Martin and
Orville.
</P>
<P>
   They bought a home in Seattle's Phinney Ridge neighborhood where
Andvik took loving care of her family, attended church, knitted and
crocheted. The family later moved to a former summer cabin above
Lake Sammamish. Her husband died in 1954.
</P>
<P>
   Andvik loves reading, although she now is blind in one eye, said
her son, Bjarne Andvik, 76, of Camano Island, Wash. ``She reads
everything she can get her hands on, especially if it's world
affairs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   She enjoyed her independence for more than three decades, but
finally decided to move into Crista House, a home run by an
independent Protestant religious institution, when she was 95.
</P>
<P>
   Her health remains good, although an old hip and back injury
bother her sometimes. ``It makes my foot hurt,'' she grumbles to
her son, Orville, during a visit.
</P>
<P>
   She remembers the first airplane flight by the Wright brothers
and marvels at how far air travel has gone. ``I wonder sometimes
how God keeps those big machines in the sky and I think it must be
a miracle.''
</P>
<P>
   While family and friends are looking forward to Andvik reaching
her third century, she is not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope I don't live until then. I never expected to live this
long and, to tell the truth, I'm getting tired. I'm looking forward
to the time when God takes me home, but it's his decision so I just
have to wait.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
