<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON WILL BE A KEY STATE IN CAMPAIGN, MCCAIN SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Arizona Sen. John McCain, undaunted by Republican
establishment support for rival George W. Bush, on Friday described
Washington as a key state in the presidential campaign and
indicated he will intensify his efforts here before February's GOP
primary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am convinced the political environment here is open and that
it values those who exercise independent judgment,'' McCain said in
an interview Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   The former Navy pilot and Vietnam POW is best known for
challenging GOP Senate leaders with his advocacy of campaign
finance reform, and his description of Washington, D.C.,
policymaking as ``gridlocked by special interest money.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain and fellow presidential hopeful Elizabeth Dole are
headliners at Saturday's King County GOP picnic on Vashon Island,
west of Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The picnic is hosted by businessman Thomas Stewart, who was
fined $5 million by the Federal Election Commission for making
illegal campaign donations to Republicans. Stewart served a 60-day
home detention sentence last year after pleading guilty to federal
misdemeanor charges.
</P>
<P>
   But while Democrats have milked publicity out of Stewart's role
in the picnic, thousands of Republicans have turned the annual
party get-together into the state's best-attended political event.
McCain and Dole will be able to court a crowd of 5,000 to 8,000
party faithful.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, to the surprise of his campaign, McCain
picked up a ringing endorsement from Washington Secretary of State
Ralph Munro, who earlier in the year sent a contribution to Bush's
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy stuck with campaign finance reform through thick and
thin: He hasn't wavered and he won't back off,'' Munro, the lone
Republican statewide official, said last night.
</P>
<P>
   McCain was, in his own words, ``a long shot'' when he began
campaigning. He joked here in May that he had ``about as much
chance as a snowball in Gila Bend, Ariz.''
</P>
<P>
   He has also raised eyebrows by applying a Navy officer's tactics
to the GOP race, picking his places of engagement and steering
clear of battles he cannot win. McCain deliberately skipped last
Saturday's Iowa GOP straw poll, calling the pay-for-votes contest
``a sham.''
</P>
<P>
   Lately, however, McCain's campaign has picked up important
endorsements and shown its first glimmers of voter recognition.
</P>
<P>
   Two top organizers of Dan Quayle's campaign in South Carolina _
a key early primary state _ defected to McCain earlier this week.
Sen. Fred Thompson, who had supported fellow Tennessean Lamar
Alexander, signed on Wednesday to be national co-chair of McCain's
campaign. McCain has also gained some ground on Bush and is solidly
in second place in a new poll of likely New Hampshire voters.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has watched Bush stumble and lose his cool as the Texas
governor has come under relentless questioning from the media about
possible past use of cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   He declined to become embroiled in the controversy swirling
around whether Bush should reveal past use _ if any _ of cocaine.
Bush said this week he has not used any illegal drugs within the
past 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The media and the American people determine what is legitimate
news and legitimate questioning,'' said McCain. ``A candidate can
choose whether he or she responds, or does not respond, to
questions. I believe the governor deserves privacy, but it isn't up
to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's part of modern politics, and something you have to
consider when getting into this business,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, 62, has acknowledged that he is ``a sinner'' and that
womanizing contributed to the breakup of his first marriage. McCain
and his second wife, Cindy, have four children, ages 7 to 14.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has sailed against the Republican Party's prevailing
winds on certain issues.
</P>
<P>
   A conservationist, he helped write an Arizona wilderness bill,
and an agreement regulating Colorado River flow through the Grand
Canyon to prevent damage to the canyon's ecology.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the good of the party, we have to pay more attention to
the environment,'' he said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has also courted minorities, specifically Native
Americans and Hispanics. He has decried ``the politics of
division'' and ballot measures establishing English as an
``official'' language.
</P>
<P>
   Christian conservatives have dominated Washington state's GOP
presidential process in recent years. Party rules favor
conservative activists again in 2000. One-third of the state's GOP
convention delegates will be chosen by the Feb. 29 primary. The
March 7 precinct caucuses will account for two-thirds of the
delegation to next year's convention in Philadelphia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-99 0101EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990821.0013 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 01:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4936 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBITS-NYT &LR;      08-21 0499
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBITS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NANCY GUILD, 73, INSOUCIANT '40S ACTRESS  
 EUGENIE MARRON, 99, FISHING RECORD-HOLDER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Colo., Fla., N.J.)   (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nancy Guild, a film actress who starred opposite some of the
leading men of the 1940s and early '50s, died on Monday at her home
in East Hampton, N.Y., after a long battle with emphysema. She was
73.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Guild, whose full name was Nancy Guild Martin, was
``discovered'' in old Hollywood style when she appeared in a 1945
Life magazine picture layout about campus fashions while a student
at the University of Arizona. With her bone structure and
insouciance, she captured the attention of five movie studios,
which offered her screen tests.
</P>
<P>
   She was signed to a seven-year contract by 20th Century-Fox,
during which she made her film debut as a nightclub singer in
Joseph Mankiewicz's ``Somewhere in the Night'' (1946), starring
John Hodiak. Movie ads urged viewers to ``meet that Guild girl; she
rhymes with wild.''
</P>
<P>
   She went on to star with George Montgomery in ``The Brasher
Doubloon'' (1947), based on the Raymond Chandler thriller ``The
High Window,'' and with Orson Welles in ``Black Magic'' (1949). She
retired from acting in the '50s and later wrote for Architectural
Digest.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Martin married the actor Charles Russell, with whom she had
a daughter, Elizabeth. They divorced in 1950 and she married Ernest
Martin, who produced Broadway hits like ``Guys and Dolls.''
Divorced from Martin in 1975, she married John Bryson, a
photojournalist, in 1978. They divorced in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   She is survived by three daughters, Elizabeth Martin of Boulder,
Colo., and Cecilia Martin Ford and Polly Martin of New York, and
three granddaughters.
</P>
<P>
   Eugenie Marron
</P>
<P>
   Eugenie Marron, a renowned big-game fisherwoman a half-century
ago, died on Monday at a hospital in West Palm Beach, Fla. She was
99.
</P>
<P>
   In her heyday, Mrs. Marron, who lived in Brielle, N.J., and Palm
Beach, Fla., held five world fishing records. One women's record,
for a 722-pound swordfish caught in 1954 off Chile, remains
unbroken, according to the International Game Fish Association in
Dania Beach, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Marron traveled the world for big-game fish with her
husband, Louis Marron, who holds a men's record with a 1,182-pound
swordfish caught off Chile in 1953.
</P>
<P>
   She wrote a book about her fishing experiences called
``Albacora: The Search for the Giant Broadbill'' (Random House,
1957). Mrs. Marron also assisted in research at the Massachusetts
Institute of Technology and the University of Miami about the
central nervous system of the giant squid.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Marron was born on Nov. 22, 1899, in Jersey City, N.J., and
received a bachelor's degree and a master's degree from Columbia
University. She was also an artist and sculptor; she studied with
Alexander Archipenko.
</P>
<P>
   She is survived by two nieces, Eugenie Wikberg of Fort
Lauderdale, Fla., and Suzanne Treacy of Deerfield Beach, Fla.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
