<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-EARNHARDT-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS THE CLOCK RUNNING OUT ON EARNHARDT? 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By PATRICK ZIER   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The clock has run out on Dale Earnhardt this year. The question
is whether his time has passed.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt, 48, is one of four veteran drivers who, as late as
the mid-1990s, pretty much set the pace in NASCAR. The others are
Terry Labonte, Mark Martin and Rusty Wallace.
</P>
<P>
   In 93 races from 1994-1996, this group, along with newcomer Jeff
Gordon, dominated Winston Cup racing.
</P>
<P>
   Between them, Earnhardt, Labonte, Martin and Wallace won 40
times, recorded 175 top-five finishes and earned two championships.
And Earnhardt was the undisputed leader with 11 wins, 52 top fives
and the 1994 Winston Cup title.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, all except Martin have hit hard times, although
Wallace has maintained some semblance of competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt's dropoff has been especially noticeable. In 86 races
since 1996, the seven-time Winston Cup champion has won just twice
and has only 15 top fives. Since 1996, Labonte has three wins and
14 top fives while Wallace has three wins and 28 top fives,
including his third last Sunday at Watkins Glen International in
New York state.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt's contract with car owner Richard Childress expires
after 2000, and early on, there was talk that he might leave.
Earnhardt owns a Winston Cup car driven by Steve Park, who has
struggled, leading to reports that Earnhardt would replace Park to
pacify primary sponsor Pennzoil. That, however, has been denied and
Earnhardt and Childress are presently working on a new three-year
contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure people want to retire you if they see you have a bad
day or a bad streak or whatever,'' Earnhardt said. ``We feel good
about what we're doing and feel good about our chances to win
races.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to turn the corner and maybe get another
championship in the book before we quit here,'' Earnhardt said.
</P>
<P>
   It is the lure of that record eighth championship that helps
motivate Earnhardt, who is presently tied for the all-time lead
with Richard Petty at seven.
</P>
<P>
   But every year it escapes him, making it less likely he'll ever
get it.
</P>
<P>
   Unless Earnhardt and his team upgrade their performance
significantly _ and soon _ his chances of rising to the top again
become increasingly improbable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to say why this guy may never win or why he wins,''
Earnhardt said. ``You look at the mark. Rusty Wallace is not
winning as regular as he used to. I'm not winning as regular as I
used to. But Bobby Labonte and Jeff Burton and Dale Jarrett and
these guys are all of a sudden in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Why? It's because everything is working for them. The team,
engine guy, crew chief, everything is working for them,'' Earnhardt
said. ``I think Richard Childress and our team are getting closer
to that mark. We've been in the top 10 and been competitive. If we
can just get things to turn the corner a little, I think we'll be
even better.''
</P>
<P>
   While Earnhardt has lost his overall dominance, the one place he
has been overpowering is on NASCAR's two biggest tracks, Daytona
and Talladega. In the three races run on the superspeedways so far,
Earnhardt has been second at Daytona twice and won Talladega.
</P>
<P>
   But he has disappeared from sight just about every place else.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say he's good at the speedways, but he may not be as
good at the road course or at Richmond or whatever,'' Earnhardt
said, speaking about himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll prove that fact wrong. It's just circumstances, whether
it's a bad day or something happens or a chassis or an engine or
whatever,'' he said. ``We just haven't been as consistent as we
need to be or as we've been in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger of Lakeland, Fla., is part of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
