<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-GIULIANI-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER: GIULIANI WORKS THE RURAL PRECINCTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ELEANOR RANDOLPH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial observer for Saturday,
Aug. 21:
</P>
<P>
   Symbolism can lean heavily on a political event, which is why
most campaigns try to avoid zoos and hot air balloons. So it seemed
odd that Mayor Rudolph Giuliani found himself in a slightly
uncomfortable position this week _ figuratively, of course _ at a
steak roast outside Binghamton, N.Y. The mayor, upstate for the
evening as part of his coyly unannounced bid for the U.S. Senate,
found himself penned between hot barbecue grills on one side and
the hard questions of reporters on the other. As he spoke on tricky
political issues like the Northeast dairy compact, clouds of smoke
rolled over his head. As he adjusted his brash city tone to the
softer hush of the countryside, cooks hawked steaks to customers
behind him and yelled, ``medium, medium,'' like a chorus promoting
the mayor's moderated form of Republicanism.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get a better reception here than I do in New York City,''
Giuliani was boasting into the microphones. He grinned, the
fullest, most mischievous grin in the Giuliani repertoire, and
added, ``I'm the hometown favorite.''
</P>
<P>
   For many of the 3,700 or so contented carnivores attending the
fund-raising dinner for State Sen. Thomas Libous, New York City's
mayor is probably not really their hometown favorite Republican.
His hometown is, after all, New York City, the worst place for a
politician to call home, in their view, unless it's Washington,
D.C., which happens to serve as the present address for first lady
Hillary Clinton. Even those Republican upstaters who are not sure
they like Giuliani are extremely sure they do not like Mrs.
Clinton. ``We can't let Hillary win,'' explained Helen Ferris, a
92-year-old Republican activist who plans to work to help the mayor
and who proudly wears a T-shirt that says, ``I'll sleep when I'm
dead.''
</P>
<P>
   For Giuliani, however, the Clinton name may not scare enough of
his upstate voters to the polls. So he is beginning the hard part,
politically, which is figuring out how to please both his city
followers and the more conservative Republicans upstate. The dairy
compact is one example, a complicated milk-pricing agreement that
Giuliani opposed earlier, fearing it would cause higher prices to
consumers and schoolchildren in the city. The mayor told reporters
near the barbecue pit that he now favors the pact. This shift comes
a few weeks after the first lady endorsed the milk deal, which is
strongly supported by farmers upstate and environmentalists wanting
to preserve open farmlands. When he was asked if he and the first
lady now were in agreement, the mayor bristled in a distinctly
un-rural fashion and said, ``I have no idea what her position is.''
</P>
<P>
   His own position, he continued, is that many of his concerns
have been satisfied with adjustments in the compact. He also noted
that if he were a senator, he would vote for it. In some cases,
this might turn out to be his answer to other upcoming political
contradictions. As mayor of New York, he would do one thing; as a
senator representing the whole state, something different.
</P>
<P>
   This sort of politics could be confusing, if it comes to that,
since the mayor is also facing other political pressures from
conservatives. He might be forced to tilt a little to the
Conservative Party on abortion, which could then offend his
suburban voters if he leans too far against abortion rights. The
antics of the Liberal Party could also come into play here, but as
Giuliani said this week, it's a little soon for worrying about
party lines on the ballot in November 2000. The big strategy these
days is to declare himself the only insider in this race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come from New York,'' he said at the barbecue, dropping the
word ``City'' for the occasion. ``I've been to Binghamton at least
a dozen times before, probably more than that, 20, 30 times before.
I've been to most parts of the state many, many times.'' The point
here, of course, is that Mrs. Clinton merely knows New York state
by the book.
</P>
<P>
   A few minutes later Rep. Rick Lazio, from Long Island, appeared
at the fringes of the crowd. Lazio undoubtedly would have been the
favorite of many upstate Republicans, but he was forced out of the
Senate race recently by his party's elders.
</P>
<P>
   For this event, Lazio carefully stayed away from the mayor and,
at one point, vigorously began cooking steaks like a young guest
who fears that if he doesn't pitch in, he'll be off next year's
invitation list. ``I'm here to cook. I'm here to serve,'' he said,
meaning not only the food but the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the mayor returned to the city where some voters
could start wondering whether their tough-guy mayor turns softer on
some of their favorite issues once he strays upstate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
