</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-VENEZUELA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: EMERGENCE OF A VENEZUELAN POTENTATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, Aug. 21:
</P>
<P>
   Venezuela is the world's largest oil exporter outside the Middle
East, yet 80 percent of its people live in poverty. Hugo Chavez won
the presidency nine months ago promising to end the corruption and
mismanagement that has helped to squander Venezuela's riches. But
while Venezuelans overwhelmingly supported radical reform, they
should be very wary of the methods Chavez is using. He is drawing
power into his own hands, and misusing a special Constitutional
Assembly meeting now in Caracas that is composed almost entirely of
his supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez, a former paratroop commander who staged an unsuccessful
military coup in 1992, has so far shown little respect for the
compromises necessary in a democracy, which Venezuela has had for
40 years. He has defied rulings of the Senate and Supreme Court. He
has promoted his fellow coup plotters and installed military
officers in high positions, including as his chief of staff.
Venezuela, which suffered under military rule before the advent of
democracy, has laws limiting the military's role in politics. This
week the government ordered soldiers to patrol the streets to
combat crime, a move that has proved ineffective and repressive
when tried elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez's most ambitious act so far is the establishment of the
Constitutional Assembly, which was elected in April and began work
this month. Unhappily, he has urged the assembly to lengthen his
term and give him the right to succeed himself. Although the
Supreme Court has ruled that the assembly's only job is to write a
constitution, the body, at Chavez's urging, is trying to take over
the functions of the government. This week it voted to establish a
commission to evaluate all sitting judges, including those on the
Supreme Court, and the assembly's president warned that judges who
opposed its decisions would be sacked. Delegates will soon take up
a proposal to slash the size and powers of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to see how the Jacobin decisions of Chavez and the
assembly will help Venezuela. The president's economic proposals
seem destined to fail at fighting poverty. He is right to emphasize
basic services for the poor like access to credit and health care.
But Chavez also wants to add such oddities as a state automaker to
the huge government bureaucracies that are depressing the economy
today. Because of oil, the Venezuelan middle class has come to
expect government jobs, generous pensions and subsidies as their
birthright. The country can no longer afford them. But Chavez has
shown little inclination to challenge this system.
</P>
<P>
   Nor are his proposed political reforms likely to reduce
corruption. Judges are bribable largely because they get inadequate
training and the judiciary is underfinanced. Replacing judges with
those more to the assembly's liking will not change this. Countries
that have successfully fought corruption have done so by increasing
accountability and instituting checks on those in authority. Chavez
and his assembly are seeking to do the opposite by concentrating
power in the presidency.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
