A4944 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-WATER-NYT &LR;      08-21 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-WATER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE NEXT ATTACK ON DIRTY WATER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mo., Iowa, N.C., Md., Wash., Ore.)  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, Aug. 21:
</P>
<P>
   Under pressure from environmental groups, the Clinton
administration now plans to invoke a largely ignored section of the
1972 Clean Water Act to tackle the biggest remaining threat to the
nation's waterways _ polluted runoff. Federal and state governments
have greatly reduced the pollution that flows from readily
identifiable sources like factories and waste treatment plants. But
they have singularly failed to control polluted runoff from more
diffuse sources like farms, city streets, even golf courses. Farm
runoff in particular has been blamed for widespread fish kills and
even human illness. It is also the main reason why more than
two-fifths of the country's waters _ some 20,000 rivers, lakes and
estuaries altogether _ are still too dirty for fishing or swimming.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, federal regulators have made little effort to
control runoff _ known technically as ``non-point source
pollution'' _ largely because it is harder to measure and control
than toxic substances that flow from ``point sources'' like
industrial pipes. But it is no less threatening to water quality.
Farms, for example, pour out pathogens from manure and pesticides
and, in the case of huge hog- or chicken-breeding factory farms,
vast quantities of nutrients like nitrogen and phosphorus that
destroy aquatic life in rivers and streams.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups have thus brought dozens of lawsuits to try
to force Washington to resurrect and enforce a long-dormant
provision of the Clean Water Act. The provision requires each state
to assess the health of every body of water within its borders,
determine the maximum allowable levels of pollutants for each one
and then parcel out the responsibility for meeting these goals to
individual polluters _ whether they be point sources like factories
or non-point sources like farms.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Browner, the administrator of the Environmental Protection
Agency, has now promised to enforce the provision. Her plan would
require detailed assessments of water conditions in every state
within two to three years, as well as an equally detailed action
plan. States that do not comply risk federal intervention, but in
the end the dirty work _ measuring pollution, identifying the
culprits and forcing changes _ will be left to the states.
</P>
<P>
   Despite years of indifference at the state level, some states
now seem eager to tackle the problem. Missouri's attorney general,
Jay Nixon, reached a $25 million settlement with a hog operation
whose untreated waste was fouling Missouri waters _ the largest
settlement of its kind. Attorneys general in Iowa and North
Carolina have been fighting violations. In 1997, in an effort to
save the Chesapeake Bay, Maryland enacted legislation to control
farm runoff. Wisconsin has moved aggressively to control runoff
from all sources. Washington and Oregon, under court order to save
their threatened salmon runs, are carrying out their own
inventories of polluted waters and have welcomed Ms. Browner's
plan.
</P>
<P>
   The plan may inspire political opposition among some farmers and
developers, and will impose new costs on polluters who have
heretofore escaped regulation. To ease that burden, the
administration will offer grants and loans. But the key to the
plan's success will be vigorous regulatory oversight, especially in
Washington.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-99 0106EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
