<HEADER>
A4947 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-PHILLIES-     08-21 0579
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-PHILLIES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONDESI LEADS DODGERS PAST PHILLIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Raul Mondesi ended his silence. With his bat and
with his mouth. The former was more impressive than the latter.
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi's two-out, two-run homer in the ninth inning tied the
score and the Los Angeles Dodgers scored four times in the 10th to
beat Philadelphia 8-5 Friday at Veterans Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   It was Mondesi's first homer since he hit two against the Mets
12 days ago, and the first time he's spoken since lashing out at
the Dodgers' brain trust last Wednesday in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward Mondesi, who also stole a base, only wanted to talk
about the Dodgers' unexpected comeback after Phillies starter
Robert Person held them to one hit _ Eric Karros' seventh-inning
homer _ through eight innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like I always say, just do the best for the team,'' said
Mondesi, who needs five homers and six stolen bases for his second
30-30 season. ``Any time we win a game, that's good for the team no
matter how we win. We have 40 games left. Who knows? We have to
keep playing hard.''
</P>
<P>
   In a zany season in which the Dodgers (55-67) are challenging
the Angels for the greatest disappointment on the field and most
chaos away from it, this rally was inexplicable and
uncharacteristic. The Dodgers hadn't won in extra innings since May
30, a losing string of seven. They had lost their last 11 series
openers.
</P>
<P>
   Even the optimistic manager, Davey Johnson, wasn't holding his
breath for a ninth-inning rally against a pitcher who struck out a
career-high 11 through eight innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, by and large, it was over,'' Johnson said. ``Then
the kid got a little wild. We got a little more patient. To see
Mondy come through ... he didn't crush it, but it was a good way to
start the trip.''
</P>
<P>
   Person baffled the Dodgers by getting ahead quickly in the
count, but after Karros' groundout scored Mark Grudzielanek to cut
the deficit to 4-2 in the ninth, Devon White was plunked with a
pitch and Mondesi hit Person's first pitch, a slider, over the
left-field fence to tie it.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, most of the time I swing at the first pitch,'' Mondesi
said. ``I don't like to give anybody a strike.''
</P>
<P>
   In search of his first complete game, Person entered the inning
having thrown 122 pitches. He finished with 144.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's why this game is fun,'' Johnson said. ``You never take
anything for granted, and boom, boom, it's our bullpen against
their bullpen.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillies reliever Wayne Gomes allowed a leadoff single in the
10th and walked three straight batters to give the Dodgers the
lead. Todd Hollandsworth, Karros, White and Gary Sheffield each had
an RBI in the inning.
</P>
<P>
   It helped ease what, for much of the night, looked to be another
wasted Kevin Brown outing in a wasted season.
</P>
<P>
   Brown allowed eight hits, two earned runs and struck out seven
in seven innings. He was also victimized by two errors and trailed
3-1 when he left, but continued to pitch well. He didn't figure in
the decision, but he's 4-1 with a 0.99 ERA in his past six starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We showed a lot of guts hanging in there. The guy was pitching
well and we got a few breaks,'' Brown said. ``I don't think I've
thrown the ball exceptionally well during this streak you're
talking about. I've battled out of some tough situations. It's not
like I walked out there and just breezed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
