<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-COMETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Perrot's death weighing heavily on teammates
<TEXT>
<P>
   By W.H. STICKNEY JR.
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ She should have died hereafter; there would have
been a time for such a rest. Because it didn't happen, for her, we
do our best.
</P>
<P>
   With apologies to William Shakespeare, the attempt at paraphrase
typifies the manner in which the Comets are going about business
following the death Thursday of point guard Kim Perrot from cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The task Friday night was to face the Los Angeles Sparks. But
every pass, every shot, seemed not to have been executed with the
normal zest.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, the Sparks won 68-64.
</P>
<P>
   Not that it matters. Not that anyone really cares.
</P>
<P>
   The atmosphere had been quite different Monday and Wednesday
when the Comets fed off their negative emotions and beat Utah and
Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is different,'' Comets coach Van Chancellor said Friday.
``This is a lot different. This is after this is when ''
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor's train of thought was interrupted, but his idea was
clear. The Comets on Friday were playing for the first time knowing
Perrot was no longer alive.
</P>
<P>
   It was a heavy burden to bear for both sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to go out there and play like this,'' said Sparks
center Lisa Leslie.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks had ``addressed the situation'' during the morning
shootaround, said coach Orlando Woolridge. Then, the distractions
had been minimized.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sat down and talked about what to expect, the things the
Comets would bring, as far as would they be flat, how our reaction
would be to that, what the crowd reaction would be.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of things that went on tonight,'' he said.
``On top of that, it was a very important game for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. Lost in the emotion was the fact the Sparks are still
fighting Sacramento for positioning in the playoffs. Coming into
the game, the Sparks held down second place in the Western
Conference by only a half-game over the Monarchs.
</P>
<P>
   White ribbons that lit up Compaq Center during Comets wins
Monday and Wednesday were very much in evidence at the Forum.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was an emotional night,'' said Woolridge. ``I know that
people are apt to say that women are more emotional than men, but I
think Van and I probably had more of difficult time than the
players did.''
</P>
<P>
   Tina Thompson has endured a particularly tough go of it since
Perrot was airlifted last Sunday from Mexico, where she had been
undergoing ``experimental'' cancer treatment, to Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Friday was no exception. The mask of steel normally worn by the
24-year-old first player drafted out of college into the WNBA was,
at times, streaked with tears. Thompson labored to get 13 points.
</P>
<P>
   Word has it Sheryl Swoopes collapsed in the hallways at Compaq
Center last Saturday when news that Perrot's condition had worsened
crept into the Comets' locker room. But Swoopes still managed a
game-high 25 points Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Cynthia Cooper, Perrot's closest friend who didn't arrive until
approximately 8 p.m. Houston time, did not play. She sat near the
end of the Comets bench in street clothes.
</P>
<P>
   The opportunity existed for the Sparks to really pour it on.
Chancellor midway the opening period had summoned most of the
nucleus of the team over to sit with Cooper.
</P>
<P>
   Amaya Valdemoro, Jennifer Rizzotti, Jackson and Janeth Arcain
picked up loads of minutes, Arcain starting in place of Cooper.
</P>
<P>
   But mercifully, despite the fight he's in with Sacramento,
Woolridge responded by emptying his bench. Consequently, the Sparks
at halftime led by only 32-31.
</P>
<P>
   Chancellor lacked his usual enthusiasm for much of the 40-minute
game. But with 5:12 to play and the Sparks leading 59-56, he picked
up a technical foul after arguing an out-of-bounds call with an
official.
</P>
<P>
   It was perhaps a venting of his feelings that have been worn raw
over the last two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Friday's game weren't an escape, Chancellor said, ``I
don't know if I like the word escape. It was an outlet to play
ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care what you do, you're not going to escape the fact
of reality. Maybe it's the best way we could cope, and there's no
good way. There's no good way to cope with this situation, but this
was probably the best way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
