<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURDERS-INTERVIEW-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEATH SENTENCED COMMUTED, FAYE COPELAND DREAMS OF POSSIBLE
FREEDOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE HILL KAVANAUGH  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   `You didn't ask'
</P>
<P>
   Minding your own business was the family motto, says Al
Copeland, 51, who lives in Chillicothe and was the Copelands'
fourth child.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom didn't know about the killings, just like I didn't know
about them,'' he says. ``I do think she knew about Ray's cattle
scams. You've got to understand if we asked him anything about his
business, he beat the snot out of us. It was understood _ you
didn't ask.''
</P>
<P>
   Prison for his mother is an ironic twist in her life, he says,
because living with Ray prepared her for prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's using the same type of emotion in prison that she used
with him,'' says Copeland. ``She looked away then when things went
on. She stuck to her business. All the same things she does in
prison now.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they tell her to do something, she does it and doesn't
complain, just as she did with Ray. I don't see a bit of
difference. I think prison is probably better for her than home.
Nobody abuses her there.''
</P>
<P>
   Jurors were convinced of Faye Copeland's guilt when the
prosecution turned up a handwritten list of farmhands in her
writing, hidden in a camera case.
</P>
<P>
   She had written the names because Ray Copeland was illiterate.
There were 12 names with scrawled X's by them and other names with
the word ``back'' next to them, her lawyers say.
</P>
<P>
   Five of the men with an X by their names turned up dead.
</P>
<P>
   Four other transients marked with an X police later found alive
and well, her lawyers say, and three men's whereabouts are still a
mystery. Prosecutors believe they were buried near the others.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was this sinister X next to names...'' recalls Hulshof,
now a U.S. representative. ``It refutes this woman who was caught
in the circumstances and shows her as much more of an accomplice
than she claimed.''
</P>
<P>
   Early in the trial Faye Copeland was offered a plea agreement.
In exchange for telling where the other three men were buried, she
would have been able to walk out a free woman. But she told
authorities she couldn't tell them where anybody was, because she
didn't know.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Copeland had a long history of writing bad checks, going in
and out of prisons since the 1930s and disappearing for two to
three days at a time, says Sean O'Brien, Faye Copeland's attorney.
</P>
<P>
   ``Faye is just as much a victim of Ray's conduct as are those
men planted in the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Hulshof, however, says Faye Copeland may have stood up to her
husband more than she lets on. Neighbors reported hearing her curse
at Ray when working with him.
</P>
<P>
   The list of X's spooks Al Copeland.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Ray would have been arrested in 1987, I'd probably been
arrested too, because in 1986 I was going to the sale barns with
him and the hired hands, '' he says. ``I was writing down the names
and told to put X's by the men who ran off.''
</P>
<P>
   Copeland regrets his testimony at his mother's trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``They asked me if I ever saw her abused,'' he says. ``I told
them no. But I wasn't allowed to say why.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Ray got in one of his moods, we all scattered. My
brothers and sister never saw Ray hit me either. That was our
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Al Copeland says he has his own brutal memories.
</P>
<P>
   At 10, his father beat him with a claw hammer because he handed
him the wrong tool, he says.
</P>
<P>
   Another time, he was milking cows and a cow kicked over her
bucket. Al Copeland still suffers back pain from that beating by
his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``My family was very different from most families,'' he says.
Beyond prison walls
</P>
<P>
   Faye Copeland's words tumble and stop, like a square-wheeled
cart bouncing over a gravel road. But always, always, looming
somewhere in her answers is the knowledge of everything she is
missing.
</P>
<P>
   It's apparent when she talks about her grandchildren and
great-grandchildren, including ``three more on the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago was the very best day she's had yet in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cried all day, all the night and half the next day,'' she
says about the news that her life was spared. ``Now I'm waiting for
the next one.''
</P>
<P>
   Her attorneys are working and she is hoping. But she only shakes
her head when asked if she ever thought her life would end up this
way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've often thought since, maybe this was the for the best,''
she says. ``Where did I go wrong, if I went wrong? I know one place
was getting married at all. But he was my life for many, many
years. I didn't know nothing else.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will I get out? I may go out feet first but I'll get out of
here. Someday.''
</P>
</TEXT>
