<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-blinebury-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Keeping up with Jones no easy feat
<TEXT>
<P>
   By FRAN BLINEBURY
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   SEVILLE, Spain _ At the breakfast news conference hosted by
their ubiquitous shoe company, the fleet-footed twosome of Michael
Johnson and Maurice Greene sat side by side, grinning through bared
teeth like a couple of pit bulls on short leashes.
</P>
<P>
   The two men who can lay legitimate claim to the title of world's
fastest human will not square off at the World Track and Field
Championships, which open today. Greene will run in the 100 and 200
and Johnson in the 400.
</P>
<P>
   When they were asked who might win a showdown over 200 meters,
both had the same succinct answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me,'' Greene said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   That's the way it normally is in the world of elite sprinting,
where the atmosphere can often be likened to a heavyweight fight.
The combatants preen and glare and prepare silently, as though
talking will somehow sap their swiftness.
</P>
<P>
   Which is what makes the figure who sat on the other side of the
stage along the banks of the serene Guadalquivir River such a
refreshing and charming diversion.
</P>
<P>
   Marion Jones might as well have been floating on the river in
one of the paddleboats.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that the next eight days will find her running a
self-imposed gantlet that will test her speed, her strength, her
stamina and maybe even her sanity as she attempts to win four gold
medals here, then up the count to five at the 2000 Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   You might not know her now. But you will by the time NBC gets
through beaming Jones' exploits from Sydney next summer.
</P>
<P>
   This is her show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just here to try,'' she said, flashing a smile that makes
her a cross between the girl next door and Wonder Woman.
</P>
<P>
   She also is the brightest hope to lift her beleaguered sport out
of the depths of the negative publicity surrounding the latest
round of high-profile steroid busts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anyone could have thought this was going to
happen,'' Jones said. ``In the past couple of weeks, our beautiful
and lovely sport has been marred by all of this. I think the
athletes wish we could have come here to Seville and put all of
that in the past and start on a positive note. But now we can only
hope that our wonderful performances in a couple of days will
overshadow everything that has happened.''
</P>
<P>
   She is as bright and sunny as a Spanish afternoon, even in the
face of controversy and the hectic schedule that awaits her over
the next eight days. The 23-year-old faces a frantic opening
schedule today with two rounds of the 100 meters and qualifying in
the long jump.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to go out there and hopefully qualify on my first jump
and then be able to concentrate on the 100,'' she said. ``I'm just
ready to get started. That's all I know for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones talks about her schedule in the multiple events, but never
about any burden she has placed on herself to win them all, though
that is clearly the plan.
</P>
<P>
   She makes it sound no more difficult than a week's worth of
sightseeing around the cobblestone streets of the old city. But
those in the know are aware that what Jones is attempting is
something for the ages as she tries to become the first woman to
win four gold medals in the same World Championships.
</P>
<P>
   John Smith, the former Olympic medalist and now the coach for
Greene and Inger Miller, one of Jones' competitors in the 200, nods
in admiration.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's going to stand on that podium four or five times,'' he
said. ``It's just a matter of what color (medal) she's going to
stand there with. But I'm going to be watching very intently to see
it happen. There is going to be some history being made and our
sport needs that. Actually, she needs the challenges, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones won gold in the 100 and the 400 relay at the 1997 World
Championships in Athens and has been virtually untouchable in the
sprints since.
</P>
<P>
   She might be vulnerable in the long jump, where she finished in
10th place in Athens and has lost three times since, twice to
Olympic medalist Heike Drechsler and in June at the U.S. nationals
to Dawn Burrell, the younger sister of University of Houston coach
Leroy Burrell.
</P>
<P>
   In the sprints, Jones uses her long thoroughbred's legs to
simply move away from the field, in the manner of Carl Lewis. But
the long jump also requires form and technique, a combination that
makes Lewis' record of four straight Olympic gold medals in that
event even more impressive.
</P>
<P>
   So, if it's Lewis' legacy Jones is trying to run down, and even
eclipse, it is perhaps fitting it's in the event he owned that she
has the hardest work to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm ready. I need this,'' Marion Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Almost as much, right now, as track and field needs her.
</P>
</TEXT>
