r a BC-MURDERS-INTERVIEW-2TA     08-21 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURDERS-INTERVIEW-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEATH SENTENCED COMMUTED, FAYE COPELAND DREAMS OF POSSIBLE
FREEDOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE HILL KAVANAUGH  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANDALIA, Mo. _ Birthdays don't matter in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Faye Copeland's Aug. 4 birthday was just another notch in her
life, a grim reminder that 78 years had passed since she was born
in an Arkansas log cabin.
</P>
<P>
   Like every day in prison, she rose at 5 a.m. along with 1,402
other incarcerated women. She tended to seedlings in the
greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   That's her prison job. It's also her life. But there was one
difference in this 24-hour span.
</P>
<P>
   In the Kansas City federal courthouse some 220 miles away was a
stack of papers holding one of the best birthday presents Copeland
may ever get _ a judge's commutation of her death sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Barring an appeal from Attorney General Jay Nixon within 45 days
of the judgment, Copeland won't die by lethal injection.
</P>
<P>
   The commutation was only a partial victory, say her attorneys,
Sean O'Brien and Kent Gibson, who filed the petition in January
1998. Although U.S. District Judge Ortrie Smith commuted her death
sentence, agreeing with some of the issues Copeland's attorneys
raised, he upheld the punishment of life without parole.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday her attorneys filed more paperwork in U.S. District
Court, petitioning for a new trial based on information that her
jury never heard.
</P>
<P>
   They argue she was the victim of 50 years of abuse from her
husband, Ray.
</P>
<P>
   A great-grandmother 21 times over, she once won second place in
the Ozark Empire Fair for her pickled beets and still dreams of
returning to her farmhouse in Mooresville, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, prosecutors paint a far different picture of Copeland,
until two weeks ago the oldest woman on death row.
</P>
<P>
   Nine years ago she was convicted of first-degree murder for her
role in one of the largest serial murder cases in Missouri history.
Prosecutors said she was deeply involved in the killings of five
transients whose bodies were unearthed near her farm.
</P>
<P>
   Her attorneys admit a new trial is a long shot. But even its
possibility gives hope to Copeland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wouldn't you?'' Copeland said this week to visitors.
``Everyone hopes, even just to see another day. Nothing's
guaranteed in this life 'cept dying.''
Life on the inside
</P>
<P>
   The Women's Eastern Reception, Diagnostic and Correctional
Center in Vandalia is a 47-acre complex of blood-red buildings.
Opened in December 1997, the prison is a state-of-the-art facility
and one of the newest in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Faye Copeland was transferred here from the Chillicothe
Correctional Center almost a year ago, because a relative was
working there.
</P>
<P>
   Softening the edges of the Vandalia prison's razor-wire fences
are hundreds of marigolds, zinnias, euonymus and barberry bushes,
all raised by hand from prisoner 000888003.
</P>
<P>
   To inmates she is known as ``Mrs. Faye.'' To the outside world,
she is ``the murderer.''
</P>
<P>
   Copeland has been in prison since her arrest and conviction in
1990 for a scheme with her husband, Ray, involving cattle, bad
checks and five murdered transients, killings that she maintains
her deceased husband committed without her knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors thought otherwise, convicting her of first-degree murder
and sentencing her to death.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Hulshof, the co-prosecutor, called the Copeland couple
20th century cattle rustlers. Abuse in Faye Copeland's life was
never an issue, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time, the law for battered spouse syndrome only applied
to cases involving self-defense,'' he says.``And all these claims
of abuse by the family members did not come out until after Ray's
death, after Ray could no longer defend himself....
</P>
<P>
   ``We found that Faye was an equal partner with Ray. Yes, Ray was
a gruff old farmer. But Faye is not a meek demure woman, just a
woman who knew hard times.''
A tolerable life
</P>
<P>
   At the prison's visiting room, an alarm sounds announcing an
arrival. Entering is a gray-headed woman, walking with concerted
steps past vending machines and several walls of visiting rules.
</P>
<P>
   Faye Copeland's face reflects a mix of dull despair, anger and
fear. After a brief smile, her lips draw into a thin line.
</P>
<P>
   She is wary of interviews, especially after a ``60 Minutes''
piece where she was portrayed as the picture of the American Gothic
gone bad.
</P>
<P>
   But her full story, the one of the abuse and battering that the
jurors didn't hear a decade ago, needs to be heard, her attorneys
say. So, they urge her to talk about her life.
</P>
<P>
   The basis of her petition rests on the fact that evidence of her
abuse was never introduced at the trial.
</P>
<P>
   She shakes hands with her visitors, with the soft grip of a
78-year-old woman who has diabetes and a heart condition.
</P>
<P>
   Life is very different than on the farm, she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't have flowers at home,'' she says. ``He didn't like
me to be tending to anything other than him. As long as I was with
him or working the cattle or the tractor that was OK. But flowers,
no, he didn't like them.''
</P>
<P>
   As she speaks, her voice is barely louder than a whisper.
Voicing her own opinion, she says, wasn't what a wife should do if
her husband didn't like it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was raised to love my husband and support him no matter
what,'' she says. ``The man is the head of the family. The Bible
says it should be that way. It wouldn't do to say if Ray was mean
to me or not....Yes, he did mess up my life, but that's not to say
that I wasn't a good wife to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was never mean to him....Maybe we'd have got along better if
I had knocked the hell out of him a few times.''
</P>
<P>
   She laughs at that thought. Then her hands rub at an age spot on
her arm. She squints out the window where blue skies advertise a
beautiful day. Again, her lips return to their tight line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like talkin' with the media because 90 percent of the
time wasn't nothin' said right,'' she says. ``Just tell the truth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll give you that probably the worst mistake of my life was
marrying him,'' she says. Ray Copeland, 78, died in 1993 before the
state could execute him.
</P>
<P>
   ``But life can be good or it can be bad. It's what you make of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Except for Christmases and her children's birthdays, prison life
for her is tolerable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
