<HEADER>
A4954 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKL-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     08-21 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERROT'S FIRE DIMS BUT WON'T GO OUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ If Cynthia Cooper and Sheryl Swoopes were
the front and back covers of the Houston Comets' first two
storybook seasons, Kim Perrot was the spine that bound all the
pages.
</P>
<P>
   Perrot was tough as leather but it was the elasticity of her
spirit that, in the end, kept the Comets from scattering like loose
pages Friday in one of life's cold, stiff winds.
</P>
<P>
   The two-time defending WNBA champions showed up at the Forum for
a scheduled game against the Los Angeles Sparks, not because any of
them felt like playing but because they knew it was what Perrot
would have wanted.
</P>
<P>
   It is a measure of how much the fiery point guard meant to her
teammates that she continued to have a powerful, positive hold over
them in death, the same as she had in life.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's more of a tribute to the fighting spirit of Kim than
anything else,'' said Houston coach Van Chancellor of the Comets'
decision to play the Sparks the day after Perrot lost a six-month
battle with cancer.
</P>
<P>
   What a cruel, cruel summer it just became for those in cancer's
grip.
</P>
<P>
   In June and July cyclist Lance Armstrong gave renewed hope to
cancer victims and their loved ones with his improbable wins, in
short, sweet succession, over cancer and the field in the Tour de
France.
</P>
<P>
   Then on Thursday cancer roared back with a vengeance, striking
down a strong, sprightly sports figure in her prime, as if to serve
notice that it remains a very formidable foe.
</P>
<P>
   That there are eight million Americans who have survived to tell
of their close encounter with cancer is of small comfort to the
family and friends of the more than 500,000 who will lose the
battle this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no good way to cope with this situation,'' Chancellor
said.
</P>
<P>
   He stood slouched, as if the weight of Perrot's passing was his
alone to shoulder, and addressed reporters after his team's
mourning shootaround.
</P>
<P>
   The Comets _ minus Cooper, who had stayed behind in Houston to
keep a vigil at Perrot's bedside _ filed so stiffly and silently
into the Forum, they could have been stepping into a funeral
parlor. Cooper would join them later for the game, but did not
attempt to play.
</P>
<P>
   The light workout did seem more like a wake, with players
staring vacantly into space and Swoopes leaving the court at one
point to sit and bury her head in her hands.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't just the Houston players who were hurting. The Sparks'
shootaround also was cloaked in black, its solemnity signifying
that the death of a player as popular Perrot is an unspeakable loss
to the WNBA family.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely a very sad day in women's basketball,'' said
center Lisa Leslie, who knew Perrot well enough to consider her a
friend. Of course, to meet Perrot was to become her pal. She
collected friends the way lesser people do grudges.
</P>
<P>
   Perrot's personality had a way of lighting up a room. So it's
surprising klieg lights were needed on the day this past spring
when Perrot showed up at the Women's NCAA Final Four to watch
Leslie film a Nike promotional spot.
</P>
<P>
   Perrot playfully heckled Leslie between takes. ``She was still
in high spirits,'' Leslie recalled.
</P>
<P>
   The last time Leslie saw Perrot, 32, was on June 22, when the
Sparks played at Houston. In a halftime ceremony of a game the
Comets would win by eight points, the players received their 1998
championship rings.
</P>
<P>
   Swoopes and Cooper combined for 61 points but the star of the
evening was Perrot, who had just returned from the first of two
trips she would take to Tijuana seeking alternative treatment for
the cancer that had attacked her lungs and brain.
</P>
<P>
   By that time the cancer clearly had weakened her body. Perrot's
spirit, however, was as strong as ever. It remained so, Chancellor
said, right up until she drew her final breath.
</P>
<P>
   There are so many stories Chancellor would have liked to have
told about Perrot, only the lump in his throat got in the way. This
one, he coaxed out ahead of the tears:
</P>
<P>
   In mid-February Perrot underwent five hours of brain surgery to
remove cancerous tumors. She was visited in the recovery room by
her mother, Cooper and Chancellor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hi, mom,'' she whispered. ``Hi, Cynthia.'' Then, seeing
Chancellor, her voice grew stronger. ``Hey, Coach. Don't you be
going out and drafting another point guard. I'm going to be your
point guard.''
</P>
<P>
   She really believed it, too. ``She was so upbeat,'' Leslie said,
``you never really were left feeling like she'd lose the battle to
cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   Perrot made it hard for people to cry for her because she never
allowed herself a second of self-pity. So the sorrow her many, many
friends and admirers felt Friday was for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Perrot, they knew, had gone to a better place. And left this one
a little less divine.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
