<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN--Astros-Hidalgo-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Astros' Hidalgo may miss rest of season
<TEXT>
<P>
   By CARLTON THOMPSON
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Astros outfielder Richard Hidalgo's injured left knee is
not getting any better and season-ending surgery looks like a
possibility.
</P>
<P>
   Hidalgo, who has played through pain for most of the season, has
been on the disabled list since Aug. 9, a few days after his knee
gave out during batting practice in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros hoped rest would be enough of a tonic to get their
starting left fielder back onto the field, but so far he hasn't
made much progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm concerned about Richard,'' Astros general manager Gerry
Hunsicker said. ``There is a possibility that he won't be back at
all this season.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan is to re-evaluate Hidalgo's status in a week. If there
is no progress, Hunsicker said surgery would be considered.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it goes another week without improvement, there won't be
much optimism,'' Hunsicker said.
</P>
<P>
   Hidalgo's injury is the result of a congenital defect. His left
kneecap never fused the way it does with most people; it's
something he has dealt with throughout his career.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the wear and tear of playing on artificial turf worsened
the situation. This is the most extensive time Hidalgo, 24, has
spent on turf in his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Richard is extremely disappointed,'' said Peter Greenberg,
Hidalgo's agent. ``He went as far as he could on that knee. My
impression from talking to Richard is that the chances of him
making it through the year are very slim.
</P>
<P>
   ``Richard has been through a lot in his career in terms of
injuries, and he has a high tolerance for pain. If he says he can't
perform, he can't perform.''
</P>
<P>
   If Hidalgo needs surgery, it would be another blow for the
Astros, who might not get Moises Alou back this season. Right
fielder Derek Bell also is on the disabled list, and Hunsicker said
he's still sore. Bell, who pulled his left groin Monday, could be
out for three to four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Hidalgo is hitting .227 with 15 home runs and 56 RBIs. He ranks
third on the team in home runs and fifth in RBIs and his 15
outfield assists are second in the majors. He trails only Florida's
Mark Kotsay in throwing out runners.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
