<HEADER>
A4956 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-NYTBOMB-KAN &LR;      08-21 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOMB-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WWI MESS RAISES SAFETY ISSUES IN 1999 WASHINGTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star   WASHINGTON _ It is a normally quiet
corner of the city, an enclave of wealth and prestige whose winding
leafy lanes and elegant addresses are home to several foreign
ambassadors and other members of the capital's upper crust.
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is also home, however, to some worrisome ghosts from an
antique age, and it's taking more than $25 million and the combined
efforts of the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers and the city to
exorcise them.
</P>
<P>
   Beneath the green lawns and ornamental gardens of the South
Korean ambassador's back yard lies a burial pit for World War I-era
chemical weapons and munitions.
</P>
<P>
   It's a dump, for mortars, smoke bombs and mustard gas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Death Valley'' is how a soldier in 1918 ominously described
the site on the back of an old photograph unearthed several years
ago. The soldier is shown standing on a hillside _ now the
ambassador's back yard _ his face sealed inside a gas mask.
</P>
<P>
   That was 81 years ago. Last month, as the corps' ``Operation
Safe Removal'' continued, some homes had to be evacuated for a few
hours when one of those old, but apparently no less volatile,
chemical agents _ white phosphorus _ ignited and emitted a wraith
of smoke. No one was injured.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been here since 1946,'' said Mary Gibson, who lives down
the street from the ambassador. ``The neighborhood sure has
changed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spring Valley residents have come to accept the presence of
eerie-looking workers encased in protective suits, the ceaseless
cacophony of industrial noise that accompanies the project, and
their own occasional refugee status.
</P>
<P>
   It started in 1993 when workers laying a sewer pipe uncovered a
cache of chemical munitions. Federal and city agencies evacuated
the immediate neighborhood in the city's upper northwest quadrant.
</P>
<P>
   They found 141 old artillery rounds, including 43 that they
suspected contained chemicals. All were traced to American
University, which sits in the middle of Spring Valley and was an
enlistee in the war effort in 1917.
</P>
<P>
   That was the year when Germany, which had been using toxic gases
against French troops since 1915, introduced mustard gas. Causing
deadly burns and blisters, it raised warfare to a new degree of
horror. The United States, just three months into the war, began a
crash program to keep up with the Germans.
</P>
<P>
   The government leased the campus for the American University
Experiment Station, which became the second-largest chemical
munitions research center in the world.
</P>
<P>
   A team of 1,200 scientists tested 48 toxic or dangerous agents,
including mustard and cyanogen chloride, which poisons the blood.
They dug trenches in the nearby farmland where they staked goats
and dogs as test victims. The scientists hid behind ramshackle
bunkers and shacks, waiting to see which animals would die.
</P>
<P>
   Caution was not a watchword. Chemical bombs would explode, and
traffic and commerce on the nearby streets would go blithely along.
That is until one day in August 1918, when, according to an account
at the time, former Sen. Nathan B. Scott of West Virginia, and his
wife, Agnes, were ``gassed,'' though not injured when a ``cloud''
drifted by their home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The attitudes about hazmat (hazardous materials) was totally
different at that point, socially and legally,'' said Ruth Ann
Overbeck, a land use historian who has researched the history of
the experiment station. ``It was a whole different era.''
</P>
<P>
   The corps spent three years investigating the entire 660-acre
Spring Valley neighborhood after the 1993 discovery, concluding it
was free of chemicals and safe. But the city's environmental health
agency was still leery. It pointed to the 1918 photograph of the
gas mask-wearing soldier bending over a pit containing glass or
ceramic jugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The pit, the most feared and respected place in the grounds,''
the soldier wrote on the back of the photograph. ``The bottles are
full of mustard, to be destroyed here. In Death Valley. The hole
called Hades.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``pit,'' officials eventually deduced, was in South Korean
Ambassador Hong-Koo Lee's back yard, which backs up to the American
University campus.
</P>
<P>
   The army found some glass containers, but none with liquid or
jellied mustard or Lewisite, a chemical weapon that destroys tissue
and invades the lungs. The army said the agents could have degraded
over time, but they're still searching for more.
</P>
<P>
   Lewisite, however, is so deadly, said Theodore Gordon, a city
environmental health official, that ``a tablespoon in a room 10 by
10 can kill you in about 30 seconds.''
</P>
<P>
   Workers dumped 200 tons of gravel into the yard last spring to
grade the hillside to allow in cranes and other equipment. But the
actual excavation of the burial pit is done painstakingly by two
workers with shovels. Clad in protective suits with breathing
devices, they have dug out more than 540 drums of contaminated
soil.
</P>
<P>
   The site is enclosed inside a ``vapor containment structure,'' a
Quonset hut-like building, to keep hazardous materials under wraps.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are taking very tight security measures and every care,
so we have confidence in how they have done the job so far,'' said
Jong-Dae Park, a South Korean embassy official.
</P>
<P>
   The corps and the city think they're nearing the end of their
search.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of this is hit-and-miss because we don't know for
sure,'' Gordon said. ``We think we're close to cleaning it up.''
</P>
<P>
   Maj. Brian Plaisted, site manager for the corps of engineers,
said: ``This is kind of a unique situation. During wartime, things
happen, and then 20 years later they start building this really
nice neighborhood and nobody remembers what was there.''
</P>
<P>
   Now it will be a long time before they forget.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-99 0122EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
