<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 01:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4957 &Cx1f; tth-z
b x BC-MAYOR-POLICE-SPI &LR;      08-21 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAYOR-POLICE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAYOR TAKES ISSUE WITH COUNCILWOMAN'S REMARKS ON POLICE REPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ALAN SNEL AND KIMBERLY A.C. WILSON  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ A showdown over how Seattle police should investigate
themselves is brewing between Mayor Paul Schell and a councilwoman
who chairs the public safety committee.
</P>
<P>
   A day after an independent panel released a report citing flaws
in the Police Department's internal investigations operations,
Schell on Friday sharply rebuked comments by Councilwoman Tina
Podlodowski who said a proposed plan to monitor the police chief
was not good enough.
</P>
<P>
   Schell said Friday it's his job to play watchdog over Police
Chief Norm Stamper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Tina was having a bad day,'' Schell said, referring to
Podlodowski's question about who would watch the chief. ``That's
not where the council is going. I'm embarrassed for her.''
</P>
<P>
   The panel's documents suggest a civilian _ not an officer _ run
a new Police Department office called the Office of Professional
Accountability to investigate complaints of police misconduct. The
civilian would be appointed by the police chief, subject to
approval from the city council.
</P>
<P>
   Podlodowski said Thursday she was pleased with the hybrid police
overview of a civilian directing an internal investigation staff
composed of officers. But she was concerned that the new office
would not have watchdog authority over Stamper.
</P>
<P>
   She could not be reached for comment Friday.
</P>
<P>
   One of the panel's four members, lawyer Jenny Durkan, said
Friday that Stamper would be monitored adequately because ``the
chief can be fired at will by the mayor.''
</P>
<P>
   Stamper, at the center of the debate over who ultimately should
police his troops, could not be reached for comment Friday. Members
of the Internal Investigations Section leadership did not reply to
repeated interview requests.
</P>
<P>
   The report by the mayor-appointed panel chides the department
for not properly responding to misconduct complaints, criticizes
officers for failing to appear in court on cases and the chief for
not giving ethics matters ``sufficient priority.''
</P>
<P>
   The panel detailed more than 20 suggestions, including beefing
up ethics training for all officers and conducting face-to-face
interviews between accused officers and internal investigators
instead of the current policy of having accused officers respond to
written questions.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle is one of the few cities that don't conduct in-person
interviews of accused officers, the 37-page report said.
</P>
<P>
   It also recommends that the chief issue a ``bright line''
stating that lying, cheating or stealing by police will not be
tolerated.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing in that report that I was in instant
disagreement,'' Schell said in an interview Friday. He noted the
panel's point about Stamper giving his troops the explicit message
about not lying, cheating or stealing ``was an overstatement made
for emphasis. But you can't say it enough.''
</P>
<P>
   The police union would have to approve many of the panel's
suggestions for them to take effect. Many officers said Friday they
had not read the report, but union leaders expect to discuss it
with rank-and-file officers at a meeting next week.
</P>
<P>
   Schell and Stamper will respond to the panel's report in 30 days
by issuing a game plan for implementing the suggestions. Schell
said his response will show which recommendations can immediately
go into effect and which ones would need police union approval.
</P>
<P>
   While the mayor and the chief began mapping their response, the
city clerk Friday approved a proposed ballot initiative (I-50) that
would ask voters to approve an elected, five-member citizens law
enforcement board. The board would be autonomous from the mayor,
the council, Police Department and the chief.
</P>
<P>
   David Todd Olsen of a group calling itself the Coalition for a
Balanced Government must collect at least 18,830 signatures before
Feb. 16 for the issue to be placed on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Initiative 50 would empower five paid elected citizens to
``investigate allegations of misconduct or unlawful activities by
Police Department employees, call for and receive the dismissal of
Police Department employees, create and amend certain police
policies, recommend prosecution of Police Department employees, and
establish and direct a special prosecutor's office.''
</P>
<P>
   While the department brass was silent about the panel's report,
line officers weren't.
</P>
<P>
   Many were supportive of recommendations geared to restore
confidence in a department wracked earlier this year by the
revelation that a homicide detective allegedly stole $10,000 from a
crime scene.
</P>
<P>
   But others were skeptical about just how independent the
civilian oversight director could be if the buck still stops with
Stamper.
</P>
<P>
   A sergeant, who declined to be identified, said such an
arrangement ``ain't gonna work.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What good is one more yes person to the chief, when this chief
has closed his eyes to what has been going on all along?'' he
asked.
</P>
<P>
   Another officer who had read the report described it as ``right
on.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The panel sent a message that the supervisors who were in
charge of IIS really haven't been doing a good job.''
</P>
<P>
   After the reported theft came to light in April _ two years
after it reportedly occurred _ the internal investigations section
launched an investigation into Sgt. Don Cameron and Detective Earl
``Sonny'' Davis. In 1996, Davis allegedly took $10,000 from the
home of a man killed in a gunfight with police. When Davis' partner
told Cameron about the theft, the sergeant allegedly helped Davis
return the money the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, who has since retired in the wake of the scandal, goes to
trial Sept. 7 for first-degree theft.
</P>
<P>
   In commenting on the report, Schell said he did not thinking
funding to implement some of the recommendations would be a
problem.
</P>
<P>
   He noted there is money in the city budget that can be
``refocused'' to pay for two new positions and training suggested
by the report.
</P>
<P>
   Councilwoman Margaret Pageler, a former council public safety
chairwoman, said Friday that officers will not appreciate having a
civilian run an internal investigations unit.
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. J.D. Miller, the vice president of the Police Officers
Guild and a former IIS investigator, voiced few complaints about
the report.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pleased that the report is saying what we've believed
for a long time,'' Miller said without elaborating.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
