<HEADLINE>
VISITORS TO FRED PHELPS' WEB SITE FIND A SURPRISE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 ROBERT A. CRONKLETON  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Visitors to a
nationally known, anti-homosexual Web site got a surprise when they
tried to connect to the Internet site this week: a message
sympathetic to homosexuals.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Instead of seeing the Web site with ties to the Rev. Fred
Phelps, a Topeka minister who preaches that God hates homosexuals,
people were redirected to a site that promotes itself as a resource
for gay, lesbian, straight, bisexual and transgendered persons of
faith.
</P>
<P>
   An official with the Westboro Baptist Church, where Phelps is
pastor, blamed computer hackers for the switch and said the actions
are criminal.
</P>
<P>
   But a New Hampshire man who runs the pro-gay Web site denied any
wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Late Friday, a notice was placed on the site, promising to
restore access to the Phelps Web page.
</P>
<P>
   According to Network Solutions Inc. of Herndon, Va., a provider
of Web address registration services, ownership of the Phelps Web
site was switched Wednesday from Westboro Baptist Church in Topeka
to Westboro Baptist Church of Newport, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic to the Phelps Web site also was redirected to the
pro-gay Web site run by Kris Haight of New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Network Solutions is looking into the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, our security team is investigating it,'' said
Christina Zulandi, senior public relations specialist with Network
Solutions. ``Until then we cannot comment any further.''
</P>
<P>
   Shirley Phelps-Roper, a daughter of Fred Phelps and one of the
church's attorneys, said the action was illegal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a crime to take and mess with people's Web pages,
particularly to try to steal them,'' said Phelps-Roper. Someone
``hacked into an e-mail of the Web master and sent an e-mail to
Network Solutions Inc., telling them to change the ownership of the
Web page....He then made the pronouncement that now he owns the Web
page.''
</P>
<P>
   She said state and federal authorities had been asked to
investigate.
</P>
<P>
   Haight, however, denies any wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Haight, who is gay, said he received an anonymous e-mail this
week telling him to pay attention to the registration information
for the Web site run by the Topeka church.
</P>
<P>
   About 3 p.m. Wednesday, he said, the church's ownership of its
domain name was transferred to the Newport church.
</P>
<P>
   A check of Internet databases and directory information listed
no Westboro Baptist Church in Newport. Registration information
from Network Solutions listed the same mailing address for the New
Hampshire church and for Haight's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``While we are not aware exactly how the domain was transferred,
please note that it was by no action of our own,'' Haight said.
</P>
<P>
   An e-mail announcing the transfer appeared to be both authentic
and legal, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not hack any servers or Web sites,'' Haight said. ``We
did not hack any e-mail systems.''
</P>
<P>
   Haight said he redirected all traffic trying to access Phelps'
site to the one Haight and his Web site partner started in March.
Haight said that site spreads a message of God's love to people who
have traditionally been inundated with a message of hate. He said
it ``monitors the actions of those who spew hate in the name of
God.''
</P>
<P>
   The addresses for both Phelps' and Haight's Web sites contain a
slur.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Kresha, operations engineer for Verio Kansas City, an
Internet service provider, said it was rare for hackers to be able
to switch the ownership of a domain name, which is more commonly
known as a Web address.
</P>
<P>
   Kresha said changes would have to be initiated by the Web
address owner and even then would have to be handled by e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the e-mail address does not match the controller of that
domain, Network Solutions would reject the changes,'' Kresha said.
</P>
<P>
   Phelps-Roper said it is not uncommon for Phelps' site, which has
about 100,000 visitors a month, to be under attack.
</P>
<P>
   The Anti-Defamation League earlier this year labeled the Phelps
Web site as ``perhaps the most vile and best-known anti-gay Web
site.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a little bit of an inconvenience,'' Phelps-Roper said,
``but it is easily correctable. It takes just 24 or 48 hours.''
</P>
<P>
   Once the dust is settled, she said, the church will continue to
promote its anti-gay ministry.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
