<HEADLINE>
GALAXY BACK TO FOCUSING ON MLS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM BARRERO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ No more CONCACAF Champions Cup qualifiers to
worry about, no more U.S. Open Cup matches to ponder and no more
exhibitions.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning tonight, the Galaxy can finally focus on what would
seem to matter most to this franchise _ a drive toward the MLS Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles begins a final stretch run of 10 games against
MLS-only competition with a matchup against the lowly New York/New
Jersey MetroStars tonight at 7:30 at the Rose Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   A penalty-kicks loss to Necaxa of Mexico in a Champions Cup
qualifier on Wednesday left the Galaxy without any outside
distractions leading up to the MLS playoffs in mid-October. A
victory would have moved the team on to an eight-team tournament in
Las Vegas at the end of September.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that we're out of this tournament, we need to focus on the
rest of the season and try catching Colorado and hopefully be there
when it's all over,'' Galaxy defender Ezra Hendrickson said.
</P>
<P>
   Said forward Carlos Hermosillo, who plays with Necaxa when not
with the Galaxy: ``Now that this is over, we can begin to focus on
the MLS Cup '99. Our team is playing well and hopefully we will
make a good run toward the cup and bring it home to our fans.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles (14-8, 36 points) is second in the Western
Conference behind Colorado and has won nine of its past 11 MLS
games, capturing the league's attention as the Galaxy players have
adapted nicely to coach Sigi Schmid's approach.
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy can creep within three points of the Rapids with a
regulation victory tonight. Colorado lost to Dallas on Wednesday
3-0.
</P>
<P>
   The chance for L.A. to continue its ascent up the conference
standings appears to be good, considering N.Y./N.J. has not
defeated a Western Conference opponent on the road since April 17,
1998 in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   The MetroStars lead the league in shots taken (390), but are
last in goals scored (21).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-99 0132EDT &QL; 
