<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRIVER'S-SIDE HATCH SETS SATURN APART
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB GOLFEN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This review is not so much about an entire car as it is about a
single door. It's the door that makes this car something of a
unique entity, at least something that I'd never heard of: a
three-door coupe.
</P>
<P>
   Leave it to Saturn to create a big wave from a small innovation.
That's been the story with this company since it was started by
General Motors almost a decade ago as a private corporation
dedicated to building a new small car, as well as creating a new
corporate culture and dealership experience.
</P>
<P>
   The real news at Saturn for 2000 is the introduction of its
first midsize car, the LS sedan and wagon, to supplement its
compact SL sedan, wagon and SC coupe. But there's still some
applause left for Saturn's innovation of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Really, there is so little in the automotive world that is truly
singular or unique, once you get past such sideshows as the Dodge
Viper and the New Beetle. Doors are all the rage, of course, now
that stretch-cab pickups require four doors and minivans must have
sliding passenger doors on both sides. All the Saturn coupes are
now being built as three-doors.
</P>
<P>
   The third door on the SC is one of those deft strokes that makes
you go, ``Hey, why didn't I think of that?'' The third-door setup
on the Saturn is akin to the rear doors on those stretch-cab
pickups, rear-hinged and opening backwards, to allow access to the
back seat. Not quite a real back door, but a reasonable facsimile.
</P>
<P>
   Putting it behind the driver's door also was smart. Even though
it doesn't open at the curb for passenger entry, the third door and
its backward opening configuration make it convenient for the
driver to gain access to the rear seat, even more so than a normal
four-door.
</P>
<P>
   The driver's door has to be opened before the third door can
open, but once it is, there is no pillar in the center to get in
the way.
</P>
<P>
   A major complaint: There is no handle or any other provision for
the passenger in the rear seat to open the door. That is a
significant omission, which can result in pinched fingers and hard
feelings.
</P>
<P>
   Rear-hinged doors of any kind were once referred to as ``suicide
doors'' because in the event of crash, they were likely to pop open
and the nearest occupant would fly through the opening. But that
was before the widespread use of seat belts. Now that anybody with
half a brain is wearing a seat belt, it's kind of a moot point.
</P>
<P>
   The third door is more a cosmetic consideration than anything
else, allowing a driver to zip around in a stylish, sporty coupe
without anyone knowing that it's also practical. It's hard to spot
the third door because it's so blended in with the body line, the
only clue being the rear seam where it opens.
</P>
<P>
   But here's a question: Why just three doors? Why not four? Why
not have this interesting clamshell setup on both sides of the car,
making it a four-door coupe? Of course, that doesn't sound nearly
as interesting or quirky as a three-door coupe.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the third door, the Saturn is a nice driving little
car that's surprisingly roomy behind the wheel. The test car was
the less-expensive SC1, with its 100-horsepower four-cylinder
engine, rather than the SC2, with slightly more powerful
dual-overhead-cam four, which creates 124 horsepower.
</P>
<P>
   The lesser engine, a single-overhead-cam four, was originally a
noisy, underpowered critter that I always recommended against. But
Saturn has done an admirable job of civilizing its base engine, and
I found the SC1 to be powerful enough and fun to drive. Gas mileage
is excellent.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the fun-to-drive quotient was a stick-shift
transmission. Saturn started out with one of the nicest shifting
manuals in the business, and it still rates as one of the best. I'm
unsure how the SC1 would perform with an automatic, but I'd wager
on the side of anemic.
</P>
<P>
   Ride and handling are decent, and the steering is quick enough
and responsive enough to give the SC a good, sporty feel.
</P>
<P>
   The coupe styling is sharp and edgy, even aggressive-looking in
a small-car sort of way. The third door is essentially invisible,
unless you're looking for it.
</P>
<P>
   The price is right for this little coupe, even with the fair
load of optional equipment on the test car. One of those options
was antilock brakes, which certainly should be standard. GM was a
pioneer in offering standard antilock on moderately priced cars,
and Saturn should be no different.
</P>
<P>
   Saturn has suffered during recent years from not moving forward
and creating a new generation of cars to supplement its original
team. The LS should rectify that, giving Saturn owners something to
move up to and attracting a new group of people who prefer a
midsize car.
</P>
<P>
   The three-door coupe is also a revolutionary move.
</P>
<P>
   So does the inclusion of the third door make the SC1 a practical
family car? Not really, since the back seat is still limited in
both headroom and legroom. It is still a coupe, after all. &QL; 
Bob Golfen can be reached at (602) 444-8106 or at
bob.golfen &LR; pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
