<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-HEROES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARAMEDIC, TEENS IN SHOOTING RAMPAGE LAUDED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY TROY ANDERSON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURBANK -- Four teen-age camp counselors from the North Valley
Jewish Community Center and a Los Angeles Fire Department paramedic
were honored at Temple Beth Emet Reform of Burbank for helping the
center's children during the Aug. 10 shooting rampage at the
center's day camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see sitting before you the epitome of good deeds that day
and every day,'' said Rabbi Mark Sobel on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   With about 75 people attending the evening service, Sobel and
others paid tribute to the counselors, Bryan Benmaor, 18; Jennifer
Benmaor, 23; Michelle Markiz, 18; and Gabriel Schkliar, 18; and to
Fire Department Station 87 Paramedic Todd Carb.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great, I didn't expect this,'' said Schkliar. He reported
that the children injured in the shooting are doing fine. The boy
who was shot in the foot is a ``speed demon on his crutches now,''
he said. ``They all have smiles on their faces.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Sen. Adam Schiff, D-Pasadena, presented the five with
Senate Certificates of Recognition, Sobel gave Carb a silver-plated
Torah. The paramedic carried it through the congregation as people
touched it for a blessing with their prayer books and shawls.
</P>
<P>
   Carb was the first firefighter to reach Benjamin Kadish, the
5-year-old boy most seriously injured in the shooting attack
allegedly committed by white supremacist Buford O'Neal Furrow Jr.
Carb, who is stationed two miles from the center, is credited with
helping save the boy's life.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a tradition in Judaism,'' Sobel said. ``If you save a
life, you save the world. Judaism has a prayer for thanking God for
saving one from danger. We wanted to honor them for being
custodians of the children.''
</P>
<P>
   Furrow is facing federal and state charges naming him as the
gunman who shot and injured the children and staff members at the
Granada Hills center camp and in the shooting death of a mail
carrier afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Bryan Benmaor and Schkliar were on opposite sides of the
building with about 95 children when the shots were first fired,
Sobel said.
</P>
<P>
   When they heard the shots, they hurried the children onto two
buses and the driver drove them to safety at a Northridge Park,
Sobel said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bus driver got off and said, `Load the buses,' and we got
all the little kids on the buses and then we left,'' Schkliar said.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, Bryan Benmaor and Schkliar sang songs with the
children to keep their minds off what had happened.
</P>
<P>
   Markiz was the counselor who had a group of children at the
Simon Wiesenthal Center's Museum of Tolerance on a field trip that
day.
</P>
<P>
   ``She kept calm and order at the museum after learning what
happened,'' Sobel said.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Benmoar was inside the building with some children and
kept them out of danger, Sobel said.
</P>
<P>
   Sobel said they decided to honor the teen-agers and Carb as a
way to ``move away from the violence and talk about saving lives.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to pray with them and help them heal,'' Sobel said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
