<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMMIGRATION-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ILLEGALS ACCUSE FIRM OF BIAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM WALSH  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For months, the women say, they endured sexual harassment, an
endless torrent of racial slurs, a subminimum wage in sweatshop
conditions, even a demeaning mandatory strip-search.
</P>
<P>
   But because they were illegal immigrants from Mexico and
Guatemala, they never complained about the owners of a Gilbert
print-painting factory, fearing they would be deported.
</P>
<P>
   Now, they're fighting back. The women are preparing a lawsuit
against the owners of Quality Art Manufacturing, alleging not only
sexual and verbal abuse, but also seeking minimum wages and
overtime, said Stephen Montoya, their attorney.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just sheer exploitation. I fear this is not the only
employer in the Valley and state that is engaging in this type of
conduct,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   John Burns, one of the company's owners, acknowledged hiring
illegal workers but said he is attempting to remedy the problem. He
denied abusing any workers.
</P>
<P>
   The women have filed complaints with the federal Equal
Opportunity Employment Commission.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, commission investigators acted on their complaints,
serving the lithography company with a notice of investigation
involving racial and sexual discrimination, along with subpoenas
for personnel records.
</P>
<P>
   Sue Grace, an EEOC spokeswoman, said hefty fines can be leveled
against companies with discriminatory practices. She said the
agency's investigations usually take about six months. Negotiated
settlements usually are sought, but firms are prosecuted in U.S.
District Court, if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   The women sought legal help after the firing of a sympathetic
supervisor triggered a revolt reminiscent of coal miners a century
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody got angry,'' said Beatrice Colores, 34, a former
supervisor for Quality Art. ``I kept getting myself in trouble
defending them.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got fired, they all walked out. They were standing
behind me. They said they weren't going to take it anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Owner John Burns said Colores was fired for lying and
threatening a fellow employee.
</P>
<P>
   Company attorneys eventually will prove the discrimination
charges are without merit, Burns said.
</P>
<P>
   During the Aug. 5 uprising, the women resigned en masse.
</P>
<P>
   Montoya said he will file a civil lawsuit against Quality Art on
behalf of the former employees, seeking a substantial settlement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose of this case is to stop this type of behavior and
to let employers know this is not a profitable way of doing
business,'' Montoya said.
</P>
<P>
   When she was hired in May, Colores said she was told the company
knew the workers were illegal but hired them anyway. The hours were
6 a.m to 9:30 p.m., with a half-hour for lunch and two 10-minute
breaks. Hours increased to 7 a.m. to 11:30 p.m. during busy
periods.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was told that this was a sweatshop, and it was going to be
run as a sweatshop,'' Colores said.
</P>
<P>
   But Jim Burns, John Burns' brother and an owner of Quality Art,
said his records will prove the workers were paid at least minimum
wage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the people making these accusations were making $6 and
$7 an hour,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Burns said his shop is not a hostile or abusive workplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is going to have their own beliefs of what is
acceptable or unacceptable,'' he said. ``I don't think there is
anything here but trying to be fair.''
</P>
<P>
   John Burns said he is ``very personally offended'' by the
discrimination charges. He said he held Christmas parties for the
workers at his home and gave them cash advances on numerous
occasions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not a single prejudicial word has ever come out of my mouth,''
he added.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews and affidavits, the former workers tell a
different story.
</P>
<P>
   In the affidavits, the women tell of being called ``stupid
Mexicans'' and ``wetbacks'' repeatedly by Jim and John Burns.
</P>
<P>
   Maria Josephina Gonzalez Solis said in her affidavit that the
racially derogatory statements included ``that we didn't have
rights . . . and that we are in America and not Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   When the women demanded overtime on Memorial Day, Colores said,
the owners ``told them . . . they did not know what Memorial Day
meant, that this was an American holiday, not a stupid Mexican
holiday.''
</P>
<P>
   Solis said she was humiliated by the April 12 strip-search,
performed by supervisors of the same gender when $1,000 was
reported missing.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it was like they were making fun of me,'' Solis said
through an interpreter. ``I felt bad. Why are they doing this to
us?''
</P>
<P>
   Maria Elena Osorio Rodriguez, who is from Guatemala, described
sexual harassment in her affidavit.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day in June 1999, when all the workers were in line ready
to punch out from work, John passed and touched my buttocks,'' she
said. ``Touching the female workers on the buttocks was a daily
occurrence.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the most chilling accusations are those of Maria De La Luz
Gonzalez, 22, of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   John Burns ``would always pass me on purpose and touch my
butt,'' she said through a translator.
</P>
<P>
   One day, she was showing another employee how to do a job and
accidentally ripped a lithograph.
</P>
<P>
   ``John Burns hit me across the face because he did not like the
work I was doing,'' she said in her affidavit.
</P>
<P>
   A Spanish-speaking supervisor told Gonzalez that the slap was
``just a joke,'' she said, an accusation she didn't buy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very angry. I wanted to cry, but I held it back,''
Gonzalez said.
</P>
<P>
   John Burns said he was flabbergasted by her accusations, adding
that he is happily married to a beautiful woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knows my character,'' he said. ``I would never, ever
touch a woman's butt.''
</P>
<P>
   Colores was born in Douglas and raised in Chandler Heights,
where she toiled as a migrant worker during summers and on
weekends. Despite her lowly position, Colores said she was never
ridiculed with racial slurs and never felt the sting of racism
until she worked for Quality Art.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was always angry,'' she said. ``I would tell the employees
that they don't have to put up with this.'' &QL; 
Jim Walsh can be reached at (602) 444-7984 or at
jim.walsh(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
