<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 01:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4969 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-RANGERS-REDSOX-BOS &LR;      08-21 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RANGERS-RED </SLUG>
 SOX-BOS  
 Rangers thwart Red Sox  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ In hindsight, Mark Portugal's impetuous
decision to retire, which he rescinded a few days later, has been
one of the milder misadventures to befall Red Sox starters this
season. But that was of little consolation to him Friday night,
when he pitched just well enough to lose to the Texas Rangers, 4-3,
before 35,036 in The Ballpark at Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny,'' said Portugal, who spotted the Rangers two runs
in the second and another pair in the third, then combined with
Rich Garces to shut out the Rangers on three hits over the last
five innings. ``But someone said I haven't been getting any love,
so to speak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody's got to go loveless, and I guess it's me.''
</P>
<P>
   Portugal might have felt less forlorn if the Sox had been able
to cash in on either of their last two scoring chances. But John
Valentin, compounding the 3-for-28 slump he's in, apparently missed
a hit-and-run sign in the seventh, leaving Jose Offerman to be
gunned down by All-Star catcher Ivan Rodriguez. Then, with two out
in the ninth, pinch hitter Reggie Jefferson singled and Trot Nixon,
who drove in two runs with sacrifice flies, walked, but Offerman
flied out on John Wetteland's next pitch, giving the Rangers'
closer his 34th save.
</P>
<P>
   ``The team tried to come back,'' said Portugal, whose record
dropped to 7-11, ``but we came up short.''
</P>
<P>
   Think of all that has happened to the five pitchers who opened
the season in the rotation. Pedro Martinez, of course, touched off
a firestorm this past week when the manager gave him a tardy slip
instead of a start. Bret Saberhagen has been on the disabled list
twice, once after stepping on broken glass at a team party he was
hosting, and his shoulder seems to be hanging by a thread. Tim
Wakefield went to the bullpen to take the place of injured closer
Tom Gordon; what he thought would be temporary service became a
14-week tour of duty.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Rapp was banished to the bullpen, was restored to the
rotation, and now is pitching in between vigils at the bedside of
his ailing wife, Rebecca, who is dealing with a difficult
pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, Portugal has muddled along, rarely stringing
together good games, but at least showing up when called upon, his
23 starts improbably the most on the team. The 36-year-old
righthander was ready to jump ship in June to become a stay-at-home
dad, but here it is nearing the end of August, and he's still
pitching games that count.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather lead this team in innings than starts,'' he said.
``All that means is I haven't been hurt. I've been a pretty
fortunate man all my life. They say it all evens out. I guess I'll
just have to wait for it to change direction.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers scored twice in the second inning on Rafael
Palmeiro's 34th home run, then twice more in the third inning on
four singles, the last three with two out, including Palmeiro's RBI
hit.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, fresh from taking three out of four games from the
AL Central-leading Indians and owners of the best record in the
league since the All-Star break (24-11), appeared poised to apply
even more heat on the sweating Portugal, already coping with
91-degree temperatures at game time (the Sox caught a break; after
23 straight days of 100-degree readings, Fridat topped out at only
98).
</P>
<P>
   A fine time to quit? Not for Portugal, who allowed just two hits
over the next three innings, giving the Sox time to start
counterpunching against Esteban Loaiza, the Mexican-born
righthander who has become the Rangers' most reliable starter since
the All-Star break, spinning off five straight wins.
</P>
<P>
   DH Butch Huskey, who continues to make a strong case for regular
playing time, led off the fifth with his 19th home run, fourth in
46 at-bats with the Sox. Jason Varitek then drew a walk, Darren
Lewis singled him to third, and Trot Nixon's sacrifice fly brought
him home to make it 4-2.
</P>
<P>
   Loiaza wasn't out of trouble yet. He walked Offerman, and after
Valentin looked at a third strike, Nomar Garciaparra walked to load
the bases. But Mike Stanley, who had struck out his first two
at-bats, flied deep to the track to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis's triple off Juan Gonzalez's glove to open the seventh
finished Loiaza. Nixon's second sacrifice fly of the night, this
one off Mike Munoz, made it 4-3. Offerman walked, leading Rangers
manager Johnny Oates to summon another reliever, Tim Crabtree.
Offerman, who last season stole 45 bases, then set out for second
while Valentin looked at Crabtree's pitch. Offerman still nearly
made it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't swing,'' Williams said of Valentin, ``so I guess he
missed the sign.''
</P>
<P>
   Valentin then popped out, ending the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Portugal, having thrown 95 pitches, parted after the sixth,
giving way to Garces, who loaded the bases on a single and two
walks, but then induced Palmeiro to pop out to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Garces got the equivalent of a Billy Blanks tae-bo workout in
the eighth, when he scrambled to field Todd Zeile's roller along
the first-base line and tagged Zeile out, then had to hustle over
to cover first on Lee Stevens' bouncer to first. Jimy Williams,
figuring his pitcher needed a little breather, came out for a visit
while Garces was pitching to Royce Clayton, who ended up looking at
a third strike from El Guapo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
