<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG IS ON JOHNSON PLAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Los Angeles Dodgers manager Davey Johnson glossed
over Eric Young' return from the disabled list by saying the second
baseman would get his starting job back _ though it would come with
a few more rests to keep the 32-year-old spry.
</P>
<P>
   However, more than a week after Young's return it's clear the
second base position has evolved into exactly what Johnson
envisioned a month ago _ a platoon.
</P>
<P>
   Young's been back for seven games, and after sitting through
Friday's 8-5 win in 10 innings against Philadelphia, he's started
just four of them.
</P>
<P>
   And it doesn't have much to do with Young not playing well. He's
6 for 16 with four walks, three stolen bases and three runs scored.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm on his plan,'' Young said of Johnson. ``Whatever he
wants.''
</P>
<P>
   During the season the Dodgers have become disenchanted with
Young because, as a leadoff hitter, they think he hits too many
balls in the air. Defensively, the team believes he lacks range.
</P>
<P>
   The situation came to a head last month in Arizona when Johnson
said he was making a switch at second base to give Young time to
heal his bumps and bruises. Young asked to go on the disabled list
but the Dodgers didn't want to place him there because he couldn't
be traded.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, three days before the July 31 non-waiver trading
deadline, the Dodgers placed Young on the disabled list with a
sprained ankle.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberthal signs: The Phillies signed catcher Mike Lieberthal, a
Westlake High graduate, to a three-year, $19 million contract
extension before the game. There's also a club option for the 2003
season at $7.25 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main reason I want to stay here is the players we have
here, and the coaching staff and the general manager,'' said
Lieberthal, a first-round pick of the Phillies in 1990. ``We have a
chance to win here the next few years. We've had some injuries here
lately, but there are a lot of parts in place. No longer are we a
handful of players away from winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberthal, 27, was a career .252 hitter in 310 games spanning
five seasons before breaking out this year. He was named to the NL
all-star squad this summer and entered the Dodgers' series hitting
.310 with 25 homers and 78 RBI. He also leads NL catchers with a
.999 fielding percentage. He's committed one error this season and
hasn't made one in 84 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike's a prime example of what we've been trying to do here,''
Phillies general manager Ed Wade said. ``We made a commitment a
couple of years ago to build around our young nucleus. ...I think
this is a clear signal that we're going to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberthal makes $2.2 million this season. He was given a $1
million signing bonus and will be paid $4.5 million next year, $6
million in 2001 and $7 million in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Extra bases: Dodgers right-hander Robinson Checo (groin) threw
66 pitches in a rehab assignment for Single-A San Bernardino on
Thursday. He allowed six runs on four hits in three innings against
Rancho Cucamonga.... Former Dodgers lefty Carlos Perez, now the
highest-paid pitcher in the minors, allowed six runs (four earned)
in a loss Thursday for Triple-A Albuquerque against Tucson. Perez
allowed 11 hits, walked two, struck out one and allowed a homer.
Johnson said Perez needs one or two more starts before returning to
the Dodgers, making him a prime Sept. 1 call-up.... Former Dodgers
right-hander Hideo Nomo is slated to start the series opener for
Milwaukee against the Dodgers on Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
