r a BC-STOLEN-PAINTING-LADN     08-21 0561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STOLEN-PAINTING-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX_UCLA COUNSELOR CONVICTED IN THEFT OF PAINTING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DOUGLAS HABERMAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- A federal jury on Friday convicted former UCLA
counseling director Jane Crawford, 50, on charges related to the
theft from the university of a 19th-century painting valued at
$250,000.
</P>
<P>
   The jury found the Van Nuys woman guilty on four felony charges
_ two counts of wire fraud relating to the faxing of sales
documents and two counts of interstate transportation of property
obtained through fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Crawford, who remains free without bail until her Nov. 8
sentencing, faces time in a federal prison, Assistant U.S. Attorney
Ranee Katzenstein said. But she couldn't say how long the sentence
is likely to be. The statutory maximum is 30 years, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a significant case,'' Katzenstein said, ``in that it has
a significant message to send: You don't take property from your
employer just because nobody will notice.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the University of California, Los Angeles, acquired the
painting in 1928 but ``there happened not to be a precise inventory
record of this painting.''
</P>
<P>
   Crawford knew that and took advantage of it, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the jury did its job,'' Katzenstein said. ``I believe
the evidence was overwhelming.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorney Lawrence Strauss said his client is probably
facing 18 months in prison. He plans to appeal to the 9th District
U.S. Court of Appeals, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed in the verdict,'' he said. There was a lack
of evidence to show Crawford stole the painting from the
university, Strauss said, and a lack of evidence UCLA even owns the
painting.
</P>
<P>
   He said Crawford would not be available for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The painting at the center of the case is a 19th-century piece
by Arthur Wesley Dow called ``Frost Flowers, Ipswitch 1889.'' Dow
was an artist and influential art educator who died in 1922. His
widow donated the painting to UCLA in 1928, Katzenstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Crawford claimed a UCLA official offered her the painting after
it had hung in his house for 10 years. She hung it in her office
then took it home in 1993, eventually storing it at her father's
house.
</P>
<P>
   When her father fell ill, now-deceased attorney Ken Weaver was
handling the liquidation of his assets and said he could sell it
for cash, Strauss said.
</P>
<P>
   Weaver sold it in 1994 to a New York gallery for $200,000, which
sold it shortly thereafter for $300,000, Katzenstein said.
</P>
<P>
   Katzenstein alleged Jane Crawford sold the painting through
Weaver to avoid having her name tied to the sale.
</P>
<P>
   Weaver and Crawford had a falling out, and Weaver told the Los
Angeles Police Department's art theft squad that the painting was
stolen from UCLA. The FBI later joined in the investigation and the
painting is now in the custody of the FBI's Los Angeles office,
Katzenstein said.
</P>
<P>
   A federal civil suit over ownership of the painting is now
making its way through the courts, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, UCLA has very specific and detailed inventory procedures
for all noncash gifts and regularly audits its inventories, said
Harlan Lebo, director of communications for the College of Letters
and Science. ``The message is: UCLA is an extremely safe place to
give a noncash gift,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-99 0157EDT &QL; 
