<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-IRWINDALE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILD WINSTON WEST RETURNS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH LAIR  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRWINDALE, Calif. _ When NASCAR Winston West cars made their
initial pit stops at Irwindale Speedway on June 19, NASCAR
officials went crazy.
</P>
<P>
   Cars entering pit road were credited with an extra lap upon
exiting because they re-entered before the pace car passed. Cars
entering a lap down emerged among the top 5. It was chaos as
officials and lap-counters took nearly 20 minutes to sort out the
correct order.
</P>
<P>
   The track's scoreboard resembled a bingo board, car numbers
bouncing up and down, back and forth. On the track, cars kept
swapping orders at officials' whims.
</P>
<P>
   Originally, NASCAR officials blamed the track's transponders for
the scoring error.
</P>
<P>
   ``The transponders worked fine,'' track competition director
Jeff Schrader recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, (officials) figured out what was happening early
on,'' Winston West spokesman Kevin Green said.
</P>
<P>
   So when cars exit the pits for tonight's $105,644 Snap-On Tools
250, which benefits the City of Hope, a NASCAR official will make
certain the pace car has passed, a practice employed at the end of
the first Irwindale race.
</P>
<P>
   ``It won't happen again,'' Green said of pit problems.
</P>
<P>
   However, the racing is likely to be just as wacky as last time.
In the Irwindale debut there were 26 lead changes among nine
drivers, a series record for a half-mile track. Steve Portegna
pulled off the victory with a last-lap pass to win by half a car
length.
</P>
<P>
   A sixth-place finish in Portland last week put Saugus' Sean
Woodside in the season points lead, 31 ahead of Mike Chase. Only
217 points separate first from 10th place after nine of 14 events.
</P>
<P>
   Portegna averaged 69.93 mph for the 125-lap race last time here.
Butch Gilliland of Chino Hills was on the pole, going 100.722 mph
in front of 6,247, the largest Irwindale crowd other than the 6,500
opening-night show.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, fans will be able to watch the final practice session _
gates open at 2 p.m. with practice starting at 2:30 p.m. Qualifying
is at 5 p.m. and an autograph session with all drivers follows at
6. Racing begins at 7 with the Mechanix Wear Speed Truck Challenge
and the American Cities Racing League is also scheduled to compete.
</P>
<P>
   Also signing autographs will be Craftsman Truck driver Rick
Carelli, who suffered a near career-ending head injury at Memphis
earlier this summer. The Denver resident will be making his first
public appearance since the accident, doing so on behalf of High
Hopes, a foundation which specializes in the rehabilitation of
head-injury victims.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-99 0157EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
