<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 02:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4993 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BBA-MARINERS-NOTEBOOK     08-21 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-NOTEBOOK-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUNTER LOOKS BACK FOR HELP ON SWING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Brian Hunter was missing pitches right down the middle
of the plate. They were pitches he used to hit _ the kind most
major leaguers devour _ but Hunter was helpless. By the end of the
Mariners' road trip, the left fielder had just three hits over his
previous 41 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   So Hunter and his family did some research. He called his mother
in Vancouver, Wash., and asked her to find some videotapes from his
minor league days. His sister delivered them to Seattle when Hunter
returned from the road. And from his personal collection, Hunter
found five baseball cards that depicted him batting as a Houston
Astros rookie in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   To Hunter, it was hard evidence that he had abandoned his
natural hitting technique.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've hit .250 the last couple of years, and that's not me,''
said Hunter, who was batting .244 before Friday night's game.
``I've been playing since I was 5 years old, and ever since I got
to the big leagues I've tried to do something different. So I sat
back and said, well, if I'm going to get out as many times as I've
been getting out, I'm at least going to do it the way I got here. I
know I can help contribute more on offense than I've been doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Mariners hitting coach Jesse Barfield said he'd been urging
Hunter to return to his roots for a month. When Hunter presented
Barfield with the old baseball cards, the coach had flashbacks.
</P>
<P>
   The photos on the cards were taken from a first-base angle _
near where Barfield stood as Houston's first-base coach that year.
He recognized the exagerrated knee kick and, especially, Hunter's
hands, which were near his ear and not near the back of his head,
where they've been much of this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything's in a better position,'' Barfield said, examining
the cards. ``You can't have the bat wrapped around your head unless
you're Juan Gonzalez or Julio Franco. Even Edgar (Martinez) doesn't
wrap the bat around his head. It's up high, but it's not wrapped.
Nobody can hit from that wrapped position _ that's too long a
distance to travel.''
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday in batting practice, Hunter displayed a pronounced
up-down hitch with his hands, which were nowhere near the back of
his head. Teammates noticed, and Barfield showed the cards to
others as Hunter hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the best batting practice I've ever taken since I've
been in the big leagues,'' Hunter said.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter developed bad habits, he said, because the Astros and
Detroit Tigers wanted him to slap the ball as traditional leadoff
men do. His speed made that approach work, to some extent, because
he could leg out ground-ball hits. But his natural technique,
Hunter said, will produce more line drives and balls hit into the
gaps.
</P>
<P>
   Though he's an aggressive hitter who rarely walks, Hunter said
he also should walk more often. Up to now, he said, he has thought
so much about mechanics that he couldn't concentrate on pitchers'
release points, often picking up pitches just a few feet from the
plate. Now, he thinks he can be more selective.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was fighting my brain trying to do it the way I wasn't used
to doing it, and hitting is so mental,'' Hunter said. ``(My way)
looks crazy, and it may be one of the worst swings in baseball, at
the start. But it's second nature to me. It may not happen right
away, but in the long run, it's going to be better.''
</P>
<P>
   HENRY NEARING RETURN: Left-hander Butch Henry threw 41 pitches
of batting practice yesterday, using all his pitches and throwing
at full exertion. It was the most he's thrown since having surgery
to repair a torn labrum in May, and pitching coach Stan Williams
told trainer Rick Griffin that Henry passed the test.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stan said, after what he saw today, he thought (Henry) was
very close to being ready to pitch,'' Griffin said. ``Tomorrow, if
he feels good _ and I don't think there will be any problems _ he
should be ready to start doing some rehab work.''
</P>
<P>
   The return of Henry would be especially welcome to the Mariners,
whose rotation includes three rookies who have never pitched deep
into September. Manager Lou Piniella already has been using off
days to give those starters _ Freddy Garcia, John Halama and Gil
Meche _ extra rest.
</P>
<P>
   AROUND THE HORN: Mariners hitters were greeted by a new
center-field backdrop when they returned home yesterday. The team
used a bolder green this time, with a different paint base designed
to reduce glare during day games. ... Shortstop Alex Rodriguez
entered Friday night's game with 87 runs batted in and 88 runs
scored in 87 games played. The last player to average a run and an
RBI per game was Joe DiMaggio in 1937. ... According to a
preliminary American League schedule, the Mariners will be the
visiting team when the Detroit Tigers open Comerica Park next April
11. ... Former M's second baseman Harold Reynolds took part in
pregame drills with the team yesterday. Reynolds, an ESPN analyst,
was in Oregon on Thursday with Ken Griffey Jr., who had a building
named after him on the Nike campus. A Nike representative said only
nine or 10 athletes have been so honored. ... The Mariners played a
highlight video and set off fireworks before the game to
congratulate Piniella on his 1,000th win as a manager. Others
trying to offer congratulations had no luck. ``My phone's been out
of order since I've been here,'' Piniella said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
