<HEADLINE>
MURDER SUSPECT WINS DELAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY LISA VAN PROYEN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- A 24-year-old parolee accused of murdering a
Woodland Hills telemarketer in February appeared in court as police
awaited DNA tests that might tie two other men to the crime.
</P>
<P>
   Kirell Francis Taylor, also known as Kirell Francis Bettis and
Taylorbettis, asked to delay arraignment until Aug. 27 so he could
meet with his public defender. The request was granted.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor is charged with robbing, abducting and murdering
Christopher Rawlings, a 30-year-old former football star at Crespi
High School in Encino who was under federal investigation for his
telemarketing business.
</P>
<P>
   Because the killing was committed during a robbery, Taylor could
face the death penalty if convicted. Taylor also is charged with
robbery, carjacking, burglary and kidnapping. He is being held
without bail.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators linked Taylor to the killing through eyewitnesses,
DNA evidence and a gold bracelet and gold earring that was found at
Taylor's home in Pacoima but belong to Rawlings' wife, detectives
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a very strong case,'' said Los Angeles County Deputy
District Attorney Shellie Samuels.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives said Taylor and two accomplices singled out Rawlings
because of his white Bentley, followed him home, beat him and
stuffed him in the trunk of his car. After his wife called 911, the
robbers led officers on a wild chase that ended when the Bentley
crashed, critically injuring Rawlings.
</P>
<P>
   Two others remain at large.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, detectives said they are waiting for DNA results on
two of Taylor's ``close associates,'' including an Inglewood man
under arrest on suspicion of robbing a used-car sales lot March 12
in Hawthorne.
</P>
<P>
   The other, a Pacoima man, has been jailed for a week on a parole
violation for his alleged involvement in the same robbery.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor's wallet, identification and boots were found in the car
used in that Hawthorne robbery, said Los Angeles police Detective
Rick Swanston of the West Valley Division.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Taylor worked with three or four ``very organized''
robbers who have hit throughout Southern California, including a
home-invasion robbery in Encino in December.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wear ski masks and gloves and carry walkie-talkies and
police scanners,'' Swanston said.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said Rawlings, a co-owner of a Woodland Hills
clothing store, appears to be a ``random'' victim of a robbery,
rather than a victim of a business deal gone awry.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was driving an expensive car, wearing an expensive watch
and carrying a lot of cash,'' Samuels said. ``He was sort of a
robbery victim waiting to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors also do not believe Rawlings knew Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's absolutely no reason to believe they knew each other
at all,'' said Los Angeles County Deputy District Attorney Larry
Diamond, who filed the case. ``It seems they just picked him out
that night.''
</P>
<P>
   However, detectives said Rawlings knew many people _ any of whom
could have tipped off Taylor that he kept cash and flashy jewelry
at his home.
</P>
<P>
   The six months that led up to Taylor's arrest involved complex
detective work, Swanston said. Police received about 100 tips,
including that the killer is named ``Kirell.''
</P>
<P>
   Detectives searched records for weeks until they found a Kirell
Taylor was an ex-con on parole for robbery, said Detective Andy
Purdy. If the name had not been so unusual, the crime may have
never been solved, Swanston said.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives took a blood sample from Taylor and matched it to
blood from the Bentley, Swanston said.
</P>
<P>
   Rawlings' family expressed relief after Taylor's arrest, a
detective said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are very, very happy,'' Purdy said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
