<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 02:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4997 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BBO-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     08-21 1162
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GET OUT YOUR HISTORY BOOKS, GRANDMA _ IT'S TIME TO VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Lou Gehrig was a lock, then came the tough part. What
other first baseman would I vote for on the Major League Baseball
All Century Team?
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Murray, Jimmie Foxx, Harmon Killebrew or Mark McGwire?
</P>
<P>
   Having grown up a Mets fan, the fact that Keith Hernandez was
not one of the choices threw me for a small loop. But I soon got
over it.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, my instincts were to pick Murray along with
Gehrig, mostly because Murray would satisfy my conscience that not
everything about baseball, especially first base, is about the home
run.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the Zen and all the nuances that make baseball the
perfect game, it sure seems as if baseball has transmuted into the
glorification of the home run. And while no other position is as
stockpiled with sluggers as first base, to my way of thinking, at
least Gehrig (two-time Triple Crown winner) and Murray (504 homers
and 3,255 hits) had more than just pure power.
</P>
<P>
   The initial (and, in the end, ludicrous) argument against
McGwire was that despite the captivating way in which he conducted
his 1998 assault on Roger Maris' home run record, there isn't any
other All Century ballot entry worthy of selection based solely on
a single-season record.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, if baseball was just about being Bluto and smashing
balls to the stratosphere, why isn't Boog Powell on the ballot?
</P>
<P>
   Finally, though, after many attempts at rationalizing the
switch-hitting, versatile Murray, whose reputation of surliness has
some merit, it was impossible to pick against McGwire, who went
from 400 homers in '98 to the 500 plateau in '99 _ a feat
remarkable no matter what supplements he is or is not taking.
</P>
<P>
   One position down. Eight to go. See how easy it is to get sucked
in?
</P>
<P>
   We are obsessed with lists. File, rank, serial number and how
great thou art.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, our sporting society's fondness for lists of the
all-time greatest anything is out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't long ago that my brother, the walking encyclopedia of
sports, started going apoplectic every time a new issue of Sports
Illustrated hit the doorstep.
</P>
<P>
   The Best this. The Greatest that. Linebackers to die for.
Cricket players to look out for. Twenty hockey guys you'd want on
your power play.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine finally got so desperate for a new category, it
actually had a piece about the top five Pac-10 point guards.
</P>
<P>
   Snooze, you loose. And I started snoozing.
</P>
<P>
   Needless to say, when the official ballot for the Major League
Baseball All Century Team wound up in my mailbox two weeks ago, I
paid no attention. Whatever, I decided.
</P>
<P>
   After seeing the 50 greatest NBA players lined up on the court
during halftime of the 1996 All-Star Game, I figured there was no
way any other league could do better.
</P>
<P>
   Something happened, though. While watching the Mariners on TV,
the camera panned to a group of young girls looking over the All
Century ballot. It was then that announcers Dave Valle and Rick
Rizzs joked that they doubted the ability of those kids to make a
wise selection.
</P>
<P>
   That's when I pulled out my ballot, just to see how tough
picking this All Century team would be.
</P>
<P>
   I found the choosing to be a lot more fun than expected _ if you
consider a night in bed with ``Total Baseball,'' major league
baseball's all-inclusive encyclopedia, fun. Here are the rest of my
picks:
</P>
<P>
   Second base: It, too, was a snap, mostly because Wally Backman
wasn't included. (Any other '86 Mets fans out there?)
</P>
<P>
   Rogers Hornsby and Jackie Robinson. Hornsby got my vote for the
sheer offensive numbers (his .358 career batting average is second
only to Ty Cobb, and three times he hit over .400) and Robinson for
his numbers and for his strength and fortitude in breaking
baseball's race barrier.
</P>
<P>
   Third base did not stump me, either.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Schmidt, despite his strikeouts, was the best-hitting third
baseman and he won eight Gold Gloves, three MVPs, four RBI titles
and eight home run crowns.
</P>
<P>
   Now the tougher part: George Brett (three batting titles in
three decades) or Brooks Robinson (16 consecutive Gold Gloves)?
</P>
<P>
   After some struggle, I took the poised, powerful Robinson,
although his career .267 batting average paled next to Brett's .305
mark.
</P>
<P>
   Now it gets tougher.
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop: Honus Wagner, Cal Ripken Jr. and Ozzie Smith were the
contenders out of the list that includes Ernie Banks, Luis
Aparicio, Luke Appling, Robin Yount and Joe Cronin.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner (.327 average, 3,415 hits, 1,732 RBIs and 722 stolen
bases) is a lock. In Total Baseball, his biographical sketch
includes anecdotes about how Wagner knocked Ty Cobb's teeth loose
in a tag out in the 1909 World Series and how Wagner was so
bow-legged and long-armed, he could tie his shoes without bending
down.
</P>
<P>
   The second pick is where it gets tricky. Smith was the best
defensive shortstop, and the Wizard endeavored to make himself a
more-than-respectable offensive presence.
</P>
<P>
   But how can you avoid picking Ripken, whose iron will made him
baseball's Iron Man? Ripken's career also has spanned Rookie of the
Year, two MVPs and his imprint as the guy who started a new era of
power-hitting shortstops.
</P>
<P>
   Catcher: Yogi Berra is easy. His work behind and at the plate
for the New York Yankees puts him on top of the list.
</P>
<P>
   But what about picking between Johnny Bench, Roy Campanella,
Carlton Fisk and Josh Gibson?
</P>
<P>
   Fisk should be pleased to get a mention and Gibson, the Negro
League star, is woefully unknown.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a catcher that any big league club would like to buy
for $200,000. His name is Gibson. He can do anything,'' said
pitching great Walter Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can hit the ball a mile, catches the ball so easily, it
looks like he's in a rocking chair, throws like a bullet. Bill
Dickey isn't as good a catcher. Too bad this Gibson fella is a
colored fella.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Campy's Dodgers so epically battled Berra's Yanks, we'll
take Campanella.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the outfield. You get to pick nine.
</P>
<P>
   The first three are easy: Babe Ruth, Ted Williams and Hank
Aaron.
</P>
<P>
   Second three are almost as easy: Willie Mays, Joe DiMaggio and
Ty Cobb.
</P>
<P>
   The third three picks are miserably hard, but here goes:
</P>
<P>
   Pete Rose (Charlie Hustle's got the numbers, baby); Ken Griffey
Jr. (Already a Hall of Famer, he's going to break a few records
before his induction ceremony); and Roberto Clemente (his last hit
was his 3,000th and he was the first Latin player elected to the
Hall).
</P>
<P>
   Now, for something Mariner fans know little about _ great
pitching. You get to pick six pitchers and at least one of them
must be a lefty. How 'bout: Walter Johnson, Cy Young, Warren Spahn
(L), Sandy Koufax (L), Nolan Ryan and Tom Seaver ('69 Mets).
</P>
<P>
   Now there's a rotation, Mariner fans.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
