<SLUG> BC-BKL-SPARKS-COMETS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAME GOES ON, AND SPARKS WIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAMELA LEWIS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ There was a strange mix of emotions in the
Forum on Friday night as the Sparks and the Houston Comets played
with heavy hearts in a game Los Angeles needed to win.
</P>
<P>
   With two-time Most Valuable Player Cynthia Cooper sitting out
for Houston, Penny Toler made four late free throws in the final
minute to clinch a 68-64 victory before a season-high crowd of
13,116.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the circumstances, the game seemed almost secondary.
</P>
<P>
   The death of Kim Perrot shook the Houston organization and the
entire WNBA family hard.
</P>
<P>
   Described as the heart, soul and energy of the Comets, the
spirited point guard lost her battle to cancer Thursday. She was
32.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Houston (25-6), which had already clinched the
Western Conference title to earn a first-round bye, discussed
forfeiting the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that was something we could do,'' Houston coach Van
Chancellor said. ``But (Kim's) sister did not think that was
something Kim would want us to do, nor did the family want us to.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks (20-11), who conclude their season at Utah today,
will host the Sacramento Monarchs in a single-elimination game
Tuesday. Houston will play the winner Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Except for Cooper, who was at Perrot's bedside with family
members when her best friend died, the Comets were in Los Angeles
when they found out their teammate was gone.
</P>
<P>
   The news hit Cooper particularly hard. She and the diminutive
guard bonded after Perrot was voted onto the team after a Comets
tryout before the inaugural season. Cooper also lost her mother to
a long bout with cancer on Feb.12, just nine days before Perrot's
diagnosis.
</P>
<P>
   Perrot died six months after being diagnosed with lung cancer
that had spread to her brain. She had surgery to remove tumors in
February. ``She was a personal friend,'' Chancellor said. ``She was
my domino-playing buddy. We were good friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Perrot touched many lives during the time she led the Comets to
two WNBA championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now the team is just thinking about Kim individually in
our own minds,'' said Tammy Jackson, who spoke on behalf the team
before the game. ``If we think too much it will be too hard. We're
using basketball as an outlet.''
</P>
<P>
   As a gesture of compassion, the Sparks gave spiritual bracelets
to each Houston player and embraced them in an emotional display of
support before the game. All the players wore black bands on their
jerseys.
</P>
<P>
   Perrot was in Tijuana, Mexico, receiving alternative treatment
for the cancer before her condition worsened. She returned to
Houston on Saturday and was admitted to the University of Texas
M.D. Anderson Cancer Center last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   At halftime, a video tribute to Perrot was shown and a moment of
silence was observed.
</P>
<P>
   A celebration of Perrot's life will held Monday in Houston. She
will be buried Tuesday in her hometown of Lafayette, La. in a
private service with family and close friends.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
