<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 02:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4999 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-ANGELS-TIGERS-LAD     08-21 0695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-TIGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINLEY LIFTS ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Behind starting pitcher Chuck Finley, the
Anaheim Angels beat the Detroit Tigers 5-1 before 29,910 at Edison
Field on Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Finley, who is 3-0 with a 1.19 ERA in four starts since the
trading deadline, gave up one run and five hits while throwing his
first complete game of the season.
</P>
<P>
   But before the Angels and Tigers _ two last-place teams _ got
together on the field to play a game that meant very little, one
Angels player sat in the clubhouse and pondered his future.
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Ken Hill is on the disabled list and probably won't
pitch again until September. He's eligible to come off the DL Aug.
30.
</P>
<P>
   But Hill, who was placed on the DL Aug. 15 with a strained right
groin and tendinitis in his left knee, says he could pitch today if
asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm ready to pitch, I'm ready to pitch right now,'' Hill said.
``I didn't want to go on the DL. I'm fine.''
</P>
<P>
   So why is he on the disabled list?
</P>
<P>
   The Angels need to take a look at some of their pitching
prospects. Manager Terry Collins said Jarrod Washburn and Ramon
Ortiz _ ``and there may be others'' _ will be in the rotation
through the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Hill, though, believes there might be more to it. Hill will make
a guaranteed $5.6 million next season, and he has a vested option
for 2001.
</P>
<P>
   If Hill makes a combined 55 starts in 1999 and 2000, he is
guaranteed $6 million for 2001. He also could guarantee 2001 by
pitching 190 innings next season, or 385 innings combined in '99
and 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Hill has made 22 starts this season and pitched 1232/3 innings.
The less Hill pitches, the better the Angels' chances of saving $6
million on a pitcher who has a history of elbow trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``They do what they want to do,'' said Hill, who also spent time
on the DL this year with an inflamed elbow. ``I'm not worried about
it. I have plenty of money.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they don't want me here, trade me. I'll go to another team.
It's no big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels probably would love to trade Hill, but it's difficult
to trade a pitcher, with an arthritic elbow, making better than $5
million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Hill, though, can't help but wonder where he fits in.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chuck's probably going to sign here next year,'' Hill said.
``And (Tim) Belcher's going to be here next year. (Steve) Sparks, I
don't know his situation. We don't even know if we're going to have
a GM and a manager. There's so much talk and speculation. We might
even have a new owner. You never know what's going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill is 4-11 this season, but his ERA of 4.80 is better than the
American League average of 4.95. He has pitched well since his
first stint on the DL, but admits his right elbow will never be
what it was before he injured it and had surgery last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's never going to be healthy, they know that,'' Hill said.
``If they find something to cure arthritis, I'll be healthy. Other
than that, it's something I have to deal with.''
</P>
<P>
   Finley, at 36, has no such problems. He has pitched into the
seventh inning in six consecutive starts. The complete game was his
first since April 17, 1998 and was the Angels' fourth of the
season. Omar Olivares, since traded to Oakland, has the other
three.
</P>
<P>
   Finley (8-10) admitted his recent success might have something
to do with getting beyond the trade speculation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the first time I ever went through something like
that,'' he said. ``If it ever happens again, I'll know how to
handle it better. When I got past it, it freed my mind up.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the season is lost for the team, Finley said he
feels he has something to prove.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to pitch well and finish strong,'' he said. ``And
show the organization and my players I'm a lot better pitcher than
what I was showing.''
</P>
<P>
   Finley got support from an offense that made the most of its
seven hits. The Angels had three sacrifice flies, the most they've
had in a game this season. Second baseman Trent Durrington was the
only Angels with more than one hit, going 2 for 3.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-99 0230EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
