<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 02:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5000 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      08-21 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATE BURST OFF M'S OFFENSE NOT ENOUGH TO CATCH CLEVELAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Two weeks ago, with optimism high and a pennant race
in sight, the Mariners faced an elite team in a four-game series at
Safeco Field. The New York Yankees won the opener, 7-4, and swept
the series.
</P>
<P>
   The M's have been recovering ever since. When the equally
menacing Cleveland Indians came to town Friday night, Seattle had
an even record and a second chance.
</P>
<P>
   It could not have been a good omen that Cleveland won the opener
by that same 7-4 score.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to come up to their level of play,'' said shortstop
Alex Rodriguez, who batted as the tying run in the ninth inning and
struck out to end the game. ``They've got great defense, good
offense, good pitching. Everyone has to excel and bring their game
up to that level. Personally, I had opportunities to do damage, and
I didn't get it done. No excuses.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners put runners at first and second with one out
against Indians closer Mike Jackson, a two-time M's castoff.
Jackson struck out Ken Griffey Jr., then got Rodriguez to chase a
slider, sending 44,915 fans home.
</P>
<P>
   The pessimists among them could have left four innings earlier.
The Indians, who share the AL's best record, built a 5-0 lead
through five off starter John Halama.
</P>
<P>
   At the All-Star break, Halama was in the midst of a nine-game
winning streak, which tied a single-season club record, and had a
2.89 earned-run average and just three home runs allowed. In seven
starts since, his ERA is 7.23 and he has surrendered seven homers.
His loss Friday was his third in a row.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't seem to me like he's changing speeds as well as
early in the year,'' said manager Lou Piniella. ``But I'm going to
look at the film.''
</P>
<P>
   Piniella, who looks at film occasionally but not often, said
Halama has not been as sharp his last few outings. Halama had no
plans to study the outing, but said he hasn't changed anything from
early in the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been doing the same things,'' Halama said. ``I'm not
fatigued. I'm just going through a rut right now. It's just one of
those things pitchers go through.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, he hit Manny Ramirez to lead off the second and
gave up a two-run homer to Richie Sexson on the next pitch. Halama,
a control specialist, then loaded the bases on two walks and a
single. He got out of the inning with a grounder, but Roberto
Alomar led off the third with a homer to put Cleveland ahead, 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   Halama was trying to induce a double-play ball from Sexson, but
left his fastball up and over the plate _ dangerous territory for a
pitcher without an overpowering fastball.
</P>
<P>
   In the fifth, Dave Roberts led off with a bunt single, and
Halama _ who has no pickoffs despite a move that one Yankee
recently called the best in the league _ caught him leading off
first. Roberts sped toward second, but Ryan Jackson's wild throw
turned a would-be pick-off into a dire situation: runner on third,
no outs.
</P>
<P>
   A double by Omar Vizquel scored Roberts, and two sacrifices
scored Vizquel to give the Indians a 5-0 lead. But Halama (9-5) had
re-gained his command, and he worked 1-2-3 innings in the sixth and
seventh.
</P>
<P>
   That kept the Mariners close, and they rallied for four runs
when Indians starter Bartolo Colon left in the sixth inning. Colon,
5-1 since the All-Star break, allowed just two singles and a walk,
striking out six, in five innings. But after a one-out walk to
David Bell, Colon was removed because of tightness in his left
knee. Rookie David Riske, a native of Kent, was summoned, and four
consecutive hits brought in the four runs.
</P>
<P>
   A bases-loaded double by Edgar Martinez _ who had three hits and
is batting .403 in August _ scored two. Jay Buhner followed with an
infield single when first baseman Jim Thome stabbed a sharp
grounder in the hole but found Riske nowhere near the bag for the
toss. A Ryan Jackson ground out cut Cleveland's lead to 5-4.
</P>
<P>
   In the seventh, Riske was replaced by veteran Paul Shuey, who
allowed a leadoff single to Russ Davis. Davis made it to second on
a sacrifice by Brian Hunter, but Shuey recovered to strike out
David Bell and get Ken Griffey Jr. to bounce to first, ending the
inning.
</P>
<P>
   Shuey left two on in the eighth, striking out Dan Wilson with
runners at first and second to end the inning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
