 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(th) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, Aug. 22:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-QUAKE (Istanbul, Turkey) _ With victims bemoaning a lack
of government authority to help them recover from Tuesday's
shattering earthquake, the Turkish Army entered the rescue and
cleanup effort Saturday after spending days on the sidelines. By
Stephen Kinzer. (With a map.)
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-FAMILIES (Golcuk, Turkey) _ It was in the early hours of
Saturday morning when members of Aydin family finally took a break
from digging out corpses of their relatives. Golcuk, pulverized by
Turkey's huge earthquake on Tuesday, seemed a scene from hell. Its
buildings are in rubble; most of its residents evacuated _ or dead;
its air increasingly unbreathable from decaying flesh. By Edmund L.
Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-REUNIFY (Berlin) _ The tale of Wally Mueller and
Waltraut Neumann is a normal German story _ one of loss, division
and elusive reconciliation _ a tale of two women tossed this way
and that by the traumas of their city and their country. By Roger
Cohen. (With a map.)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-POLITICS (Moscow) _ If ever there was an example of how
hard it is for Russia's liberal politicians to work together it was
Saturday when Sergei Stepashin's new centerist electoral bloc
collapsed. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   NY-BANK-RUSSIA-MOB _ At the intersection of illicit Russian
money and the Bank of New York is Bruce Rappaport, a Swiss banker
with a shadowy past who has long had an important connection to the
bank.
</P>
<P>
   SIERRA-LEONE (Freetown, Sierra Leone) _ After the rebels had
fled into the surrounding hills, Lamine Jusu Jarka was carried to
the main hospital here one morning last January. A young man named
Mr. Junior, wearing a shirt that declared ``C.O. Cut Hands,'' had
chopped off his arms with an ax. Half a year later, as a fragile
peace agreement has stayed the fighting in one of Africa's cruelest
wars, Jarka is still alive _ a living symbol of the terror of that
dark time. By Norimitsu Onishi. (With a map.)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-ELECTION-PANEL (Mexico City) _ If there is one reason
Mexico expects to break with decades-old tradition and have a clean
and fair presidential election next year, it is that an elections
council will oversee the vote. By Julia Preston.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-NUKE-POLICY (New Delhi, India) _ For the past week, many
of India's political elite have been thinking about that most
chilling of subjects: the hows and whys of building a nuclear
arsenal. The cause for this reflection was a six-page document
titled ``Indian Nuclear Doctrine.'' By Barry Bearak.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA-PHILANTHROPIST _ Dominique Lapierre has ranged over
several continents in his best-selling books on modern history, but
only one place has never let go of him. More than two decades ago,
after the publication of ``Freedom at Midnight,'' the story of
Indian independence, Mr. Lapierre went back to India to try to
share his success with the people who had inspired his work. ``It
was the beginning of an adventure that never stopped,'' he said in
an interview during a recent stopover in New York. He was on his
way home to France with his wife, also named Dominique, after
talking to business executives in Aspen, Colo., about the private
aid projects the couple finance. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   HP-GLASS-CEILING (Palo Alto, Calif.) _ Hewlett-Packard's
elevation of Carly Fiorina to the post of chief executive last
month solidified the company's reputation as a bastion of
egalitarianism in a male-dominated corporate world. With more than
a quarter of Hewlett-Packard's managers women _ including one who
was a main rival of Ms. Fiorina for the top job _ it seemed
incontestable that the glass ceiling that stops the rise of female
executives at so many other companies had been shattered. But what
enlightened soul shattered it? The surprising answer: a middle-aged
white guy who never thought much about women in the workplace _
until he was thrust suddenly into the uncomfortable role of single
parent. By Reed Abelson. (With a photo.)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-VACATION (Edgartown, Mass.) _ A year ago, President
Clinton made a faltering speech about forgiveness and attracted
widespread media attention. Now, the language of forgive and forget
rolls off his tongue in a manner that no longer surprises and,
perhaps more importantly, no longer carries the freighted question
of whether he will be forgiven. Clinton and his wife, Hillary
Rodham Clinton, are back on Martha's Vineyard for their fifth
summer vacation. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   SILICON-VALLEY-TRAFFIC (San Francisco) _ For many professionals
at dot-com companies in Silicon Valley, the boom in the Internet
has resulted in a commuting bust, forcing them to funnel onto
increasingly congested highways that snake in and around the
crowded Bay Area. From San Francisco to San Jose, the expanding
economy has created a traffic jam of unprecedented proportions. By
Laura M. Holson. (With a photo and a map.)
</P>
<P>
   URBAN-ARMY-SCHOOL (Ft. Knox, Ky.) _ The Army has spent millions
to build a 26 acre mock city, full of high-tech simulation borrowed
from amusement parks, for training armored forces in urban combat.
But like a Hollywood set from a movie that was never shot, the site
is unused because the armor school has not decided where it fits
into the curriculum. By Steven A. Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   YEAR-2000-DOOMSAYER _ For months, government officials have
worried that zealous pessimists about the world's preparations for
Year 2000 computer problems could stir panic. Thanks to a prominent
doomsayer named Jim Lord, they have a fresh example of what they
fear. By Barnaby J. Feder.
</P>
<P>
   WORLD-CHESS-MATCH _ The gathering of attention among chess
devotees that accompanies the start of any world championship
match, either at the site of play or at computer terminals around
the world, was under way in earnest Saturday as the title match of
the International Chess Federation went through final preparations
for its opening Sunday evening at Caesar's Palace in Las Vegas. By
Robert Byrne.
</P>
<P>
   YELLOWSTONE-LAND-DEAL (Washington) _ The federal government and
a new age church have completed a deal that protects bison and
geysers in Yellowstone National Park, President Clinton announced
Saturday in his weekly radio address. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (Moving in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-MEDIA-POLITICS _ Texas Gov. George W. Bush's refusal to
give a ``yes'' or ``no'' answer when asked if he had used cocaine
had been old news since his first campaign for governor of Texas in
1994. Then, he rebuffed the question with the words: ``What I did
as a kid? I don't think it's relevant.'' There the question and
answer stood, basically unchanged, as the Governor rose to national
political prominence. But in the last three weeks, the alchemy of
repetition made the old question new news in some news outlets. By
Felicity Barringer.
</P>
<P>
   NM-GOV-DRUGS (Undated) _ The Republican governor of New Mexico,
who has admitted he used cocaine in college, is the highest-ranking
official to call for decriminalizing of drugs. By Michael Janofsky.
(With a photo.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (Moving in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MEDICAID-LEAD-POISON (Washington) _ Federal investigators say
most states are flouting a 1989 law under which all children on
Medicaid are supposed to be tested for lead poisoning. By Robert
Pear.
</P>
<P>
   HMO-DRUG-STUDY (Washington) _ While many Medicare beneficiaries
have prescription drug benefits through health maintenance
organizations, a new study shows that there are wide variations in
those benefits and that some are quite modest. By Robin Toner.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;  (Moving in ``k'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN _ Details to come. By Maureen Dowd.
</P>
<P>
   HERBERT-COLUMN _ Details to come. By Bob Herbert.
