<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990821.0063 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 11:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5027 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-GERMANY-REUNIFY-ART-2     08-21 0976
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-REUNIFY-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE STORY OF A FRIENDSHIP AND OF THE FATE OF BERLIN
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Map is being
sent to NYT graphics clients. Nonsubscribers can make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By ROGER COHEN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ This is a normal German story _ one of loss, division
and elusive reconciliation _ a tale of two women tossed this way
and that by the traumas of their city and their country.
</P>
<P>
   When Wally Mueller and Waltraut Neumann met at the end of World
War II, close to 90 percent of Berlin's 1.5 million apartments had
been damaged by Allied bombing. Aged 18, penniless, they went to
work as ``Truemmerfrauen'' _ two of the thousands of ``rubble
women'' whose job it was to clear up the mess.
</P>
<P>
   Sifting good bricks from bad, working with their bare hands,
paid first with food stamps and only later in cash, they toiled for
several years. When they look today at the hill in Friedrichshain
park, where children sled in winter, what they see is the great
mound of bombed-out masonry that lies underneath.
</P>
<P>
   That is Berlin today _ layer upon hidden layer of damage, of
pain _ an archeological dig of Europe in this century.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hard to believe now that everything was kaput in 1945,''
Mrs. Mueller, now 72, said. ``But it was kaput. Finished. And when
I see the people wandering around the city today, I wonder if they
understand that.''
</P>
<P>
   Among those people, as of Monday, will be Chancellor Gerhard
Schroeder and his government, who arrive at last from Bonn, a town
chosen as the postwar capital because it was, in Konrad Adenauer's
words, ``a city without a past.'' What will confront Schroeder here
is, in essence, Germany's past divisions.
</P>
<P>
   That history is present in the lives of Mrs. Mueller and Mrs.
Neumann, who found themselves on opposite sides of the Berlin wall
when it went up in 1961, just as it is alive in the hearts of many
of this city's 3.5 million people. In Berlin, unlike Bonn, the
difficulty of making Germany whole is palpable.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now see it will take another generation or two to bring
Germany together,'' said Barbel Dieckmann, the mayor of Bonn. ``Our
mistake was to underestimate the thousand differences in mentality
and to talk of flowering fields in the East instead of how
difficult it would be to achieve that.''
</P>
<P>
   The errors of the past will provide scant consolation to
Schroeder, who knows that the East-West acrimony, rooted in high
unemployment, slow economic growth and a cultural divide, is
certain to sap his popularity, already at a low ebb. The
frustrations of the two ``rubble women'' suggest that his
conciliatory task in Berlin will not be easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can still hear that Soviet propaganda coming over the wall _
the so-called voice of truth and reason,'' said Mrs. Neumann, who
was on the Western side. ``When I think of my friend stuck in the
East, subjected to that for all those years, it is a wonder we
still communicate.''
</P>
<P>
   But the communication between the two women is often difficult _
just as German unification, now almost a decade old, has proved
extremely arduous _ despite the strange symmetry to their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Both Mrs. Mueller and Mrs. Neumann were born in 1927, and both
married in 1952. Godparents to each other's children, they have
always felt a bond. But there is symmetry, too, in their scars and
intermittent anger.
</P>
<P>
   The war was hard on Mrs. Neumann. Her only brother, Karl-Heinz
Schmidt, aged 18, was sent to the eastern front in 1941. Within a
day he was dead, his demise announced in a letter saying that he
had fallen ``for Volk and Vaterland''.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember my father throwing the letter on the floor and
saying he had one son and had not raised him to die for Volk and
Vaterland,'' Mrs. Neumann said. ``The next day, another letter
arrived announcing his arrival at the front. He must have been
killed within hours, and the death notice reached us before the
arrival notice.''
</P>
<P>
   The man she would marry, Willi Neumann, was also deeply marked
by the war. He joined the German army in 1942 _ ``I was not a party
member, but I was not against Hitler,'' he said _ and ended the war
in Holland, where he was captured by the Americans as he tried to
flee on a horse-drawn cart.
</P>
<P>
   Several years in Allied prisoner-of-war camps followed, first
under the Americans, then the British, finally the French, who took
Neumann to northern France and put him to work in the mines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those were not nice times,'' he said. ``But then these are not
nice times either.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Neumanns, as for the Muellers and many other older
Germans, a lingering feeling of frustration often surfaces, clearly
rooted in the sense that their wartime suffering was real but that
the scale of Nazi Holocaust crimes has made it almost impossible to
talk about their losses and wounds.
</P>
<P>
   When the Neumanns married, they made one decision they would not
regret. They moved from the east of the city to Wedding, a
working-class district, taking an apartment that, nine years later,
would be just a few hundred yards west of the Berlin wall. Neumann
began to work at the AEG electronics factory.
</P>
<P>
   Before the wall went up, Mrs. Neumann begged her friend Mrs.
Mueller to join her in Wedding. It was becoming steadily more
difficult to move between the Russian and Allied sectors; pay was
far better in the western one. But with most of her family in
Leipzig in the east, Mrs. Mueller was reluctant to move.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, we never imagined there could be a wall between
us,'' Mrs. Mueller said. ``For the year before the wall went up, my
husband was traveling to the west every day to work as a
bricklayer. Then, overnight, he could not go to work, and telephone
contact was cut until 1975.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Her husband, Ronald Mueller, also bore war scars. Sent to the
Russian front to help build an airfield, he was almost recruited by
the SS, but ultimately rejected because he was not tall enough. So
he eventually went to fight in North Africa, where he was captured
by the British.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was held until 1948,'' Mueller said. ``After the war, the
commander of the camp was a British Jew. He kept telling me _
`You're a Nazi, you're a Nazi, you're a Nazi.' Of course, I
understand his anger, but I was not a Nazi, I was a young German
drafted into the army.''
</P>
<P>
   For 15 years _ from 1961 to 1976 _ the Muellers and Neumanns
were unable to see or speak to each other. Mrs. Mueller had two
children, a boy and a girl, while her friend on the Western side of
the wall had one son. Mrs. Mueller held jobs _ first in a
kindergarten, then as a receptionist _ while Mrs. Neumann raised
her boy.
</P>
<P>
   The Muellers did not become Communists, and the Neumanns were
not lifted to wealth by the postwar economic miracle in the West.
Mueller worked on the East German railroads until 1976; Neumann
labored for 27 years in the AEG factory in the West. But the ideas
of the two families slowly diverged.
</P>
<P>
   As long as the wall was there, and visits rare and emotional,
these differences were masked. But over the past decade, traveling
freely across a Berlin undergoing yet another reinvention, the
effect of long-divided lives has become clearer.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Neumann, whose husband is weak after heart surgery, appears
deeply embittered. She is angry that her husband's pension _ about
$1,300 a month _ is too low. She is angry that her work as a
``rubble woman'' was never formally recognized, so she is not
entitled to a pension for those years.
</P>
<P>
   She is worried that her son, Heimo, a seasonal construction
worker, does not have enough money to pay his mortgage. She is
troubled by all the money the West has had to pour into the East.
And she is angry at the large influx of Turkish immigrants into
Wedding and the rest of Berlin. Over 140,000 Turks live in the
city.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not antiforeigners,'' she said, ``but here there are only
foreigners. You cannot find a German in my local park. That is too
much. I do not want to go to Turkey, so why do they all want to
come here? I might have found a job at the till in a supermarket.
But they prefer Turks to me.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Neumann, who votes for the small ``Gray Panther'' party
representing angry pensioners while her husband votes for the
extreme-right Republikaners, went on to say that she found it
strange that Turkish women with veils were not allowed in the
Turkish parliament, but abounded in Wedding, where their children
were constantly shouting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like telling them that if they do not want to educate
their children, I will,'' she remarked.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   To Mrs. Mueller, who has retained a feisty good cheer, these
complaints are excessive. She spent many years adjusting to the
penury of Communist society, and feels her old friend has been
spoiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell her to be more positive, but she tells me that we in
the East have had everything since 1989, and the Westerners have
had to pay for it.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   A few years after the wall came down, the two couples decided to
celebrate their reconciliation by going on vacation in Austria. But
the trip was not altogether a success. Mrs. Mueller found Mrs.
Neumann too fussy _ complaining that the bed was too hard, that she
needed a separate room because her husband snored, that the food
was not right.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the East we learned that if there was something you could
not change, you just got on and lived with it,'' Mrs. Mueller said.
``But she complains all the time. I am sorry about these problems,
because we used to get along so well.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   On balance, Mrs. Mueller now feels that she was better off in
the former East Germany _ a view that shocks and troubles her
friend. She could work, her children had jobs, and if there was no
freedom, there was a sort of security.
</P>
<P>
   Now her son, Kurt, a construction worker who had a steady job on
the railroads in the former East Germany, has been out of a job for
a year, one of the more than four million unemployed in Germany.
His quest for a job obsesses his mother, who is angry at his
exclusion from a ``united Germany'' and responds to job
advertisements on his behalf.
</P>
<P>
   But with no luck. Kurt receives about $1,500 a month in
unemployment benefits, a sum scarcely sufficient to support his
companion and their 11-year-old child.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can't afford a wedding, so he does not get married,'' Mrs.
Mueller said of Kurt, before adding with a laugh, ``And if they did
get married, they certainly would not be able to afford a
divorce!''
</P>
<P>
   The two women still meet regularly to play table tennis at a
social club, and they marvel at the construction that has again
made rubble a common sight in Berlin, 54 years after they began
picking the good bricks from the shattered ruins.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been a bad century for this city,'' Mrs. Mueller said.
``But at least we had hoped for better for our children. Despite
everything, I am proud to be a German, but if people do not have
jobs, this country will not heal and move forward as one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
