<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   NY-JEWISH-SHOPPING (New York) _ At first glance, the central
shopping district of Borough Park would not seem world-class.
Parking is difficult, upscale restaurants are few, and there are
none of the famed stores that draw shoppers to Manhattan _ like
Bloomingdale's, Barney's and Tiffany. But driven by the density and
entrepreneurial spirit of its Jewish population, especially over
the last few years, Borough Park has become what the Lower East
Side used to be, the place for Orthodox Jews to shop. By Kit R.
Roane.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move the story by 1:30 p.m. ET in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-POLITICS (Moscow) _ If ever there was an example of how
hard it is for Russia's liberal politicians to work together it was
Saturday when Sergei Stepashin's new centrist electoral bloc
collapsed. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move the story by 12:30 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
</TEXT>
