<DOCNO> NYT19990821.0067 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 11:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5031 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-TURKEY-FAMILIES-NYT &LR;      08-21 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-FAMILIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY BRINGS ITS OWN RESCUE OPERATION TO EARTHQUAKE SITE 
</HEADLINE>
  (With TURKEY-QUAKE) 
(mk) 
 By EDMUND L. ANDREWS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GOLCUK, Turkey _ It was shortly after midnight Saturday morning
when members of the Aydin family finally took a break from digging
out corpses of their relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Golcuk, pulverized by Turkey's huge earthquake on Tuesday,
seemed a scene from hell. Its buildings are in rubble, most of its
residents evacuated _ or dead; its air is increasingly unbreathable
from decaying flesh.
</P>
<P>
   But the Aydins were an island of calm. A clan of nearly 40
brothers, sisters, cousins and spouses, they had traveled nearly
600 miles from the eastern city of Erzincan to rescue or at least
bury five trapped relatives. They have met with both success and
grief.
</P>
<P>
   They had brought their own jackhammers, drills, electric
generators and lights. They had worked around the clock, taking
shifts. And now, camped in front of an abandoned school, they
relaxed i the soft glow of candlelight to drink tea and smoke
cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't escape earthquakes,'' said Ridvan Aydin, 30, who
helps manage the family construction company. ``We worked hard back
in Erzincan to build earthquake-proof houses, only to find
ourselves called into this earthquake here.''
</P>
<P>
   Turkey is a nation built around families and extended families,
but they have been particularly crucial in the aftermath of the
earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   As of Friday, the government had yet to provide tents or toilets
for the hundreds of thousands of people wh have become homeless.
Food, water and commodities like soap and diapers have been
distributed almost entirely by charitable groups and as donations
by private companies.
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of government coordination, families and
neighbors have set up impromptu tent communities and mutual-support
networks from Istanbul and Izmit.
</P>
<P>
   It is common to find three generations of a family sleeping on
the same blanket and setting up routines to divide the labor. Men
help one another excavating bodies. Mothers and grandmothers focus
on food preparation, figuring out ways to cook okra with few
seasonings available, except for tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   At Anik Park near the Izmit bay, neighbors serve each other tea
in Turkish tea glasses and silver saucers in the evenings. They
also cluster to watch television sets connected by very long
extension cords to the park's meeting hall.
</P>
<P>
   But the Aydin family may be in a league of its own.
</P>
<P>
   Over in Izmit, for all the damaged buildings, there are still
people and power and open stores. But Golcuk, where they have come,
is demolished and rotting. Nights are dominated by screaming
ambulances and excavation crews digging up bodies under the white
glare of spotlights. Fears about cholera and typhoid outbreaks are
mounting daily, and rumors about a possible quarantine of the city
are circulating widely.
</P>
<P>
   Small wonder that most residents have fled for villages in the
nearby hills, coming back only to watch excavation of their
buildings. The Aydins, by contrast, not only have set up a
permanent camp but also have begun helping out on other buildings.
</P>
<P>
   The Aydins also brought what amounted to their own engineering
corps.
</P>
<P>
   Construction is the family business, and dealing with
earthquakes is a long tradition in Erzincan, which was hit by a
deadly one in 1939 that killed 30,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government has been rather weak,'' said Ridvan Aydin.
``But we know a lot about earthquakes and we know where to start
looking for people.''
</P>
<P>
   The Aydins were pulled to Golcuk by both loyalty and grief. The
loyalty was to Ridvan's mother and the family matriarch, Fazilet,
who had lived here years ago when her husband found work at the
factories in Izmit. Fazilet formed the center of the family group
that came here for the rescue operation.
</P>
<P>
   The grief centered on a 4-year-old girl named Halil, the
daughter of Ridvan and his wife, Sevil. Halil had come for a visit
with her maternal grandmother, who lives in Golcuk. Of the five
relatives who had been trapped when their house fell in on them
Tuesday, Halil was the only one still missing.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first came I had no idea of how bad the destruction
was,'' said Ridvan. ``I immediately called back home and told them
I needed electric generators and a lot of other equipment.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ridvan scored a huge victory even before the reinforcements
arrived. Thirty-three hours after the quake, he pulled out his
wife's still-living mother, Hamide Celebi. She was badly bruised
and weak, but a government helicopter whisked her away to a
hospital in Istanbul.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept shouting to my mother that everything would be fine
because Ridvan was here to get her out,'' said Sevil.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a huge clan of brothers, cousins, nephews, nieces and
wives organized themselves into a caravan of trucks and cars and
the next day. By that point, the road to Golcuk was so choked with
similar rescue efforts that it took more than four hours to drive
the last 10 miles from Izmit.
</P>
<P>
   What they encountered here was unmitigated mayhem. Thanks to
hundreds of truckloads of food and water donated by companies
across Turkey, hunger was not a problem.
</P>
<P>
   But government relief operations were a disaster. There were
almost no portable electric generators, necessary for lights to
keep searching at night. It took two full days for government
bulldozers and cranes to arrive at buildings in which people had
been trapped.
</P>
<P>
   The family members quickly commandeered an empty school just a
few doors from the collapsed house that held their kin here. They
laid out blankets in front along with a couple of tiny plastic
tables for eating.
</P>
<P>
   They also brought out the family samovar, the tall silver
Turkish kettles used for serving tea. The family had brought their
own bottled water and propane stove, and they tapped the school's
well for washing water.
</P>
<P>
   The men, ranging from teen-agers to fathers in their '40s,
divided themselves into two 12-hour shifts a day. The women made
meals and kept the rudimentary house in order.
</P>
<P>
   By late Friday night, they had extracted two of the remaining
three bodies belonging to relatives. The one that was still missing
was Halil's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until just a few minutes ago, we had been working 24 hours a
day in shifts,'' said Sevil. ``But even if we had to work two full
days straight, I don't think I would feel tired.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-99 1141EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
