<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 12:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5042 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-NYT &LR;      08-21 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLD FEET DOOM STEPASHIN'S MARRIAGE OF CONVENIENCE IN RUSSIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ If ever there was an example of how hard it is for
Russia's liberal politicians to work together it was the implosion
Saturday of Sergei Stepashin's new centrist electoral bloc.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday was expected to be the day when Stepashin, who was
ousted from his prime minister's post by President Boris Yeltsin
this month, announced he would be leading the new alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Stepashin surprised much of the country by declaring
somewhat bitterly that he had failed to pull together the disparate
group of democrats and power brokers and would now be going it
alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bringing people together who cannot be united is impossible,''
the 47-year-old Stepashin told the Russian news service Interfax
Saturday. ``Their personal ambitions are too big.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of serving as the standard-bearer of a new center-right
alternative to Yevgeny Primakov, the enigmatic former prime
minister who leads in the opinion polls, Stepashin will run for a
seat in the Parliament as a representative from St. Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
   With Russia entering a political season of expedient alliances
and back-room deals it is possible that some liberals and centrists
might form new marriages of convenience. But the immediate effect
of Stepashin's failure to form a new coalition was to improve the
prospects of Primakov and his new political ally, Yuri Luzhkov, the
pugnacious Moscow mayor.
</P>
<P>
   The goal of the the Primakov-Luzhkov coalition is to capture a
dominant position in the Parliament in elections scheduled for
December and to use those gains as a springboard in the 2000
presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently aiming at the ultimate prize _ the Kremlin _ Luzhkov
on Saturday assailed Yeltsin and the economic reformers who once
served him as a threat to Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The country is being robbed in a way that is unprecedented in
its cynicism and permissiveness,'' said Luzhkov, whose own city
government is no paragon of probity.
</P>
<P>
   Just Friday night, the Russian news media were reporting that a
Stepashin-led coalition was starting to jell. A key element of the
emerging alliance, the media reported, was Viktor Chernomyrdin's
movement, Our Home Is Russia. By linking up with Chernomyrdin,
another former prime minister, Stepashin hoped to capture the
political center.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, however, aides to Chernomyrdin disclosed that the
coalition began to fall when Chernomyrdin refused to include the
Democratic Choice party of Yegor Gaidar, another former prime
minister, who played a historic role in building capitalism by
liberalizing prices following the collapse of the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   Another deal breaker was Chernomyrdin's refusal to allow yet
another former prime minister, Sergei Kiriyenko, who was another
prospective member of the bloc, to be listed among the top three
leaders of the alliance in the parliamentary slate.
</P>
<P>
   Chernomyrdin still hoped to form some sort of centrist bloc with
Stepashin at the head. But Stepashin called Saturday to say he was
not interested.
</P>
<P>
   The collapse of the effort was a particular setback for some of
Russia's most ardent democrats and supporters of capitalism, like
Gaidar. They are in a particularly difficult position because of
the rules governing parliamentary elections.
</P>
<P>
   In order to win a place in the Parliament, a party must receive
at least 5 percent of the Parliamentary vote. Gaidar's party was
unable to overcome this threshold in the 1996 parliamentary
election and has little chance of doing so this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Just Cause movement faces a similar problem. That movement
includes Boris Fyodorov, the blunt-spoken former tax collector and
free-marketeer, and Boris Netsov, the telegenic pro-reform former
Kremlin aide.
</P>
<P>
   So does the New Force movement established by Kiriyenko. Even
without Chernomyrdin, these liberal groups would be in a better
position if they all worked together.
</P>
<P>
   But Kiriyenko has been reluctant to associate himself too
closely with Gaidar and with Anatoly Chubais, a member of Gaidar's
party, the former director of the program to privatize state
property and the current chief of Russia's electricity monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has a fear of being associated too closely with
Gaidar and Chubais,'' said Andrei Piontkovsky, a political analyst.
``They are seen as responsible for everything that went right in
the move to a market economy and everything that was bad, like
crony capitalism.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Chernomyrdin, whose own popularity ratings are
nothing to brag about, indicated that he might still try to form a
new coalition with Kiriyenko, who apparently would play a kind of
junior role.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should not set up sort of one-day unions that are
premature,'' Chernomyrdin said, alluding to Stepashin's efforts.
``They will fall apart quickly afterward.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
