<HEADER>
A5053 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-SIERRA-LEONE-ART-775(     08-21 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIERRA-LEONE-ART-775(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIERRA LEONE MEASURES TERROR IN SEVERED LIMBS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By NORIMITSU ONISHI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone _ After the rebels had fled into the
surrounding hills, Lamine Jusu Jarka was carried to the main
hospital here one morning in January. A young man named Mr. Junior,
wearing a shirt that declared ``C.O. Cut Hands,'' had chopped off
his arms with an ax.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt as if I am finishing the world,'' Jarka recounted from
the hospital floor where he lay at the time, surrounded by the
legless and armless, as his niece fed him biscuits to stop him from
slipping into unconsciousness.
</P>
<P>
   Half a year later, as a fragile peace agreement has stayed the
fighting in one of Africa's cruelest wars, Jarka is still alive. He
lives with his family in a makeshift camp for amputees here in the
capital, along with hundreds of other men, women and children who
are missing a leg, an arm and sometimes, like Jarka, both arms.
</P>
<P>
   The residents of this camp lost their arms and feet to a rebel
force that spread terror among Sierra Leoneans not by killing but
by leaving people like Jarka as living, limbless symbols of its
savage power. The campaign worked.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the government of President Ahmad Tejan Kabbah and
the Revolutionary United Front rebels signed a peace agreement that
many regard as a surrender by a government that has no army of its
own and that has been cut off from most of the country's diamond
mines. These have bought the rebels a seemingly endless supply of
arms and ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   But in the eastern stretches of Freetown, where whole
neighborhoods were destroyed or burned down in the rebel assault
last January, and even here in the so-called Amputee and War
Wounded Camp, almost everyone described a universal weariness of
war and seemed resigned to supporting the accord.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is no peace,'' said Jarka, 46, ``everybody will be
killed or everybody will be amputated.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not annoy them,'' he said of the rebels, not angrily,
but matter-of-factly. ``I am not a politician. I have no power of
taking the power from Tejan Kabbah and giving it to them. There's
nothing that I could say. I have no voice, you see. I am just an
ordinary citizen.''
</P>
<P>
   No one knows how many ordinary citizens have been mutilated in
Sierra Leone's eight-year civil war, because Sierra Leone has
essentially ceased functioning as a state and, despite the accord,
at least half its territory remains effectively under rebel
control.
</P>
<P>
   Though the number of the maimed may never be known, the
government has said it will conduct a census of the amputees, and
the peace deal calls for the creation of a truth and reconciliation
panel.
</P>
<P>
   Widespread reports of mutilations in rebel-held areas began
surfacing two years ago. Then in January, after nearly capturing
Freetown, the rebels were pushed out of the city by Nigerian-led
peacekeeping forces, though not before killing thousands and
mutilating hundreds.
</P>
<P>
   Most international relief officials and amputation experts do
not expect the numbers to approach the level found in Angola _ or
in Cambodia, with the highest per capita amputee rate in the world,
one in 250. But what makes Sierra Leone unique, they say, is that
people elsewhere have usually lost limbs to mines; here, the limbs
were hacked off by human beings with an ax or machete.
</P>
<P>
   What is more, the amputees elsewhere have typically lost a leg
or sometimes two legs, which though horrible still allows the
victim to function with crutches or a wheelchair. In Sierra Leone,
most amputees have lost an arm, and many are what technicians call
``double upper-limb amputees.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexis Randin, a prosthetics specialist for Handicap
International, a private French organization that has set up an
office in the camp, said he had never seen a double-arm amputee
until he came here. ``It was shocking,'' he said. ``I don't think
you will find double amputees of the upper limbs anywhere else in
the world _ maybe isolated cases, but not like in Sierra Leone.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Amputee and War Wounded Camp, which is run by another aid
group, Doctors Without Borders, 28 of 146 amputees have no arms,
said Wahab Shaw, the camp's manager. Ninety-seven lost one arm;
twenty-one, a leg. About 160 other people with severe injuries to
their limbs are also here, living with relatives in tarpaulin tents
set up on a soccer field and on the flank of a hill that,
incongruously, is in Freetown's palm-dotted resort area.
</P>
<P>
   In the camp's macabre hierarchy of suffering, the double
amputees are considered the unluckiest. Those without arms, like
Jarka, openly express envy of those with a missing leg, who will
one day wear trousers over an artificial leg, or those wih at
least one good arm.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Jarka, the father of six children, lost his arms when rebels
invaded his neighborhood in eastern Freetown. Maybe because he once
worked as a security guard at Barclays Bank, Jarka vividly
remembers dates, faces and events. He recognized a foreign reporter
who interviewed him as he lay on the hospital floor last January,
even though he was incapable of spelling his own name correctly at
the time.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels forced Jarka and his neighbors under a mangrove tree,
where the ax-wielding Junior made them rest their arms on a flat
root. ``Then I was amputated and the man told me to go to Tejan
Kabbah,'' Jarka recalled, mentioning the name of the president who
was elected to office in 1996. ``These hands I used to vote for
Tejan Kabbah. So I will never vote for him, no more again.''
</P>
<P>
   A couple of weeks after he was admitted to the hospital,
surgeons from Doctors Without Borders cleanly cut the remaining
stumps, leaving some inches below each elbow. At the camp he now
attends rehabilitation at Handicap International several times a
week, learning how to use a hook that he can operate with a cord
around his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Once the patriarch of an extended family, Jarka used to bring
home a 110-pound bag of rice on the last day of each month, taking
care of his and his wife's relatives. Today he is completely
dependent on his wife, Mariama Jusu Jarka, 30 _ a sudden reversal
of roles for a woman he had married when she was 14.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to run everything,'' he said. ``I would come and tell
her: `I have gone to your father, I have gone to your mother. Your
father extends his greetings.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``But now I am like a baby,'' he said. ``There's nothing being
done with me now if she cannot contribute. For instance, in terms
of eating, in terms of wearing clothes, even in terms of when I am
lying down at night, she has to cover me up.''
</P>
<P>
   His wife, who has set up a stand selling candy and cigarettes in
front of their tent, remained silent. ``When I think too much,''
she said, ``I feel pain in my heart. I feel headache.''
</P>
<P>
   Valerie Cresson, a psychologist at Handicap International who
treats the amputees, said the Revolutionary United Front appeared
to have selected men whose maiming would most profoundly affect the
social order. ``It was the goal of the rebels to take away their
role as men, fathers and husbands,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In a guest house a mile or two from the camp, Solomon Rogers,
who was leading a delegation from the rebel group on a visit to
Freetown, dismissed the accusations. Stating the official line
established by the rebel leader, Foday Sankoh, at the peace talks,
Rogers said, ``We don't say we haven't committed atrocities, but
the level that has been assigned to us _ we don't agree.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal made Sankoh chairman of a new commission of the
country's mineral resources, and it gave four top Cabinet positions
to his commanders. The accord was criticized by the U.N. human
rights commissioner and other human rights organizations for
granting blanket amnesty to those guilty of atrocities and war
crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Sankoh, Jarka said: ``He has created all these
problems. He was the person who went to Liberia and organized these
boys, went to Libya to undergo so many processes in order to come
and destabilize this country. Today he wants to come and rule this
country. Let him come and see some of us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
