u a BC-CLINTON-VACATION-2TAK     08-21 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-VACATION-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR VACATIONING CLINTONS, A FLAVOR OF OLD TIMES 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDGARTOWN, Mass. _ A year ago in a sweltering church near here,
President Clinton made a faltering speech about forgiveness and
attracted widespread media attention. Now, the language of forgive
and forget rolls off his tongue in a manner that no longer
surprises and, perhaps more important, no longer carries the
freighted question of whether he will be forgiven.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and his wife, Hillary Rodham Clinton, are back on
Martha's Vineyard for a vacation. In some ways their summer visits
to this dune-swept Atlantic island _ this is their fifth _ have
become as routine as post-season reruns. Their secluded, borrowed
home at Oyster Pond, the open arms of Vernon Jordan, the
celebrity-studded dinners _ all by now are familiar props in the
summer stock of the Clinton marriage.
</P>
<P>
   But this summer is like no other, and certainly not like the
last. After admitting to the nation a year ago that he had had a
relationship that was ``not appropriate'' with Monica Lewinsky when
she was a White House intern, Clinton seemed iced out of his wife's
personal space. He ruminated on the beach by himself. He dared not
play golf. Democratic support in Congress was draining.
</P>
<P>
   Even the ubiquitous Jordan, the Washington power-broker _ and
one of Clinton's closest friends, who it was suggested had tried to
arrange for Ms. Lewinsky to vanish from Washington and find a job
in New York _ laid low. Uncharacteristically, even Jordan appeared
more hunted than hunting. And an even darker winter for the
Clintons, of impeachment and finally acquittal, would ensue.
</P>
<P>
   But now, it seems, Jordan is back to his jaunty self. And so are
the Clintons.
</P>
<P>
   And so, especially, is Hillary Clinton, who in a year has
transformed her image from wronged wife to wronged-wife-with-a-plan
_ to run for the Senate from New York, with a supportive and
chastened husband.
</P>
<P>
   The president gave his wife's race for the Senate his
full-throated support on Friday night in Nantucket in their first
joint fund-raising appearance for her candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Before an audience of more than 100 people at the home of Smith
and Elizabeth Bagley, the president went down memory lane as he
sought to capture the essence of his wife.
</P>
<P>
   In an amusing turn, Bagley said that as the husband of a former
administration official (Mrs. Bagley was ambassador to Portugal),
he rarely got to speak and so he wanted to give another muted
spouse the chance to raise his voice. That was his introduction to
Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In an ode to destiny, Clinton recalled that in 1971, at Yale Law
School, Hillary Rodham had made the first move on him.
</P>
<P>
   ``This woman has initiative,'' Clinton said, explaining that
this was a useful trait as a senator. But shortly after their first
meeting, he said, he had also decided she was ``nothing but
trouble.'' When she confronted him and asked him who he was, he
said, ``I couldn't remember my name.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that he had found Ms. Rodham ``an interesting,
compelling-looking woman, so I followed her out of this class'' and
then ``stalked her around the law school'' for a few weeks. He
decided she was trouble, he told reporters later in the press cabin
of Air Force One (another rare appearance) as he returned to
Martha's Vineyard. He said he had just broken up with another
girlfriend. ``I thought I would fall in love with her,'' he said of
Ms. Rodham. ``And I didn't want to fall in love.''
</P>
<P>
   The rest is history. But there also was a future, as Ms. Rodham
abandoned her career for the Arkansas politician. ``In 1973, after
we had gone together for two years and we were very much in love,''
the president said in a monologue about the relationship, ``I was
very ambivalent about Hillary coming home to Arkansas. I thought
she had such enormous potential for public service.''
</P>
<P>
   She was the ``most gifted person'' he knew, Clinton said, and so
after they moved to the White House in 1993, he told her: ``I want
you to decide where you want to go and what you want to do when we
get out of here. For 20 years, we've gone where I wanted to go and
done what I wanted to do, and I'll give you the next 20 years. And
if I'm still alive after that, we'll fight over the rest.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the tensions in their marriage burst into public view
as the Republican-led Congress sent Clinton to the presidential
gallows for his extramarital affair.
</P>
<P>
   And on last year's so-called vacation, a clearly anxious Chelsea
Clinton seemed intent on gluing her parents together. At the
airport here, she descended from Air Force One just hours after her
father's confession and worked the rope line. This year, as she
reached the final step of the plane ramp, she threw herself into
Jordan's arms.
</P>
<P>
   After all the Clintons had worked the rope line this year, they
stopped long enough to drop their bags at the home of Richard
Friedman, a developer who has lent them his house for the last
three years, before zooming off to Jordan's for a birthday party
for the president (Clinton turned 53 on Thursday). About 40
friends, including Maurice Templesman, the former companion of
Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis, author William Styron, investment
banker Steven Rattner and television correspondent Charlayne
Hunter-Gault, came for a home-cooked buffet of seafood paella,
roast beef and birthday cake.
</P>
<P>
   The host, who had skirted reporters during the impeachment
cloud, sent out some white wine to members of the news media who
were stuck outside in the president's waiting motorcade for three
hours. The wine was described as coming from grapes in Jordan's
vineyard. The label, ``Decoy,'' showed a picture of a duck. The
vintage was 1996, a good year for the president.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The president and Mrs. Clinton seem more effusive about each
other than ever. Already, in the opening two days of their two-week
vacation, both are together in public and more visibly upbeat _ and
more laudatory of each other _ than they had appeared in their
entire visit last year.
</P>
<P>
   As Air Force One lifted off on Thursday from Washington toward
this island retreat, Clinton, once morose and distant from
reporters, bounded into the press cabin and asked, ``Hey, guys, are
we going to have a good time?''
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons' language bears the stamp of personal
reconciliation and forgiveness, a chord that Clinton struck
publicly for the first time last year in a church in the Oak Bluffs
section of the Vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is important that we are able to forgive those we believe
have wronged us, even as we ask for forgiveness from people we have
wronged,'' he said then. It was the first time Clinton broached the
subject after having appeared less than contrite in an earlier
address to the nation. It was also a chance to test his plea for
redemption among a sympathetic audience, largely of black people,
who remain his most reliable supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm having to become quite an expert in this business of
asking for forgiveness,'' he said then. ``It gets a little easier
the more you do it.''
</P>
<P>
   He has been doing it so much since then that by now it is almost
old hat. He and his wife talk freely about trust and letting go and
moving on.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton, introducing her husband on Friday night at a
fund-raising event for peace in Northern Ireland, told the
audience, ``No one has prayed harder or worked harder than the man
I'm going to introduce.''
</P>
<P>
   She spoke of his commitment to peace, and added, ``We've had
some wonderful times together, and our visits, to Belfast and
Dublin and so many other places where we have been so warmly
received, have only strengthened his commitment, which he intends
to carry out to the very last day he's in office.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton put their relationship in more stark terms still.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, he was talking about the Good Friday peace agreement
and the warring factions in Northern Ireland. But so many of his
comments in the last year have lent themselves to a personal
interpretation, and this was no exception.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point, they're going to have to figure out a way that
they're both trusting each other at the same time,'' Clinton said
of the Irish leaders, adding, ``You know, it's like two kids
standing on a big, old diving board holding hands and looking down
into a deep pool.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have to do,'' he said, ``is to find ways to help them
let go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
