for Lamar Alexander, the former Tennessee governor, who quit the
race last week. ``He has yet to present a presidential persona.''
(Alexander did have such a persona, but that did not seem to be
enough.)
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, a former executive director of the Republican Governors
Association, recalled, ``I first observed it at meetings when other
governors would sit in their chairs and listen to the discussions
about policy. He just had no interest in doing that. He would get
up and slap people on the back, joke around and stay for as little
time as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Bush, 53, conducts himself in ways that are appealing to
some and off-putting to others. He is forever mugging for the
cameras, winking at reporters from the lectern and entertaining
people with his impression of Dr. Evil, the campy villain from
``Austin Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me.'' In his spontaneity, he
sometimes borders on the inappropriate, as when he bounded up to a
graying reporter, smiling, and blurted, ``It's the reporter from
the AARP!''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, Bush seems as bemused as anyone that only five years
ago he had never been elected to anything and now he is the man to
beat. But clearly, he seems certain that he will win. During a
visit to California last month, he described it as ``my first trip
as president of the United States.'' He corrected himself, saying,
``Soon to be president of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   There can be an air of overconfidence in Bush, which may be a
reflection of his early dominance in the race. While his opponents
toiled in Iowa for weeks or months, if not years, before the straw
poll, Bush went on vacation. Unlike his opponents, Bush has not had
to beg for donations _ the checks pour in.
</P>
<P>
   On issues, Bush has given his detractors reason for pause. He
has defended his lack of preparedness in foreign policy experience
by saying he would turn to the best experts for help. His advisers
say he is a quick study who is diligent about learning the issues.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's opponents are ardently trying to fill in the blanks in
the most negative way possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``The swagger has to be reduced to a stride, and the air of
arrogance diminished to an air of confidence,'' said William Dal
Col, the campaign manager for Steve Forbes, who finished second in
the Iowa straw poll. ``And if they're unable to do that, it could
have a fatal effect on his candidacy.''
</P>
<P>
   (Forbes, who has never been elected to anything, is trying so
hard to appear presidential that he has filmed commercials in an
Oval Office-like setting.)
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Quayle accused Bush of having many of the faults that
she says were unfairly attributed to her husband, former Vice
President Dan Quayle. She told The Arizona Republic recently that
her husband's rival was ``the party frat-boy type.'' She also said
Bush was ``the guy that never accomplished anything, everything he
got Daddy took care of.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Gov. Roy Romer of Colorado, the general chairman of the
Democratic Party, said that if Bush is the nominee, he would look
weak and unprepared compared with Vice President Al Gore or former
Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``People take this presidency very seriously,'' Romer said.
``There's a flippancy that shows in his demeanor. Maybe it's part
of having the Bush name. Maybe he feels anointed and ready to go.''
</P>
<P>
   The questions about Bush's disposition intensified after an
article in the new magazine Talk. The writer Tucker Carlson quoted
the governor using curse words, boasting that ``I'm not interested
in process,'' and making fun of Karla Faye Tucker, a double
murderer who was executed in Texas last year. Mimicking the woman
when she was asked on television what she would say to Bush if she
could appeal to him for clemency, Carlson wrote, Bush ``whimpers,
his lips pursed in mock desperation: `Please don't kill me.'''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said his comments were misinterpreted. ``I didn't do the
interview for Talk,'' he said, portraying Carlson as ``somebody
coming to get a flavor of the campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gary Bauer, a favorite among religious conservatives, who is
also seeking the Republican nomination, said the governor's
comments in the magazine were ``inappropriate, disgusting and
profoundly disturbing.''
</P>
<P>
   The article prompted George F. Will, the conservative columnist,
to write that Bush was operating in ``an atmosphere of adolescence,
a lack of gravitas _ a carelessness, even a recklessness, perhaps
born of things having gone a bit too easily so far.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Last week reporters were consumed with questioning Bush about
rumors that have lingered for years that he used illegal drugs as a
young man, and his careful responses only seemed to escalate the
issue. The Washington Post even called the question Bush's first
crisis. But how relevant will it seem in five months, when voting
in the primaries begins? No evidence has been presented to support
the rumors. Nor have they dissuaded Texans from electing him
governor twice.
</P>
<P>
   This year, his rivals haven't made it an issue. If anything, how
Bush handles the questions now _ like Clinton and his admission
during the 1992 campaign that he tried marijuana in college _ may
impress voters more than what he did or may have done in his youth.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Greenstein, a historian at Princeton, dismissed some of the
scathing judgments of Bush as alarmist, yet inescapable. ``If he
didn't have any of these slight angularities,'' he said, ``then the
question would be: Is he bland and soapy?''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, what his detractors do not seem to like about Bush is
what makes him likable to others.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Bill Clinton or Al Gore, for example, Bush has not
plotted his life to make it to the Oval Office, a fact that makes
him more down-to-earth and less desperate. He is not embarrassed to
say when he does not know something. And while his father, former
President Bush, may have appeared more presidential, he was forever
denounced for not knowing how to connect.
</P>
<P>
   There are signs that Bush is trying to come off as less the frat
boy and more the commander in chief. During an interview recently,
he referred to his best friend and finance chairman, Donald Evans,
as Donny. Then he quickly instructed a reporter to revise it to a
more grown-up sounding Don.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's advisers say he also intends to roll out a series of
policy speeches in the fall _ just as Bill Clinton did, when he was
trying to get people to take him seriously.
</P>
<P>
   The root of the criticism, Evans, the governor's close friend,
said, is that ``we're the front-runner, we're winning, we're
leading, so people are trying to concoct anything they can. It's a
total misrepresentation of the friend I've known for 25 years and
my wife's known for 50 years. They don't understand the heart and
soul and mind of this guy like I do.''
</P>
<P>
   But often the governor cannot help himself. At an event in
Texas, he was horsing around with someone for a photograph and
pointed to the man next to him and said, ``He's the ugly one!''
Then, spotting a reporter looking on, he quickly explained that
they were old buddies who always teased each other.
</P>
<P>
   The governor can take solace in the fact that in 1960 Richard M.
Nixon questioned whether John F. Kennedy was mature enough, and
steeped enough in the issues, to be president. But that future
president happily seized on his youthfulness as an asset. He was
only 43.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-99 1320EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990821.0096 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 13:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4393 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-BUSH-REVIEW-REVIEW-2N     08-21 0490
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-REVIEW-REVIEW-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: so far.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last week reporters were consumed with questioning Bush about
rumors that have lingered for years that he used illegal drugs as a
young man, and his careful responses only seemed to escalate the
issue. The Washington Post even called the question Bush's first
crisis. But how relevant will it seem in five months, when voting
in the primaries begins? No evidence has been presented to support
the rumors. Nor have they dissuaded Texans from electing him
governor twice.
</P>
<P>
   This year, his rivals haven't made it an issue. If anything, how
Bush handles the questions now _ like Clinton and his admission
during the 1992 campaign that he tried marijuana in college _ may
impress voters more than what he did or may have done in his youth.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Greenstein, a historian at Princeton, dismissed some of the
scathing judgments of Bush as alarmist, yet inescapable. ``If he
didn't have any of these slight angularities,'' he said, ``then the
question would be: Is he bland and soapy?''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, what his detractors do not seem to like about Bush is
what makes him likable to others.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Bill Clinton or Al Gore, for example, Bush has not
plotted his life to make it to the Oval Office, a fact that makes
him more down-to-earth and less desperate. He is not embarrassed to
say when he does not know something. And while his father, former
President Bush, may have appeared more presidential, he was forever
denounced for not knowing how to connect.
</P>
<P>
   There are signs that Bush is trying to come off as less the frat
boy and more the commander in chief. During an interview recently,
he referred to his best friend and finance chairman, Donald Evans,
as Donny. Then he quickly instructed a reporter to revise it to a
more grown-up sounding Don.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's advisers say he also intends to roll out a series of
policy speeches in the fall _ just as Bill Clinton did, when he was
trying to get people to take him seriously.
</P>
<P>
   The root of the criticism, Evans, the governor's close friend,
said, is that ``we're the front-runner, we're winning, we're
leading, so people are trying to concoct anything they can. It's a
total misrepresentation of the friend I've known for 25 years and
my wife's known for 50 years. They don't understand the heart and
soul and mind of this guy like I do.''
</P>
<P>
   But often the governor cannot help himself. At an event in
Texas, he was horsing around with someone for a photograph and
pointed to the man next to him and said, ``He's the ugly one!''
Then, spotting a reporter looking on, he quickly explained that
they were old buddies who always teased each other.
</P>
<P>
   The governor can take solace in the fact that in 1960 Richard M.
Nixon questioned whether John F. Kennedy was mature enough, and
steeped enough in the issues, to be president. But that future
president happily seized on his youthfulness as an asset. He was
only 43.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
