<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5081 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-NEW-WORDS-REVIEW-REVI     08-21 1348
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-WORDS-REVIEW-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW WORDS TO SOME, BUT NOT TO OTHERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
(lh) 
 ELIN SCHOEN BROCKMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The people who compile dictionaries always have ``news'' (n. pl.
Oxford English Dictionaries' in-house word for new words). But
neologisms are not always newly minted. Take ``yada yada yada,''
which long before ``Seinfeld'' was used by Lenny Bruce.
</P>
<P>
   Jesse Sheidlower, the senior editor in charge of new words at
Random House, became convinced of yada yada yada's staying power
not only by its history, but also by the existence of
well-established parallel expressions (blah blah blah, for
instance). He put it in the 1996 Random House Webster's College
Dictionary.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Agnes, editor in chief of Webster's New World College
Dictionary, excluded yada yada yada from his 1996 edition. And
having tracked a decline in its use, he is glad he did. ``This year
we would have had to take it out,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   New words help give each dictionary its personality. The
differences among them may not be readily apparent to the average
reader, but when the editors of four dictionaries provided their
unabridged new word lists for comparison, there was no overlap. One
of the editors, on hearing just six words from the list of a
competitor, was able to guess its identity immediately.
</P>
<P>
   What follows is only a brief sampling of the news. The fourth
edition of Webster's New World College Dictionary, the only one
represented here for which a final count is available, because it
has been published, added 7,000 entries. One of them, Nunavut, just
made the deadline, because the editors had to wait until Canada
officially declared the new territory of Nunavut.
</P>
<P>
   There are always late-breaking news, words waiting to be
accepted. Oxford U.S. Dictionaries, for instance, which publishes
several dictionaries including the Oxford American Dictionary and
Language Guide, has this on its waiting list, pending more
evidence: ``Fuggedaboudit.''
</P>
<P>
   WEBSTER'S NEW WORLD COLLEGE DICTIONARY, FOURTH EDITION
(published July 1999)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Bubba &LR;  (also b--) (Chiefly South) (Slang)  &UR; 1 &LR;  Brother:
sometimes used as a familiar term of address  &UR; 2 &LR;  close friend  &UR; 3 &LR;  a
man of the Southern U.S., variously characterized as easygoing,
companionable, assertively masculine, uneducated, bigoted, violent,
etc.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; 4x4 &LR;  n., pl.  &UR; 4x4s &LR;  or  &UR; 4x4's &LR;  A four-wheel drive vehicle
</P>
<P>
   &UR; gigaflops &LR;  n., pl.  &UR; -flops &LR;  A unit of processing speed in a
computer, equal to one billion flops
</P>
<P>
   &UR; headbanger &LR;  n. A devotee, fan, or performer of heavy metal; see
headbanging
</P>
<P>
   &UR; pedestrianize &LR;  vt.  &UR; -ized &LR; ,  &UR; -izing &LR;  To make (an area, esp. a
street) accessible to pedestrians only by closing to use by
automobiles, buses, etc.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; problematize &LR;  vt.  &UR; -tized &LR; ,  &UR; -tizing &LR;  To demonstrate, to be
unsettled or uncertain, or more complex than originally assumed or
regarded; show to be problematic
</P>
<P>
   &UR; pumped &LR;  adj. (slang) Full of confidence, enthusiasm, etc.:
pumped up
</P>
<P>
   &UR; reality check &LR;  An instance of confronting or acknowledging the
facts about something and thus dispelling unrealistic notions or
expectations
</P>
<P>
   &UR; satisfice &LR;  vi.  &UR; -ficed &LR; ,  &UR; -ficing &LR; , coined by H.A. Simon
(United States social scientist and economist), satis(fy) +
(suf)fice. To be satisfied with a minimum or merely satisfactory
level of performance, profitability, etc. rather than a maximum or
optimum level.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; semi-staged &LR;  adj. Produced with the use of only a limited
number of props, costumes, etc.: said as of an opera staged for an
exhibition performance, in a concert hall, etc.
</P>
<P>
   OXFORD AMERICAN DICTIONARY AND LANGUAGE GUIDE (to be published
this fall)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; big-box retailer &LR;  n. Retail store with large amount of open
floor space, many departments
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DSL &LR;  n. A telecommunications technology allowing high-speed
transmission using standard phone lines (DSL equals digital
subscriber line)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; hat hair &LR;  n. Matted condition of the hair along the line of the
hatband after one's hat has been removed
</P>
<P>
   &UR; heart-healthy &LR;  adj. Of or pertaining to food or dishes that are
low in fat, sodium, and other ingredients that may lead to heart
disease
</P>
<P>
   &UR; megaplex &LR;  n. Complex of movie theaters in a single facility
offering a variety of different feature films
</P>
<P>
   &UR; racial profiling &LR;  n. Alleged police policy of stopping and
searching vehicles driven by people from particular racial groups
</P>
<P>
   &UR; slamming &LR;  n. (from verb) Practice of switching a person's
long-distance telephone service to a different company without the
person's authorization
</P>
<P>
   &UR; viewbook &LR;  n. Illustrated publication produced by a college or
university for prospective students
</P>
<P>
   &UR; wakeboard &LR;  n. Board, similar to a surfboard, used to ride over
water while being towed behind a boat. vs. sport of riding
wakeboard
</P>
<P>
   RANDOM HOUSE WEBSTER'S COLLEGE DICTIONARY (to be published this
fall)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; backstory &LR;  n. Background narrative or history implicit in a
fictional or real story or situation
</P>
<P>
   &UR; brownfield &LR;  n. Vacant former industrial site regarded as a
candidate for development
</P>
<P>
   &UR; D.W.B. &LR;  Driving While Black (used ironically to refer to the
stoppage of a black motorist by police because of the motorist's
race rather than for any real offense)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; eyeballs &LR;  n. pl. ( Business) Viewers, as of a television show,
Web site, etc.; audience
</P>
<P>
   &UR; fashionista &LR;  n. An extremely fashionable person, esp. one who
works in the fashion industry
</P>
<P>
   &UR; microcap &LR;  n. (Business) A company having a market
capitalization smaller than a small cap, as under $250 million
</P>
<P>
   &UR; open-source &LR;  adj. Of, being, or pertaining to software for
which the source code is made freely available
</P>
<P>
   &UR; props &LR;  n. pl. (Slang) A public acknowledgment of respect;
credit; praise; acknowledgment
</P>
<P>
   &UR; small cap &LR;  n. (Business) A company having a relatively small
market capitalization, as under $2 billion
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SSRI &LR;  n. Selective Serotonin Reuptake Inhibitor: any of several
drugs that inhibit the reabsorption of serotonin by nerve cells,
leading to more serotonin activity in the brain: used chiefly as an
antidepressant
</P>
<P>
   WORDS BEING TRACKED BY AMERICAN HERITAGE FOR FUTURE DICTIONARIES
(THE AMERICAN HERITAGE DICTIONARY, THIRD EDITION, WAS PUBLISHED IN
1996.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; altar girl &LR;  n. A girl who is an altar server
</P>
<P>
   &UR; body-piercing &LR;  n. The perforation of body parts for the purpose
of attaching a piece of jewelry
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Bose-Einstein Condensate &LR;  n. A state of matter that forms below
a critical temperature in which all bosons that comprise the matter
fall into the same quantum state
</P>
<P>
   &UR; face time &LR;  n. Time spent interacting in the presence of or in
the same location as another or others: putting in face time in the
office instead of working at home
</P>
<P>
   &UR; home-school &LR;  tr. v. To instruct (a pupil, for example) in an
educational program outside of established schools, especially in
the home. intr. vs. To provide educational instruction in a
homeschool
</P>
<P>
   &UR; netiquette &LR;  n. Etiquette practiced or advocated in electronic
communication over a computer network
</P>
<P>
   &UR; nuceloside analogue &LR;  n. Any of a group of antiviral drugs,
including AZT, DDC, and DDI, that interfere with the activity of
the viral enzyme reverse transcriptase and are used in the
treatment of HIV
</P>
<P>
   &UR; soft money &LR;  n. Political donations made in such a way as to
avoid federal regulations or limits, as by donating to a party
organization rather than to a particular candidate or campaign
</P>
<P>
   &UR; xenotransplantation &LR;  n. The surgical transfer of cells,
tissues, or especially whole organs from one species to another
</P>
<P>
   &UR; zine &LR;  n. An inexpensively produced, self-published, underground
publication
</P>
