<HEADLINE>
NEW INDEPENDENT MEXICAN ELECTION COUNCIL VEERS OFF HIGH ROAD 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JULIA PRESTON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ If there is one reason Mexico expects to break
with decades-old tradition and have a clean and fair presidential
election next year, it is that an elections council will oversee
the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago President Ernesto Zedillo, in one of his most
far-reaching reforms, liberated the federal agency that runs
national elections from his direct control and made it independent.
The legislative elections of July 1997, the new organization's
first, were the most democratic and least fraud-tainted Mexico has
had in memory.
</P>
<P>
   But during the last year the sober deliberations of the Federal
Electoral Institute, as it is formally named, gave way to shrill
quarreling among political parties. The disputes, council members
said, have begun to hamper their ability to plan the big election
set for July 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The infighting began late last year when several voting members
tried to get the council to investigate Zedillo's 1994 campaign
finances. They supported a petition by an opposition party,
contending that the campaign had received illegal donations from
Mexican business people.
</P>
<P>
   After a series of shouting matches, the representatives from
Zedillo's Institutional Revolutionary Party walked off the council
in November 1998 in protest. Eventually the council decided it
lacked clear legal authority for the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The council has nine voting members _ academics and elections
experts approved by all 11 parties. Representatives of these
parties can speak during public meetings of the council but have no
vote. The largest, like the governing party, have two
representatives.
</P>
<P>
   When delegates of the governing party returned to the council in
March, they went to its inspector general to complain about four
council members seen as close to the opposition. The party accused
them of violating their impartiality and of misspending council
funds.
</P>
<P>
   One council member, Jesus Cantu Escalante, was accused of
squandering public money on leisure trips to Monterrey and on
highballs served at a conference he organized in 1997. He said that
the council had paid for his travel to his home in Monterrey as
part of his contract and that council financial officials had
approved the budget for the 1997 event.
</P>
<P>
   Early this month the inspector general, Carlos Munoz Villalobos,
fired Cantu, saying he had failed to observe ``austerity'' because
the guests at his conference imbibed an average of 2.2 cocktails a
day.
</P>
<P>
   The move by the inspector general, a governing party member,
awakened the ire of the council president, Jose Woldenberg, who had
remained so impassive throughout the feuding that all sides were
mad at him. He agreed that Munoz had overstepped his authority, and
on Aug. 15 the council voted unanimously to fire him.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition council members believe they are facing a deliberate
drive by the governing party to weaken the council and improve
chances of swaying the elections.
</P>
<P>
   The party ``is trying to undermine us so we will fail to be an
effective force in favor of impartiality in 2000,'' said Emilio
Zebadua, one member who faced accusations. But the party's
delegates countered by saying they were acting to keep the council
honest.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone agrees that the spats have sapped the council's energy
for the huge task of organizing the vote. ``I'm just not sleeping
at night,'' Zebadua said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
