<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HMO-DRUG-STUDY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WIDE VARIANCE FOUND IN HMO DRUG BENEFITS FOR ELDERLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ROBIN TONER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ While many Medicare beneficiaries have prescription
drug benefits through health maintenance organizations, a new study
shows that there are wide variations in those benefits and that
some are quite modest.
</P>
<P>
   The study, conducted for the Kaiser Family Foundation, a
nonprofit research group, addresses a core issue in the debate over
Medicare restructuring: Is it really necessary to add a
prescription drug benefit to the Medicare program, as the Clinton
administration is proposing?
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the Clinton plan argue that two-thirds of Medicare
beneficiaries already have coverage for prescription drugs, either
through their HMOs, the purchase of supplemental coverage or
retiree plans provided by their employers. But proponents of the
Clinton plan assert that these sources of private coverage have big
holes.
</P>
<P>
   The Kaiser study looked at the 15 percent of Medicare
beneficiaries who are members of HMOs and found a huge range in
drug benefits. For example, more than one in six were in a plan
with no drug benefits, while one in four was in a plan with
unlimited drug benefits. The rest were in the middle, with about a
third in a plan with annual drug benefit limits of more than
$1,000. The average limit was $1,149.
</P>
<P>
   ``It shows the infinite variety of prescription drug benefits
that are offered today by Medicare HMOs, which questions the
general presumption that all beneficiaries in Medicare HMOs have
good coverage for their drugs,'' said Tricia Neuman, director of
the Medicare Policy Project at Kaiser. ``Some do, some have really
great coverage, some have really meager coverage and some have
none.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Jennings, coordinator of health policy at the White House,
said such findings ``generally track with the information we have,
although in the most recent data supplied by Medicare HMOs we find
there's a significant increase in the number of plans capping
benefits at or below $500.'' He added that the administration was
compiling more data on these trends, but suggested that he already
saw evidence that more and more HMOs were putting limits on drug
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Jennings added, ``Really, there's only about 25 percent of the
Medicare population that has a significant drug benefit _ those
people who are fortunate enough to have retiree health plans.'' And
employers are increasingly cutting back that form of coverage as
well, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Pisano, a spokeswoman for the American Association of
Health Plans, the group for the managed care industry, said that
the prescription drug issue needed to be examined in a broader
context, noting that the industry was engaged in a continuing
struggle with the federal government over the adequacy of payments
for Medicare beneficiaries. Health plans are taking a variety of
steps to deal with these cost pressures, including limits on drug
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Still, she argued, ``Prescription drug benefits available
through Medicare HMOs are still the most affordable way, and for
many the only affordable way, to get prescription drug coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   The study raised the complexity of the issue. For example, a
Medicare beneficiary with multiple medical conditions requiring
high prescription drug usage could incur out-of-pocket costs of
$5,358 in a ``least generous'' HMO, and just $1,080 in the ``most
generous,'' the study reported.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-99 1333EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990821.0107 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5087 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SILICON-VALLEY-TRAFFI     08-21 1175
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SILICON-VALLEY-TRAFFIC-ART-840&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOM IN SILICON VALLEY TURNS INTO A TRAFFIC NIGHTMARE FOR DOT.COM
COMMUTERS
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Map is being
sent to NYT graphics clients. Non-subscribers may make individual
purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By LAURA M. HOLSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Lindsey Cigarran never thought she would spend
her 20s trapped in a Saab convertible. But the 24-year-old group
manager of Beyond.com's entertainment software division commutes an
average of 2 1/2 hours every day to and from her San Francisco
apartment and an office in Sunnyvale, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a full-on nightmare,'' Ms. Cigarran said recently.
</P>
<P>
   So much so, she rented a room near work where she sleeps when
she is too tired to make the 40-mile drive home. Most of her
driving time is spent talking on her cellular phone with clients.
And she has taken to hoarding secret routes, like an alley behind a
gasoline station near work that is a shortcut to the highway.
</P>
<P>
   For many professionals at dot-com companies in Silicon Valley,
the boom in the Internet has resulted in a commuting bust, forcing
them to funnel onto increasingly congested highways that snake in
and around the crowded Bay Area. From San Francisco to San Jose,
the expanding economy has created a traffic jam of unprecedented
proportions.
</P>
<P>
   Statistics tallied by the Santa Clara Valley Transportation
Authority, a regional management group, show that the percentage of
freeways in the Silicon Valley region receiving the worst possible
congestion rating has tripled in the past four years, to 46
percent. That is akin to hooking up a fast computer with a slow
modem; almost half of all freeway drivers poke along at less than
35 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's gotten pretty bad,'' said Carolyn Gonot, manager of the
authority's congestion management program. She knows firsthand. Ms.
Gonot, who drives to work in Silicon Valley from the East Bay,
acknowledged that she traveled in off-peak hours, saving as many as
10 hours weekly. ``I'm a test case,'' she said. ``We promote flex
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Business leaders in Northern California worry that
traffic-clogged freeways are eroding their wine-sipping,
khaki-wearing, laid-back quality of life that residents have come
to expect, threatening the area with a tied-up traffic fate similar
to that facing their brethren in the Los Angeles basin.
</P>
<P>
   The area is doing its best to cope with the influx of new
people: The San Mateo Bridge, which connects the East Bay with
Silicon Valley, is being expanded to six lanes from four. Several
cities shuttle passengers to commuter train stations, the cost
partly borne by some local companies. And a 1996 half-cent sales
tax will pay for a variety of freeway projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course there will be an impact when a person only has time
to work, drive and sleep,'' said Steve Tedesco, a California native
and president of the San Jose Silicon Valley Chamber of Commerce.
``They don't have time to get involved in their communities. They
can't get home in time for Little League games.''
</P>
<P>
   Congestion is likely to worsen as communities use new-found
riches (also a result of the Internet boom) to fuel a construction
frenzy. A range of projects now on the horizon have several of San
Francisco's leaders predicting traffic catastrophe in the near
future: Caltrans, the state's highway construction division, will
soon embark on a large project that will include demolishing and
rebuilding several blocks of the elevated freeway that feeds into
the San Francisco-Oakland Bay Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Many believe the project will create long-term chaos in a region
where traffic already creeps for hours on end. The Harrison Street
ramp _ a major downtown exit for morning commute traffic _ is
scheduled to be closed for 4 1/2 years. And several development
projects, including office buildings, hotels and a new ballpark in
the South of Market neighborhood of the city, have led city
officials to forecast the elimination of more than 10,000 parking
spaces, 6,000 of which will be permanent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems you don't have to worry so much about drunk driving
anymore,'' said Gary Skraba, a Los Angeles marketing executive who
travels to the Bay Area several times yearly for business. ``You
have to worry about road rage.''
</P>
<P>
   Doug Wills, a San Francisco native and group manager of
corporate public relations at Cisco Systems, lasted only four
months when he moved back to his hometown last year to be near his
wife's restaurant. Sometimes it took him two hours to drive the 50
miles to Cisco's headquarters in San Jose. His wife, Nasreen, had
it just as bad: It took her 40 minutes to go across town.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't make sense,'' Wills said. ``It shouldn't be this
difficult to get to work.''
</P>
<P>
   So 16 months ago, the couple packed up their furniture and moved
to a house in Silicon Valley. His commute is shorter, and his
wife's 30-mile train trip to her restaurant takes about the same
time as her old 4-mile trip across town.
</P>
<P>
   Some drivers have come up with interesting ways to live in the
fast lane, particularly in the troublesome rush hours. It is common
to see drivers putting on makeup, checking stock quotes on their
laptops, even lifting hand weights.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to figure out how to make those hours productive,''
Ms. Cigarran said. ``There are times when you don't have an extra
five minutes to comb your hair.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   John Marren, an investment banker at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter
who is based in Menlo Park, said he had, on occasion, asked a
junior banker to accompany him to a meeting to take advantage of
the speedier commuter lane.
</P>
<P>
   A number of Silicon Valley's luminaries, including the venture
capitalist John Doerr, now use car services so they can work or
read on their commutes.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate executives who do not want to drive themselves have
their own strategy for coping: high-brow hitchhiking. Every
morning, scores of them, like Francis Torrence, a lawyer at
Seyfarth, Shaw, Fairweather &AMP; Geraldson in San Francisco, line up
near a commuter train station in Oakland to catch a ride.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers mill about until drivers, whom they do not know but
who want to save the $2 San Francisco-Oakland Bay Bridge toll and
use the commuter lane, pick them up. An unspoken etiquette has
evolved among repeat carpoolers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone says `Good morning,' but usually people don't talk,''
Torrence said. ``Drivers pick the radio station. And generally the
bus terminal is where people bail out.''
</P>
<P>
   For many, the daily Silicon Valley commute is likely to get
worse before it gets better, leaving some to wonder whether the
plugged-in driving lifestyle will end.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're looking up a phone number that's one thing,'' said
Kimball Brown, a computer analyst at Dataquest, a market research
concern at San Jose, ``but if it gets to the point of using a
spreadsheet, I'm sorry, but that's going too far.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
