<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, Aug. 22, 1999, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(nk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cloudy, cool and damp weather will linger Sunday from the east
slopes of the central Appalachians to New England as low pressure
gradually shifts off the Northeast coast. Patchy light rain and
drizzle will occur near the coast where onshore breezes prevail. A
few locally heavy showers accompanied by rumbles of thunder may
develop during the afternoon near the southern New England coast.
Skies will brighten near the Appalachians during the afternoon as
drier air arrives from the Ohio Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Mainly dry and warm conditions will cover most of the
Southeastern states. A few afternoon thunderstorms will erupt
around a dissipating front near the Gulf of Mexico coast. Much of
central and southern Florida will be unsettled with limited
sunshine and frequent thundershowers which will produce locally
heavy rain.
</P>
<P>
   Scattered showers and thunderstorms will accompany a disturbance
as it moves from the northern Rockies to the central Plains. Some
strong thunderstorms with high winds and hail are expected this
afternoon from eastern Colorado and Wyoming to the western Dakotas
and Nebraska. Isolated afternoon thunderstorms will also occur over
the mountains of the interior West. Elsewhere in the West, it will
be sunny and warm.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Bret with central winds over 100 mph will move slowly
north parallel to the east coast of northern Mexico. Bands of heavy
showers and gusty winds will reach extreme southern Texas on
Sunday, but hurricane-force winds will remain offshore later in the
day.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Born In Africa
</P>
<P>
   Many of the hurricanes that strike the Caribbean and eastern
United States are born in Africa. In the summer and early fall
dozens of clusters of thunderstorms form in the strongly heated air
near the Sahel. As the clusters move westward, the chilly waters
near the Africa's west coast are inhospitable territory for the
disturbances struggling to strengthen. But, when the high-level
winds are favorable, the African disturbances can reach the warmer
waters to the west where hurricanes take shape. On Friday, Tropical
Storm Cindy sprang to life 300 miles west of the Cape Verde
Islands.
</P>
</TEXT>
