<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 14:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5112 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TAKE     08-21 1063
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WEEK IN REVIEW 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Deep in Space, a Cosmic Puzzle
</P>
<P>
   Astronomers think they understand much about how the universe
began, why stars shine and galaxies take majestic shape, and where
planets orbit other stars. But one tiny point of faint light deep
in the northern sky in the constellation Serpens has astronomers
mystified.
</P>
<P>
   They don't know if they are seeing some odd variation of a
familiar object or the first evidence of something entirely
unsuspected, perhaps a challenge to cherished theories.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since it was detected three years ago, the mystery object
has confounded astronomers because they cannot decipher the
language of its light. Usually, they are able in minutes or hours
to determine an object's composition, distance and nature by
breaking down and analyzing its light spectrum. Not this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen a spectrum anything like this, and I take
spectra for a living,'' said Dr. S. George Djorgovski, an
astronomer at the California Institute of Technology whose team at
Palomar Observatory detected the mystery object.
</P>
<P>
   Repeated photographs reveal only a steady light, neither flaring
nor fading over time, which would appear to rule out a stellar
explosion, or supernova. Nor is it recognizable as a distant galaxy
or a quasar, sources of tremendous energy believed to be powered by
matter falling into massive black holes.
</P>
<P>
   If it turns out to be a quasar, some scientists speculate, it is
almost certainly a rare kind beyond current understanding. Other
astronomers and some of the most powerful telescopes have been
called on to help solve the mystery.
</P>
<P>
   With bigger, more sensitive telescopes, astronomers may have to
get used to new mysteries like this one. As Djorgovski said, ``We
can't think we have discovered all the kinds of things there are
out there.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By JOHN NOBLE WILFORD
</P>
<P>
   A Brownout Hits New England
</P>
<P>
   One word that Yankees dread more than ``drought'' is ``drab.''
And a menacing brown is enveloping New England roadsides, as
thirsty red oaks and sugar maples shed their shriveled leaves a
good two months before the invasion of tourists drawn to the
region's foliage show each fall.
</P>
<P>
   Foresters fear that by the time the leaf-peepers begin clogging
mountain roads next month, the only leaves left will be a muddy
mustard color, with the coveted scarlet, purple and fiery orange _
the spectacular death throes of a healthy leaf _ available only on
postcards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not seeing a lot of outright death,'' said Glenn D.
Dreyer, director of the Connecticut College Arboretum. ``But I'm
seeing a lot of defoliating and browning out.''
</P>
<P>
   The quest for the peak leaf week, an annual obsession that
includes nightly updates from television weathercasters and Web-cam
views offered by state tourism departments, may become even more
desperate than usual. (Botanists patiently explain that the only
sure way to know a leaf has peaked is when it falls off.)
</P>
<P>
   Farmers, who could lose their crops, are annoyed by the leaf
panic, and hard-core hikers are bemused. But foliage-gawking has
become an $8 billion annual business in New England, with tour
packagers offering journeys by bus, boat and rail, with hot
chocolate included.
</P>
<P>
   So proprietors like Rolf Hammer, owner of the Homestead Inn in
New Milford, Conn., are scrambling to save the season. ``The
scenery isn't just trees,'' he points out. That may be little
consolation to the tourists who visit the same stand of trees each
year, or the ones who wait for rain so they can revel in the
contrast between the vivid leaves and the dark earth.
</P>
<P>
   But there is an upside. Wineries in New England say the dry,
sunny summer will produce smaller but more flavorful grapes. So
next season tasting may rival peeping as the region's leading
autumn attraction.
</P>
<P>
   _ By MIKE ALLEN
</P>
<P>
   Metropolitan Life Agrees to Settle Fraud Suits
</P>
<P>
   Metropolitan Life Insurance Co. agreed to settle lawsuits that
accused the company of using deceptive sale practices to cheat
policyholders out of billions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Metropolitan Life, the nation's second-largest life insurer,
placed the value of the deal, which is subject to approval by a
federal judge, at $1.7 billion, though fees for the plaintiffs'
lawyers' and other costs will come from that sum. Some 7 million
customers who bought life insurance and annuities between 1982 and
1997 can seek to get cash or increases in their death benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuits against Metropolitan Life, like similar ones
against other life insurers, alleged that the company, competing
for consumers' money with banks paying high interest, persuaded
customers to trade in valuable existing policies for more costly
ones, a practice called ``churning.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By BARRY MEIER
</P>
<P>
   Corruption in Bosnia
</P>
<P>
   An American-led anti-fraud unit investigating corruption in
Bosnia reported that up to $1 billion has been stolen from
international aid projects or has disappeared from public funds or
been lost through Bosnian officials' failure to collect taxes. The
investigators documented the fraud in a report that names several
officials linked to governing parties that it says profited from
the corruption.
</P>
<P>
   At least $20 million of the total was in foreign aid; the vast
majority was stolen from Bosnian public funds or lost through
uncollected taxes. The missing money was to have been spent to
repair roads, buildings and schools, as well as to provide
municipal services in Bosnian towns.
</P>
<P>
   Bias Seen in Spy Case
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese atomic spy scandal, for months a shadowy maze of
complex allegations, has been roiled anew by charges of racial
bias.
</P>
<P>
   A key investigator in the case asserted that Wen Ho Lee, a
Taiwan-born scientist at the Los Alamos weapons lab in New Mexico
who became the top suspect, had been unfairly singled out four
years ago for federal investigation because of his ethnicity.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of Caucasians'' with equivalent access to secrets and
trips to China were not investigated, said Robert S. Vrooman, the
former head of counterintelligence at the Los Alamos National
Laboratory.
</P>
<P>
   Energy Department officials denied the charge. ``Race was never
a factor,'' said Notra Trulock, who began the federal probe in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   _ By WILLIAM J. BROAD
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Russian Coalition Gets a Lift
</P>
<P>
   A new center-left coalition in Russia gained momentum when
Yevgeny Primakov, the popular former prime minister who was fired
three months ago by President Boris Yeltsin, decided to join the
alliance in advance of parliamentary elections in December.
</P>
<P>
   The Fatherland-All Russia coalition, led by the mayor of Moscow,
Yuri Luzhkov, appears poised to take a commanding lead in the
coming campaign. It remains unclear whether Luzhkov or Primakov, a
Soviet-era survivor and former spymaster, will emerge as the
alliance's leading candidate in the presidential election in 2000,
when Yeltsin is scheduled to step down.
</P>
<P>
   Starr to Leave Soon
</P>
<P>
   After five years of investigation, independent counsel Kenneth
Starr has decided to call it quits. His associates said he would
step aside to resume his private law practice as early as October.
Starr plans to stay to put the last touches on a final report on
his inquiries _ a document that could embarrass Hillary Rodham
Clinton as she moves closer to entering the New York Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   Starr will depart with his reputation for scholarly probity
damaged by attacks from Clinton's supporters _ even as Starr
uncovered an Oval Office sex scandal that led to Clinton's
impeachment in the House and his subsequent trial and acquittal in
the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   _ By DAVID JOHNSTON
</P>
<P>
   A Lutheran-Episcopalian Link
</P>
<P>
   Another merger? Big deal. Banks and media companies routinely
gobble one another for breakfast. But this one's different: The
nation's largest Lutheran group voted to link up with the Episcopal
Church. It's not a merger exactly, for each will keep its rituals.
But the plan, involving nearly 8 million American Protestants,
bears a striking resemblance to deals out in the cold corporate
world, for it involves, basically, economies of scale. When
congregations are small and poor, they could, say, pool resources
or share a pastor.
</P>
<P>
   But here's where it diverges from the corporate model: It will
not, presumably, involve layoffs among the faithful.
</P>
<P>
   _ By HUBERT B. HERRING
</P>
<P>
   Pursuers of Diana Cleared
</P>
<P>
   The Paris prosecutor's office concluded that nine celebrity
photographers and a photo-agency motorcycle driver arrested after
the crash that killed Diana, Princess of Wales, her escort and
their French driver two years ago bore no criminal responsibility
for the accident.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors' report said the accident appeared to have been
caused by the driver of the Mercedes S280 limousine, who was
inebriated and traveling at an excessive speed. The two
investigating magistrates who carried out the probe have the last
word on whether to bring charges and are expected to rule by Aug.
31, the second anniversary of Diana's death.
</P>
<P>
   _ By CRAIG R. WHITNEY
</P>
<P>
   China Sets Production Limits
</P>
<P>
   After years of fearing the social consequences of runaway
inflation, China's leaders now face the opposite problem:
deflation. Prices have fallen for 22 months in a row, leaving
factories with stacks of unbought goods. Yet the state-run nature
of operations means many local officials are still eager to open
even more factories.
</P>
<P>
   In a drastic move to stop them, China's leaders ordered a
nationwide ban on any new production of several consumer goods, as
well as on all new luxury hotels, apartment and office buildings
and department stores. The unanswered question is how well the ban
will be enforced.
</P>
<P>
   _ By SETH FAISON
</P>
<P>
   School Drug Test Challenge
</P>
<P>
   High-school students in Tecumseh, Okla. _ as well as in school
districts in North Carolina, Idaho and Wyoming, among other states
_ have been subject to drug testing if they wish to participate in
extracurricular activities like the debate team, the drama club,
even the Future Farmers of America. Otherwise, they risk being
dropped from the activity.
</P>
<P>
   Though the testing of high-school athletes has gone largely
unchallenged after the Supreme Court upheld an Oregon program in
1995, the American Civil Liberties Union believes the Tecumseh
policy goes too far. The group has filed suit against the district
in federal court in Oklahoma City.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JACQUES STEINBERG
</P>
<P>
   A New Bacteria Threat
</P>
<P>
   More than 200 people in Minnesota and North Dakota have become
sick _ and four children have died _ over the past two years from a
drug-resistant bacteria that for more than 30 years has been
confined to hospitals and nursing homes.
</P>
<P>
   The fatalities were the first reported in the United States from
the germ, a strain of Staphylococcus aureus, and federal officials
don't know if the bug has spread. But the deaths suggest the public
is now at risk.
</P>
<P>
   _ By SHERYL GAY STOLBERG
</P>
<P>
   Huge Japanese Bank Merger
</P>
<P>
   Three giant Japanese banks _ Industrial Bank of Japan, Fuji Bank
and Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank _ announced their intention to merge.
Combined, they would have $1.3 trillion in assets and become the
world's No. 1 banking powerhouse. But if Japanese banking history
is any indication, bigger does not mean better. Large or small,
Japanese banks are not highly profitable, especially when compared
with American rivals.
</P>
<P>
   _ By JOSEPH KAHN
</P>
