<HEADLINE>
HECTIC FLOW, BUT ARMSTRONG SPINS ALONG 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Colo., Ore., Texas, Vt.)  (rk) 
 By FRANK LITSKY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOUNT SNOW, Vt. _ For Lance Armstrong, winning the Tour de
France was only the beginning. Since his near-miraculous recovery
from cancer surgery less than three years ago and then his
improbable triumph in the world's most celebrated bicycle race, his
life has been one festive moment after another.
</P>
<P>
   The public mobs him. The news media enjoys his fresh responses
to questions. Advertisers have made him a target almost as
appealing as Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong's $400,000 salary from the U.S. Postal Service team
will jump to $2 million next year. The Austin American-Statesman,
his hometown newspaper, said salary, endorsements, a movie and a
book would bring his 2000 income to $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview over dinner Friday night, Armstrong said he was
baffled by his new celebrity status.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to be me and understand what I mean to people,'' he
said. ``If I walk through an airport now and get stopped by
someone, it still surprises me. Am I the same guy? I think so.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm enjoying this. It won't last forever. If you lose the fame
and the recognition, it all goes away. I know that. I'm not
addicted to this. I have to know that in 10 years' time I'll be
another ex-athlete. And that's fine with me. Maybe some people will
remember me, but people forget. That doesn't bother me. The cause _
the foundation _ will live on.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lance Armstrong Foundation subsidizes cancer research and
helps cancer patients and their families deal with the illness.
Armstrong, whose testicular cancer spread to his abdomen, lungs and
brain before being wiped out by intense chemotherapy, has pledged
at least $250,000 to the foundation next year.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong has been here for the Chevy Trucks national finals for
mountain bikes. He said racing mountain bikes was far different
from racing road bikes, but he rode impressively Friday in
finishing sixth in the men's cross-country race.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, his schedule had two major stops. The first, at 6:30
a.m., was fishing. The next, in the afternoon, was a cross-country
short-track race, consisting of 30 minutes of loops around a 3/4
mile course plus three finishing laps.
</P>
<P>
   He is racing mountain bikes here because he likes the change and
the challenge. Last winter, he agreed to race this week and in
Colorado next week for Trek-Volkswagen. Had the agreement been made
after the Tour de France, Armstrong would have made much more
money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' he said, ``but money isn't that important. The illness
changed a lot of that. Before, I was motivated by making money.
I'll earn more this year than I ever did in my life, but that's not
important. It's important in the sense that I have a family, but
I'd rather have my health than money.''
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, he has it all, including wonderful memories since
the day he became only the second American (after Greg LeMond) to
win the Tour de France. There was the parade lap on the
Champs-Elysees, the visit to President Clinton in the White House,
the television appearance with David Letterman, the parade in
Austin. His training has suffered. So have his eating habits,
although his weight is still under control.
</P>
<P>
   ``For five months,'' he said, ``I ate like a monk. Since the
night the race ended, I've been eating what I like _ chitterlings,
beer, ice cream, hamburgers.''
</P>
<P>
   As he said this, he was attacking a ham sandwich and perhaps the
world's largest order of french fries.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life has been extremely hectic,'' he said. ``The attention and
the response have been much bigger than I thought. I've been very
busy, and I have another month of this crazy schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, he squeezed in four days with his wife, Kristin,
in Vail, Colo. ``We finally had time to ourselves,'' he said. ``No
media, no appearances.''
</P>
<P>
   Kristin is expecting their first child in October and is cutting
back on travel. She stayed in Vail while Armstrong flew here
Tuesday. He will fly to Vail on Sunday before returning home. Then
comes another round of trips _ to Portland, Ore., for a visit to
Nike and a four-month health checkup; to Las Vegas for a bike show,
to College Station, Tex., for wind-tunnel testing for new bikes.
</P>
<P>
   He knows he will be a marked man in next year's Tour de France.
He talked about Miguel Indurain of Spain, who won five in a row in
the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's probably not going to happen with me,'' Armstrong said.
``But I'm 27, and in cycling you can be competitive until 31 or 32.
I think you win one or you win five or six. Well, nobody ever won
six. It's hard to win one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
