<HEADLINE>
U.S. VICTIMS OF THE QUAKE HAD REVISITED THEIR ROOTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ala., Ga.)  (See also TURKEY-QUAKE, TURKEY-FAMILIES) 
(js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The five Americans who died in the Turkish earthquake
last week belonged to a family of doctors who had been visiting
Turkey for decades.
</P>
<P>
   Turkan and Nizam Kilic, both pediatricians, came to the United
States in the 1950s to complete their residencies, and they set up
a practice in Birmingham, Ala., that they maintained for more than
30 years.
</P>
<P>
   In their retirement, they moved to Atlanta to be closer to their
three sons, all anesthesiologists, who practiced there.
</P>
<P>
   Lately the elder Kilics had returned to Yalova, Turkey, for four
months every year, said Diane Kilic, a daughter-in-law. Their sons,
wives and grandchildren also visited often.
</P>
<P>
   Family members had been in Yalova, about 30 miles southeast of
Istanbul, when the earthquake struck. Five were killed: Nizam Kilic
and four grandchildren: Jeffrey, 6; Jennifer, 5; David, 2; and
Katie, 9 months.
</P>
<P>
   Nizam's wife, Turkan, and his daughter-in-law, Jan Kilic, the
mother of the children, were found alive and taken to a makeshift
hospital and then to the American Hospital in Istanbul. Turkan was
in critical condition. Jan, though injured, was expected to recover
fully.
</P>
<P>
   Beneath the rubble, Jan could hear the voice of Nizam Kilic, and
they talked, according to Jan's brother Bill Kemp.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nizam kept telling Jan to be strong,'' Kemp said in an
interview.
</P>
<P>
   But after about 12 hours, Jan Kilic could no longer hear her
father-in-law, Kemp said.
</P>
<P>
   Jan was told that all five of her children were killed, but a
Turkish relative went to the scene and persuaded authorities not to
bulldoze the rubble and to search further.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the children's bodies were found, and after 20 hours of
digging, emergency workers thought they had found the fifth child,
3-year-old Natalie, dead too. But rescuers noticed that the dust
around Natalie's mouth and nose stirred and realized she was
breathing. Natalie survived.
</P>
</TEXT>
