<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-CUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON GOLF: TALK IS CHEAP. IT'S TIME FOR U.S. PLAYERS TO WIN BACK THE
RYDER CUP
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Recently, there has been plenty of talk about profit from the
Ryder Cup, and less talk about winning it.
</P>
<P>
   The heated debate concerning Ryder Cup revenue, and whether
players should be paid and the money donated to their favorite
charities, has been brewing for several years. It finally reached
the boiling point before the PGA Championship, when details of a
closed-door meeting leaked out faster than a downhill putt at
Augusta National.
</P>
<P>
   However, the issue has done little to diminish interest in next
month's biennial event. Come Sept. 24-26 at The Country Club in
Brookline, Mass., the gallery and the corporate tents will be
packed, as will hotel rooms in Boston and the surrounding areas.
</P>
<P>
   The allure of the Ryder Cup won't be ruined if players are given
money to donate to charity, not with people used to seeing athletes
in other sports sign million-dollar contracts before they catch a
pass, or make a layup. If anything, the squabble gave the Ryder Cup
even more publicity, even if it wasn't the kind of publicity sought
by the PGA of America and the players.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, the days before last week's PGA Championship sounded
like a soap opera, and that is something golf doesn't need. Ben
Crenshaw, the U.S. Ryder Cup captain, publicly chastised four of
his top players _ Tiger Woods, David Duval, Mark O'Meara, and Phil
Mickelson _ who all feel strongly that they should be allowed to
allocate money from the Ryder Cup toward charity. For the next two
days, players took sides, and people began to wonder if this year's
team would need a referee as well as a captain.
</P>
<P>
   But in the coming months, chances seem good that an agreement
will be reached between players and the PGA of America. With Golf
Digest reporting in its September issue that the Ryder Cup will
gross $63 million this year, there is enough money to satisfy
everyone. The PGA of America can allocate some money toward player
charities and still have ample money left for its many fine
programs that support golf across the country.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. players would be wise to put this issue on the back
burner, keep their mouths closed on the subject and head to The
Country Club with determination to win back the cup. Players can
downplay the importance of the Ryder Cup if they want to, but the
history of the event speaks for itself. The public cares about it.
The greatest players in history from both sides of the Atlantic
have cared about it. And with Europe having won the last two Ryder
Cups, the United States will arrive in Brookline facing extra
pressure.
</P>
<P>
   If the United States wins, then the so-called pay-for-play issue
can't be used as a possible reason for the demise of this year's
team. Winning cures many things, and the public will most likely be
eager to embrace a team that wins the final Ryder Cup match of the
century.
</P>
<P>
   But if the United States is defeated, the money issue will
almost surely be fingered as a reason. You can almost see the
headlines _ the team lacked unity, the players weren't committed
enough. Those things will be said, even if they aren't true. Some
U.S. players felt they were criticized unfairly in 1997 after
losing the Ryder Cup in Spain, but if they lose again next month,
expect the criticism to be harsher.
</P>
<P>
   Without question, this year's U.S. team looks like one of the
most talented ever _ Woods, Duval, Payne Stewart, Davis Love III,
Mark O'Meara, Justin Leonard, Hal Sutton, Tom Lehman, Phil
Mickelson, Jeff Maggert, Jim Furyk and Steve Pate. But one of the
strange things about the Ryder Cup is that Europe always seems to
be underrated.
</P>
<P>
   The final 12-man European team will be decided Sunday night,
when captain Mark James adds his two picks to the top 10 players in
the point standings through Sunday's final round of the BMW
International tournament on the European Tour. But Europe has
proven winners who have already secured their place on the squad _
Jose Maria Olazabal, who won this year's Masters, Paul Lawrie, who
won this year's British Open, 19-year-old Sergio Garcia, who almost
won the PGA Championship, and Europe's two most consistent players,
Colin Montgomerie and Lee Westwood.
</P>
<P>
   The European team is undergoing a transition, with longtime
Ryder Cup stalwarts like Nick Faldo, Ian Woosnam and Constantino
Rocca unlikely to be chosen as captain's picks unless James pulls a
last-minute surprise. For the first time since 1983, Seve
Ballesteros will not be in the Ryder Cup as a player or captain,
and his leadership will be missed by Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, in the last two competitions, the European team has shown a
superior short game, and some of its lesser stars have earned key
points when called upon. Call the United States the favorite if you
wish, but Europe has flourished in the underdog role. And in match
play, especially under intense pressure, almost anything can
happen.
</P>
<P>
   This has already been a splendid year for golf. Each of the four
men's major championships was compelling, from Olazabal's
courageous victory over Greg Norman at the Masters, to Woods'
sensational duel with Garcia at the PGA. Meanwhile, the LPGA Tour
is also enjoying a vintage year, with Juli Inkster completing a
career grand slam and Karrie Webb winning her first major in
comeback fashion.
</P>
<P>
   But the Ryder Cup is always special, no matter what the year, or
what the controversy. It has history, it has suspense, and it has a
tradition that money can't buy. The discussion about Ryder Cup
money is just another reminder that sports has become big business.
However, that shouldn't make the event any less fun to watch.
</P>
</TEXT>
