<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL NOTEBOOK: TIGERS STYMIE MCGWIRE; LOOKING FOR LEFTIES; GM
ON THE SPOT 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Go figure. The Detroit pitching staff has given up the most home
runs in the American League this season, second most in the major
leagues, but the Tigers are the only team that has faced Mark
McGwire in the past two seasons and has not allowed him to hit a
home run.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire has hit 11 home runs against San Diego and the Chicago
Cubs, 10 against San Francisco, nine against Florida but none
against the Tigers. In 32 at-bats over eight games, two last
season, six this season, McGwire has eight hits but only one
extra-base hit, a double.
</P>
<P>
   ``We basically stuck with the same approach for two years with
him and made good pitches,'' said Rock Adair, whom the Tigers fired
as their pitching coach last month. ``We just kept the ball away
from him for the most part. We very seldom tried to come inside on
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Dave Mlicki started against St. Louis twice in a week in June
and thwarted McGwire five times in 12 innings, allowing only a
single, walking him once and striking him out twice. In 125 2/3
other innings this season, the right-hander has given up 17 home
runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the wind must have been blowing in,'' Mlicki said,
laughing. Then he added, ``When I faced him in the National League,
we'd try to pitch him in. But here when we faced him, we noticed he
was kind of pulling off the ball. We stayed away from him, threw
soft stuff away, down and away, and tried to run fastballs up and
away. If we came in, we missed in. Pitch him in and down and in and
he just crushes balls.''
</P>
<P>
   Mlicki and his fellow pitchers did not boast about their success
against McGwire. ``If he's hot and feeling good,'' Mlicki said,
``it's not going to matter how you pitch him. We just caught him at
a good time.''
</P>
<P>
   Lefties Left Out
</P>
<P>
   Where are all the left-handers? Don't look for them among the
clubs contending for American League playoff spots. The starting
pitching rotations of six teams have a total of two left-handers.
The Yankees have Andy Pettitte, the Toronto Blue Jays have David
Wells. That's it.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland, Texas, Boston and Oakland have all-right-handed
rotations. Even the replacements for injured starters, with one
exception, have been right-handed. The one exception is Mark
Langston, who has made five fill-in starts for the Indians but who
went on the disabled list last week.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians tried to get Chuck Finley from Anaheim last month
but balked at the Angels' steep price.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one would like to have a left-hander more than me,'' Doug
Melvin, the Rangers' general manager, said. ``Some of those teams
have some potent left-handers in their lineups. Carlos Delgado hit
five home runs against us.''
</P>
<P>
   Time for Change
</P>
<P>
   Season's end grows closer and for some managers and general
managers, it will mark the end of their terms. Randy Smith, the
Tigers' general manager, was last week's hot topic in baseball
circles.
</P>
<P>
   Talk among other executives is that Mike Ilitch, the Tigers'
owner, is not happy with the state of the team as it prepares to
open a new park next season, and he plans to make changes. Smith,
the talk goes, will be fired or will resign. In Part II of the
talk, Smith will replace Bob Gebhard in Colorado as the Rockies'
general manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard none of the above other than they've mentioned me
in Colorado,'' Smith said. ``I'm certainly not going to resign and
I haven't heard anything about being fired. I signed on here to do
a job. We have had a horrible year, no doubt about it. We thought
we'd be a .500 team and we've drastically underachieved that. But I
believe we still have good talent and I'm not going to quit on
doing the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith's name has surfaced in Colorado as a possible successor to
Gebhard, who resigned Friday, because he was the Rockies' assistant
general manager in the early '90s. ``I dismiss it,'' Smith said.
``It's just a name people are familiar with. I'm a Tiger and I want
to finish what we've started here.''
</P>
<P>
   Gebhard survived last winter when the Rockies fired Don Baylor
as their manager, but the team made no improvement this season and
a change at the top had been expected. The same could happen in
Detroit, where the Tigers have played as poorly as they did last
season.
</P>
<P>
   And they have played as poorly with a payroll that is nearly
double _ $35 million, up from $19 million. While the Tigers
struggle despite the signing of Dean Palmer (29 home runs) and
Gregg Jefferies (.204) and the reacquisition of Willie Blair (1-9,
6.77), their owner sees Jose Lima (16-7), Luis Gonzalez (.337) and
Joe Randa (.322) succeed elsewhere after the club traded them.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a very competitive man,'' Smith said of Ilitch, who also
owns a team that has won the National Hockey League's Stanley Cup.
``He wants to win now, but he's also realistic about where we
started and what we've had to work with over the last few years.
But he expects results. He expects us to put a good team on the
field when we move into Comerica Park.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
