<SLUG> BC-BBA-HOME-FIELD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RACE FOR HOME-FIELD ADVANTAGE GAINS IMPORTANCE IN A.L. 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Texas clobbered Cleveland three times, but the Indians won the
fourth game of their series last week. The Rangers get the Yankees
in a three-game series beginning Monday night in Arlington, Texas.
The Indians play a pair of games in Texas Sept. 7 and 8. The
Yankees play four games in Cleveland later in the month.
</P>
<P>
   The games are a prelude to the playoffs for these three teams
destined to be the American League's division champions, and they
are the highlight of the league's third race. First come the
division races, then comes the wild-card competition and finally
there is the dash for home-field advantage.
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't always been thus. Until last year, the format of the
playoffs provided for rotation between the divisions for the league
series and among the divisions for the first-round matchups. The
teams' records meant nothing.
</P>
<P>
   But last year the format was changed to give the team with the
best record home-field advantage in both series. In the
three-of-five-games division series, that team gets the first two
games and the fifth at home; in the four-of-seven-games league
championship series, it gets the first two games and the last two
at home.
</P>
<P>
   Teams are reluctant to talk about the race for home-field
advantage before they clinch a postseason spot, but that is one of
their goals.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Hicks, the Rangers' owner, discussed that goal with his
people at the All-Star Game break last month. ``He got people
motivated to try to do that instead of just looking to get to the
postseason,'' Doug Melvin, Hicks' general manager, said. ``He felt
we'd have a better chance to compete with the Yankees and the
Indians if we got home-field advantage. It's tough to beat them at
their ballpark.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Melvin said, ``We'd like to give more to our fans
than they got last year in postseason play. We lost the first two
games in New York and then gave them five innings here. We came
home and had that horrible rain delay. So our fans haven't had a
chance to get excited about the postseason.''
</P>
<P>
   With their 114 victories last season, the Yankees had home-field
advantage in each of the first two series. The World Series
continues to alternate between leagues. This season the three
division leaders are much more closely bunched with six weeks left.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things can dramatically change every week in this game,''
Melvin said. ``I get nervous talking about it too early. You've got
to be careful. You have to get to the postseason first.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Cashman, the Yankees' general manager, also spoke of
having to win the division title first but said if the team can
accomplish that, as if there's any question, and gain home-field
advantage, too, ``no doubt that's what we'd like to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only from a playing standpoint,'' Cashman added, ``but
from a business standpoint _ concessions, parking. There are
financial advantages to it.'' Plus, he said, ``You get your crowd.
You'd rather have your crowd than going into some of these
jungles.''
</P>
<P>
   John Hart, the Indians' general manager, offered a different
perspective on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously,'' he said, ``the home-field advantage is very nice
to have, but the only thing we're fighting for right now is to get
our team healthy, which we haven't been the better part of the
year. It's taking its toll not only on our ability to win games
right now but our ability to even think about something like
home-field advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   The Indians easily have the longest injury list among the three
division leaders. Two months ago, the Indians had the best record
among the three teams _46-21 to the Yankees' 39-28 and the Rangers'
39-30 _ but the injuries helped bring the Indians back to the other
teams.
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Travis Fryman (July 4), catcher Sandy Alomar Jr.
(May 11) and designated hitter Wil Cordero (June 9) remain on the
disabled list. Center fielder Kenny Lofton had been there and may
return.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he's not back in four, five days,'' Hart said of Lofton,
``we'll have to disable him again.'' Alomar could be back this week
and Fryman may be ready the first week of September. The Indians,
however, can only hope that Cordero can play by mid-September.
</P>
<P>
   ``The priority is for us to get healthy and hold the fort until
we do,'' Hart said. ``Last year we had home-field advantage in the
division series and it worked to our benefit. We didn't have
home-field advantage against the Yankees and it hurt us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
