<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL LAND DEAL PROTECTS YELLOWSTONE HERDS AND GEYSERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mont.)  (js) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The federal government and a New Age church have
completed a deal that will protect bison and geysers in Yellowstone
National Park, President Clinton announced Saturday in his weekly
radio address.
</P>
<P>
   The $13 million deal involves 9,000 acres of land adjacent to
the park. The Carter administration had negotiated over the same
land, the Royal Teton Ranch, in 1980, but the Reagan administration
dropped the deal. In 1981, the Church Universal and Triumphant
bought the property from the publisher Malcolm Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement includes a swap of about 1,000 acres that will
give the church more land near a fallout shelter it maintains. The
church will receive $13 million, which it will use in part for
maintenance of local churches and for a retirement fund for its
founder's widow, Elizabeth Prophet.
</P>
<P>
   The government will get prime wintering territory for bison
along the park's northern edge and rights to underground supplies
of hot water, which, if tapped, might disrupt geysers and hot
springs in the park. In exchange, it gave the church rights to
surface water.
</P>
<P>
   The Yellowstone bison herd of 2,400 is the only one in the
country that is not interbred with cattle, said Michael S. Clark,
the executive director of the Greater Yellowstone Coalition, a
nonprofit group in Bozeman, Mont. Clark said that state employees
had been shooting the animals as they left the park in an effort to
control the bacterial disease brucellosis, which the state said the
bison would pass on to cattle. He said this deal would protect the
animals.
</P>
<P>
   The park is on a 7,000-foot plateau, and the bison, along with
elk and other animals, seek lower elevations with milder climates
in winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a vital piece of private land that we've got a second
chance on,'' Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   A vice president of the church, Murray L. Steinman, said, ``It's
a small land swap but the deal was very complicated because it had
so many different components.''
</P>
<P>
   The land, Steinman said, is ``some of the finest natural habitat
in the United States.'' One phase of the transfer is complete, he
said, and others would follow; for example, the government may buy
and then retire the grazing rights on some church land, to keep
cattle off it.
</P>
<P>
   The church will retain 12 square miles of land in the deal,
Steinman said.
</P>
<P>
   Church officials said in depositions in the early 1990s that
more than 100 firearms and two armored personnel carriers were
stored near the fallout shelter. Steinman, asked about the
catastrophe preparedness, said the weapons were contained in a
16-acre area ``out of thousands and thousands.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like the term `survivalist' as much as `insurance
policy,''' Steinman said.
</P>
<P>
   The president, in an address taped on Nantucket Island, near
where he is vacationing, said, ``With more Americans visiting our
national parks and forests than ever before, we must do more.''
</P>
<P>
   In connection with the radio address, the White House released a
list of dozens of land acquisitions made this year. One is the Weir
Farm, in Wilton, Conn. The only National Historic Site in
Connecticut, it is the former home of J. Alden Weir, the American
Impressionist painter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
