</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-CHESS-MATCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW FACES AT THE TABLE FOR THE TITLE IN TOP CHESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ROBERT BYRNE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The gathering of attention among chess devotees that accompanies
the start of any world championship match, either at the site of
play or at computer terminals around the world, was under way in
earnest Saturday as the title match of the International Chess
Federation went through final preparations for its opening Sunday
evening at Caesar's Palace in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   After a month of qualifying matches, many of them featuring
bruising, sometimes dazzling play, two finalists have emerged,
Aleksandr Khalifman of Russia and Vladimir Akopian of Armenia, who
are not well known outside the tournament circuit but who both
performed brilliantly in the preliminaries.
</P>
<P>
   A salient feature of this year's championship is the absence of
celebrities. Garry Kasparov, universally regarded as the world's
strongest grandmaster despite his humiliating loss two years ago to
the IBM supercomputer Deep Blue, is boycotting the federation
(known by its French acronym, FIDE) and trying to organize a match
of his own with Viswanathan Anand of India, who also passed up the
Las Vegas event.
</P>
<P>
   Anatoly Karpov, the present FIDE champion, is sitting out the
series as well, unhappy that he was not seeded into the finals.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, as a result of a tough, unforgiving knockout format
that did not recognize star power, several other stars _ among them
Vladimir Kramnik of Russia, Alexei Shirov of Spain and Michael
Adams of Britain _ were unexpectedly and unceremoniously brushed
aside during the preliminaries. They played as though they were
overconfident, overreaching on attack and wilting under the
imaginative counterattacks sprung on them by their hungry,
up-and-coming opponents.
</P>
<P>
   The shortness of the elimination matches, only two games before
a high-speed tiebreaker, increased everyone's anxiety. Losing a
single game often let an opponent win by playing conservatively for
a draw in the next game. This system is a far cry from the lengthy
championship matches that were the rule years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But that classical format, in which games were adjourned after
five hours and resumed the next morning, could not be continued
with today's lightning-quick computers to assist overnight
analysis. The present system keeps the human element uppermost.
</P>
<P>
   Akopian, a 27-year-old former world junior champion, emphasizes
positional play, somewhat in the manner of his illustrious Armenian
predecessor, Tigran Petrosion. Creating tentacles of pawns around
his opponent, Akopian often holds back his attack until his prey is
totally imprisoned, then pounces with devastating effect.
</P>
<P>
   Khalifman, 33, is forceful but not a gambler. He will aim for
open positions in which the play of the pieces dominates the
outcome. The sudden sword strike, taking the opponent by surprise,
either winning at once or creating a whole series of blows, is his
method. If he senses a tentacle coming his way, he must cut if off
at once.
</P>
<P>
   The FIDE series, then, is the debut on the championship stage of
two new, relatively unheralded cast members. Does that mean the
event is a disappointment before it starts? Hardly, for it is an
opportunity to watch ambitious, talented players try to prove
themselves under the pressure of high-stakes play.
</P>
<P>
   The games, which begin at 6 p.m. EDT, can be followed at
www.uschess.org.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-99 1512EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
