<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-TURKEY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: AS THE TOLL IN TURKEY RISES 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Sunday, Aug. 22:
</P>
<P>
   It is impossible to grasp the emotional and civil weight of the
death count in Turkey even at present numbers, much less at the
numbers some observers are predicting _ perhaps as many as 40,000
dead. That estimate, if reached, would place this earthquake in the
same category as those that struck Soviet Armenia in 1988, killing
25,000, and Iran in 1990, killing 40,000. The only equivalent for
so much destruction in lives and material in such a short time is
the 20th-century battlefield, and it is one of the premises of
civilized existence, especially in America, that all but those who
have been to war _ a small fraction of society at any time _ should
find the conditions of the battlefield unimaginable.
</P>
<P>
   The Johnstown flood in 1889 and the Galveston hurricane in 1900
are still bywords in this country. Some 2,200 people died in the
flood, 6,000 in the hurricane. There is simply no analogy in recent
American experience that allows our imagination to penetrate the
dimensions of Turkey's suffering. The Turks cannot have fully
grasped it yet themselves.
</P>
<P>
   A number of wholly incommensurate thoughts do occur, though. It
is hard to read the articles or watch the news reports from Turkey
without reflecting on the intricacy and, ultimately, the delicacy
of the interwoven systems, as well as the habits of mind and
behavior, that make up a society. There is water, electricity,
communication, the layout of buildings in the urban grid, political
power, social services, economic interchange, friendship, family.
In the sudden landscape that followed last week's earthquake, all
of that came crashing down, revealing instantly, tragically, what a
lustrous, infinite web ordinary life really is.
</P>
<P>
   It is worth noticing, too, how hard it is to restore any part of
that web from outside. Rescuers have streamed into the cities of
western Turkey only to discover that they are without civil
coherence themselves, much less capable of providing it to the
immediate victims of the quake. Civilization is more local, more
organic, than we tend to remember on this furiously globalizing
planet.
</P>
<P>
   For years to come, researchers will be trying to distinguish
what was natural in this earthquake _ the shock and aftershocks
themselves, a certain inevitable minimum of death in an earthquake
of this scale _ from what was artificial. Death was compounded many
times over by bad construction and violations of building-code
provisions meant to mitigate the effects of earthquakes. It was
compounded still further by an extraordinary lack of disaster
preparation, extraordinary not least of all because Turkey is such
a seismically active region with long experience of crippling
earthquakes. The chaos that has characterized the response to this
disaster suggests that though the popular will is strong, political
will may be one of the things that collapsed last Tuesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The staggering death toll in Turkey may lead some people to
conclude that there is no preparing for a force as abrupt and
unpredictable as a major earthquake, that nature, in some forms, is
simply insuperable and human means inadequate. That would be the
wrong conclusion. It is not a question of stopping earthquakes or
preventing death altogether. It is a question of preventing
needless death, of keeping a city from killing itself when an
earthquake strikes. Nature may be insuperable in some forms, but
human neglect is not.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-99 1513EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990821.0139 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 15:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5131 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-N.Y.-TRANSIT-NYT     08-21 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-N.Y.-TRANSIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: MAKING A TRANSIT WISH LIST REAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Sunday, Aug. 22:
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who lives or works in New York City probably has some
suggestions for what the Metropolitan Transportation Authority
should include in its next five-year building plan. The MTA will
not announce its decisions until October, but it seems committed to
construction of a tunnel connecting the Long Island Rail Road to
Grand Central Terminal. The project, strongly supported by Gov.
George Pataki, would give commuters the option of arriving in
Manhattan on the east side rather than going on to Pennsylvania
Station on the west. But mass-transit advocates say that project
must be coupled with construction of the long-delayed Second Avenue
subway, to relieve overcrowding on the already jammed Lexington
Avenue line.
</P>
<P>
   There is actually not much debate about the value of both
projects, but the MTA chokes on the price tag _ $4 billion for the
LIRR project, including new railroad cars, and $10 billion to $15
billion for the subway, which now exists only as sections of
abandoned tunnel in Harlem. The city's Independent Budget Office
recently questioned whether the MTA, despite recent surpluses, has
the capacity to pay for any major building projects at all without
new sources of money.
</P>
<P>
   To the dismay of mass-transit advocates, the MTA has announced
that it will consider only the option of building a section of the
Second Avenue subway line, from 125th Street to 63rd Street, where
it would connect to the N and R lines. That would be no help to the
thousands of additional commuters coming into Grand Central
Terminal from the new LIRR tunnel, although it might divert some
Upper East Side residents to the N and R lines before they got to
midtown, freeing up space for new riders.
</P>
<P>
   The mass-transit advocates are right about the long-term
importance of a full Second Avenue subway line. The city has been
working hard to keep the major stock exchanges in the financial
district and to spur residential development and new uses for older
office buildings in lower Manhattan. But the potential job growth
will be stunted if the people who live and work there are unable to
get to other parts of the city and the suburbs. Once completed, the
Second Avenue line could be the basis for a major expansion of the
region's entire mass-transit system, as the Regional Plan
Association demonstrated in an imaginative report released earlier
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Over the short term, the MTA plan may be adequate. In the
real-life world of public works, there is no reason that a
truncated Second Avenue subway line could not be the beginning of
the mass-transit advocates' larger goal, particularly if the
suburban commuters dumped off at Grand Central eventually joined
city subway riders in demanding it.
</P>
<P>
   The real issue is one of long-term vision. The current MTA,
which is controlled by Pataki, tends to accept whatever financing
the state provides and then make its plans accordingly. It needs to
be more aggressive, to come up with a capital plan that
acknowledges that the city cannot create new jobs without expanded
transportation services. Once the MTA is committed in principle to
a project like the Second Avenue line, it will be in a stronger
position to lobby the city and state for money to finance it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-99 1514EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
