u k BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-WEALTH-     08-21 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-WEALTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER: A DEBATE OVER WEALTH, VIRTUE AND JUSTICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By STEVEN R. WEISMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the weeks since Congress passed a tax cut that would be the
biggest since the Reagan era if enacted, Republicans have had a
tough time selling the issue politically. President Clinton's
threat to veto the $792 billion tax bill was hardly mentioned at
the recent Iowa straw poll. But the debate among those talking
about the tax cut is revealing. It suggests that class conflict
continues to play a role in American politics, and that politicians
may have to be sensitive to widespread resentment toward those who
have benefited the most from boom times.
</P>
<P>
   Tax-cut advocates are at their most awkward when addressing the
fact that the tax cut showers its benefits on the rich. Their
argument is that, after all, the rich pay the most taxes and thus
should get the most out of a tax cut. ``Heaven forbid somebody
making $500,000 is going to get a greater benefit than somebody
making $10,000,'' Sen. Don Nickles of Oklahoma declared
sarcastically when the bill passed earlier this month. The
conservative National Review asserts that the bill ``cuts
Americans' taxes in roughly the proportion that they bear the tax
burden.'' The magazine adds: ``No, poor people don't get an
income-tax cut in this bill. But then, poor people don't pay
federal income tax.''
</P>
<P>
   That is a misleading formulation because the income tax accounts
for only about half of federal tax revenues. Americans of modest
means may pay little income tax, but they pay heavily with payroll
deductions for Social Security and Medicare, two programs that
Democrats note face insolvency unless the budget surplus is
diverted to shore them up instead of being used to provide tax
relief.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, the Republican tax cut distributes its benefits
disproportionately to the rich, making the tax system less
progressive than it is now. The tax cut is actually an amalgamation
of a 1 percent cut in the income tax rate and additional tax breaks
for student loans, capital gains, estates, health costs and other
expenses. According to the Treasury Department, the wealthiest 20
percent of American taxpayers earn 49 percent of the nation's total
income and pay 59 percent of American taxes, which is logical given
the progressive nature of the tax system. This top tier of earners
would, however, receive 78 percent of the money from the tax cut.
Similarly, the top 1 percent of Americans earn 14 percent of the
nation's income and pay 19 percent of the taxes. But they would get
24 percent of the tax cut money. That is hardly returning their
proportionate share.
</P>
<P>
   Debates about taxes almost always start with who-gets-what and
then jump to larger issues. At what point, for example, do higher
taxes imposed on the rich discourage people from trying to get
rich?
</P>
<P>
   Many tax-cut advocates argue that the progressive income tax is
inherently unfair because it is unjust to punish the energy, hard
work and risk-taking that yield higher incomes. In its most
exaggerated form, the argument is the one advanced by Alan Keyes,
an African-American who is running way behind for the Republican
presidential nomination. He calls the progressive income tax a form
of slavery. Many other politicians join with Steve Forbes in
supporting a flat tax that would eliminate the idea of
progressivity, which has been around since the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   The argument in favor of tax progressivity is that the rich have
a greater ability to pay, and that they benefit the most from
society's blessings and sound government. People who favor higher
taxes for the rich also tend to view wealth as less a matter of
virtuous behavior than the arbitrary nature of life. In this view,
progressivity is not so much to punish the rich as to lessen some
of the unfairness in the way wealth is distributed.
</P>
<P>
   The final argument for a tax cut is that the revenue collected
by the government ``belongs'' to the taxpayer and should be
returned when there is a surplus. But the national debt also
``belongs'' to the taxpayers. So does the obligation to keep Social
Security and Medicare solvent, educate the next generation,
preserve the environment and carry out other government services.
The more that Americans see the debate in these terms, the greater
the chance that they will continue to reject a big tax cut geared
to the wealthy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
