<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGRY WORDS FLUTTER OVER DIXIE  
 FOR VENTURA, ONE HOUSE WILL DO  
 JOSEPH KENNEDY INVESTS WISELY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: S.C., Minn., Neb., Mass.)  (mk) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES JR.    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In South Carolina, where the Civil War started and sometimes
seems never to have quite ended, the fighting has flared up again.
</P>
<P>
   This time, as so often in recent decades, the issue is the
Confederate flag. A hundred thirty-four years after Appomattox, it
still flies over the Capitol dome in Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   Blacks and many New South Southerners see that as a gratuitous
insult. Old South Southerners tend to see it as heritage on parade
and, in some lingering cases, as defiance.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the NAACP called for an economic boycott of
South Carolina, beginning next January, to force the state to
remove the flag. Some organizations planning to hold conventions in
the state have since canceled them even though the boycott has not
officially begun.
</P>
<P>
   But the flag nevertheless has stayed up. Only the state
Legislature can order its removal, and so far a majority of its
members have not been moved by a few convention cancellations.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes Dick Harpootlian, the chairman of the South Carolina
Democratic Party and a flag opponent, with a plan he contends will
break the impasse.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic legislators who want to keep the flag up, he says,
should be singled out for defeat by the party in next year's
primary elections. Without Democratic votes, he argues, Republicans
in the Legislature _ they are the flag's staunchest supporters _
could not muster enough votes to keep it flying.
</P>
<P>
   ``This ought to be the litmus test for candidates,'' he told the
party's executive committee last week. ``We'll take them
individually and beat them. We see the enemy and it is us.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats countered that the enemy was, in fact, ``us'' _
one Dick Harpootlian.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Geddings, the chief of staff to Gov. Jim Hodges, a
Democrat, accused Harpootlian of irresponsible ``political
hyperbole.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This doesn't get us anywhere near a compromise that someday
will bring the flag down,'' Geddings said, alluding to efforts by
the governor to find a middle ground in the flag fight, perhaps by
moving it to a memorial park.
</P>
<P>
   The governor has been working on the issue since the day he took
office, having won election last year when the incumbent
Republican, David Beasley, lost a bid for a second term after
running afoul of both flag proponents and opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Harpootlian, always outspoken, always politically testy, always
spoiling for a fight, said that his only interest was keeping the
party on a course true to its core beliefs and a course that would
build up the party after years of decline.
</P>
<P>
   That was not good enough for state Rep. Marion Carnell of
Greenwood County, one of the pro-flag Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to destroy an already weakened party,'' Carnell
warned.
</P>
<P>
   But it was more than good enough for Republican leaders. They
invited threatened Democrats to join the GOP.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura's Mission: Turning Two Into One
</P>
<P>
   Jesse Ventura says he is tired of talking about whether he would
rather be president than governor of Minnesota. So he is spreading
the word that for the foreseeable future he will grant interviews
only to reporters who want to ask him about his latest Gopher State
project.
</P>
<P>
   Like the governor, it's no ordinary project.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura proposes combining Minnesota's 134-seat House and
67-seat Senate into a single, smaller, 135-seat legislative body in
which candidates would run for office without party labels.
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska is the only one of the 50 states that has a unicameral,
or one-house, legislative system. Members also run without party
labels.
</P>
<P>
   As Ventura sees things, the bicameral, or two-house, system of
legislating is gummed up with partisan bickering and, worst of all,
allows legislators to duck accountability by saying that
shortcomings were caused by members of the other house. He wants
the current two-house Legislature in Minnesota to authorize a
statewide vote next year on whether to rewrite the state's
constitution and shift to a unicameral system.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're at a pivotal point,'' he declared last week as he
barnstormed the state to promote his idea. ``The people aren't
satisfied with politics as usual.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, old professional wrestler that he is, he flexed some
muscle, got up into some faces and warned that he would work hard
against any legislators who resisted putting 66 legislative jobs on
the chopping block, their own in many cases.
</P>
<P>
   Other governors have fought this fight without success, both in
Minnesota and several other states. Should Ventura succeed,
Minnesota would see the biggest structural change in its government
since it joined the Union in 1858.
</P>
<P>
   Don't count out Ventura, the Reform Party's highest-ranking
elected official, on this far-reaching reform. Minnesotans like
their politics different, even quirky, Ventura being living proof.
Besides, he has powerful allies in the fight, among them the House
speaker, Steve Sviggum of Kenyon.
</P>
<P>
   Sviggum says he would be comfortable running for a seat in a
single-house legislature and, he adds, he especially likes the idea
of campaigning not as a member of any party (he's a Republican) but
``as the individual _ who you are, what your principles are, what
you stand for.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the powerful opponents of the Ventura proposal is the
Senate majority leader, Roger Moe, a member of the
Democratic-Farmer-Labor Party from Erskine. Also in the fight is a
newly organized bipartisan group of lobbyists, lawyers, legislators
and former legislators that calls itself OUCH, as in Opponents of a
Unicameral House.
</P>
<P>
   The group's founder, state Rep. Dave Bishop of Rochester, a
Republican, contends a unicameral legislature would not have as
much healthy give and take as a bicameral legislature and would
concentrate power in the hands of just a few members. He says his
side faces a particularly tough battle because the state's most
outspoken political leader, Ventura, is leading the charge from the
other side.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Jesse,'' he laments, ``it's got legs.''
</P>
<P>
   A Campaign Fund Keeps Growing
</P>
<P>
   When Rep. Joseph Kennedy II of Massachusetts retired last year
and returned to his nonprofit company, which distributes cheap
heating oil to the poor, he had $1.4 million in his re-election
campaign fund, an impressive amount for a House member. Under
campaign finance rules, he could have given the money to charity,
used it to help elect other Democrats or salted it away for some
future charitable or political use.
</P>
<P>
   He chose to salt it away, raising speculation anew that sooner
or later he might get back into politics, maybe to run for
governor.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever.
</P>
<P>
   This much is already clear: Like the Kennedy he is named for,
former Rep. Kennedy knows how to make a buck, or at least how to
find someone who can make a buck for him.
</P>
<P>
   He handed the $1.4 million over to a Massachusetts investment
manager, who, according to The Boston Herald, put it into a mixed
portfolio of stocks, bonds and Treasury bills and in the first six
months of this year increased its value by more than 30 percent, to
$1.85 million.
</P>
<P>
   In that same period, the Standard &AMP; Poor's index of 500 popular
stocks, a major market measure, rose about 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, campaign funds are invested in certificates of deposit
to minimize risk. The return on them is typically around 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The rich get richer....
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
