<SLUG> BC-BBO-DROPOUT-ART-1200(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPTING OUT OF THE PROS FOR A REC-LEAGUE LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, N.Y.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By ALAN SCHWARZ    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Shards of broken beer bottles pop beneath their feet
as players from the Dark Side, a recreation-league softball team in
the Bronx, mill about their bench early on an August Sunday. Their
field is a concrete blacktop enclosed by a 12-foot chain-link
fence, base markings painted on the pavement, the only grass in
sight a few weeds poking through the cracks. As Mike Marchena
watches his teammate George Carrion, the shortstop, he can't help
but wonder, ``Man, what are you doing here?''
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, Carrion was one of the best high school baseball
prospects to come out of New York in 20 years, a hard-throwing
pitcher and power-hitting shortstop from the Bronx's De Witt
Clinton High. After one season at a Texas junior college, the Texas
Rangers signed him to a contract with a $700,000 bonus to play in
their minor league system.
</P>
<P>
   Yet last summer, Carrion abruptly quit. He bolted from the
Rangers with neither warning nor explanation, drove home to Yonkers
(where he had bought his family a five-bedroom house) and has been,
in his words, ``just hanging out with buddies'' ever since. The
22-year-old Carrion sleeps till noon most days, goes to nightclubs
on weekends and, five or six times a week, plays rec-league
softball for a half-dozen teams around the Bronx. His mother,
Margie Carrion, said recently, ``Not a day goes by when I don't
want to strangle that kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Blithely explaining that ``I wasn't having fun anymore'' with
the Rangers, Carrion said he might want to return to pro ball
someday, but Texas officials, already taken for that $700,000, said
they would be very reluctant to have him back. Meanwhile, he lives
off what's left of the bonus money. Recent purchases include a new,
loaded Lexus for $40,000, a mammoth diamond crucifix necklace
(``just for the fashion'') and a cell phone that rings the 1812
Overture.
</P>
<P>
   Almost daily, Carrion watches baseball highlights on the
television in his basement bedroom and comes across a former minor
league teammate or opponent who has reached the big leagues. Dozens
of empty rum, tequila and beer bottles, sharing his shelves with
his youth-league baseball trophies, form an eerie skyline as they
ring the room.
</P>
<P>
   Even the Rangers consider George Carrion a good-natured kid who
wouldn't hurt anyone _ except maybe himself. A true bonus baby.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of feel sorry for him,'' said Reid Nichols, the
Rangers' director of player development. ``There's a million people
who would love to trade places with him and be in his position to
have a chance to play in the big leagues. And he turned his back on
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The $700,000 bonus, in many ways, sabotaged Carrion's career
from the start. The Rangers paid him that much in part to get him
to give up shortstop _ a position at which they believed he had no
major league promise _ and to focus on pitching, where his
97-mile-an-hour fastball made him a potential ace. The two sides
agreed that Carrion would pitch full time while getting 50 at-bats
a month during the 1996 and 1997 seasons, after which he would
pitch only.
</P>
<P>
   His first summer at Port Charlotte in the rookie-level Gulf
Coast League, Carrion performed well on the mound (a 2-0 record and
1.76 ERA) and at the plate (a .309 batting average) but complained
of shoulder pain in August. He later had surgery for a torn labrum.
He struggled the following season at rookie-level Pulaski in the
Appalachian League, posting a 4.74 ERA and .198 batting average,
and last year he was miserable during his first summer of pitching
exclusively.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost my love for it because I wasn't playing every day,''
Carrion said this month. ``I wasn't having fun pitching and sitting
on the bench.''
</P>
<P>
   When he is hitting, ``I know I can mess up one day and the next
day go out there and make up for it,'' he said. ``Pitching, you get
lit up one night, you got to wait four more nights to go out there
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Compounding Carrion's malaise were the deaths of two close
family members. His great-grandfather died in May 1996 while George
was playing in the Junior College World Series, and the following
April, his cousin and best friend, Louie Lebron, was killed in an
automobile accident. His mother recalled Carrion saying, ``Every
time I go away, something happens.''
</P>
<P>
   On June 18 of last year, Carrion had a 5-5 record and a 5.65 ERA
for the Class A Savannah Sand Gnats when he yielded 10 runs in just
two-thirds of an inning against the Augusta Greenjackets. He
trudged to the clubhouse, iced his shoulder on a couch and pondered
the worst outing of his career. ``I went out there and I had
nothin','' he said. ``I just got lit up. I don't know, I just
didn't want to sit on the bench for four more days thinking about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   When Carrion's roommate and closest friend on the team, Emar
Fleming, later found Carrion's belongings cleared out of their
hotel room, he pounded on the door of manager Paul Carey. Both
feared Carrion might have committed suicide. Only after enlisting
the help of the Augusta, Ga., police did they learn that Carrion
had paid a local taxi company $200 to drive him three hours back to
Savannah, where he packed the rest of his things and began driving
to New York, crying for much of the trip.
</P>
<P>
   He rang the doorbell in Yonkers at 4:30 the following morning.
His stepfather, Michael O'Farrell, recalled having the following
exchange:
</P>
<P>
   ``What the hell are you doing here?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I quit.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you mean, you quit?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not happy with it no more.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You're kidding me, right?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ever since then,'' O'Farrell said, ``here he is.''
</P>
<P>
   Carrion has had almost no contact with the Rangers since. Last
September, he agreed by telephone to pitch in the team's fall
instructional league program, but he did not show up. Legally, he
can keep the bonus money, and when asked whether he will return any
of it, he laughed and responded, ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   Carey, the Savannah manager, believes that Carrion could have
made far more than $700,000 had he stayed with the team. ``He was
getting his strength back,'' Carey said recently. ``I think he
could have been a successful big leaguer _ at least a million
dollars a year.'' The Mets' assistant general manager, Omar Minaya,
who scouted Carrion in high school for the Rangers, remembered
Carrion's talent as being similar to that of ``a young Pedro
Martinez.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Carrion is living at home with no plan to go to school
or get a job. ``Someday it'll come to that,'' he said, relaxing on
one of his room's leather couches. ``Go out there, have to find a
9-to-5 or something.'' His stepfather, who sells subway tokens at
the nearby Fordham Road station, has given up trying to guide him.
``You can't babysit him all his life,'' O'Farrell said. ``He comes
up with all different excuses, and I say, `All right, that's your
decision, that's your choice, but 10 years down the line I don't
want to hear you going, when you've got that dreary job doing
nothing, `That could have been me, that could have been me.' ''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Carrion once showed tremendous commitment to baseball. In his
teens, when he lived at 198th Street and Grand Concourse in the
Bronx, he rode the D train an hour to Brooklyn every day to play in
the Youth Service League, whose alumni include Manny Ramirez,
Shawon Dunston and seven other major league players. Carrion woke
up at 6 a.m. on weekends and went every day after school to play as
many games as he could. His mitt had the words ``Hard Work,''
``Think'' and ``Dedication'' written on the leather.
</P>
<P>
   He gave a professional career little mind, instead letting the
Youth Service League's director, Mel Zitter, become his negotiator
when major league scouts came calling. The Rangers selected Carrion
in the seventh round of the 1995 amateur draft and offered him
$100,000; Zitter persuaded him to attend Northeast Texas Community
College for one year to live away from home before turning pro.
</P>
<P>
   Pat Rigby, a Rangers scout, had a year, until midnight the
following June 3, to sign Carrion before the team lost his rights.
At 10:30 that night Rigby negotiated the $700,000 bonus with
Zitter. But when Zitter phoned Carrion to arrange a formal signing
to beat the deadline, he wasn't home. He was ``hanging out on the
street, where I was born and raised,'' Carrion recalled with a
proud smile.
</P>
<P>
   When Carrion returned at 11, he called Zitter, who hastily drove
to the Bronx, scooped up Carrion and drove him to a Ramada Inn in
Queens, where the contract was signed at 11:50 p.m. Rangers general
manager Doug Melvin declared at the time, ``The one thing about him
is we're getting another player who loves to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Zitter and Carrion, once as close as father and son, no longer
speak. Carrion declined to comment on why. Zitter said:
``Apparently, he doesn't want to talk to me. I think he knows if he
talked to me, I'll try to talk him into going back.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``Inner city kids bring something to the table that
other kids don't, emotionally. They have a desire to compete, for
competition. But they have lags as far as dealing with discipline
and trusting people. Kids from the city, in many ways they're a lot
older than they are, and in many ways younger than they are.''
</P>
<P>
   Fleming, who speaks with Carrion every few weeks, said that
Carrion has told him he wants to return to the Rangers. Carrion
said that maybe he would call them someday. But Nichols said he
would not necessarily welcome him back: ``I think I would be very
guarded. I don't think he'll play for us again.'' The Rangers, for
fear he will sign with another team, will also not release Carrion
from his contract.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Carrion continues to play softball. He helped his
Dark Side team reach its rec-league championship series, showing a
strong arm at shortstop and power at the plate. ``I'm happy to have
him on the team,'' right fielder Josh Hollander said. ``Hey, it
worked out well for us.'' Carrion does not keep track of his
batting average and said he preferred it that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day I tell him: `Why can't you go back? Why don't you go
back?' '' Margie Carrion said, shaking her head. ``Especially when
I see him getting up to play softball at 7 o'clock on weekends.
`Why can you go play softball and not baseball?' He doesn't want to
talk about it. I'm just hoping he doesn't wake up and it's too
late.''
</P>
<P>
   Said George, with his ever-present grin: ``You only live once.
We'll see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, outside the house, Carrion was asked whether he would
reach the major leagues if he returned to the Rangers. As the
family dog barked from the doorway, he did not hesitate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll make it,'' he said. ``It ain't that tough, really. You
just have to go out there and work hard. I ain't afraid of doing
that. Not really.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
