<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 16:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5152 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-CAR-NASCARSERIES2-COX     08-21 1373
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCARSERIES2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Second is a series on the early days of NASCAR
 &HT;    Jack Smith: Winner with every stock
 &HT;    By Al Levine
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SPARTANBURG, S.C. _ The bays are full at Jack Smith's Automatic
Transmission Center on Main Street. Which leads one to conclude
that the roads around here are tough on gears or it's the only shop
in town.
</P>
<P>
   Or perhaps it's simply because the customers like to come to the
office to gape at the pictures, hammered into the walls, of Jack
Smith's racing career.
</P>
<P>
   Talking about the races with Smith, that's another thing. You've
got to contend with the whining of electric wrenches and the
hacking of Smith's persistent bronchial cough.
</P>
<P>
   On July 3, 1997, Smith had a heart attack. ``Had five-way bypass
surgery,'' he said. The congestive heart failure now turns a common
cold into a bronchial ordeal. ``It makes everything 10 times worse.
I'm OK, long as I don't talk.''
</P>
<P>
   The 75-year-old Smith still comes in the office nearly every
day, although his son, Lance, runs the shop. Business is good. ``I
thought when I made my first million I'd have it made,'' Smith
said. ``Then I found out how many people I owed.''
</P>
<P>
   Except for the occasional bronchial attack, life also is good.
There's just one thing that nags at Smith. ``I ought to be in that
Hall of Fame,'' he said. He's talking about the Georgia Sports Hall
of Fame, whose enshrinees include just two racers, Tim Flock and
Bill Elliott, despite the state's rich history in stock cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not the only one that's been overlooked,'' Smith said. But
he is the best spokesman for his candidacy, which any elector can
read about in one of the 11 career scrapbooks that Smith put
together for his children and grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Notes kept on every race
</P>
<P>
   From a race at Charlotte: ``I led 193 of the 400 laps and was
five laps ahead of the second-place car when disaster struck. A
large chunk of asphalt tore a hole in my fuel tank; gasoline came
pouring out. We tried stuffing rags into the hole and even tried
Camay soap. If we would have had a bar of Octagon soap, it would
have plugged the hole. I would have never believed that a bar of
soap could be worth over $25,000.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith was in 263 NASCAR races 1949-64, winning 21 times and
$139,470. He finished fourth in points once and fifth twice. He was
the Most Popular Driver in 1959.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could go run in Atlanta, a 25- or 30- or 50-lap race right
near home (Sandy Springs) and make $500,'' Smith said. ``Like Tim
(Flock) _ he'd get in his car or ride with somebody in a tow truck,
go all the way to Bangor, Maine, to run a race that paid $800. I'd
run the Peach Bowl in Atlanta, make $500 and it didn't cost me $3
for gas and oil to run and to get there and back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tim won the championship in 1952, and I won more races and
more money right in the Peach Bowl, way down there on Howell Mill
Road.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith ran in hundreds more races in the modifieds, which he
preferred, with great success. He won 31 races in a row in a 1953
Studebaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't run a whole lot of these Grand National Races until
1955,'' he said. ``I hated to get in the car. I wanted to get in
that old modified and spin them wheels and have them rooster tails
(spray of dirt) coming off the back.''
</P>
<P>
   He got interested in racing while growing up near Dawsonville
and Dahlonega.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where all the whiskey was made at,'' Smith said.
``These two boys, Roy Hall and Lloyd Seay, would come down through
there, stop in Buckhead and tell the police, `We'll be back across
the Kellogg Creek bridge at 7:09.' They'd tell them when they would
come back with a load, just for the chase, just for the fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who went into racing from those parts was suspected of
hauling illegal liquor during Prohibition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody said if you're not a whiskey hauler, you can't drive
a race car,'' Smith said. ``People would tell me that, and it would
make me that much madder. So I built up a '34 Ford and went racing.
I didn't haul any whiskey. My boss man wouldn't let somebody do
that. His car ran at Lakewood Park in Atlanta. They had a city
ordinance that after you've been convicted you couldn't run
Lakewood. There were lots of them that couldn't run at Lakewood.''
</P>
<P>
   The scrapbook contains so many nuggets.
</P>
<P>
   Setting speed records
</P>
<P>
   He drove a solid red Chevrolet in 1959 that was called the Red
Fox. ``Buddy Davenport, who used to announce all the races, would
say, `Now, when that Red Fox gets out in front, them hound dogs are
gonna have a hard time catchin' it,''' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, headlines called Smith the ``World's Fastest Stock
Car Driver,'' because he set speed records in a Pontiac at Daytona
in a five-mile qualifying run, 25-mile race, 100-mile race and a
250-mile race, averaging 146 mph. ``Ain't nobody ever heard of
anything like that,'' he said. ``I just went flat out.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith was the first driver with radio controls in his car,
although it initially had one major glitch: Besides his crew chief,
Smith would constantly get directions from the dispatcher at a
Coca-Cola plant near the Charlotte Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a 12-lap lead at Charlotte on account of that radio,''
Smith said. ``I was coming by the start/finish line, and they said
`Wreck in (turn) number four, wreck in number four,' and, `Wreck
comin' off two, wreck comin' off two.' I knew right where it was
at; I could run up there and brake and drive down through there
where everybody else didn't know where the wreck was. It was a
crude setup. If you wanted to talk to somebody, you mashed your
dimmer switch and talked into the radio speaker. Everybody had them
within three weeks time.''
</P>
<P>
   Newspaper stories also called him ``The Original Hard Luck
Guy,'' for destroying three race cars in less than three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1958 Southern 500 at Darlington, he got into some oil
after Jim Reed blew an engine, smashed into the scaffolding
surrounding the track, went up and over the railing and landed
car-nose-down in sand.
</P>
<P>
   ``This happened on a Monday,'' Smith said. ``Sunday, I'm leading
the race and gone. They motioned for me to come in, and I backed
off of it and started coming into the pits. When I did I blowed the
right front tire, went through the fence. Back then they had them
old 2-x-10 oak fences. One of the boards had my head pushed up
against the roll bar. Well, we come back and got another car. This
is a second brand-new automobile. The next Sunday we were running
in Nashville. Rex White was leading; I was running second; he blows
a right front tire and tore up the prettiest little ol' car you
ever seen. I was sitting there riding around while they got it
cleaned up, thinking how pitiful that was. Well, eight laps later,
I put mine through the wall. I demolished three cars in 11 or 12
days.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith's worst racing injury was a cut nose.
</P>
<P>
   He owned his own car, worked for factory teams and was one of
the drivers that Carl Kiekhaefer hired as the sport's first
multi-car owner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a transmission shop (in Atlanta) before I went to work
for Kiekhaefer,'' Smith said. ``There was no amount of money I
could make in a garage that I was making with Kiekhafer. He paid us
$1,100 a month salary in 1957. You think that wasn't some money?
And he paid you so much a meal from the time you left home till you
got back. If you left home on Friday at 12 o'clock, every four
hours he paid you. It wasn't but a dollar and half for a meal. That
added up, back then, seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Old race fans come in the shop now _ it was his race shop during
his career _ to talk about the good old days. Smith is happy to
oblige.
</P>
<P>
   ``A man come in the shop, and he said if he had been in the
grandstand that day in Charlotte (when a chunk of asphalt caused a
gas leak), he would've fixed us up, and we would have won the race.
He went to his car and got out a gallon of gas, reached into his
pocket for a little thing, rolled it out just a little bit, put gas
halfway in there, tied a knot in it, and for 40 minutes it didn't
drop a drop.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a condom. I never dreamed _ gas don't bother a
condom.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
