<HEADER>
A5153 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-R-BBO-TOMS-RIVER-ART-     08-21 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-BBO-TOMS-RIVER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITTLE LEAGUE'S SECOND SERIES IS JUST AS SWEET IN TOMS RIVER
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Refiling to include photo note.) 
(ATTN: Ala., N.J., Pa.)  (ART ADV: Photois being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
may make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By MARIA NEWMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service      
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOMS RIVER, N.J. _ The day after the hometown Boys of Summer
landed once again in the Little League World Series, a handful of
fathers, members of the Toms River East Little League board,
huddled over a long table at the league's headquarters and planned
another parade down Main Street.
</P>
<P>
   If the team of mostly 12-year-olds returns victorious from
Williamsport, Pa., where the series begins on Sunday, the world
title will be its second in a row, but it will be no less exciting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was telling someone yesterday that winning the series last
year was a once-in-a-lifetime opportunity,'' said Kevin Fox, a vice
president of the board who is trying to raise $70,000 for a bronze
sculpture of a ballplayer with his coach to commemorate last year's
victory. ``But I guess we're going to break that old saying.''
</P>
<P>
   As he spoke, Fox stood inside the league's new $150,000 indoor
practice center with batting cages, pitching areas and televisions
to show videos during clinics. It was built with donations to allow
for training in the winter.
</P>
<P>
   With its 3-0 victory over Middleboro, Mass., on Thursday, Toms
River became just the third team in the United States to return to
the Little League World Series the year after winning the title.
Lock Haven, Pa., did so in 1948-49, and Long Beach, Calif., did in
1992-93.
</P>
<P>
   To say that people in this Ocean County community were jubilant
would be an understatement. On Thursday night, hundreds of people
crowded into Mugsy's, a sports bar on Hooper Avenue, to watch the
game on ESPN. Those who did not find room here watched it at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just incredible,'' said Anthony Baiamonte, owner of
Mugsy's, which calls itself the unofficial headquarters of the
team. ``We need some new adjectives _ that's how good these kids
are.''
</P>
<P>
   No one could explain what it is about Toms River, a suburb that
is part of Dover Township, a community of 90,000, that produced
winners two years in a row.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it's the water,'' Chuck Friesema, an electrician who was
having a drink at Mugsy's, said about Toms River, which until last
year was best known as the possible site of a cancer cluster. ``I
don't know if it's the kids who take it more seriously here, or if
it's the coaching, and the parents just enjoy doing it and living
vicariously through the kids,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor of Dover Township, Raymond P. Fox (no relation to
Kevin, the board vice president), had another explanation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just great people, and a great town,'' he said at his
office in the township hall, where pictures of last year's victory
are plastered along the hallways. ``Certainly our Little League
organizations are the best around. And our schools, too. The Toms
River regional school system is one of the best in the state.''
</P>
<P>
   Baseball is definitely a big deal here, but so are other sports,
the mayor pointed out. There are two leagues here, Toms River with
600 players, and Toms River East, with 1,200, which is sending a
team of its all-stars to the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   The town's soccer leagues actually have more players, and there
is also a girls' softball league, a Pop Warner football league and
Biddy Basketball.
</P>
<P>
   But obviously, Little League is king right now. The Toms River
East Little League, with headquarters on Windsor Avenue, has an
annual budget of $200,000.
</P>
<P>
   The fields here look like those tucked into a thousand other
suburban communities, but the grass seems lusher and some of the
fields are lighted for nighttime play. The indoor center opened in
February.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to have this if we're going to compete against teams
from California and Puerto Rico who can play all year long,'' said
Fox, the Little League board member, who is also a United Airlines
pilot. ``The season here only runs from June, when practice begins,
to late August, if the teams make the finals.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, the Town Council donated a four-acre parcel to the
league to expand its playing area.
</P>
<P>
   Fox and Stan Benisz, another board member, conceded that some of
the parents might be living vicariously through their sons and
daughters. But the team could not succeed without the parents, who
volunteer to fill every job from coaching to managing the
concession stands.
</P>
<P>
   Some parents take leaves of absence from their jobs to follow
the children around, said Benisz, who said it is not uncommon for
some parents on the board to put in 500 or 600 hours a year on team
business.
</P>
<P>
   It is all worth it, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of last year we kept saying to ourselves: `How are you
going to top this? How are we going to top this?''' said Gary
Goldsack, president of the league board. ``Well, we just found out
how.''
</P>
<P>
   In Williamsport, where the team will play Phenix City, Ala., on
Sunday at 6 p.m., Mike Gaynor, manager of the Toms River East
Americans Little League team, was reflecting on what made his team
a winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got good players,'' he said. ``They've done a nice job. When
we needed to win, we found a way to win. I guess I'm doing
something right.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think any time you have a Little League team with
12-year-olds, as much talent as you have, you never know how the
kids are going to handle the pressure. You really don't learn the
chemistry until you start playing. And hopefully, you're not losing
games in the meantime before you find out what you need.''
</P>
<P>
   What captures the imagination of the townspeople is that the
boys are so young, and they play with such fervor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids are psyched,'' said Darren Lardieri, who has a
woodworking business here and has been following the team, even
though he has no children on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not thinking about whether they get hurt or their
contracts, like the professional athletes are. These kids, they'll
take the chance. They'll do what it takes to win. It makes the
whole game nicer.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, when the Little Leaguers won the World Series,
townspeople by the thousands lined up along Route 37, one of the
community's main thoroughfares, from the Garden State Parkway to
downtown. Route 37 had to be closed for a few hours. A few days
later, the town held an official parade for them.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the team and the township leaders are planning only
one parade, on the day the players return from the finals in
Williamsport, whether they win or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt about it,'' the Mayor said. ``Win, lose or
draw, they're champions anyway, as far as we're concerned.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
