<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jarrett eager for Pepsi 400 victory
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Brooklyn, Mich. _ Dale Jarrett returns today to Michigan
Speedway, the very same track he threatened to reach Winston Cup's
ultimate single-event achievement two months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett, the points leader who will start third in today's Pepsi
400, had the season's most dominant performance by a driver during
the circuit's last stop at the two-mile oval. During the ride to
victory lane at June's Kmart 400, Jarrett briefly threatened to lap
the field, which has not been accomplished on track longer than a
mile in more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   The Ford No. 88 driver led by as many as nine seconds during the
race. Only four other drivers were on the lead lap when Jarrett
crossed the finish line. Jarrett is back in same Ford Taurus for
today's race, but does not necessarily expect the same outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about this racin' is that even though you may have a
great car at a track one time, you go back the next time and you
might take everything the same,'' Jarrett said, ``and it doesn't
work the same.''
</P>
<P>
   The last driver to lap the field on a superspeedway was Kyle
Petty at the then-Charlotte Motor Speedway in 1987. The last to do
it on a short track was Geoffrey Bodine at North Wilkesboro, N.C.,
(0.625 mile) in '94.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a once in a lifetime thing for most people,'' recalled
Petty. ``Even when you look at the season (Bill) Elliott had in
'85, and how much stronger he was than everybody else and how great
they ran week after week, he did it just (once on a short track).
Mere mortals have a shot at it once in a lifetime.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett's final margin of victory in the June race was .505
seconds, but runner-up Jeff Gordon said that was only because
Jarrett choose to not make it larger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just rode around out there most of the day,'' Gordon said.
``We were so strung out that I couldn't see the leader and third
place (Jeff Burton) couldn't see me. The only time that's any fun
is when you're leading.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett, in his usual humble mood on Saturday, downplayed his
chances of lapping the field at the last Michigan race or any
future race.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way that is going to happen is basically if you catch
somebody in the pits and a caution flag comes out,'' Jarrett said.
``That's the only way to get everybody a lap down. ``Just doing it
on the race track, that was the best car I've ever had (at the
Kmart 400), and there were still four guys on the lead lap with us.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Jarrett's father Ned is well-remembered for lapping
the field. The former Winston Cup great won the '65 Darlington race
by a shocking 14 laps over the runner-up. Those days are long gone
and so are the chances of winning by a single lap, many drivers
say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is close to impossible,'' Dale Jarrett said.
``There are just so many good cars out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Pepsi 400 pole sitter Ward Burton, ``They'd have to have a
perfect car, perfect pit stops, just a totally perfect day. The
thing is nowadays you'd have to do all of that just to have a
chance at winning the race at all, (much less) lapping the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
