<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Middle Ga. stage for overlooked
 &HT;    By Guy Curtright
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COCHRAN, Ga. _ The football budget is so small at Middle Georgia
College that it would barely cover training-room expenses at some
big-time schools.
</P>
<P>
   Despite limited funds and no full athletic scholarships,
however, Middle Georgia has gone to three junior- college bowl
games since resuming football in 1994 and has sent more than 90
players on to four-year colleges.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-three players from last year's team signed scholarships
with four-year schools, including 18 of 20 who played at Middle
Georgia for two seasons. Leading the way was linebacker Kendrell
Bell, a Georgia signee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're here to give players a chance who didn't have the grades
or were overlooked for some other reason,'' said coach Randy
Pippin, who won a 1994 junior-college title at Trinity Valley in
Texas. ``If things had gone right for these kids, they won't be
here.''
</P>
<P>
   Middle Georgia was ranked as high as No. 2 in the nation last
year, but then had to forfeit two games because of an ineligible
player and were upset by rival Georgia Military College 13-6 in the
regular-season finale. The Warriors bounced back to rout Northwest
Mississippi 41-3 in the Mineral Water Bowl, finishing 9-3 and
ranked No. 11.
</P>
<P>
   Middle Georgia's success has come despite a buget that has
usually been below $100,000 and a taxing road schedule that eats up
a good part of the funds. With only one other junior-college
program in the state, the Warriors will make two trips by bus to
Texas this season and one each to New York, Maryland and North
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Pippin is the only member of the 10-man staff paid for coaching,
and he also is the athletics director. Several assistants are dorm
directors. Other are volunteers, including former Kansas City
Chiefs defensive back Jim Marsalis, who drives from his home in
Warner Robins each day.
</P>
<P>
   More than 150 players _ including four from Class AAAA state
champ Valdosta _ turned out for practice this season, making
equipment scarce. Middle Georgia receives hand-me-downs from
several colleges, and the Atlanta Falcons have donated game pants
and jersies; the Warriors' colors are red and black, too.
</P>
<P>
   At least Middle Georgia now has its own place to play. A
3,000-seat stadium just off campus opened last year, thanks in part
to a $100,000 donation by alumnus Doyle NeSmith Sr. Lights will be
in place before Middle Georgia's home-opener Sept. 11 against
Navarro of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Walker, who had signed with Auburn, naturally was
disappointed when he didn't qualify academically. But the freshman
from Hardaway High School in Columbus is trying to make the best of
the situation. ``There is a lot of talent here,'' Walker said. ``We
just want a chance to show what we can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
