<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 16:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5169 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-FBC-GIRLPLAYER-COX     08-21 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GIRLPLAYER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Middle Georgia gets a kick from Butler
 &HT;    By Guy Curtright
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COCHRAN, Ga. _ Even on a team that started practice with 152
football hopefuls of all sizes and shapes, one player stands out at
Middle Georgia College.
</P>
<P>
   The new placekicker is the one with the ponytail, a leggy photo
in Atlanta magazine and, temporarily, a whole dorm to herself.
</P>
<P>
   At Middle Georgia, the football team is co-ed, but student
housing isn't. That's why freshman Tonya Butler has spent most of
the last two weeks sleeping alone in a girl's dorm that at times
has seemed as eerie as a haunted house.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kinda creepy in there all by myself,'' Butler said after
a recent practice. ``I'll be glad when the other students get here.
I guess it might get a little noisy then, but right now it's too
quiet.''
</P>
<P>
   All of that will change soon.
</P>
<P>
   Classes begin Monday at Middle Georgia, a junior college of
2,000 students about 40 miles southeast of Macon.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Butler will make her junior college football debut,
handling the extra point and field goal attempts when the Warriors
open the season at Kilgore, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope they don't look at the roster and notice my name,''
said Butler, who got so much coverage in high school that teammates
called her ``Miss Hollywood'' for a while. ``It sure would be nice
if they wouldn't make a big deal about me being a girl, because
I'll be nervous enough as it is. But by now, I guess I should be
used to all the attention.''
</P>
<P>
   Middle Georgia has won 40 games, been ranked as high as No. 2
nationally and gone to three bowl games since resuming football in
1994 after a 35-year absence. But all that winning didn't create
the attention that signing a female kicker did.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had people calling from everywhere after we signed Tonya,''
said coach Randy Pippin, in his second season. ``For us, it's a
win-win situation. The publicity is nice, but that's not why she's
here. She's here to help us win games, and she will.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone here hopes to earn a scholarship to an NCAA school,
and I think Tonya will. She's that good of a kicker.''
</P>
<P>
   In three seasons at Riverdale High School in Clayton County,
Butler made 112 of 119 extra points and 17 of 30 field-goal
attempts while receiving all-state mention and earning a spot in
the Georgia Athletic Coaches Association North-South All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   But no female ever has received a football scholarship to a
four-year school, so Butler had to go off to junior college to
prove herself again. ``I knew I was good enough to keep kicking,''
said Butler, whose brother, Tony, is a senior linebacker at Georgia
Southern.
</P>
<P>
   The only female to kick for a four-year college in a
regular-season game was Liz Heaston of Willamette University, an
NAIA school in Oregon. She was 2 of 4 on extra points in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Heather Sue Mercer tried out at Duke and kicked a field goal in
the Blue Devils' 1995 spring game. But she didn't make the team and
filed a sex-discrimination suit that is still pending.
</P>
<P>
   When Middle Georgia players first heard that the school was
recruiting Butler, they feared the worst. ``Everyone wanted to know
what the heck was going on,'' sophomore wide receiver Daniel
O'Brien said. ``Our goal here is to win a national title. No one
was interested in striking a blow for women's lib or something.''
</P>
<P>
   But once Butler arrived on campus and her new teammates got a
chance to see her kick, the Middle Georgia players were won over
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Damn, she can kick,'' O'Brien said after several practices,
still marveling at Butler's accuracy. ``Last season, we missed a
lot of extra points. If she can help us win games, what difference
does it make if she's a girl? To us, she's just a kicker.''
</P>
<P>
   Casey Sirmons kicked for Middle Georgia last season, but he
broke his foot helping to lay carpet for his father just before the
start of practice. The sophomore from West Laurens High School is
expected to miss the first half of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonya is coming along real good,'' said volunteer kicking
coach Mickey McPhaul, who played at Middle Georgia in the
mid-1950s. ``I never thought I'd be working with a girl, but then
when I played we didn't even lift weights. Times change.''
</P>
<P>
   Butler, who worked on her kicking all summer, said she has
adjusted to kicking without the tee allowed in high school. But she
said it has cut her top range from up to 50 yards to about 40.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to build my range back up,'' said Butler, who is 5 feet
6 and 130 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   But she said that most of her adjusting has had to come away
from the field. Cochran, with a population of 4,390, is not like
being in metro Atlanta, and she has college classes to get used to
and new friends to make.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've already made the rule that I won't date teammates,'' said
Butler, who has her college costs covered by a Hope Scholarship and
other grants.
</P>
<P>
   Butler, a member of the homecoming court in high school, had
hoped that the August issue of Atlanta magazine with her posing in
a miniskirt for an article titled ``Nothing Beats a Great Pair of
Legs'' wouldn't make it to Cochran.
</P>
<P>
   She was wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got here, one of the coaches already had a copy,''
Butler said. ``I don't know if any of the players have seen it yet,
but at least no one has given me a hard time yet. Really, the skirt
wasn't as short as it looked. I promise.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
