<HEADER>
A5170 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-FBC-TARHEELS-COX     08-21 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TARHEELS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tarheels have plenty of young talent
 &HT;    By Norman Arey
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHAPEL HILL, N.C. _ Ronald Curry was a huge disappointment last
year during his freshman season at North Carolina. The shooting
guard averaged only 2.8 points per game, managed just 1.7 assists
and grabbed 1.5 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Oh yeah, that was basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Curry was a huge success last year during his freshman
season on the football field. The 18-year-old quarterback from
Hampton, Va., perhaps the highest profile athlete ever coming out
of high school, threw for 975 yards and six touchdowns and rushed
419 yards and two other scores in leading the Tar Heels to a 7-5
season. Curry was voted the MPV in Carolina's 20-13 win over San
Diego State in the Las Vegas Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The two-sport athlete was as big a success in football as he was
a flop in basketball. The fact that he was forced into football
action when Oscar Davenport was injured in the season opener and
wasn't counted on to contribute much in basketball may have had a
lot to do with his first year in Chapel Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I surprised a lot of people last year,'' Curry said. ``I think
the coaches were just planning on using me as a punt returner.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ronald's not just an athlete, he's a great quarterback,'' said
Carolina offensive coordinator Steve Marshall. ``I't s a
semi-insult, to my way of thinking, to call him an athlete.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ronald's much, much improved,'' said coach Carl Torbush.
``He's in complete command of our offense now. Over the past 10
practices, he's throwing the ball as well as anybody I've seen here
in 12 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Torbush admits that having Curry does have its drawbacks. ``We
tried to sign quarterbacks last year and nobody wanted to come,''
he said. ``We've absolutely got to sign one for next season. You
can't operate a program with just two quarterbacks.''
</P>
<P>
   Curry is backed up by redshirt freshman Luke Huard. Behind Huard
is no one.
</P>
<P>
   Carolina opens its season against arch-rival Virginia in a
strange scheduling year in the ACC. But the Tar Heels, who
struggled offensively last year, may be a completely different team
in '99. ``Last year, of the eleven starters on offense coming into
the first game, only three were left standing at the end of the
year,'' Torbush said. ``But with the experience Ronald had last
year, we're going to be better. We have five tailbacks who I feel
can contribute. Last year, we had to move two fullbacks to the
tailback spot.''
</P>
<P>
   Torbush compares Curry to Charlie Ward, who won the Heisman
while directing Florida State's attack. ``Ward was a special player
and if we can put more good players around Ronald, he has the
opportunity to be that good. He's at the point that he can make a
good team great.''
</P>
<P>
   Curry says the hoopla and gaggle of writers and radio/TV folks
that constantly seek him out doesn't bother him. ``In my first game
in high school, we went into overtime and I scored the winning
touchdown and I've had a lot of press ever since,'' he said. ``I'm
just going to be the same old Ronald. I'm never going to change
personally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've changed as a football player, I'm much better,'' he said.
``When I make mistakes now, I know the mistake I made. Being a
quarterback takes a lot. I know everything about it now.''
</P>
<P>
   As to which sport he'll eventually pursue full time, Curry
shakes his head. ``The decision is mine to make and I'm not even
close to making it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Over the summer, Curry shed the No. 13 jersey he wore last
season and donned No. 1 _ as if he needed any more attention than
he gets on the field anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Location: Chapel Hill, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Enrollment: 24,255
</P>
<P>
   Coach: Carl Torbush is 8-5 in second year at North Carolina;
11-13 overall
</P>
<P>
   Nickname: Tar Heels
</P>
<P>
   Stadium: Kenan Memorial Stadium (60,000).
</P>
<P>
   All-time record: 591-412-54
</P>
<P>
   Conference Championships: Five (1963, 1971, 1972, 1977, 1980).
</P>
<P>
   1998 Record: 7-5 overall, 5-3 ACC
</P>
<P>
   1999 Schedule:
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 4, Virginia; Sept. 11,at Indiana; Sept. 25, Florida State;
Oct. 2, at Clemson; Oct. 9, at Georgia Tech; Oct. 16, at Houston;
Oct. 23 at Maryland; Oct. 30, Furman; Nov. 6, Wake Forest; Nov. 11,
N.C. State (Charlotte); Nov. 20 , Duke.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
