<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5171 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-FBC-TECH-DEFENSE-COX     08-21 0625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TECH-DEFENSE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New defense aides have effect at Tech
 &HT;    By J.C. Clemons
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Although the whirlwind of defensive coaches exiting
the Georgia Tech program after last season was not forced, it left
a perception that working for Yellow Jackets head coach George
O'Leary _ a defensive maestro _ may be hazardous to one's coaching
health.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing could be further from the truth, insists the three new
defensive assistants. That nearly a hundred coaches inquired about
the vacancies adds credence to that stance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been absolutely great working with Coach O'Leary,'' says
new defensive line coach Dave Sollazzo, ``because No. 1, he cares
about his coaches very much.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, he expects you to work hard, but he's an
outstanding student of the game.... I've already learned so much.''
</P>
<P>
   Sollazzo, along with first-year defensive backs coach Paul
Ferraro and new defensive ends/special teams coach Danny Crossman,
have been hired to shore up a defense that surrendered an average
of nearly 400 yards per game a year ago. And they will be guided by
former Tech linebackers coach Ted Roof, the Jackets' third
defensive coordinator in as many years.
</P>
<P>
   After last season, in which Tech was 10-2, shared the ACC title
with Florida State and finished ranked No. 9 in the country,
defensive coordinator Randy Edsall, defensive line coach Lance
Thompson, and special teams and ends coach Bob Casullo departed.
</P>
<P>
   Edsall was hired as head coach at Connecticut. Thompson moved to
Alabama to be an assistant, and Casullo went to Michigan State for
the same reason.
</P>
<P>
   With an opportunity to rebuild, O'Leary, the defensive
coordinator of Tech's 1990 co-national championship team, came up
with a wish list: ``I was looking for good teachers, guys who can
communicate and get maximum potential out of what they have to work
with.''
</P>
<P>
   It appears O'Leary hit the mark. Each practice session is filled
with their commands:
</P>
<P>
   ``Stop and think about what you're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Look for your keys.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Listen to me.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not hard to spot Sollazzo. Just follow the booming voice
and you will find the Citadel graduate and 10-year college
assistant exhorting his troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``The defensive line position is always the holler guy,''
O'Leary said. ``I can see Sollazzo starting to have an impact, and
I see (the players) taking to his coaching, which is critical
because that is an area where we have to play better.''
</P>
<P>
   Sollazzo says he is comfortable with his boss' directive.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had to get mentally tough. That's the key,'' he said.
``They all have the ability. But at our position, defensive line,
it's a very tough job.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're not enthusiastic about what you're doing, you're not
going to be able to put up with all the elements up in there _
people blocking at you from every side. You've go to stay
focused.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferraro, a 17-year college coaching veteran, spent the past
eight seasons at Bowling Green as defensive coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see that experience at work,'' O'Leary said. ``He
picks up matchups really quick.''
</P>
<P>
   Crossman, 32, played at Kansas and Pitt, and in the NFL and
WLAF. He was at Central Florida the past two seasons. An energetic,
hands-on sort, Crossman often lines up to demonstrate techniques.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been at this place eight months, and by now, everybody
knows what I'm about,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It's coincidence that all three coached at the mid-major school
level or below. To them, though, football is football.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all fundamentals and effort,'' Sollazzo said. ``Where I
coach, it doesn't matter what level you're at.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
