<P>
   CAR-NASCAR-SERIES2 _ ATLANTA _ NASCAR SERIES PART II/LIFE AFTER
THE FAST LANE: 1950s: JACK SMITH. At age 71, Jack Smith still shows
up at work everyday at his transmission shop in Spartanburgh, S.C.
Business is good because of it. Customers like to talk to Smith
about his NASCAR career. From 1949-64, Smith, who lived in Sandy
Springs, Ga., an Atlanta suburb, raced in 263 NASCAR races and won
21. He was named NASCAR's Most Popular Driver in 1959. ``I could go
run in Atlanta, a 25- or 30- or 50-lap race right near home and
make $500,'' Smith said. ``Like Tim Flock _ he'd get in his car or
ride with somebody in a tow truck, go all the way to Bangor, Maine,
to run a race that paid $800. I'd run the Peach Bowl in Atlanta,
make $500 and it didn't cost me $3 for gas and oil to run and to
get there and back.'' (Levine, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 41.
WITH PHOTOS. MOVED
