u s BC-FBN-JETS-MIRER-560&AMP;AD     08-21 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-MIRER-560&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN A PERSONNEL QUARTERBACK SNEAK, JETS QUIETLY HIRE MIRER
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Things move quick around here,'' said the New York Jets'
wide-eyed rookie guard, Randy Thomas, who probably has not caught
his breath yet.
</P>
<P>
   Only moments after the Jets had beaten the Philadelphia Eagles,
10-9, Friday night, Thomas heard his first Bill Parcells postgame
tirade and then learned that the club had acquired another backup
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   That move came on the heels of four other big-name acquisitions
in the past three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Even the starting quarterback, Vinny Testaverde, did not
understand what the Rick Mirer questions were about during the news
conference that followed the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was unaware of that,'' Testaverde said about the arrival of
Mirer from the Green Bay Packers in a trade for a draft choice.
Mirer was brought in to fix the one major potential obstacle facing
the offense: What would happen if Testaverde were injured?
</P>
<P>
   That theoretical question resonated throughout Giants Stadium as
Scott Zolak's debut in a Jets uniform unfolded.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, he had little help when he replaced Testaverde at the
start of the second half. Only center Kevin Mawae was a
first-stringer, and he was in for just one series, to get Zolak
started.
</P>
<P>
   But Zolak could do little with what he had to work with. He
directed a total of six series and failed to lead the club to any
points. All six drives ended with a punt; in three series the Jets
got no more than three downs and out.
</P>
<P>
   Zolak, like the backup, Ray Lucas, the week before at Green Bay,
failed to complete half his passes. Zolak hit on 10 of 22, and they
gained only 90 yards. Like Lucas, though, he avoided throwing any
interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Jets' backup quarterbacks ended the first half of the
exhibition schedule having directed a total of 15 drives and
failing to cross the goal-line. In Lucas' nine drives against the
Packers, the Jets got only a pair of field goals.
</P>
<P>
   Those numbers contrast with the remarkably quick start
Testaverde has displayed this summer.
</P>
<P>
   He was on target for a second consecutive game in connecting on
11 of 14 passes for 130 yards. He produced his first interception,
but also found Wayne Chrebet for a 12-yard touchdown. In preseason
play, Testaverde has hit on 22 of 27 passes. Against opposing
first-string defenses, he has put points on the board on four of 7
drives, including two touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   So the point total shows Testaverde-led drives 20, backup-led
drives 6. Now there are three quarterback backups on the squad, and
Parcells will soon cut one, or even two, from among Zolak, Lucas
and Mirer. In punter Tom Tupa, the Jets have a versatile player who
has started 13 games at quarterback in his NFL career.
</P>
<P>
   Zolak was surprised that Mirer had been brought in. He learned
about it just before game time. When he took the field, Zolak said:
``We seemed flat. It was tough to come in and rally people. A lot
of players' jobs were on the line and we shouldn't have been
flat.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the quarterback uncertainty, it was the play of the
special teams that led Parcells to growl at the entire squad.
Perhaps melodramatically, he described it as ``the worst special
teams play I've seen in 15 years as a head coach.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad I wasn't playing specials tonight,'' said Lucas, who
usually does just that.
</P>
<P>
   As for his own future with Mirer's arrival, Lucas said: ``I've
got nothing to say. Parcells is the coach and he knows what he's
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Special teams stalwart Chris Hayes described the unit's play
as ``just horrible.''
</P>
<P>
   It included a muffed punt by Leon Johnson that led to an Eagles
possession on the 1-yard line and subsequent field goal, a
mishandled kickoff by Kevin Williams, and faulty kick-coverage that
allowed two long Philadelphia runbacks: one of 34 yards on a punt
and a 31-yarder on a kickoff.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to worrying about backup quarterback, the special
teams' play has been a long-consuming concern for the coach. He
determined after last season that his backups, as well as his
starting linebackers, would have to play special teams and
attempted to find players at a high athletic level to do this.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Parcells' anger, his career preseason mark stands at
43-16, including 8-2 with the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   And while he blew up at the team in the locker room, there were
some significant positives. The Jets' defense once again was
stingy. The only touchdown it has yielded to the opposition's first
string came on Green Bay's opening drive, directed by Brett Favre.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles, meanwhile, got only a pair of first-half field goals
against the starting defense _ one of them positioned by the
Johnson turnover on the 1-yard line. Mo Lewis led a sack parade
against the Eagles' starter, Doug Pederson, who was dumped four
times. Lewis caught him twice.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets also lowered their penalty total from nine at Green Bay
to six, saw place-kicker John Hall connect on his fourth field goal
in five preseason attempts, and actually did some good things on
special teams to offset the bad.
</P>
<P>
   Punter Tom Tupa, who launched a 51-yarder, had a 43.3 average.
Johnson generated a kickoff return of 21 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Still, to Parcells, this team that so many people expect to go
to the Super Bowl is ``light-years away from where we need to be to
have a chance to compete in this league.''
</P>
</TEXT>
