<SLUG> BC-N.J.-SHORE-VACATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOWNS COLUMN: CHECK-IN DAY AT THE SHORE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By IVER PETERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SURF CITY, N.J. _ Charles Marple left his family in the parking
lot of the Greenhouse restaurant to see about a table for
breakfast. ``She said at least 45 minutes,'' he reported a moment
later, and, strangely, nobody seemed surprised. But then, this was
a Saturday in August, and on the Jersey Shore, as everyone already
knew, Saturday is check-in day.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, Saturday at the shore is about relaxation and fun,
but the reality is all about waiting, and traffic, and children
needing a bathroom, and no place to park. For on every seaside
Saturday from June to September, thousands of weekly rentals
expire, and three hours later, thousands more begin for the next
tenants.
</P>
<P>
   For first-day vacationers caught between checkout and check-in,
the tingle of anticipation gives way to a tangle of minivans and
sport utility vehicles loaded with bikes, grills, boogie boards,
beach chairs and enough rapidly thawing steaks to last a week.
These workaday refugees inch their way over barrier island
causeways, grimly pursuing a week of fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has a check-in day story,'' said Ken Sichau, an AT&AMP;T
executive waiting to move into a two-week rental. ``And if it's a
rainy day, it's a mess because the kids can't go to the beach and
you end up driving up and down the island.''
</P>
<P>
   But his wife, Jane, said, ``To me, it's just part of the
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' Sichau had to agree. ``You have a problem, but that's
the time you remember.''
</P>
<P>
   There are 32 real estate rental agencies on Long Beach Island,
and if they average 100 rentals each _ some do fewer, others many
more _ that means about 3,000 condos, apartments and houses, from
beach front to bay side, change hands on a given summer Saturday,
all more or less at once.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've talked about staggering the hours so everybody doesn't
have to come and go at the same time,'' said John D. Franzoni of
Oceanside Realty, one of the bigger agencies, ``but nobody wants to
change anything.''
</P>
<P>
   So the renters employ strategies. Marple, a postal worker from
Hightstown, N.J., got his wife, Pat, his daughter Fran and her
husband, Rich Seip, and the Seips' three boys loaded up and on the
road by 9 a.m. the other week, determined to beat the traffic that
backs up on the Route 72 causeway from the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   They got on the island by 10:30 a.m., only to find themselves
caught in another kind of traffic, in the crowd waiting for a table
at the cafe. ``You just have to be patient,'' Mrs. Marple said.
</P>
<P>
   The hours between checkout and check-in belong to the rental
agents and the cleaning crews. Tenants bring their own towels and
sheets, and they leave behind sand, and sometimes a little more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ice cream,'' said Jerry Hansen, Franzoni's partner, when he
opened a freezer door after a tenant had left one of his units.
``That's a no-no.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside, Gail Cook, a broker with HCH Real Estate, was also
doing her check-in day rounds, and Hansen introduced her to a
visitor. ``Hello!'' she said brightly. ``Do you do emergency
cleaning?'' She was just joking, sort of.
</P>
<P>
   People often try to outguess the physics of moving countless
people and cars off a narrow island more or less at once, and
sometimes small miracles are granted.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff and Christine Nordenholt have been renting here for years.
But this was going to be the first check-in day for their
11-month-old son, Alexander, so they decided to leave their home on
Staten Island a little later to let the rush pass, and to roll onto
the island around 2:30. What with the baby, it took much longer for
them to get going than they had expected, and yet they still
arrived within a few minutes of their goal.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Nordenholt was amazed to tell the story, and if it doesn't
sound like a big deal, you haven't experienced check-in day.
</P>
<P>
   There is even a class of renters who disdain the elbows and
aspirins that make check-in day special. So unwilling are they to
do the stop-and-go with the kids squirming ominously in the back
that they blow off that first Saturday night and don't bother to
show up until Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sunday!'' Mrs. Nordenholt said, aghast. ``I would never
consider that. Each moment is too precious.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
