<HEADER>
A5186 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OUTDOORS-BASS-NYT &LR;      08-21 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-BASS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTDOORS: STALKING STRIPERS ON MARTHA'S VINEYARD 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By NELSON BRYANT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST TISBURY, Mass. _ Whenever you take a visiting angler
fishing, the wish to be successful intensifies. You want him to
have a good time, and you also feel that your reputation as a local
expert is at stake.
</P>
<P>
   I had an additional reason for wanting to find striped bass for
Lawrence ``Lucky'' Pyne of Milton, Vt., when we got together on
Martha's Vineyard, where I live. A friendly, enthusiastic
outdoorsman who is an editor-at-large for Field and Stream
magazine, he confided to me that decades ago when he was a boy he
would read my fishing and hunting yarns at the breakfast table
while munching through his Wheaties and vow that someday he too
would chronicle such endeavors.
</P>
<P>
   Lucky arrived on the Vineyard during some of this searing
summer's hottest days. I explained to him that for the past 10
years, shore fly-fishing _ which interested both of us most _ for
stripers on the Vineyard has always deteriorated by the third week
in July. This year, I added, such fishing had fallen off even
earlier, perhaps the result of rapidly warming water. I told him
that we probably wouldn't find striped bass of keeper size (28
inches in Massachusetts) along the shore within reach of our fly
rods, and that we might even have difficulty locating smaller bass.
</P>
<P>
   This didn't trouble my new friend. On our first trip, we took
our fly rods to the western end of Lobsterville Beach at Dogfish
Bar. We arrived shortly before sunset. There was a strong rising
tide. I prefer a strong falling tide in that location, but moving
water in either direction is the first consideration.
</P>
<P>
   Within a few minutes, Lucky was fast to a small bass of about
five pounds. He stayed put, caught three more of similar size and
had strikes from several fish that weren't hooked.
</P>
<P>
   I, meanwhile, lumbered up and down the beach in my waders for a
half mile in either direction, hoping to find a spot where larger
stripers were present. I found nothing. No bass were visible
feeding on the surface and baitfish were scarce. I eventually
settled in beside Lucky and had one hit before the bass departed.
</P>
<P>
   We then moved a mile to the east along Lobsterville Beach to a
spot where in recent weeks I had often found small schools of small
to medium-sized bass foraging along the shore late at night. Few
anglers were present, not a good sign, but we did encounter a woman
fly-fisher walking through the dunes who had lost a good bass.
</P>
<P>
   We caught nothing and departed at midnight. Lucky was pleased _
he had taken stripers from Vineyard Sound with a fly rod _ but over
the next few days I chafed at my failure to find better fishing for
him.
</P>
<P>
   In a conversation with one of my grandsons, I learned that he
and some of his friends were still having good luck fishing for
stripers in Tisbury Great Pond. Opened to the sea through the
barrier beach by man two or three times a year, this salt pond,
nearly two miles long and a mile wide, had been open for a short
time in early summer before onshore winds closed it, trapping a
considerable number of migrating stripers. The pond was still
closed and the bass were foraging throughout it, even into remote,
shallow coves, my grandson said, adding that, although most of the
bass were small, a few keepers had been taken.
</P>
<P>
   I called Lucky that evening. He was eager to try for the Tisbury
Great Pond bass, but had to head back to Vermont the following day
at noon.
</P>
<P>
   We made a 5 a.m. date for his last day. When I stepped out of my
house at 4:30 that morning, the fog was so thick that I could
barely see my pickup truck with a canoe on top 60 feet away.
Lucky's vehicle crept into the dooryard at about 5:10.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sorry, I'm late,'' he said, ``but there were times when I
could hardly see the white line on the drive up from Edgartown.''
</P>
<P>
   Launching my canoe on the pond, I fired up its little outboard
and within a minute the shoreline disappeared. Using a pocket
compass, I set a course for an area along the barrier beach where
the aforementioned opening had cut a deep channel along the pond
shore before it had closed. On one occasion, we passed within a few
feet of six Canada geese that simply paddled away into the fog _
conditions were unsuitable for flying.
</P>
<P>
   Reaching our destination, we beached the canoe and began to cast
from shore using top-water plugs and one-handed spinning rods as
blue claw crabs scuttled back and forth in the sandy shallows
before us, and, at our backs 100 yards away, the unseen surf
pounded the beach. We had fly rods with us, but wanted to cover as
much water as possible in the limited time we had to fish.
</P>
<P>
   The bass were there, and even though we caught none over six
pounds, we were delighted by the ferocity with which they struck at
our surface lures, sending bursts of spray aloft and occasionally
leaping out of the water when first hooked. We caught six or seven
and lost nearly as many more.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to find bigger fish, I moved us back up the pond to the
entrance of Deep Bottom cove. The fog was still so dense that I
couldn't find the channel I was seeking, but even so we took three
or four more small stripers.
</P>
<P>
   Our final effort, made when the fog was burning off, was near a
point a quarter of a mile inside the entrance of Tiah's Cove. My
friend caught two more bass. A few casts later, a large fish,
clearly a keeper, followed his lure to the canoe. He couldn't raise
it again, and it was time for us to leave.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
