<DOCNO> NYT19990821.0162 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5188 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-LEGISLATION-3TAKES     08-21 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LEGISLATION-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACTIONS OF NEW YORK LEGISLATURE'S 222ND SESSION 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By CLIFFORD J. LEVY and RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The New York Legislature has weathered some
tumultuous years, but the 222nd session left even Albany veterans
shaking their heads at the partisan fisticuffs and sullen
standoffs, the tendency to hunker down on routine matters. When the
session finally concluded nearly two months late with the Assembly
recessing around 3 a.m. on Aug. 6, members leaving the chambers
seemed relieved that it was over.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, it wasn't. The last hours were marked by the same
disarray that was apparent all year: The traditional
down-to-the-wire agreements between the governor and the
Legislature could not be immediately translated into laws because
leaders of the Republican-controlled state Senate had ended the
session in frustration several hours earlier, while the Assembly
continued meeting. The Senate is now scheduled to approve those
bills in a short special session in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   To many lawmakers, it was an exasperating coda to an
unsatisfying and unproductive session, one that began with big
hopes but yielded a budget that was tied for the latest in state
history. Relations between Gov. George Pataki, a Republican, and
the Democrats in control of the Assembly were more prickly than
ever, and in the spring, the budget stalemate essentially thwarted
progress on everything else for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   There was one major issue that drew consensus during that time.
Legislative leaders of both parties, eager to win the favor of
voters in a suburban special election, swiftly and unexpectedly
repealed the decades-old tax on commuters who work in New York
City.
</P>
<P>
   As the session wound down, lawmakers agreed to stiffen penalties
for stalking and for blocking abortion clinics, expand the state's
database of DNA specimens from criminals, and allow the
construction of new power plants. But talks on many important
matters, from revamping the state's drug laws to writing new rules
for polluted industrial sites, were abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 8,807 bills introduced in the Assembly, 1,606 passed,
officials said. In the Senate, 6,117 bills were introduced, and
1,432 passed. A total of 715 bills passed both houses, a relatively
low figure compared with recent years. Of those, the governor has
signed 409 and vetoed 13. The remaining ones are awaiting his
decision on whether to sign.
</P>
<P>
   The following were the major actions of the session:
</P>
<P>
   The Budget
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature completed passage of the 1999-2000 budget in the
early morning hours of Aug. 4, tying the record for tardiness set
in 1997 by going 126 days into the fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   But the delay was misleading. Once the governor agreed to
negotiate actively with legislative leaders, it took just a month
to settle the outlines of the budget, and another month to hammer
out the details, draft it and pass it. And while a record for
lateness would suggest a difficult budget filled with sacrifice,
the final $73.3 billion package gave everyone enough to claim
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the budget raises spending 3.8 percent, though the part
generated from state taxes will rise more slowly. The increase is
larger than the governor had wanted, though still modest for such
flush times, and considerably smaller than what the Democrats had
sought.
</P>
<P>
   At Pataki's insistence, the budget spends none of the $1.8
billion surplus that accumulated during the last fiscal year.
Instead, it will be salted away to ease the way for tax cuts that
are to take effect next year and the year after.
</P>
<P>
   The governor also succeeded in nearly doubling spending on
child-care subsidies for the poor, to more than $800 million, an
effort that is seen as crucial to helping parents move from welfare
to work.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature beat back the governor's proposed cuts to
Medicaid and education, and the budget even raises aid to local
school districts by more than $900 million, a record sum, to a
total of more than $12 billion. The Assembly Democrats made sure
that it also expanded a program to provide prekindergarten classes
and reduce class sizes in the early grades.
</P>
<P>
   The basic outlines of the budget are about what the Senate
Republicans had proposed all along, and they also secured more than
$400 million a year in new tax cuts that they had sought. The
budget also reflects more than $1 billion in tax cuts that were
passed in previous years, and are now going into effect.
</P>
<P>
   Crime and Justice
</P>
<P>
   LEGISLATION ENACTED
</P>
<P>
   Makes it a felony, rather than a misdemeanor, to cause extreme
pain or death to a domestic animal, raising the maximum penalty to
two years in prison and a $5,000 fine, rather than one year and
$1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Requires the Parole Board to keep the identity of crime victims
confidential in certain instances.
</P>
<P>
   Makes it a crime to make a false bomb report, punishable by
having to pay restitution up to $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   AWAITING SIGNATURE
</P>
<P>
   Would ban ``bar crawls,'' organized bar-hopping events.
</P>
<P>
   EXPECTED TO PASS BOTH HOUSES
</P>
<P>
   Would mandate the collection of DNA samples from about 50
percent of all people convicted of felonies, up from 8 percent now,
and from about 100,000 people now in prison, on probation or on
parole, for entry into a computer database and use in solving
future crimes. (The Assembly has passed this bill and the Senate
has committed to passing it at a special session later this year.)
</P>
<P>
   Would make it a crime to stalk a person, defining stalking as
following or harassing with intent to cause harm, with penalties up
to seven years in prison. (The Assembly has passed this bill and
the Senate has committed to passing it at a special session later
this year.)
</P>
<P>
   Would make it a crime to block access to an abortion clinic and
increase penalties for injuring clinic workers. (The Assembly has
passed this bill and the Senate has committed to passing it at a
special session later this year.)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   LEGISLATION FAILED
</P>
<P>
   Would have softened some of the severest drug possession
penalties under the state's Rockefeller-era drug laws, while
providing for more treatment of people arrested on drug charges.
</P>
<P>
   Would have strengthened several of the state's sex crime laws,
including: imposing a mandatory sentence of 25 years to life in
prison for anyone convicted for the second time of a sex crime
against a person under the age of 15; making it a separate crime to
use ``date rape'' drugs to commit rape or sodomy, and prohibiting
the granting of bail to any person arrested who has a history of
sex crimes against children.
</P>
<P>
   Would have allowed prosecutors, like defendants, to appeal
sentences and decisions on bail.
</P>
<P>
   Would have imposed a wide range of restrictions on gun
possession and sale, including requiring that lost or stolen guns
be reported to the police and that a person complete a gun safety
course before obtaining a firearms license.
</P>
<P>
   Would have increased penalties for a range of violent crimes
committed by juveniles.
</P>
<P>
   Would have simplified the state's multilayered court system.
</P>
<P>
   Would have eliminated discretionary parole by ending the
practice of sentencing felons to a range of time in prison,
replacing such sentences with specific terms.
</P>
<P>
   Would have authorized construction of a new maximum-security
prison.
</P>
<P>
   Would have created a category of ``bias crimes,'' raising the
penalties for various crimes when the victim has been chosen on the
basis of race, ethnicity, sex or sexual orientation.
</P>
<P>
   Would have allowed the state to commit sex offenders to mental
hospitals for an indefinite period after their prison terms are
completed.
</P>
<P>
   Would have raised fees paid by local governments for
court-appointed lawyers who represent indigent criminal defendants
to $100 an hour from $40.
</P>
<P>
   Would have toughened the standard for drunken driving to a blood
alcohol level of 0.08 percent from the current 0.10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Would have provided automatic revocation of a driver's license
for five years for a person convicted the third time in 10 years of
driving while intoxicated or impaired by drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Would have created the crime of ``identity theft'' for people
who use other people's names and credit information, and would have
required financial-services companies to notify customers that they
are selling or transferring information about customers to someone
else.
</P>
<P>
   Would have required that prison inmates make a $7 co-payment for
medical treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Would have limited the ability of inmates to file lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Would have required New York City police officers to reside in
the city, with the same requirement imposed in certain other
localities.
</P>
<P>
   Would have created new county and family court judges.
</P>
<P>
   Education
</P>
<P>
   LEGISLATION ENACTED
</P>
<P>
   Allows certain communities to break away from existing school
districts and form their own districts, specifically aimed at
Kiryas Joel, a Hasidic enclave in Orange County.
</P>
<P>
   Continues to exempt the New York City School Construction
Authority from rules that require government agencies to split most
construction jobs among many contractors.
</P>
<P>
   AWAITING SIGNATURE
</P>
<P>
   Would overhaul special-education programs to reduce incentives
to local districts to classify students as learning-disabled.
</P>
<P>
   Would raise to 17 from 16 the age at which a person can legally
drop out of school.
</P>
<P>
   LEGISLATION FAILED
</P>
<P>
   Would have relaxed new requirement of the Board of Regents that
students pass Regents examinations to earn high school diplomas.
</P>
<P>
   Would have allowed teachers to expel persistently troublesome
students from their classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Taxes
</P>
<P>
   LEGISLATION ENACTED
</P>
<P>
   Eliminates New York City's income tax on commuters who work in
the city but live elsewhere. Applied only to commuters living in
New York state, but a court subsequently ruled that it must apply
to out-of-state-commuters as well. Estimated savings to taxpayers:
$360 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Allows Nassau County to impose a 1 percent tax on all property
sales, until Jan. 31, 2001. Estimated cost to taxpayers: $70
million.
</P>
<P>
   Reduces the corporate-profits tax on banks and insurance
companies to a top rate of 7.5 percent from 9 percent. Estimated
savings to businesses: $100 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Raises by 25 percent the state's earned income tax credit for
the working poor, particularly those with children, to a maximum of
$939 a year. Estimated savings to taxpayers: $125 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Extends a property tax break for the owners of 280,000
cooperative apartments and condominiums in New York City that
averages almost $600 per unit. Estimated savings to taxpayers: $166
million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Postpones from Dec. 1, 1999, to March 1, 2000, the elimination
of the sales tax on clothes, up to $110 per item. Estimated cost to
taxpayers: $100 million.
</P>
<P>
   Suspends the sales tax on clothes, up to $500 per item, for a
week in September 1999, and another week in February 2000.
Estimated savings to taxpayers: $50 million.
</P>
<P>
   Health Care
</P>
<P>
   AWAITING SIGNATURE
</P>
<P>
   Would allow a judge to compel a mentally ill person with a
history of violence to receive treatment, including involuntary
confinement, if such action is requested by a family member, doctor
or roommate.
</P>
<P>
   Would require that all residents and employees of nursing homes
receive influenza vaccinations.
</P>
<P>
   Would require that children receive the hepatitis B vaccine by
seventh grade.
</P>
<P>
   LEGISLATION FAILED
</P>
<P>
   Would have continued the state's system of imposing charges on
hospital bills to finance hospital care for the indigent, and to
help pay for the education of doctors at teaching hospitals. (The
system, which expires at the end of the year, will be taken up in a
special legislative session later this year.)
</P>
<P>
   Would have greatly expanded the state's anti-tobacco advertising
and education program.
</P>
<P>
   Would have allowed patients to sue health-maintenance
organizations for denying coverage of treatments.
</P>
<P>
   Would have created a state registry to provide consumers with
information about any doctor, including educational background,
malpractice history and any disciplinary actions.
</P>
<P>
   Consumer Affairs
</P>
<P>
   LEGISLATION ENACTED
</P>
<P>
   Requires that used mattresses be labeled as such with prominent
tags.
</P>
<P>
   AWAITING SIGNATURE
</P>
<P>
   Would require that all automated teller machines display on
screen any charges that will be assessed for use of the machine.
</P>
<P>
   Would create an office within the state Department of Health to
advise people who are having problems with managed-care companies.
</P>
<P>
   Would allow anyone aged 62 or older to terminate a housing lease
without penalty when a medical condition leaves the tenant unable
to live independently, and the tenant is moving in with a family
member.
</P>
<P>
   Would renew for one year the law against ticket-scalping.
</P>
<P>
   Would renew for two years the law allowing thousands of lofts,
mostly in Manhattan, to be used as dwellings.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   LEGISLATION FAILED
</P>
<P>
   Would have required health insurance companies to pay for
fertility treatments.
</P>
<P>
   Would have required health insurance companies, under policies
that cover prescription drugs, to cover prescribed contraceptives
as well.
</P>
<P>
   Would have allowed car rental companies to sell customers
collision damage waivers, insurance policies covering damage to the
rental cars, and would have eliminated the cap on the renter's
liability for damage to the car.
</P>
<P>
   Would have required credit-reporting agencies to provide a free
credit report to any resident, as often as once a year, upon
request.
</P>
<P>
   Would have allowed for-profit credit counseling, a practice now
outlawed.
</P>
<P>
   Would have imposed several limitations on consumer lawsuits and
damage awards.
</P>
<P>
   Environment and Energy
</P>
<P>
   LEGISLATION VETOED
</P>
<P>
   Would have allowed cities to ban the use of the pesticide
Avitrol, which is used to poison pigeons.
</P>
<P>
   LEGISLATION ENACTED
</P>
<P>
   Directs the creation of a statewide cancer map, the first in the
nation, matching types and frequency of cancers with known sources
of air and water pollution.
</P>
<P>
   AWAITING SIGNATURE
</P>
<P>
   Would allow the Public Service Commission, appointed by the
governor, to issue environmental permits for new power plants; no
state agency is now authorized to do so.
</P>
<P>
   LEGISLATION FAILED
</P>
<P>
   Would have refinanced the state's Superfund program for cleaning
toxic contamination sites, which is nearly out of money, by
imposing new fees on industry.
</P>
<P>
   Would have prohibited New York industries from selling or
trading ``pollution credits,'' earned by reducing airborne
emissions, in such a way that they would end up being acquired by
industries in the Midwest that contribute to the state's acid rain.
</P>
<P>
   Would have required that neighbors be notified 48 hours in
advance of the application of pesticides to any property by a
commercial firm.
</P>
<P>
   Would have allowed the construction of cellular phone towers
without environmental review.
</P>
<P>
   Transportation
</P>
<P>
   LEGISLATION ENACTED
</P>
<P>
   Requires school buses to be operated with headlights and
taillights on, day or night.
</P>
<P>
   Allows the Department of Motor Vehicles to deny registration to
a prospective school bus operating company when it appears that the
same operator had a registration revoked while doing business under
a different name.
</P>
<P>
   AWAITING SIGNATURE
</P>
<P>
   Would allow New York City to reduce speed limits to as low as 15
mph, from the current minimum of 25 mph, on streets where speed
bumps and other traffic-slowing devices are used.
</P>
<P>
   Would allow mentally disabled people to ride New York City
subways and buses at half-fare, as physically disabled people now
do.
</P>
<P>
   LEGISLATION FAILED
</P>
<P>
   Would have allowed a speed limit of 65 mph, rather than 55, on
some Long Island highways.
</P>
<P>
   Would have required bus drivers and motorists involved in
accidents with buses to submit to a breath test.
</P>
<P>
   Would have required the mandatory revocation of the driver's
license of a bus driver who tested positive in a random drug or
alcohol test.
</P>
<P>
   Welfare and Families
</P>
<P>
   LEGISLATION ENACTED
</P>
<P>
   Brings New York into compliance with federal law on adoptions;
includes requirements that ``permanency planning'' hearings be held
for foster children every year and that the state establish a
system for checking to see if prospective adoptive or foster
parents have criminal records.
</P>
<P>
   LEGISLATION FAILED
</P>
<P>
   Would have increased penalties for failure to pay child support.
</P>
<P>
   Would have raised the amount that parents receiving welfare can
collect in child support payments without losing their welfare
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Would have created the crime of unlawfully providing a child
with a large quantity of alcoholic beverages.
</P>
<P>
   Would have made it a crime to do body piercing on people under
18, with the exception of ear piercing.
</P>
<P>
   Would have prohibited the sale of laser pointers to people under
18.
</P>
<P>
   Government and Ethics
</P>
<P>
   LEGISLATION ENACTED
</P>
<P>
   Makes it easier for presidential candidates to get on New York's
primary ballots by reducing the number of voter signatures
candidates must collect on petitions.
</P>
<P>
   AWAITING SIGNATURE
</P>
<P>
   Would speed disbursement of state aid to municipalities.
</P>
<P>
   LEGISLATION FAILED
</P>
<P>
   Would have extended for four years the state's law governing
lobbyists. (A more stringent proposal is expected to be taken up at
a special session later this year.)
</P>
<P>
   Would have imposed significant new campaign-finance limitations,
including a ban on ``soft money'' contributions to party committees
and lower ceilings on individual contributions to campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Would have provided for government financing of political
campaigns, linked to campaign spending limits.
</P>
<P>
   Would have allowed legislative committee chairmen to call a
joint Senate-Assembly conference committee when both houses pass
substantially similar bills, rather than limiting the power to call
conference committees to the leaders of the two houses.
</P>
<P>
   Would have provided for television coverage of Senate and
Assembly sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Business and Labor
</P>
<P>
   LEGISLATION ENACTED
</P>
<P>
   Authorizes the creation of trademarks for use in marketing
agricultural products as being from New York state, and as being
from particular regions of the state.
</P>
<P>
   AWAITING SIGNATURE
</P>
<P>
   Would allow the New York City corrections officers union to take
millions of dollars a year out of the city's pension fund for
distribution to its members.
</P>
<P>
   Would allow state prison guards with heart conditions to retire
with full, tax-free pensions.
</P>
<P>
   Would extend authorization for the Quick Draw lottery game until
March 31, 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Would make electronic signatures legally binding.
</P>
<P>
   Would require that boxing judges disclose their scoring after
each round.
</P>
<P>
   LEGISLATION FAILED
</P>
<P>
   Would have created a voluntary system to allow merchants to use
devices that scan driver's licenses to verify the age of people
buying tobacco and alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   Would have allowed New York to join Powerball, the multistate
lottery game.
</P>
<P>
   Would have attempted to limit the ability of plaintiffs to file
lawsuits for damages and reduced the potential for punitive
damages.
</P>
<P>
   Would have prohibited banks from charging more than a $15
penalty for returned checks.
</P>
</TEXT>
