<DOCNO> NYT19990821.0165 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 17:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5191 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SLAYING-ANNIVERSARY-N     08-21 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLAYING-ANNIVERSARY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECALLING YUSUF HAWKINS AND THE HATE THAT KILLED HIM
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ten years ago Monday, Moses Stewart lost his child to
one of New York City's most wrenching hate crimes. His son, Yusuf
Hawkins, then 16, was attacked by a mob of bat-wielding white
youths and shot to death in the Bensonhurst section of Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very hard to watch your children die,'' Stewart said
Saturday, in an emotional speech to friends and supporters in
Harlem. ``Look over at the children in this room and imagine their
life's blood running out of them for no other reason than that
someone deemed them less than human because of the color of their
skin.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he lifted a white handkerchief to his eyes and wiped away
tears. ``He died for something I did,'' Stewart continued, as
shouts of ``no, no'' rang from the audience. ``I'm the one who gave
him his color. He was born black because of me.''
</P>
<P>
   The killing of Yusuf Hawkins on Aug. 23, 1989, held up a mirror
to the city and the neighborhood. The image that looked back was
ugly enough to shake up the political establishment and fortify a
civil rights movement that has since rallied thousands for
demonstrations against police brutality and racism.
</P>
<P>
   Black protesters and members of Hawkins' family who marched
through Bensonhurst after the shooting were cursed by the
residents, hit with pieces of food and spat upon. They were taunted
with chants of ``useless, useless,'' a play on the name ``Yusuf.''
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks after the killing, David Dinkins, who went on to
become the city's first black mayor, beat three-term incumbent
Mayor Edward Koch in the Democratic mayoral primary. The changing
of the guard was attributed, in part, to the Bensonhurst uproar.
</P>
<P>
   Racial tensions from the killing ran strong for years. In 1991,
when he led another march through the largely white neighborhood to
protest some of the verdicts in the Hawkins case, the Rev. Al
Sharpton was stabbed in the chest with a steak knife by a young
white man.
</P>
<P>
   Eight men were eventually tried in connection with the Hawkins
killing. One was convicted of murder, four others were convicted of
lesser charges including weapons possession and rioting, and three
were acquitted of all charges. Keith Mondello, who spent eight
years in prison for organizing the gang of youths that attacked
Hawkins, was released this year and met with Stewart to offer his
apologies.
</P>
<P>
   But Stewart, who now works for Sharpton's National Action
Network, counseling and comforting other families who feel they are
victims of racism, indicated that he has other concerns than
forgiveness. He said the same virulent hatred that destroyed his
son still stalks the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to watch out for our children, watch out for the demon
that is out there waiting to take their lives,'' he told the crowd
at the network's headquarters. ``Yusuf is not the first or the
last. They are out there.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the 10th anniversary of his son's death is, in many
ways, harder on him than the first months of grieving. ``I have
lived Bensonhurst personally,'' he said, ``and now I am living
Bensonhurst through the eyes and hearts and pains of others.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton's group organized the Hawkins memorial and had invited
several other victims of racial violence or their relatives to
attend. Among those who were expected to share the stage with
Stewart were Abner Louima, the Haitian immigrant brutalized by a
police officer in Brooklyn, and the mother of Amadou Diallo, the
Guinean immigrant who was killed by four police officers in the
Bronx last year.
</P>
<P>
   Both their causes had been taken up and publicized by Sharpton
and when neither showed up, Sharpton noted their absence,
indirectly but pointedly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people, you fight for them and then you never hear from
them again,'' he said, adding that some of those he had helped had
disappeared after they received some money and fame.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton was joined by the Rev. Benjamin F. Muhammad, who said
he came as the envoy of Louis Farrakhan, leader of the Nation of
Islam. ``The color of our people is a gift from God,'' he told
Stewart. ``We are the original man and the original woman.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
