<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON BASKETBALL: NETS ARE BURYING PAST AND SEE A BRIGHT FUTURE
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A team that loses 68 percent of its games and ends the season
with two starters signed to 10-day contracts often winds up with a
fired head coach and a need to make some major roster moves. But
the New Jersey Nets, despite their disastrous 1998-99 season in
which they had a 16-34 record, will return virtually intact. And
they will do so proudly.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets viewed last season as if it were a necessary evil _ a
time to be humbled, a time to have the unpopular coach, John
Calipari, removed from the organization, a time to have nearly
everything that could go wrong go wrong.
</P>
<P>
   They do not believe the problem was the players. Barring a minor
trade that would send away one of the backup point guards, Eric
Murdock or Elliot Perry, or the signing of the Cuban defector
Lazaro Borrell, the Nets will have only one new player. And that
player, Evan Eschmeyer, a second-round draft pick, has a long way
to go to chip away at the incumbents' minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets deserve credit for not panicking. They subtracted no
one of significance and their only notable addition was to sign
Gheorghe Muresan, the 7-foot-7-inch center who is the tallest
player in National Basketball Association history.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets hope that Muresan, whose season consisted of 69 seconds
in the final game, is able to give them 15 to 20 minutes a game.
They believe such a contribution would enable them to contend for
the Eastern Conference title, assuming, of course, that Jayson
Williams, Kerry Kittles and Jim McIlvaine are healthy and that
Scott Burrell is in shape.
</P>
<P>
   Nine Nets missed a total of 176 games because of injury last
season, and injuries could be an obstacle again. While Williams is
on schedule to compete in the October training camp _ Dr. Russell
Warren announced last week that his broken right leg was completely
healed _ there are those within the organization who believe the
team's inspirational leader will not play basketball before
November.
</P>
<P>
   Even if he is healthy, it remains to be seen how strong the
well-worn Williams, 31, is upon his return. An undersized center,
he has been battered throughout his nine-year career, missing an
average of 26 games a season with injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Muresan's health will always be a question mark because of his
size and history of injuries, and then there is Kittles, whose sore
right knee was partly responsible for his career-worst performance
last season.
</P>
<P>
   The wiry shooting guard underwent arthroscopic surgery on May 12
and was unable to put weight on his leg for the next six weeks. As
is the case of Williams, the Nets will be happy if Kittles can
participate in one of their two daily practices in camp.
</P>
<P>
   Healthy or not, Kittles, who started for most of his first three
seasons and received a six-year, $50 million contract extension in
March, may end up coming off the bench. Coach Don Casey said last
week that, at present, his starting five includes Williams, Keith
Van Horn, Kendall Gill, Stephon Marbury and Burrell, who was signed
for one-year at $1 million last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Burrell's name is written with a light pencil,'' Casey
said in jest and in truth.
</P>
<P>
   As the sixth man, Kittles would still play 30 minutes a game
while backing up both guard positions _ Gill at shooting guard and
Marbury at the point. But Kittles is sensitive, and sitting him
down at the start of games could become a sticky situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Players want to play big minutes,'' general manager John Nash
said. ``And the guys that don't play are unhappy. Casey's got a
difficult job trying to keep the whole team in a good mood. But I
think that's one of Casey's strengths.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea of making Kittles a permanent sixth man was undoubtedly
conceived on the evening of April 16, when the Nets trounced
Seattle by 121-91 on the road. Burrell started at small forward
that night, hitting four 3-pointers to score a season-high 18
points as one of six Nets scorers in double figures. Kittles, who
had been struggling as a starter, was electrifying as a reserve.
Hitting 7 of 10 shots, he scored 15 points in 14 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   That game, in which Seattle was vying for a playoff spot, still
resonates with the Nets, who refer to it as proof of how good they
can be.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's an example of how I see us playing next year: running
and playing good, hard-nosed defense,'' said Gill, who scored 16
points while starting at shooting guard in that game. ``We have the
makings of a great team if everybody's healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Signing Muresan and Jamie Feick, who along with Mark Hendrickson
started the final six games of last season after joining the Nets
on a 10-day contract, gives the Nets increased depth and
flexibility in the frontcourt. With centers Muresan, Feick and
McIlvaine, whose left shoulder injury has healed, Casey can give
the Nets a different look at times by moving Williams to power
forward and Van Horn to small forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``Talent-wise, I think we can match up with anybody,'' said Van
Horn, who signed a six-year, $73 million contract extension on Aug.
1. ``And I think we have a good coaching staff in place. All of the
pieces to the puzzle are here if everyone is healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Nets that ``if'' may be as big as their new center. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
