<DOCNO> NYT19990821.0169 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 17:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5197 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-MEMPHIS-MAYOR-COX     08-21 1573
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEMPHIS-MAYOR-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Memphis mayoral race has just about everything
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell Konigsmark
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEMPHIS _ He's the only candidate for mayor who wears a velvet
crown and tights, who calls women's breasts ``puppies,'' and who
could crush his opponents_with his bare hands.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Lawler, known to professional wrestling fans for more than
20 years as ``The King,'' is now known in Memphis as The Candidate.
Following in the footsteps of Jesse ``The Body'' Ventura, who was
elected governor of Minnesota last year, Lawler is running for
mayor as the anti-politician. He promises to ``run Memphis like a
business where the taxpayers are the customers and the customers
are always right.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Jesse made everybody aware that you don't have to be a
politician to win an election,'' said Lawler, standing in his
kitchen, which is filled with Coca-Cola memorabilia. He has several
theme rooms in his single-story, east Memphis home, including a
``Gone With the Wind'' room, a shell room and a crown room, where
he keeps two suits of armor. ``There's an idea out there that you
have to cast your vote for whoever is most likely to win, or else
you're wasting your vote. That is simply not true.''
</P>
<P>
   Ventura proved that, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Lawler, 49, knows he could be headed for a pile driver into the
mat; there are 16 people running for mayor, and in recent polls, he
trails far behind the lead candidates. And he is white in a
majority-black city now enjoying its first black mayor, who is
seeking a third term. Mayor Willie Herenton's chief opponent, City
Councilman Joe Ford, is a member of the most powerful political
family in town. Also running is Pepper Rodgers, former Georgia Tech
football coach and former head coach of the Memphis Showboats, a
team in the now-defunct United States Football League.
</P>
<P>
   All the long-shot candidates have one thing going for them:
There is no runoff in Memphis mayor's races. Whoever gets the most
votes on Oct. 7 wins.
</P>
<P>
   Lawler has another advantage: Everyone in Memphis knows him.
When he asks for a vote, the voter asks for an autograph.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have more name recognition than anyone in this race, and I
haven't spent one penny,'' he said recently while signing
autographs at a grocery store grand opening.
</P>
<P>
   Spending a day with Lawler is like hanging out with a movie
star. From the event at the grocery to lunch at Corky's, the city's
favorite barbeque joint, residents young and old, black and white,
male and female not only recognized him but approached him for
autographs.
</P>
<P>
   ``My son has decided who I am voting for,'' said Majdoline
Hanna, whose son, Meelad, 10, was staring in awe as Lawler signed a
picture of himself. ``To my pal Meelad,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's popular and everyone is hoping for a change,''
Meelad's mom continued. ``And just because he's a wrestler doesn't
mean he doesn't want to do things for his community. Look at Jesse
Ventura.'' Lawler, a Memphis native, has been wrestling locally
since 1972. He also wrestles for the World Wrestling Federation,
and is an announcer on WWF's Monday night show on the USA Network.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the most watched show on cable,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even people who don't watch wrestling know Lawler as the
wrestler who slapped the late comedian, Andy Kaufman, on the ``Late
Night with David Letterman'' TV show in 1982. Lawler will play
himself in an upcoming movie about Kaufman called ``The Man in the
Moon.'' Jim Carrey will play Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   Lawler and Kaufman never revealed whether the slap was staged,
but Lawler now admits it was. He said Kaufman gave him the idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything Andy did was to elicit a response,'' he said. ``He
could not be normal.''
</P>
<P>
   Letterman, however, was not in on the joke. His discomfort after
the slap and Kaufman's subsequent cursing spree was genuine, Lawler
said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawler's wrestling persona has clashed more than once with his
candidate persona. While he is campaigning, he is barred from
appearing on ``Power Pro Wrestling,'' the local wrestling TV show,
because of rules regarding equal air time. Lawler's response: ``The
other candidates can wrestle too if they want.''
</P>
<P>
   And a local chapter of the National Organization for Women
lashed out at Lawler because his Internet Web site features
pictures of his girlfriend, Stacy Carter, scantily clad in bikinis
and nighties. He said all wrestlers' girlfriends dress like that;
it's part of the entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wrestling is a sporting event combined with a rock concert
combined with a soap opera,'' he said. And yes, they do know who
will win a match before it starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the entertainment part,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawler wants people to know he's more than just a wrestler,
however. He has a seven-point plan to ``reclaim'' Memphis. He
shares with his opponents a feeling that Memphis is lagging behind
other cities its size in terms of race relations and economic
development. The city lost its bid for a $300 million federal
empowerment zone grant, and it lost a chance to be the new home of
a National Football League team. The former Houston Oilers went to
Nashville instead, where they were promised a new stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Lawler will have a tough time convincing black people to vote
for him instead of the two leading candidates, Herenton and Ford.
He also has competition from Pete Sisson, a well-known white
politician who likely will get an endorsement from the Republican
party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unless a white candidate breaks out of the pack and the other
white candidates pretty much drop out, and the Republican party
throws its full weight behind that person, (the winner) will be
Ford or Herenton,'' said Marcus Pohlmann, a political science
professor at Rhodes College in Memphis. Jimmy Hooker, a roofer who
is black, said he will vote for Lawler.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like the administration now, and with Ford, it would
be the same thing,'' he said. ``Ford comes from a family of
politicians, so it's the same old malarkey.''
</P>
<P>
   Herenton says he is not concerned about Lawler's appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a wrestler,'' he said. Asked to elaborate, he repeated,
``He's a wrestler.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford was not so dismissive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like Jerry,'' he said. ``And he has something, some appeal,
like President Clinton. You get around him and you can't talk. If
he gets out there and meets a lot of voters, look out.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ford is concentrating his efforts on beating the
frontrunner, Herenton.
</P>
<P>
   Herenton, 59, became the city's first black mayor when he beat
the white incumbent in 1991 by just over 140 votes. He had some
help: Harold Ford Sr., then a U.S. Congressman, came down from
Washington to campaign for Herenton.
</P>
<P>
   But as soon as the election was over, Herenton and Ford went
their separate ways. Herenton says Ford wanted too much power; Ford
says Herenton dropped him like a hot potato. Both say they now are
barely civil to one another.
</P>
<P>
   Herenton faced little opposition when he ran for a second term,
but this time, he has a crowded field of candidates to beat. Harold
Ford Sr., who retired from Congress and helped pass the job on to
his son, Harold Ford Jr., considered running for mayor, but decided
his consulting firm was too lucrative to leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``I anticipated making the bid, but I couldn't, so I talked to
Joe about it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Ford, 45, is not as well-known as his brother, who is
running his campaign. In fact, when people talk about the Ford who
is running for mayor, they often say ``Harold,'' and then correct
themselves and say ``Joe.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Herenton is leading in the polls, experts say the Fords
have a lot of admirers in the black community and a talent for
getting out the vote. Harold and Joe have been working day and
night to shake as many hands in as many neighborhoods as possible
before Oct. 7.
</P>
<P>
   Herenton says his record speaks for itself.
</P>
<P>
   He enjoys strong support in the black community, as well as
support from white business people who have liked his pro-business
attitude. And then there's Atlanta native Pepper Rodgers, 67, who
is so nonchalant about the campaign that he's been on vacation. He
will not accept donations from his friends. He has no bumper
stickers or yard signs: He wrinkles his nose and shakes his
white-haired head at the thought and says he wants to be the
``statesman'' in the race.
</P>
<P>
   And he has a unique campaign promise: If elected, he'll resign.
</P>
<P>
   Memphis has two mayors, one for the city, and one for the
county. Rodgers says the metropolitan area wastes money by doubling
up on services, such as fire and police.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a consolidated government -- one head coach, one CEO,
whatever you want to call it,'' he said. ``So if I'm elected, I'd
surrender my job and the city charter to the city council and let
the people vote on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, he'd like to be that one mayor, and he's not sure his
plan would work, but the way he sees it, no one will know unless
someone tries it.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever wins, the race will go down as one of the most colorful
and contentious in this city's history.
</P>
<P>
   On a recent afternoon, Herenton looked out the window of his
huge office and watched the Mississippi River roll by. Asked if he
feels besieged by the onslaught of candidates, he said, ``That's a
good word for it. There's a lot of interest in this high-stress,
demanding job.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
