<SLUG> BC-BOATING-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKERBOCKER CUP; BLIND SAILORS COMPETE; HANDBOOK FOR NOVICES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., N.Y., R.I., Vt.)  (js) 
 By BARBARA LLOYD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Captain of Hobart-Smith Moves Up to Big-Time Match Sailing
</P>
<P>
   Only a year ago last spring, Andy Horton, as captain of the
Hobart and William Smith sailing squad, led a team that was favored
to win the national collegiate title. It was an unlikely
opportunity for a fledgling varsity crew from Geneva, N.Y., that
built a reputation as ``the little club that could.''
</P>
<P>
   The team ultimately lost. But Horton has shown since graduating
in 1998 that he can win on the national level and beyond. Last
month, he won a gold medal for the three-person division in sailing
at the Pan American Games in Canada. And now he is taking on the
big time in match racing.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers of the Knickerbocker Cup, an international match
event being sailed this year off Port Washington, N.Y., have
invited the 24-year-old Horton to compete. The event begins Friday
on Manhasset Bay with qualifying rounds, and ends Sunday with a
two-boat final.
</P>
<P>
   The Knickerbocker, now in its 18th year, usually draws its
skippers from the top echelons of match racing. But the pending
America's Cup trials in New Zealand, and the match-race world
championship last week in Copenhagen, narrowed the talent list.
Enter Andy Horton.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a little intimidating, but it is the big leagues
finally,'' Horton said from Carlyle, Ill., where he won the
Lightning Class North American championship last week. ``I've been
training for the Olympics in a Soling, and my crew needs the
match-race experience. So the opportunity is really important for
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Horton, who is from Burlington, Vt., will sail with his Olympic
crew: Andy Herlihy of Dartmouth, Mass., and Drew Buttner of
Plymouth, Mass. The lineup of the other seven Knickerbocker
skippers includes top-level racers like David Dellenbaugh of
Easton, Conn., a former America's Cup veteran; Tony Rey, a member
of the Young America cup team from New York, and Tomislav Basic of
Croatia, a world-class match-racer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Blind Sailors Competing
</P>
<P>
   Sailors who are blind or have varying degrees of visual
impairment are scheduled to compete on Wednesday and Thursday in
the ninth annual Sail Newport Blind National Championships. The
regatta, which will be sailed off Newport, R.I., is expected to
include seven teams. A fleet of J/22 sloops is being made available
by Sail Newport, a local sailing center, for the championship.
</P>
<P>
   Among those competing will be Paul Mullen of Melrose, Mass., the
defending champion, and Matt Chao of Boston, a three-time national
champion. Chao, who is fully blind, will depend on an on-board
guide to help him with directions. He will steer the boat by
depending on the feel of the tiller in his hand, the heeling angle
of the sailboat under way, and the wind in his face.
</P>
<P>
   ``The championship is becoming more competitive as we gain
experience,'' Chao said about visually impaired sailors. ``Time on
the water is everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Handbook for Novice Boaters
</P>
<P>
   The recent popularity of small craft such as kayaks and canoes
has prompted New York Harbor officials to publish a special
handbook for novice boaters.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot more people are kayaking around New York,'' said William
Winslow, spokesman for the U.S. Coast Guard Auxiliary in New York
City. ``It has become quite a sport. I think it's because the
water, especially the Hudson River, is getting a lot cleaner. But
many of the new people don't understand the currents. They also
don't understand that kayaks aren't meant to be launched from a
dock where there are tidal changes.''
</P>
<P>
   Statistics from the National Marine Manufacturers Association in
Chicago estimate that 107,800 small boats, such as canoes and
kayaks, were sold in the United States last year. The number is the
highest it has been since 1981 when 126,000 were sold.
</P>
<P>
   The 38-page information booklet was produced with a grant from
Boat/US, a national trade group. Carol Stanis of New York, the
author, said the harbor can be dangerous for small boaters given
its array of ferry boats, tugs, barges, ships and pleasure craft.
``We see that the number of people taking boating classes is not
increasing but the number of boaters is,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The safety information booklet includes local 1999 tide tables
reprinted from the ``Eldridge Tide and Pilot Book,'' as well as
basic rules of the road for New York's waterways. It is also a
resource for obtaining more detailed regulations, and for
contacting local boating groups.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
