<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5206 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-R-NY-UPSTATE-CLINTONS     08-21 1016
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-NY-UPSTATE-CLINTONS-960(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SKANEATELES, N.Y., GETS READY FOR THE CLINTONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING to delete photo note)   (See also CLINTON-VACATION) 
 (mk) 
 By JODI WILGOREN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SKANEATELES, N.Y. _ John Angyal wants to have his bologna and
eat it, too.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as the first family announced plans to vacation here at
the end of August, Angyal, the owner of the almost-eponymous Johnny
Angel's burger joint in the heart of this historic village, renamed
a signature sandwich the Hillary Special _ Full of Baloney.
</P>
<P>
   But even though he is every bit as critical of the Clintons'
politics and personalities as the proprietor of Doug's Fish Fry a
few doors down _ who has been roundly denounced for declaring that
he would not serve the president and his wife _ Angyal is hoping
the first lady will become the ``first customer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very popular sandwich,'' Angyal, 60, said as he showed
off a hamburger roll with three thick slabs of grilled bologna,
topped with melted cheese _ formerly known as the ``Politician's
Special'' _ which sells for $3.50. ``I hope she comes in and
samples it. You don't want to eat it every day, but it's good. She
should be proud.''
</P>
<P>
   Angyal, a former town supervisor who defines his politics as
``to the right of Attila the Hun,'' said he would be honored to
welcome a sitting president, though he can hardly stand the sight
of President Clinton and likes Hillary Rodham Clinton even less.
</P>
<P>
   A similar ambivalence runs through this community where
everybody knows your name _ among other things _ and it is not just
because Republicans outnumber Democrats 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   Come February, they say, you can safely shoot a cannon down the
main street, but in late summer tourists clog traffic so much that
it can take three changes of the stoplight to get through the
intersection downtown. Even without the Secret Service and hordes
of reporters, restaurants overflow with visitors in August.
</P>
<P>
   In a place where businesses have to get the approval of two
planning boards before switching signs, and a property owner who
cut down some backyard trees one morning had a complaint from the
building inspector by lunchtime, change can be a dirty word. Many
who supported the recent ban on malls and fast-food restaurants are
not so sure they want their little jewel discovered by the nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It puts us on the map a little bit, but I don't want to be on
the map,'' said Louise Robinson, 75, a Clinton fan whose lakefront
lawn is the site of weekly chamber music concerts. ``I think it's
exciting, but I just don't want all this publicity. Really. We like
this town the way it is.''
</P>
<P>
   The way it is, is the way it has been for a while.
</P>
<P>
   First settled right after the Revolutionary War, Skaneateles
(pronounced, at least by locals, skanny-AT-less) was named, using
an Indian word meaning ``long lake,'' in 1804, when the first post
office opened. The town formed in 1830; the village at its center
incorporated three years later. Travelers have been staying at the
Sherwood Inn _ and natives drinking at its tavern _ since 1807. The
Krebs, a seafood restaurant where Franklin Delano Roosevelt sat on
a wooden rocker on the porch before he became president, is
celebrating its 100th birthday this year.
</P>
<P>
   Skaneateles Lake, a 16-mile stretch that forms the index finger
of the Finger Lakes, is said to be New York's cleanest, its water
the color of Crayola's aquamarine crayon. It quenches the thirst of
some 250,000 residents in the area around Syracuse, which is 20
miles east of here.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the homes around the crystal-clear lake have been passed
down through four generations, though in recent years, wealthy
business people have begun to replace ramshackle cottages with vast
estates, like the one where the Clintons will stay Aug. 30 to Sept.
3. The town's average household income is $62,000, though there are
genuine working people ``down the road,'' as the locals say, in the
neighborhoods north of the lake.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the White House nor aides to Mrs. Clinton's presumed
campaign for the U.S. Senate will say why the first family has
chosen this conservative community that few people outside central
New York have heard of. But the locals think it is obvious.
</P>
<P>
   A quiet, pristine lake where sailors often find themselves alone
on the water. Golf courses aplenty, including the country club just
over a mile across the lake where Clinton is expected to play with
his host and two other developers. A quaint two-street village of
antique stores and sweet shops that declared itself a ``stress-free
zone'' a few years ago to attract tourists. All just a half-hour's
drive from the New York State Fair in Syracuse, where hundreds of
thousands of farmer types will be on hand in case Mrs. Clinton
cares to continue listening.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Martha's Vineyard and the Hamptons, where the first
family has vacationed in the past and plans to spend this week, in
Skaneateles the Clintons are unlikely to be feted at dinner parties
filled with Hollywood stars and big-city notables.
</P>
<P>
   Skaneateles' far-dimmer roster of marquee names includes Tim
Green, the Atlanta Falcons' former No. 99; John Walsh of
``America's Most Wanted,'' and actors Alec Baldwin and Kim
Basinger, who sometimes stroll through town when visiting Baldwin's
mother nearby (rumor has it that the celebrity couple are scoping
out a $4 million estate adjacent to the country club).
</P>
<P>
   But the Clintons can earn points for visiting a resort town that
serves the upper reaches of the much-pandered-to middle class.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the village atmosphere,'' said Tom Shaver, owner of the
Arbor House Inn, a new bed and breakfast that is already booked
with White House aides and reporters for the Clinton visit, in
explaining what is special about his hometown _ where more than
half of this year's senior class made the National Honor Society.
``The idea that it takes a whole village. Well, she came up with
that. This is a good place for it.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   The square-mile village of Skaneateles has 2,724 residents; the
town around it by the same name has 4,802 more. Local officials
said they are doing nothing special to prepare for the visit _
Supervisor Bill Pavlus, who is hoping to put a picture of himself
with the president next to the one of him and Gov. George Pataki in
his bay window, insisted that the new bricks being laid in the
sidewalk in front of Town Hall were ordered two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   While most residents are greeting the visit with a collective
shrug, there are already a few glimpses of red, white and blue
bunting and signs of a flourishing entrepreneurial spirit. One man
has been selling ``Clinton Go Home'' T-shirts out of the trunk of
his car, and practically everybody a reporter meets on the street
offers to rent his or her house (the chamber of commerce has a list
of 30 properties available that week, and the owner of Mid-Lakes
Navigation Co. says his office, complete with Internet connection,
can be had for $1,000 a day).
</P>
<P>
   Skaneateles T-shirts that say ``Where Presidents Vacation'' and
``Clinton Slept Here, Too'' are already starting to arrive. Donna
Stockweather sent Mrs. Clinton a $50 gift certificate for a facial
at her Hairtique Salon. Hilary Whitmore, owner of the Aristocats
and Friends pet boutique, has plenty of regalia on hand with
pictures of black-and-white cats resembling Socks, the first cat,
and has ordered special mugs ($20) with chocolate Labrador
retrievers and paw prints in honor of the first dog.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ordered half a dozen of them, in case his aides want to buy
him a present,'' Ms. Whitmore said. ``If somebody wants to put the
name Buddy on, we'll ship it to the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, the White House has issued a vacation schedule
indicating ``No public events,'' and many locals are convinced that
the first family will stay secluded at the home of Thomas and Cathy
McDonald, where the 8,000-square-foot main house is shaped like an
M, and the beach is set off by slabs of stone a la Greek
amphitheater.
</P>
<P>
   But one can hope. The best bet so far seems to be Rosalie's
Cucina, the priciest restaurant in town, where strings of garlic
hang over the wood pizza oven, and a guy with a mandolin sings
``It's a Small World After All'' tableside. Rosalie's owner, Gary
Robinson, is friendly with the McDonalds, and, after the flap with
Doug's Fish Fry, the White House called to check whether it would
be OK for the Clintons to dine there (absolutely).
</P>
<P>
   In a town filled with, as Angyal puts it, ``Wascally
Wepublicans,'' many residents are quick to say they would not cross
the street to shake hands with Clinton. Others argue that the
office of the presidency must be respected, regardless of who
occupies it (those spouting this view tend to be Democrats). Lots
of people are talking about fleeing town to avoid the throng; lots
more say they will stay home, maybe watch the spectacle from the
lake.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about the impending visit, most talk instead about
Doug Clark, whose public pronouncements that the Clintons would be
unwelcome in his Fish Fry have spawned letters to the local papers,
calls for a boycott and, Clark says, about 200 private pats on the
back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably should have been a little more tactful and a little
more careful,'' Clark acknowledged one recent morning as he sat at
a picnic table in his outdoor dining area, surrounded by the flower
garden he cares for himself. ``I have integrity, I have morals _ he
doesn't. I'm not the type to serve him and get on CNN and in your
paper, and then when he leaves have people say, `Gee, Doug, I
thought you thought he was a jerk.'''
</P>
<P>
   So let them go down the block to Johnny Angel's, where the owner
is cracking jokes about the contents of his bologna _ pork from
Illinois, where Mrs. Clinton was born, chicken from Arkansas, where
she spent most of her adult life, and ``not very much beef'' _ but
has also ordered 100 extra Johnny Angel's T-shirts ($12 each) in
hopes of becoming the next Black Dog, the Martha's Vineyard
restaurant whose T-shirt was a footnote in the Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives us something to talk about,'' Joe Spalding, a member
of the school board, said after lunch on the red-and-white checked
tablecloths of Johnny Angel's. ``We'll probably talk about it all
year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
