<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-DEGNAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DONALD E. DEGNAN, ADVERTISING EXECUTIVE AND PROMOTER OF CROQUET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., N.Y.)  (js) 
 By WILLIAM H. HONAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Donald E. Degnan, an advertising executive who helped guide the
sport of competitive croquet through a period of extraordinary
growth in the late 1980s and early 1990s, died on Aug. 7 while on a
business trip to New Orleans. He was 76 and lived in Palm Beach,
Fla., and Westhampton Beach, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was a heart attack, said his wife, Connie Merlino.
</P>
<P>
   Before Degnan promoted the sport, there were only dozens of
clubs in America where competitive croquet _ as opposed to backyard
or recreational croquet _ could be played. But after his tenure as
a leader of the U.S. Croquet Association and the U.S. Croquet
Foundation, there are now about 250 croquet clubs and about 5,000
players registered with the association.
</P>
<P>
   The competitive sport is distinguished by strict adherence to
rules, handicapping, national ranking and standardized equipment
including a 105-foot-by-84-foot court. The prizes are slim _ rarely
more than $5,000 for winning a major tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The game was avidly played on the East Coast in the 1920s by
members of the Algonquin Round Table such as George S. Kaufman and
Alexander Woollcott and on the West Coast by entertainment
celebrities like Harpo Marx and Samuel Goldwyn _ all of whom are in
the Croquet Hall of Fame in Newport, R.I.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, after a spurt in the 1980s, the number of clubs is on the
increase again,'' said Anne Robinson, secretary of the association.
</P>
<P>
   In drumming up interest in the sport, Degnan, a World War II
fighter pilot, would tell beginners that he had nerves of steel on
flying missions with the Flying Tigers over Burma, China and India,
but that he could be reduced to a nervous wreck when faced with a
hard-to-reach wicket.
</P>
<P>
   He also compared croquet with the dog-eat-dog world of
advertising in which he earned his living. ``It's me against you,''
he would say. ``You have to work out your strategy and decide
whether to play offensively or defensively.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he was a fine golfer, Degnan described croquet as more
challenging because it ``involves less distance and more
precision.''
</P>
<P>
   Degnan became attracted to the game in the mid-1970s. Ten years
later, he was ranked sixth in the nation. In 1992, Degnan was
inducted into the Croquet Hall of Fame in recognition of both his
skill as a player and as a promoter and planner of tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   Degnan was a member of the Palm Beach Croquet Club and the
Westhampton Beach Mallet Club. From 1994 to 1995, he was president
of the foundation, a fund-raising organization he also served for
20 years as vice president and board member. And from 1984 to 1991,
he was a vice president of the USCA, which arranges tournaments,
membership, rules and other aspects of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the croquet clubs in the United States are in
warm-climate states like Florida, Texas and Arizona. The
association says the average age of competitive players is 45.
</P>
<P>
   Croquet is one of the few competitive sports that does not
separate players based on their age and sex. The U.S. National
Croquet Championship to be held at the Meadow Club in Southampton,
N.Y., from Sept. 27 to Oct. 3, has registered players from
teen-agers to those in their 70s.
</P>
<P>
   The game is not cheap. A regulation court, or putting green, on
which the game is played may cost between $30,000 and $50,000 to
build. Necessary maintenance is expensive, too. A private club like
the Pinehurst Country Club in North Carolina, which has three
croquet courts and a resident professional, costs members more than
$2,000 a year. On the other hand, the New York Croquet Club, which
costs only $200 a year, holds tournaments at the Sheep Meadow in
Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Eugene Degnan was born in New York City on Nov. 18, 1922.
He was attending Notre Dame when World War II began. He left
college and joined the Flying Tigers, the band of daring volunteer
U.S. aviators who scored victories against the Japanese.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, Degnan returned to Notre Dame and graduated in
1946. In 1955, he founded the advertising firm of Donald Degnan
Associates. In addition to his wife, he is survived by two
daughters, Lissa Degnan of Denville, N.J., and Diana Degnan Thorson
of Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Croquet wasn't Degnan's only passion. He worked hard to keep the
memories of the Flying Tigers alive as vice president of the P-40
Pilots Association and as a member of the P-51 Pilots Association
and the Hump Pilots Association. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
