u f BC-MASS-TRAIN-REAL-925&AMP;A     08-21 1270
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASS-TRAIN-REAL-925&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASSACHUSETTS TOWN GETS ITS TRAIN BACK 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By SUSAN DIESENHOUSE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWBURYPORT, Mass. _ A new $55-million Massachusetts Bay Transit
Authority train station opened here last fall, becoming another
attraction drawing new home buyers to this seaside community 40
miles north of Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Direct commuter service to Boston was discontinued in 1976 when
the town declined to pay increased fees sought by the authority.
Its restoration is part of a systemwide expansion by the transit
authority in the '90s within a 50-mile radius of Boston. By the end
of this year, there will be 103 miles of new track and 22 new
stations at a cost of $700 million, said John Carlisle, an
authority spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   But until the station in Newburyport opened last October, the
last stop on the Newburyport/Rockport Line was nine miles to the
south in Ipswich. About 600 commuters a day boarded there. Now, 500
people a day board there and 575 get on in Newburyport for a net
gain of 475 riders, Carlisle said.
</P>
<P>
   The new service is not the only explanation for the surge in
home sales here, although it has played a part. Before Joseph
Mayer, 50, a financial planner, moved here from the landlocked
Boston suburb of Framingham last winter, he was driving 20 minutes
from home every day to get to the commuter train to Boston.
</P>
<P>
   He and his wife, Deborah, were looking for a waterfront
community with rail service to Boston when they bought a house
under construction in Port Village here, a 42-lot subdivision. Its
presence less than a mile from the new station on Route 1 impressed
them. ``We wanted the water for quality of life and the train
because it's the most efficient way to commute to the city,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Newburyport is a Colonial-era city of 17,000 with a downtown
that sits on the Merrimac River and offers a view of a vast expanse
of Atlantic Ocean. A 2 1/2 acre waterfront park with a boardwalk
has a harbor with public moorings for pleasure boats. The pristine
Plum Island Beach is about three miles away. About five miles west
of the center is the 480-acre Maudslay State Park, which has bike
paths as well as open-air concerts during warm weather and
cross-country skiing in winter.
</P>
<P>
   Economic growth in the region is the primary cause of the surge
in new housing construction, but Newburyport itself has also
benefited because it can offer both urban amenities and the charm
of a small seaside community. Clustered around the waterfront are
dozens of early 19th-century red Flemish brick buildings with shops
downstairs and apartments up.
</P>
<P>
   Since the late 1960s, an infusion of about $90 million in
federal and state funds went into redeveloping the city's
infrastructure. And over 10 years after 1968 about $12 million of
these funds, plus $7 million in private funds, were used to create
a pedestrian mall.
</P>
<P>
   The mall led to the restoration of dozens of the historic brick
buildings. Now these three- and four-story flower-trimmed buildings
are filled with shops, offices, apartments and a panoply of clubs,
cafes and restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   The historic renovations have doubled Newburyport's property
values, according to Byron J. Matthews, who was the city's mayor in
the '70s and is now chairman of North Essex Community College in
Haverhill, Mass. In the last two years, construction has begun on
more than 200 new homes: 120 single-family houses and 84
condominiums.
</P>
<P>
   This winter, work is to start on a 71-lot subdivision. In this
year's first half, meanwhile, renovations have been started on 210
existing houses, including many antiques, according to Dan
Raycroft, the city building inspector.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the new houses are being purchased by
out-of-towners,'' he said. ``There are even more new people moving
here than in the real estate boom of the 1980s.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the draws for buyers accustomed to the residential market
closer to Boston is substantially lower prices, according to Edward
T. Sullivan, vice president of Hunneman Coldwell Banker, in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   In this year's first quarter, condominiums in Boston's Back Bay
neighborhood brought an average of $445,158 for an
1,100-square-foot unit. That compares with an average sale price of
$283,056 for a single-family house, usually with at least 2,200
square feet of space, in Newburyport.
</P>
<P>
   A similar disparity is evident in the market for large old
downtown homes. In the Back Bay area of Boston, four large antique
town houses were recently sold for $1.5 million to $6.7 million for
10,000 square feet of space, Sullivan said.
</P>
<P>
   In June, Christopher and Teri Ebinger bought a three-story sea
captain's house, built 200 years ago on High Street in downtown
Newburyport, for $450,000. They expect to invest $150,000 more in
renovations, they said. After doing basic plumbing, electrical and
wiring work, they will convert the eight bedrooms on the upper two
floors into three suites. They expect to be at it for five years.
</P>
<P>
   Ebinger, 46, has a teen-age daughter who can walk to an
after-school job in the center of town. ``That makes it easy and
safe for her to socialize and make friends,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Newburyport prices may seem like a bargain to Boston buyers, but
the increasing demand for housing here has led values to rise
rapidly since the plan to restore rail service and build a new
station was announced two years ago. Average home sale prices are
up 20 percent so far this year from a year ago. In 1998, the
average sale price, $242,643, was 23 percent higher than in 1997,
according to town officials and realtors. A decade ago, a
single-family house averaged $153,000.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Of course, land prices have also been rising, reaching $150,000
to $200,000 for a 10,000-square-foot lot, up 25 percent from 1997,
said Albert R. Symes, the Wakefield developer who is planning to
build the 71-lot subdivision next to Interstate 95 here early next
year.
</P>
<P>
   In this rising market, therefore, most of the new single-family
houses start at $400,000, while the new condominiums begin at
$300,000, according to Evon Woods, a broker for Hunneman here.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, economic growth all around this city has enhanced
housing sales. The job market for technology, financial service and
high-skilled manufacturing workers is booming in southern New
Hampshire, just over the state line. The same is true along
metropolitan Boston's nearby beltways, I-495 and Route 128.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as the regional economy prospers, so will we,'' said
David M. Tierney, a partner in Prudential Harbor Realty here.
</P>
<P>
   The Mayers, who moved from Natick, were able to buy a new
3,000-square-foot house, with three bedrooms and four baths, for
$459,000. Mayer recently started his own financial consulting
company in nearby Methuen. His wife has set up her business, Dehaas
Advertising and Design Inc., in the bedroom over the garage, which
has a separate entrance.
</P>
<P>
   The subdivision where they live, Port Village, is being built by
Mesiti Development Corp. of Tewksbury. Early in 1998, the company
began installing roads, water and electrical systems. It is
building the project in phases. Of the 16 lots in Phase One, eight
homes are occupied, with five more under agreement or reserved, a
company spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Mayer, who does not make the daily commute to Boston anymore,
says he has found what he was looking for in Newburyport. ``We paid
a lot for a lifestyle,'' he said. ``It's about biking to the water;
the gourmet restaurants and theater downtown _ and the train to
Boston.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
