<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5218 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-TARHEELS-1STLEDE-     08-21 0717
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TARHEELS-1STLEDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    1STLEDE WRITETHRU
 &HT;    EDS: Fixes Curry's age; typos
 &HT;    Tar Heels dependent on quarterback Curry
 &HT;    By Norman Arey
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHAPEL HILL, N.C. _ Ronald Curry was a disappointment during his
freshman season at North Carolina. The shooting guard averaged only
2.8 points per game, managed just 1.7 assists and grabbed 1.5
rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   Oh yeah, that was basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Curry was a huge success during his freshman season on
the football field. The quarterback from Hampton, Va., was one of
the highest profile athletes ever coming out of high school. He
threw for 975 yards and six touchdowns and rushed for 419 yards and
two other scores in leading the Tar Heels to a 7-5 season. Curry
was voted the MVP in North Carolina's 20-13 victory against San
Diego State in the Las Vegas Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Curry was as big a success in football as he was an enigma in
basketball. The fact that he was forced into the football lineup
when Oscar Davenport was injured in the season opener and wasn't
counted on to contribute much in basketball may have had a lot to
do with his first year in Chapel Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I surprised a lot of people last year,'' Curry said. ``I think
the coaches were just planning on using me as a punt returner.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ronald's not just an athlete, he's a great quarterback,'' said
UNC offensive coordinator Steve Marshall. ``It's a semi-insult, to
my way of thinking, to call him an athlete.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ronald's much, much improved,'' said coach Carl Torbush.
``He's in complete command of our offense now. Over the past 10
practices, he's throwing the ball as well as anybody I've seen here
in 12 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Torbush, who was UNC's defensive coordinator before becoming
head coach, admits that having Curry does have its drawbacks. ``We
tried to sign quarterbacks ... and nobody wanted to come,'' he
said. ``We've absolutely got to sign one for next season. You can't
operate a program with just two quarterbacks.''
</P>
<P>
   Curry is backed up solely by redshirt freshman Luke Huard. .
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina opens its season against fast-growing rival
Virginia. But the Tar Heels, who struggled on offense last year,
may be a completely different team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, of the eleven starters on offense coming into the
first game, only three were left standing at the end of the year,''
Torbush said. ``But with the experience Ronald had last year, we're
going to be better. We have five tailbacks who I feel can
contribute. Last year, we had to move two fullbacks to the tailback
spot.''
</P>
<P>
   Torbush compares Curry to Charlie Ward, who won the Heisman
while directing Florida State's offense in the early '90s. ``Ward
was a special player and if we can put more good players around
Ronald, he has the opportunity to be that good. He's at the point
that he can make a good team great.''
</P>
<P>
   Curry says the hoopla and gaggle of writers and radio/TV folks
that constantly seek him out doesn't bother him. ``In my first game
in high school, we went into overtime and I scored the winning
touchdown and I've had a lot of press ever since,'' he said. ``I'm
just going to be the same old Ronald. I'm never going to change
personally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've changed as a football player, I'm much better,'' he said.
``When I make mistakes now, I know the mistake I made. Being a
quarterback takes a lot. I know everything about it now.''
</P>
<P>
   As to which sport he'll eventually pursue, Curry shakes his
head. ``The decision is mine to make and I'm not even close to
making it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Over the summer, Curry shed the No. 13 jersey he wore last
season and donned No. 1 _ as if he needed any more attention than
he gets on the field anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Location: Chapel Hill, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Enrollment: 24,255.
</P>
<P>
   Nickname: Tar Heels.
</P>
<P>
   Stadium: Kenan Memorial Stadium (60,000).
</P>
<P>
   Record: 591-412-54.
</P>
<P>
   Conference Championships: Five (1963, 1971, 1972, 1977, 1980).
</P>
<P>
   1998 Record: 7-5 overall, 5-3 ACC.
</P>
<P>
   1999 schedule:
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 4, Virginia; Sept. 11,at Indiana; Sept. 25, Florida State;
Oct. 2, at Clemson; Oct. 9, at Georgia Tech; Oct. 16, at Houston;
Oct. 23 at Maryland; Oct. 30, Furman; Nov. 6, Wake Forest; Nov. 11,
N.C. State (Charlotte); Nov. 20 , Duke
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
