<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 18:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5220 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-BATTER-ROUTINES-8     08-21 1142
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BATTER-ROUTINES-820&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BETWEEN PITCHES, THERE'S A GAME WITHIN A GAME
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ The Velcro straps on Chuck Knoblauch's batting
gloves don't really need tightening, there isn't any dirt in his
spikes to be tapped out, and there's nothing wrong with the grip of
his bat.
</P>
<P>
   But before every pitch, Knoblauch, the Yankees' leadoff batter,
readjusts his batting gloves, with the particularity of a
Buckingham Palace butler.
</P>
<P>
   Before every pitch, Knoblauch uses the barrel of his bat to tap
his right spike and his left, as if he had just stepped through a
cow pasture.
</P>
<P>
   Before every pitch, he holds his bat directly in front of him,
stares at it, twisting and squeezing it, like some mountain climber
feeling for a safe place to hang on.
</P>
<P>
   Before every pitch, Knoblauch steps out of the batter's box to
go through this elaborate preening, the pitcher waiting all the
while.
</P>
<P>
   But the real adjustments are going on in Knoblauch's mind, as he
reviews the circumstances and anticipates the next pitch. Knoblauch
has been going through the routine so long now that is almost
subconsciously done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't know exactly what I do, because I'm really
thinking about the pitch,'' Knoblauch said. ``Maybe the pitch or
the count, or maybe it's to slow that pitcher down a little bit and
get him out of his rhythm. It's all about getting comfortable. It's
kind of a fidgeting routine while your mind is at work.''
</P>
<P>
   It is part of what makes Knoblauch an effective leadoff hitter;
the game seems to stop during his at-bats. Knoblauch almost
uniformly takes the first pitch, steps out of the box, then often
takes the second pitch, steps out, and eventually the pitcher has
thrown five or more pitches to him and the pace of the game belongs
to Knoblauch.
</P>
<P>
   David Cone pitched to Knoblauch in the past, when they were
opponents, and Knoblauch's routine, in particular, didn't bother
Cone. He and Andy Pettitte and others said that when they faced
Knoblauch, they would try to time their own movement from pitch to
pitch so that when he was ready to bat, they were ready to throw a
pitch, rather than simply standing on the mound and waiting for
him.
</P>
<P>
   But Knoblauch's entire at-bat, taken as a whole _ his patience,
his ability to foul off pitches, stepping out of the box _ could be
exasperating. ``Maybe after a long at-bat, that's where it kind of
takes its toll,'' Cone said. ``You know you're really in for a
battle. I just remember wishing he would put the first ball in
play. If he was going to get a hit, then get a hit. I didn't want
to throw 15 pitches, and go through that whole routine. That's what
made him so tough, and difficult to face.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Jeff Nelson, the Yankees reliever: ``I don't like guys who
step out and take forever. I think that's ridiculous. But then,
maybe sometimes I walk around the mound and take my time, so ...
.''
</P>
<P>
   Every player has a routine. Before each at-bat, Bernie Williams
lays his bat down across the front of home plate, notes the spot
where the knob lies, then draws a line straight back, in the
direction of the catcher; Williams uses this to coordinate his foot
placement. Paul O'Neill, the Yankees' right fielder, steps out of
the batter's box and practices his swing, aiming his bat downward
at a 45-degree angle.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Jeter has taken to adjusting his batting gloves between
pitches. Cone recalled the deliberate at-bats of Mike Hargrove, the
Cleveland manager. When Hargrove played, he was known as the Human
Rain Delay, for all of his poking and preening and preparation.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Myers, the longtime closer, circled the front of the mound
after every pitch, left to right, before climbing back up to the
rubber from the left-field side, always careful to walk in the same
footprints. Jason Grimsley, the Yankees reliever, tugs at the same
spot on the bill of his cap before every pitch; underneath, the
stitching on the bill is worn. Mike Mussina, the Orioles' All-Star
pitcher, will pause briefly as he stands atop the rubber, staring
downward at the mound _ a moment to focus his thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   Nomar Garciaparra, Boston's shortstop, may have the longest set
of adjustments _ involving his batting gloves, his wrist bands, his
bat and, finally, his feet, lifting one and then the other as he
sets himself in the box. During Jeter's only at-bat in the All-Star
Game in Boston this year, he good-naturedly imitated some of
Garciaparra's movements, grinning and glancing over at the American
League dugout to be sure his actions were being noted.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes players aren't aware of their particular movements
until they see others imitating them. Before every pitch,
Minnesota's Terry Steinbach grabs the bill of his cap with his left
hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know it until it was called to my attention,''
Steinbach said. ``We had a guy who was good at mimicking other
players, and my reaction was, `I don't do that.' I looked at my cap
and it had pine tar on it. I don't do it before each at-bat; I do
it before every pitch. It's not orchestrated. It's just habit.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Knoblauch can't remember the origin of his routine, whether he
started in high school, in Houston, or when he was in college, at
Texas A&AMP;M. Tom Kelly, Minnesota's manager when Knoblauch broke into
the majors with the Twins, said the second baseman has had the same
approach all along.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch said: ``Two years ago I saw a videotape of when I was
hitting in the minor leagues, and I kind of did the same thing.
It's something I might've always done, or maybe it's progressed as
I've gone along.''
</P>
<P>
   The practice fits his grating professional personality as a
leadoff hitter. Knoblauch is, as Jeter called him affectionately, a
pest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pitchers probably get frustrated, but it's working if that's
the way they view it, like I'm trying to slow them down,''
Knoblauch said. ``It's like when you're a batter and you throw your
helmet: the pitcher knows he's got the best of you. If the
pitcher's thinking about me standing out of the box, then he's not
thinking about throwing his next pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Hall of Fame outfielder Frank Robinson was asked to
talk to players about ways to speed the pace of games, and Robinson
believed the Yankees consistently played some of the slowest games.
He nudged manager Joe Torre to ask his players to play faster, and
Robinson spoke to some players individually.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson approached Knoblauch, and before Robinson said
anything, Knoblauch asked, ``You're going to talk to me about
stepping out of the box?'' No, Robinson replied, he just wanted to
talk about hitting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe now, because I've been around for a while,'' Knoblauch
said, ``it's just kind of seen as part of what I do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
