<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 18:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5225 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-CIVILWAR-REMEMBER-COX     08-21 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIVILWAR-REMEMBER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Anniversary of the fall of Atlanta marked
 &HT;    By Will Anderson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ About 90 people gathered at the state Capitol Saturday
to commemorate the 135th anniversary of the fall of Atlanta and
garner support for preserving the state's Civil War battlefields.
</P>
<P>
   The event brought descendants of Civil War veterans _ Yankees
and Rebels alike _ from as far away as California to talk about
their ancestors' involvement in the war. Much of the information
was gleaned from history books, personal diaries, letters written
to loved ones and other obscure documents. A few of the attendees
had ancestors on both sides of the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   In late August 1864, Gen. William T. Sherman's troops had all
but surrounded Atlanta and his cannons were bombarding the city
every day. But the Union troops were having trouble breakihng
through because the Confederates were entrenched on the outskirts
of town behind earthen fortifications built largely by slave labor,
said Civil War historian William R. Scaife.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta troops' only supply line was the railroad that came
through Jonesboro to the south. When the Confederates were defeated
at Jonesboro on Aug. 31, it opened the door for the Union invasion
of to Atlanta, which fell the next day.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's reunion was organized by the Civil War Commission and
the private non-profit Georgia Battlefields Association. The two
groups are working jointly to preserve the state's Civil War
battlefields, such as Griswoldville near Macon, where one of the
few skirmishes took place during Sherman's march to the sea after
the burning of Atlanta. Griswoldville battle park was dedicated
last November.
</P>
<P>
   The organizations also want to buy a portion of the land where
the battle of Resaca took place between Atlanta and Chattanooga in
May 1864, but have run into difficulties with Scott Fletcher, the
owner of the 1,200-acre property, who bought the land in 1998
knowing the state wanted it preserved as a park.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers drew a parallel between Saturday's reunion and the
1911 Peace March of Atlanta, in which the Peace Monument was
unveiled in Peidmont Park. The monument, which still stands,
depicts an angel of peace tapping a Confederate soldier on the left
shoulder to announce the Civil War has ended, said Oliver J.
Keller, who serves on the Civil War Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The 1911 march brought together Civil War veterans from both the
North and South with the goal of healing the scars of war. With
that in mind, Keller said Saturday's reunion wasn't like other
Civil War gatherings in the South.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not out there waving battle flags,'' said Keller, a
Pennsylvania native. ``There was no firing of guns and no one
playing Dixie. We're all Americans North and South, and it's all
part of the American story.''
</P>
<P>
   From left to right are: Addison Farley, Brad Quinlin, Terry
Gunnels, Chip Uhlir, Mike Waters and Capers Ogletree with the 21st
of Ohio during the gathering at the State capital for the
comemoration of the Peace Monument of 1911 when a momument was
erected in Piedmont Park honoring the end of the Civil War. STAFF
PHOTO BY W.A. BRIDGES JR. for CITY.
</P>
<P>
   Photos by W.A. BRIDGES JR. / Staff
</P>
<P>
   Boldword Addison Farley, Brad Quinlin, Terry Gunnels, Chip
Uhlir, Mike Waters and Capers Ogletree with the 21st of Ohio gather
at the Capitol for the comemmoration of the fall of Atlanta and the
end of the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   990821 ATLANTA........Mike Wennin of Cartersville bows his head
during prayer at the State capital for the comemoration of the
Peace Monument of 1911 when a momument was erected in Piedmont Park
honoring the end of the Civil War. STAFF PHOTO BY W.A. BRIDGES JR.
for CITY.
</P>
<P>
   PHOTOG / Staff
</P>
<P>
   Boldword Mike Wennin of Cartersville bows his head during prayer
at the ceremony marking the end of the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
