-- For Toms River's Kevin Fox, vice president of a board that is
trying to raise $70,000 for a bronze sculpture of a ballplayer with
his coach to commemorate last year's Little League World Series
victory. For Fox, it's once-in-a-lifetime all over again, as the
hometown Boys of Summer have landed once again in the Little League
World Series. If the team returns victorious from Williamsport,
Pa., where the series begins on Sunday, the world title will be its
second in a row. (Laura Pedrick/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- Aug. 21, 1999 -- BBO-DROPOUT-2, 8-21 -- Four
years ago, George Carrion, now 22, was one of the best high school
baseball prospects to come out of New York in 20 years, a
hard-throwing pitcher and power-hitting shortstop from the Bronx's
De Witt Clinton High. After one season at a Texas junior college,
the Texas Rangers signed him to a contract with a $700,000 bonus to
play in their minor league system. Last summer, Carrion abruptly
quit. He bolted from the Rangers with neither warning nor
explanation, drove home to New York and has been, in his words,
``just hanging out'' ever since. (G. Paul Burnett/New York Times
Photo)
