<P>
   (NYT4) OAKLAND, Calif. -- Aug. 21, 1999 --
SILICON-VALLEY-TRAFFIC-2, 8-21 -- For many professionals at dot-com
companies in Silicon Valley, the boom in the Internet has resulted
in a commuting bust, forcing them to funnel onto increasingly
congested highways that snake in and around the crowded Bay Area.
Scores of people in Oakland, like Francis Torrence, right, line up
daily to catch a ride to San Francisco. Passengers mill about until
drivers, whom they do not know but who want to save the $2 San
Francisco-Oakland Bay Bridge toll and use the commuter lane, pick
them up. An unspoken etiquette has evolved among repeat carpoolers.
(Peter Dasilva/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) SAN FRANCISCO -- Aug. 21, 1999 --
SILICON-VALLEY-TRAFFIC-1, 8-21 -- As Northern California's economy
has boomed, traffic has grown increasingly congested. Lindsey
Cigarran, 24-year-old group manager of Beyond.com's entertainment
software division, with co-worker and commuting partner David
Hollister, drive an average of 2 1/2 hours every day to and from
work. For many, the daily Silicon Valley commute is likely to get
worse before it gets better, leaving some to wonder whether the
plugged-in driving lifestyle will end. ``It is a full-on
nightmare,'' says Ms. Cigarran. (Peter Dasilva/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. -- Aug. 21, 1999 -- NM-GOV-DRUGS, 8-21
-- Gov. Gary E. Johnson, 46, of New Mexico, finishing his morning
mile swim recently. Johnson, a second-term Republican,
unflinchingly admits he used marijuana and cocaine in college, and
he now wants the nation to consider alternatives to the war on
drugs. ``We are spending incredible amounts of our resources on
incarceration, law enforcement and courts,'' he says. ``As an
extension of everything I've done in office, I made a cost-benefit
analysis, and this really stinks.'' (Kevin Moloney/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) PALO ALTO, Calif. -- Aug. 21, 1999 -- HP-GLASS-CEILING,
8-21 -- Lewis E. Platt, Hewlett-Packard's 58-year-old chairman.
Platt's success in turning company policy around from the
traditional ``man rules the roost'' culture to a gender-blind ethos
holds an important lesson for the rest of corporate America: A
little direction at the top can go a long way. As for the future,
Platt is leaving it up to the company's employees to make sure
Hewlett-Packard does not revert to its old self. Specific programs
are not important, he says. ``It's the core values.'' (Peter
DaSilva/New York Times Photo)
</P>
