<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 18:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5229 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-INVEST-SCAMS-NYTR &LR;      08-21 0775
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-SCAMS-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TOP TEN INVESTMENT SCAMS
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JOHN HIELSCHER   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARASOTA, Fla. _ The time has never been better to make money in
the investment world _ and to get ripped off by scam artists.
</P>
<P>
   Securities fraud costs American consumers billions of dollars
every year, and industry regulators say technological advances and
investors' hunger for profits have generated a new wave of
investment cons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, we have an ideal climate for fraud,'' said Peter C.
Hildreth, president of the North American Administrators
Association, which represents state securities regulators.
</P>
<P>
   ``Millions of new investors, many of whom expect unrealistically
high returns, are looking for places to put their money. At the
same time, we're living through an Internet-driven technology
revolution that is a boon to investors and con artists alike,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   State and national securities regulators are the cops who are
supposed to protect investors. But they say their resources are
limited, and investors must take responsibility to protect
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``As always, investors are the first line of defense against
fraud,'' Hildreth said. ``The best weapons investors have to
protect themselves and their money are skepticism and common
sense.''
</P>
<P>
   The association recently named the ``Top Ten Investment Scams''
that target consumers these days. Here they are, in order of
seriousness or prevalence:
</P>
<P>
   _ Internet fraud. Con artists are using the World Wide Web to
``pump and dump'' small stocks, peddle bogus offshore ``prime
bank'' notes and run variations of the classic pyramid scheme.
Regulators suggest never investing based solely on an Internet tip;
do the research yourself.
</P>
<P>
   _ Investment seminars. Some expensive seminars promise people
the secret to getting rich quick. But often, it's the people
running the seminar that make the big money off admission fees and
selling books and audiotapes. Some new one-day seminars say they
can turn average investors into successful day traders. They forget
to tell you that most day traders lose their money within several
months.
</P>
<P>
   _ Affinity group fraud. Con artists like to target members of
closely knit religious, political or ethic groups. The crooks are,
or claim to be, part of the affiliation and take advantage of the
natural trust among similar people. The scammers often offer phony
employment or financial advice.
</P>
<P>
   _ Abusive sales practices. Some brokers specialize in aggressive
cold calling to promote low-priced securities. Regulators say they
are making progress by suspending and prosecuting those microcap
stock manipulators. Investors can just hang up the phone.
</P>
<P>
   _ Telemarketing fraud. Boiler rooms _ those high-pressure
telephone sales operations _ open up every day to sell illegal or
phony investments. The scammers often try to take advantage of the
news headlines, such as Y2K concerns or breakthroughs in computers
or biotechnology.
</P>
<P>
   _ Promissory notes. These investments are promoted as
high-yielding investments that are guaranteed by bonding companies.
Too often they are notes in companies that don't even exist.
Regulators say this is one of the fastest-growing frauds in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   _ Viatical investment scams. Viatical contracts are interests in
the death benefits of terminally ill patients, such as cancer or
AIDS victims. The insured gets a percentage of the death benefit to
help them during their last days, and investors get a share in the
death benefits, such as life insurance, after a fee is paid to the
viatical investment broker. Regulators say this is one the hottest
new investment products and one of the riskiest, for no other
reason than speculating on when an ill person may die.
</P>
<P>
   _ Entertainment fraud. Investors who hope to hit it big on the
next ``Titanic'' can be easy prey for scammers selling phony
interests in movies, cable TV shows, video games or other
entertainment products.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ponzi schemes. The classic swindle attracts investors with the
promise of high rates of return over a short period of time. The
earliest investors are paid with money from the most recent
investors, not from any actual earnings. The Ponzi scheme always
collapses, and the big winners are always the con artists.
</P>
<P>
   _ Illegal franchise offerings. Many people would like to own
their own businesses, but some crooks are selling phony franchises
or making inadequate disclosures about the risks and costs of such
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   (The Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
