nightmare,'' says Ms. Cigarran. (Peter Dasilva/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. -- Aug. 21, 1999 -- NM-GOV-DRUGS, 8-21
-- Gov. Gary E. Johnson, 46, of New Mexico, finishing his morning
mile swim recently. Johnson, a second-term Republican,
unflinchingly admits he used marijuana and cocaine in college, and
he now wants the nation to consider alternatives to the war on
drugs. ``We are spending incredible amounts of our resources on
incarceration, law enforcement and courts,'' he says. ``As an
extension of everything I've done in office, I made a cost-benefit
analysis, and this really stinks.'' (Kevin Moloney/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) PALO ALTO, Calif. -- Aug. 21, 1999 -- HP-GLASS-CEILING,
8-21 -- Lewis E. Platt, Hewlett-Packard's 58-year-old chairman.
Platt's success in turning company policy around from the
traditional ``man rules the roost'' culture to a gender-blind ethos
holds an important lesson for the rest of corporate America: A
little direction at the top can go a long way. As for the future,
Platt is leaving it up to the company's employees to make sure
Hewlett-Packard does not revert to its old self. Specific programs
are not important, he says. ``It's the core values.'' (Peter
DaSilva/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
