<P>
   (NYT10) UNDATED -- Aug. 21, 1999 -- GERMANY-REUNIFICATION, 8-21
-- Wally Mueller and Waltraut Neumann in 1945. When Wally Mueller
and Waltraut Neumann met at the end of World War II, close to 90
percent of Berlin's 1.5 million apartments had been damaged by
Allied bombing. Aged 18, penniless, they went to work as
``Truemmerfrauen'' -- two of the thousands of ``rubble women''
whose job it was to clear up the mess. That history is present in
the lives of Mrs. Mueller and Mrs. Neumann, who found themselves on
opposite sides of the Berlin wall when it went up in 1961, just as
it is alive in the hearts of many of this city's 3.5 million
people. In Berlin, unlike Bonn, the difficulty of making Germany
whole is palpable. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
