<HEADER>
A5237 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX     08-21 0669
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JALEEL WHITE OUTGROWS URKEL PAST WITH NEW SITCOM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Midway through his nine-year reign as the suspender-snapping,
squeaky-voiced Urkel on the family sitcom ``Family Matters,''
Jaleel White came to a disconcerting-though-hardly-startling truth:
Those who invent strong characters are usually stuck with them.
</P>
<P>
   It was around this time White began to design Life After Urkel.
The plan: To prove that he could step outside an exaggerated
character whose oversized glasses, plaid shirts and denims hiked to
the hilt got all the laughs.
</P>
<P>
   While continuing to play the beloved nerd, White worked in a
number of supporting characters. Grandpa Urkel. Grandma Urkel.
Sister Urkel. You get the drift.
</P>
<P>
   One character he designed specifically for himself. The gimmick
behind Stefan Urquelle, an Urkel alter-ego who emerged after a trip
to a ``transformation chamber,'' was no gimmick. Urquelle was
suave, handsome and wore pleated pants and fitted sport coats. He
was everything Urkel was not, exactly the image White wanted to
cultivate.
</P>
<P>
   There are similarities, but Stefan Urquelle isn't the character
who fronts ``Grown Ups,'' White's new comedy series premiering at
7:30 p.m. CDT Monday on UPN. (The sitcom is the first of more than
40 new programs that will roll out between now and October. Just a
warning.)
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the character is a variation on White himself, not to
mention something of a TV anomaly: Here's an established sitcom
star who is practically starting from scratch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grown Ups'' centers on White's J. Calvin Frazier, or ``J,''
and his quick-witted childhood buddy Gordon (Dave Ruby), who looks
like he'll be the target of fat-boy humor in regards to his girth
and his girl. He's married to a cute blonde (Marissa Ribisi) who
outside a TV stage set probably wouldn't share lunch with him, let
alone a pillow.
</P>
<P>
   The series targets that uncertain period shortly after college
and shortly before family commitments consume you. As J explains to
Buddy while shooting hoops in Monday night's pilot: ``That job I
used to have? It's now my career. That girl you used to date? She's
now your wife. Say goodbye to childhood.''
</P>
<P>
   I should mention that this serious moment comes right before
their basketball goes sailing through a car window and off they run
in the opposite direction. So much for adult responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   Old fans will be surprised by White. He's tall, angular, quite
muscular and even relatively credible as a well-dressed
professional with a serious sexual swagger. His portrayal of J is
actually written to be complicated; he seems conceited in one scene
and thoughtful and selfless in the next. As White mentioned in an
interview, ``Isn't that what real life is like? Not only are people
in that time of their lives not perfect, but they often change
stripes depending on the person they're dealing with and what they
need from them.''
</P>
<P>
   That makes sense, but I don't know how much of that comes
through in the pilot. Nor is it clear whether the series, produced
by Al Haymon (''Between Brothers'') and Jonathan Prince, (the
terrible ``Ask Harriet''), will be allowed to explore such issues
without making them appear silly.
</P>
<P>
   What ``Grown Ups'' has going for it is a surprisingly restrained
pace and rhythm, and a tendency to stay away from the traditional
sitcom fodder that characterized White's years on ``Family
Matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps we shouldn't be so surprised by the richness seeping out
of the scenes involving White and Gabrielle Union, a former
schoolmate. For a moment or two, ``Grown Ups'' actually steered
clear of the yuk-every-other-line formula. It made me double-check:
Is this UPN?
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kperkins(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-99 1912EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990821.0195 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 19:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5238 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-CHASS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      08-21 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CHASS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: MARATHON BECOMES A SPRINT IN THE NL
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1993 the San Francisco Giants won 103 games and didn't make
the playoffs because the Atlanta Braves, playing in the same
division, won 104. The wild-card beast reared its ugly head in
baseball the next time they had playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Six years later, the National League is faced with a
mathematical impossibility: Four into three won't go. The Mets,
Atlanta, Houston and Cincinnati are competing for three playoff
spots. One of them won't make it, even though they all could have
better records than the Arizona Diamondbacks, the presumptive
winner of the NL West.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's something you have to live with all winter,'' said
Brian Cashman, the Yankees' general manager, just an observer in
this instance.
</P>
<P>
   But could wild-card expansion, a la the National Football
League, be far behind?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if that's realistic,'' Gerry Hunsicker, the
Houston general manager, said.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't, said Jim Bowden, the Cincinnati general manager. ``I
think we have it right,'' he added. ``Four teams in a league is
just right. I don't like the diluted system like the NHL has.
That's what makes races so great. It'll be a lot of fun. All four
teams have six weeks to prove they're better than the other one.''
</P>
<P>
   The wild card, Bowden said, ``creates such exciting scoreboard
watching; you're not just watching your own division, you're
watching others because of the wild card.''
</P>
<P>
   The need to peruse the scoreboard will be reduced to one game
for each of the four teams this week. In one of those delightfully
great confluences of the schedule, the Mets will play the Astros
while the Braves play the Reds Monday, Tuesday and Wednesday. If
only this were the final weekend of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is fun,'' Bowden said. ``You're on pins and needles every
inning.''
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, if every team in the division races were assured of a
playoff spot, the races would command less interest. The idea of a
race is for someone to win and for someone to lose.
</P>
<P>
   The introduction of the wild card to baseball diluted the races
and the significance of a division championship. If the Mets and
the Braves were competing for the NL East title but knew the loser
would be the wild card, the suspense would be sucked out of
September.
</P>
<P>
   It took only until the third year of the expanded playoffs for a
team that didn't finish first to become the World Series champion.
The Florida Marlins, of course, instantly self-destructed, but
that's another story. The idea of a second-place team being the
major leagues' champion is insulting to nearly a century of
first-place teams that were champions.
</P>
<P>
   That is not to say the wild-card concept has not created
interest in its own right. In this instance, it makes the four-team
race more intriguing because only one team instead of two teams
will miss the October fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think our division will be decided until the last
week,'' Steve Phillips, the Mets' general manager, said. ``We play
the Braves six of the last 12 games. I figure our division will
come down to that, and it's pretty clear that neither Cincinnati or
Houston is going away. I expect both will keep themselves within
striking distance.''
</P>
<P>
   With the races so close, it is not inconceivable that the
regular-season schedule could end with one or more ties. Last
season, the Chicago Cubs and the San Francisco Giants wound up in a
tie for the NL wild-card spot, and the Cubs snatched it in a
one-game playoff.
</P>
<P>
   Consider some of the possibilities for ties this season. The
Reds and the Astros could tie for first place in the Central,
finishing with the same record as the second-place Mets. In that
event, the Mets would automatically be the wild-card team because
the loser of the playoff game between the Reds and the Astros for
the Central championship would have one more loss than the Mets.
Results of that kind of playoff count in the regular-season
standings.
</P>
<P>
   What if all four teams were to finish with the same record, not
very likely but not an impossible development? The teams tied for
first would play each other for the championships of their
respective divisions; then the losers of those games, because they
would still have the same record, would play for the wild-card
designation. Loser goes home.
</P>
<P>
   ``In April,'' Hunsicker said, ``we talk about it being a
marathon. But now it comes down to a 40-game sprint.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets were not good sprinters last season. They wore down
with the finishing line in sight, losing their last five games.
This time around they appear to be built for the long haul, and it
is Atlanta and Houston that could falter. Both have injury problems
that they have to overcome to survive the next six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   This week's series between the Mets and the Astros, and the
Braves and the Reds, won't determine the outcome of the races. But
they will serve as a nice prelude to October.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
