<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-AL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAUBACH A ROY HOBBS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A former replacement player who had never played
in the majors before Boston signed him last winter, 27-year-old
Brian Daubach has suddenly become the talk of the town. His
$230,000 salary is roughly 1/60th of Mo Vaughn's $13.3 million
average salary with the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   His three-run ninth-inning double Wednesday gave the Red Sox a
huge 6-5 over Oakland, one of their rivals for the wild-card spot.
Vaughn, their former first baseman, hasn't played in a meaningful
game since opening day. Daubach also has 19 homers and 68 RBI,
numbers comparable to Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (the fans) appreciate where he's come from, and maybe
they can associate with the work ethic and the time it's taken to
get the opportunity,'' Boston manager Jimy Williams said this past
week. ``And then to be successful like that, maybe a lot of them
feel that it's them in that uniform with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Welcome back Baerga: How badly did Carlos Baerga want to return
to Cleveland? He waived a clause that would have jacked his salary
from $500,000 to $1.5 million if he was traded from San Diego.
Baerga played with the Indians from 1990 to 1996. They traded him
because he'd lost his power and had burned himself out on the
baseball nightlife. Now he's back because the Indians need somebody
to play third base. Travis Fryman (right knee) and Wil Cordero
(left wrist) are still on the DL and not expected back until
mid-September. Enrique Wilson has played well defensively at third,
but had a recent 0-for-26 slump. Baerga started at third Monday and
went 2 for 4. Tuesday, he hit a two-run homer. Each time the fans
gave him a huge standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   Not true for Belle: The same could not be said for wayward son
Albert Belle, who went 4 for 20 this season at Jacobs Field while
his new team, Baltimore, went 0-6. Last Sunday, Belle took a wild
swing in the fourth inning and his bat went sailing into the
stands. Belle stalked over to the railing and demanded it back as
the crowd booed. One reason Belle may have demanded the bat back:
Before he got caught corking his bat in 1994, Belle often went
after his broken bats that sailed into the stands. ``Albert doesn't
want to give anything to Cleveland,'' Indians reliever Paul Shuey
said. ``I'm surprised he doesn't go up in the stands after his foul
balls here.''
</P>
<P>
   Viva Orosco: It has been 12 years since relief pitcher Jesse
Orosco put lampblack in Kirk Gibson's hat before a spring training
game, a prank that helped focus the Dodgers and touch off their
miraculous run to a World Series title. Tuesday night in Baltimore,
Orosco came out of the bullpen for the 1,072nd time in his career,
making him baseball's all-time leader in total pitching
appearances. He passed Dennis Eckersley and likely set a record
that should go unchallenged for quite awhile. Orosco threw just two
pitches, retiring Twins second baseman Todd Walker on a deep fly
ball to center on his way into the record book.
</P>
<P>
   Josh update: Outfielder Josh Hamilton, the No. 1 overall pick in
this year's June Draft by Tampa Bay, has been promoted from Rookie
League Princeton to short-season Single-A Hudson Valley in the New
York-Penn League. Hamilton hit .347 for Princeton with 49 runs, 20
doubles, four triples, 10 home runs and 18 stolen bases. The news
isn't so promising on the No. 2 pick, Florida's Josh Beckett, who
says he is prepared to go to junior college after a contract
stalemate with the Marlins. Beckett began by asking for $8 million,
and the Marlins offered a bonus similar to the $3.95 million that
the Devil Rays gave Hamilton. If Beckett goes to school, the
Marlins won't be able to negotiate with him again until the season
ends in the spring. That would give the club about a week before
next year's draft.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
