<SLUG> BC-RAC-SARATOGA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SILVERBULLETDAY CONFIRMS HER CREDENTIALS  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ In a smashing performance on a track
that often foils the greatest horses, Silverbulletday won the 119th
running of the Alabama Stakes by nine lengths Saturday and
confirmed her rank as the prima donna among 3-year-old fillies in
thoroughbred racing.
</P>
<P>
   The bay filly from California won her seventh race in eight
starts this year and the 13th in 15 starts in her career, and
erased the doubts about distance that were raised when she finished
seventh in the Belmont Stakes two months ago. She overcame a slow
pace in the Alabama, proved that she could win at a mile and a
quarter and showed that she might even become a candidate for Horse
of the Year if she can exert her talents against colts in the
second half of the racing season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Awesome, that's the word that says it best,'' the jockey Jerry
Bailey said. ``She surprised even me today, she's that good.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a little wide going into the first turn, and we had to
run down a slow pace. But she was always within five lengths of the
lead, and I knew that I had a lot of horse. I was confident she
would blow by the leader and hold off any challengers. When I rode
her in the Belmont, the race just wasn't her style. But I would be
comfortable riding her against colts again.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Baffert, the California trainer who lost Real Quiet earlier
this week to a leg injury, indicated that he would continue to run
his prize filly against other fillies for now, at least. Meanwhile,
having been thwarted in the Belmont Stakes the last two years with
a Triple Crown on the line, he crossed a personal barrier by
finally winning a Grade I stakes in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Jerry,'' he said, ```If you take this filly back and
let her lope around, you'll have so much horse, she'll outsprint
them.' When she came back, she wasn't tired at all. We were going
to run her in the Haskell, but things didn't work out. She proved
that I could win a GradeI race in New York. With Real Quiet being
out, you have to enjoy the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Silverbulletday gave her performance in a light drizzle in the
premiere event for fillies at Saratoga Race Course, and she did it
with style and command. Bailey had her placed fifth after half a
mile, third after three-quarters, second after one mile, and he
never showed her the whip as she caught Strolling Belle at the head
of the homestretch and flew past.
</P>
<P>
   At the wire, they were strung out all over the track behind her:
nine lengths back to Strolling Belle, three more to Gandria and 6{
lengths to the filly On A Soapbox, who won the Coaching Club
American Oaks last month at a mile and a half.
</P>
<P>
   Silverbulletday ran the mile and one-quarter in 2:02 3/5,
returned $2.80 for a $2 bet to win and banked $240,000, raising her
career earnings to $2.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a gift from heaven,'' said Mike Pegram, who owns the
superstar. ``A once-in-a-lifetime horse. But at this point, the
Breeders' Cup Classic is not a possibility in my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   And Mike Smith, who set the slow pace aboard Strolling Belle,
said: ``I had the pace I wanted, and more. Everything went our way.
But the real Silverbulletday showed up.''
</P>
<P>
   FINISH LINES
</P>
<P>
   The field did not include Dreams Gallore, who won the Mother
Goose at Belmont Park and ran second in the Coaching Club American
Oaks. ``The Coaching Club took a lot out of her,'' said her
trainer, Steve Asmussen. ``Right now, she's walking the shed row at
Churchill Downs, and I'm uncertain when she'll race again.'' ...
Backstage at Saratoga, the candidates were hustling for the peak
race of the season, next Saturday's $1 million Travers at a mile
and a quarter. Elliott Walden worked both his stars, Menifee,
winner of the Haskell, and Ecton Park, who won the Jim Dandy on the
same day, Aug. 8. Menifee breezed five furlongs in 1:00 3/5 and
galloped out six furlongs in 1:14 1/5. Ecton Park went five in 1:01
and galloped out six in 1:14 3/4. Walden, pleased with both
workouts, said, ``We have a shot in the Travers with both horses.''
... Lemon Drop Kid, who won the Belmont, breezed five furlongs in
1:00 2/5. It was his second workout since he ran second in the Jim
Dandy. And Badger Gold, third in the Jim Dandy, worked six furlongs
in 1:13 in his final tuneup for the Travers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-99 1949EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990821.0201 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5256 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-PALMDALE-AIRPORT-2ndT     08-21 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PALMDALE-AIRPORT-2ndTAKE-LADN </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALMDALE: called the report encouraging.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reality is catching up with them,'' she said. ``In the 30
years they've owned the land, they've never really examined what
they could do with it, before this.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles County Supervisor Michael D. Antonovich, whose
district includes the Antelope Valley, said the report underscores
the need to develop Palmdale as a regional airport. He said if the
city declines to do so, it should sell its property to county
agencies willing to push ahead.
</P>
<P>
   He also criticized the Hagler Bailly report for failing to
highlight problems anticipated with the LAX expansion.
</P>
<P>
   ``At LAX there is limited space, congested freeways, pollution.
This study indicates a regional approach toward Antelope Valley and
Ontario is needed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hagler Bailly consultants were hired after a two-day summit
of aviation experts last summer in Palmdale. The 69-page report
considers passenger projections, possible funding sources for the
airports, potential cargo and maintenance development, as well as a
review of existing environmental studies.
</P>
<P>
   It has been submitted to LAWA officials for their review and
final adoption.
</P>
<P>
   John Agoglia, president of the Board of Airport Commissioners,
said the report will be an integral part of LAWA's planning but
that it is not the ``Magna Carta.'' He said other studies will be
considered, too.
</P>
<P>
   Airports interim executive director Lydia Kennard estimated it
will be ``several months'' before a final recommendation is made on
Palmdale's future.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very, very positive about our commitment to the region,
but we need to review the study in a lot more steps before we
formalize our commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   She declined to discuss whether Palmdale will be included in the
LAX master plan, which already has cost the airport more than $30
million.
</P>
<P>
   Galanter said LAWA needs to press forward with an investment
strategy for Palmdale, as well as with a plan for enlisting the
airlines' cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope this turns into a real partnership,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The study strikes several cautionary notes, including the caveat
that it is not a precise marketing survey. Rather it is an effort
to estimate the ``optimum potential'' for the airport, which means
actual passenger demand may be less, the consultants said.
</P>
<P>
   It also rules out as impractical constructing an international
airport on the 17,700 acres of land the city of Los Angeles bought
with that in mind in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   The consultants said most international airports are within 20
miles of urban cores, with the exception being Washington Dulles
International. Dulles, which is about 25 miles from the central
business district, ``benefits from a policy decision to direct
international traffic away from Washington Reagan National to
Dulles.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmdale is about 55 miles from downtown L.A, but by 2020 at
least 1.5 million people will live closer to Palmdale Airport than
any other, the study says. Ledford said transportation improvements
to San Bernardino could boost that number to 2.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   The study estimates a maximum of up to 100 departures per day
from Palmdale.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles owns the terminal and jointly operates a landing
field with the U.S. Air Force. Ledford said there's an agreement
with the military barring expansion onto the city's property before
the airport reaches 400 flights per day.
</P>
<P>
   The report additionally underscores the airlines' longstanding
market concerns with Palmdale. Several carriers have offered
commuter service there without success.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Transport Association, which represents 23 national and
five non-U.S. airlines, has yet to take an official position on
Palmdale's revitalization as a regional airport, said Kris
Fitzgerald, director of government affairs in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to see the new report and to share it with our
colleagues and carriers. It will be nice to have something a little
more formal to review.'
</P>
<P>
   Southwest Airlines officials are among those who have examined
the Antelope Valley market and remain unconvinced it can support
aviation service in the short term, said Leslie Carr, the airlines'
manager of properties.
</P>
<P>
   ``The report is good news in that it suggests a future market in
Palmdale, but it probably doesn't have any immediate implications
for Southwest Airlines.''
</P>
<P>
   The consultants said that a subsidy might be required initially
to attract airport users.
</P>
<P>
   But the report concludes that despite the risks inherent in such
a venture, financing should be available to get the airport going.
</P>
<P>
   ``Palmdale is certainly not the first airport to face such a
start-up problem,'' it states. ``A variety of tried and true
sources of funding exist.''
</P>
<P>
   end!
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
