r a BC-PALMDALE-AIRPORT-2TAK     08-21 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PALMDALE-AIRPORT-2TAKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDY FINDS PALMDALE AIRPORT COULD EASE LAX CRUSH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY BETH BARRETT  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALMDALE -- Palmdale Airport _ ignored for decades by Los
Angeles officials and abandoned by airlines _ could serve millions
of passengers within a decade with planning, leadership and
investment, an L.A. World Airports report says.
</P>
<P>
   A copy of the confidential draft report obtained by the Daily
News outlines for the first time Palmdale's potential as a regional
hub serving fast-growing northern L.A. County and western San
Bernardino County.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioned by officials in charge of Los Angeles International
Airport who also oversee the Palmdale terminal and the vast acreage
around it, the study concludes that the facility could serve up to
4 million passengers annually within a decade and 7.3 million
passengers a year by 2020.
</P>
<P>
   There is no commercial airline service now operating at
Palmdale. Development of the airport has been raised as a key issue
by opponents of LAX expansion.
</P>
<P>
   The $231,000 report by Hagler Bailly Services Inc. of Arlington,
Va., assumed rapid population growth in the area, improved airport
highway access and a willingness by airlines to provide service.
</P>
<P>
   Palmdale would require about $240 million in terminal and
airfield improvements on top of hundreds of millions in
transportation corridor improvements if the traffic benchmarks are
to be reached, the study adds.
</P>
<P>
   Informed of the contents of the report, city officials in
Palmdale as well as a broad range of opponents of the proposed
massive expansion of LAX lauded the possibility of increased
airline service in north L.A. County, which would drain some demand
from LAX.
</P>
<P>
   ``We concur with this study 100 percent,'' said El Segundo's
Mayor Mike Gordon, who heads a coalition of 65 cities and
transportation agencies pushing for a regional solution.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have always felt that Palmdale's role was to serve as a
regional hub airport for the northern part of the county, which is
experiencing tremendous growth. This just bears out that Palmdale
could be developed in line with what Burbank Airport is today, if
you provide market incentives so that people won't drive past
Palmdale to get (cheaper) tickets at LAX.''
</P>
<P>
   The report concludes that Palmdale Airport could handle up to 7
percent of the region's passenger demand within a couple of
decades, under the best scenario.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be very significant in lessening the burden on
LAX,'' Gordon said.
</P>
<P>
   Hagler Bailly Services' consultants did not return calls for
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Palmdale Mayor James Ledford said the study ``absolutely
validates what we've been saying all along.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The beauty of the whole situation is that we have the best
land-use airport around in terms of well-defined noise corridors,
which should mean we won't repeat the situations that have been
encountered at Burbank, Van Nuys and even Ontario airports,''
Ledford said.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two years amid mounting political pressure, Palmdale
has moved from a blip on the region's aviation radar to a
legitimate player. In 1998, for instance, the Southern California
Association of Governments estimated no more than 200,000
passengers would be using Palmdale by 2020.
</P>
<P>
   SCAG executive director Mark Pisano said those numbers are now
being re-evaluated by the organization's aviation subcommittee and
that there now is consensus Palmdale ``could be larger.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It depends on how many steps the public and private sector
take to increase the capacity,'' he said. ``The airport could
increase several-fold beyond the 200,000 number.''
</P>
<P>
   Ledford added that Palmdale and LAWA have been cooperating and
are in final negotiations over a ``memorandum of understanding''
that would formally spell out some of the planned transportation
improvements near the airport.
</P>
<P>
   The consultants estimated that demand for the airport could be
boosted by as much as 10 percent if approximately $550 million is
spent on dedicated airport lanes along Highway 14 from Santa
Clarita and on improving Highway 138, the highway linking Palmdale
and Interstate 15 in San Bernardino.
</P>
<P>
   Ledford said Palmdale still hopes for formal consideration in
LAWA's master plan, which to date has focused on the proposal to
expand LAX from an airport serving about 60 million passengers a
year to one capable of handling 92 million. It is being backed by
Los Angeles Mayor Richard Riordan, the airlines and downtown
business interests.
</P>
<P>
   Ledford said increasingly both ``opponents and proponents'' of
the LAX expansion are joining to urge that Palmdale be developed as
the region's next major airport.
</P>
<P>
   City Councilwoman Ruth Galanter, who represents many of the
neighborhoods around LAX that fear further degradation of their
communities if the expansion is approved, called the report
encouraging.
</P>
<P>
   (CONTINUED ON NEXT TAKE)
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
