</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BASEBALL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINNING CARRIES MORE WEIGHT THAN LONG BALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It is hard to imagine Mark McGwire could hit more
than 60 home runs in back-to-back seasons, even harder to believe
he will not be named National League Most Valuable Player either
year.
</P>
<P>
   But winning drives award voting and that was never clearer than
last year when Sammy Sosa was named MVP more for leading the
Chicago Cubs into the playoffs than just his 66 homers.
</P>
<P>
   Sosa, like McGwire, will hit 60 again this year, but both are
playing for losing teams. The difference in 1999 was never clearer
than last weekend in St. Louis. After McGwire was retired in the
seventh inning of a close game fans raced to the exits.
</P>
<P>
   Can you imagine fans leaving in the seventh inning? It was
because the big boppers were done for the day, even if the game was
on the line.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways 1999 might be even more important to baseball than
last season's run at Roger Maris. There are two riveting division
races in the National League and an intriguing three-way struggle
for the wild-card spot in the American League.
</P>
<P>
   Now, you might like the wild card as much as the designated
hitter and interleague play. You might say there is no way to
capture the Sosa/McGwire magic in a series between the Toronto Blue
Jays and Oakland Athletics.
</P>
<P>
   But baseball likes what it sees. Some of the teams involved in
the wild-card chase are of the small-market variety, the have-nots
that were not supposed to have any chance against the Dodgers and
New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   True, the NL East race is between the filthy-rich Atlanta Braves
and New York Mets. But in the Central, Cincinnati and Houston have
tight budgets. In the AL, Oakland has no budget and fewer fans. But
with a new ballpark going up in San Francisco and the sale of the
A's expected this winter, Oakland's success could not have come at
a better time.
</P>
<P>
   With Montreal on the verge of leaving if it can't get a downtown
ballpark, Toronto's poor showing the past few years left Canada as
baseball's bush leagues. But young stars Shawn Green and Carlos
Delgado and reliever Billy Koch make this a team worth watching.
</P>
<P>
   There is no mega team this season. Not even the Yankees are the
Yankees from a year ago. Each has flaws, some more important than
others.
</P>
<P>
   _A 17-for-83 (.205) skid since July 24 has dropped the Reds'
Sean Casey's average from a league-leading .374 to a season-low
.341.
</P>
<P>
   _The Astros have been beating up on teams with losing records
but since June 14, they are 3-16 against Atlanta, Cincinnati and
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   _The A's wild-card chances took a big hit after fiery Tony
Phillips suffered a season-ending broken left leg. Oakland
responded by beating Pedro Martinez on Thursday to earn a split
with the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   As for MVP, remember Ted Williams hit .406 in 1941 and captured
the Triple Crown in 1947, but did not win either year. This season,
the winners should be Texas catcher Pudge Rodriguez and the Mets'
Robin Ventura. Both are having career years on the field and in the
clubhouse. The Rangers are considered the lightweights of the AL
elite, almost certain to lose in the first round to either
Cleveland or the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   But Rodriguez has done some remarkable things during one of the
hottest summers in Texas memory. He is the first catcher to record
20 homers and 20 stolen bases. He is throwing out a staggering 60
percent of baserunners. He has guided a weak starting staff and
helped nurture a strong bullpen that could give playoff teams fits
in the late innings of low-scoring games.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez could lose some votes to teammate Rafael Palmeiro.
Ventura could lose some to Houston's Jeff Bagwell because Mets
second baseman Edgardo Alfonso also is closing in on 100 RBI. Mike
Piazza, who is having a Mike Piazza year for the Mets, might
further split the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Sosa and McGwire, all of them play for winners.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
