<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5265 &Cx1f; tdy-z
r v TheArizonaRepublicplanst     08-21 0269
</HEADER>
<BODY>
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of
the NYTimes News Service for Sunday, Aug. 22. If you have any
questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602) 444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
POLLY-100 _ Like so many before her and after, Edwynne Prendergast
came to Arizona in 1929 to start over. Unlike most, Prendergast _
soon nicknamed ``Polly'' for that incurable optimist _ sta yed to
help write Arizona history. Prendergast, a former legislator known
to Arizona as Polly Rosenbaum, will celebrate her 100th birthday on
Sept. 4. By MAUREEN WEST. Story will move in the ` `A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
RESUME _ James Castellano seemed like the perfect man for the job.
When his resume landed at Mesa Airlines, the commuter carrier
stopped searching for a new payroll manager. Two months later h e
was fired, accused of embezzling more than $30,000 and approving
advances and extra time for co-workers to keep them quiet. Although
Castellano's case is extreme, it points up the persisten t problem
of resume fraud. By DAWN GILBERTSON. Story will move in the ``A''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
MONTINI-COLUMN _ (Phoenix) Sometime after she'd bashed herself on
the head, dug ugly scratches into her neck and upper thighs, and
used a pair of scissors to slice apart her shirt and bra, Kari Ray
Bodenski had to invent a rapist. She has a storyteller's gift, it
turns out, and made her attacker believable, frightful and _ in
ways she hadn't planned _ useful. Instead of condemning the poor
woman, we should praise her creativity and her insight. By EJ
MONTINI. Story will move in the ``A'' and ``K'' categories. &QL;
</P>
