<HEADER>
A5267 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-CARDS-NYT &LR;      08-21 0946
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-CARDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS BEAT CARDINALS, 7-4  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mist filled Shea Stadium Saturday, and every weekend
warrior in town felt a little bit of creakiness. But when a
starting pitcher like Kenny Rogers feels a twinge when he gets out
of bed, it is a more worrisome development.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers woke up Saturday, sneezed a few times and felt a pain
between his shoulder blades that insured that he would be
ineffective. But the Mets are in the pennant race because of a
balance of powerful offense, enigmatic starting pitching and nearly
flawless relief. Saturday, as they have all season, the Mets relied
on a sterling effort from the bullpen _ it has worked 242/3
consecutive scoreless innings _ plus well-timed hits and Mike
Piazza's 29th home run of the season to beat the Cardinals, 7-4.
The victory kept the Mets (75-48) in first place in the National
League East by two percentage points over the Braves, who beat the
Padres.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're fortunate we outlasted them and the rain,'' said Piazza,
whose three-run homer in the first inning was his sixth home run in
his last seven games.
</P>
<P>
   It was obvious almost immediately that the Mets would need a lot
of good fortune to prevail Saturday, or even to play. Until minutes
before game time, it seemed unlikely that the game would start, but
then the tarp was rolled off. During the early innings, when bulky
clouds hung low over the stadium, even the home plate umpire Bruce
Froemming expressed his doubts to Piazza about whether the game
could be completed.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers probably wished it had been postponed from the start. He
had hoped that warming up would relieve the pulling he felt in his
back. But the spasm limited his ability to finish his pitches. They
were high in the strike zone with little velocity. He fell behind
almost every hitter.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals' leadoff hitter, Edgar Renteria, blasted a double
to right-center field that Benny Agbayani approached hesitantly,
tiptoeing through a soaked warning track like a child splashing
through puddles. After J.D. Drew bunted Renteria to third and was
safe at first, Rogers narrowly escaped an encounter with Mark
McGwire. McGwire cracked an enormous shot that drifted just left of
the left-field foul pole, only to later look at a Rogers changeup
on the corner for strike three.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers then walked Ray Lankford to load the bases and Fernando
Tatis hit a shattered-bat blooper to shallow right that scored the
first two runs. A rout seemed imminent. But Craig Paquette hit a
grounder up the middle that Rey Ordonez grasped in a full face-down
stretch. Flopping once, he tossed the ball with his glove hand to
Edgardo Alfonzo to start a double play that allowed Rogers to
escape, down by 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some players have more errors than their whole infield has,''
St. Louis Manager Tony La Russa said.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza's three-run homer gave the Mets the lead in the bottom of
the first, but no amount of cushion would be enough for Rogers. He
struggled through the second and third innings, but Pat Mahomes,
who last pitched Aug. 11 against San Diego, was already warming up.
Rogers gave up singles to McGwire and Lankford to start the third
before Tatis doubled over Rickey Henderson to score McGwire.
Henderson, like Agbayani, was tentative near the puddly warning
track.
</P>
<P>
   With the game tied, Bobby Valentine visited the mound with the
trainer Fred Hina. Rogers had hoped to get through five innings,
especially because the Mets play a doubleheader on Sunday, and he
knew Valentine would want to save the bullpen. But Rogers gave up
another run to give the Cardinals a 4-3 lead and, when the inning
was done, so was he. He had allowed four runs on seven hits, but
Valentine said he was likely to make his next start, Wednesday
against Houston. ``I don't see this as being a lingering problem,''
Rogers said. ``I've had it before but it doesn't usually affect the
way I pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, after the Mets tied the score in the bottom of the
third when Piazza (2 for 2 with three runs) singled and later
scored, the bullpen was anxious to get to work. The starting
rotation got its first two complete games of the season during the
road trip to the West Coast, so the oft-used relievers were
unusually rested and restless. ``We're all down there pretty
antsy,'' said Turk Wendell, who allowed just one hit in one and a
third innings.
</P>
<P>
   Mahomes retired the side in the fourth, then struck out McGwire
(he was limited to one hit in four at-bats) to start the fifth.
``When he steps into the box, and everybody stands up, you feel a
rush,'' Mahomes said. ``You don't want to be the guy on
`SportsCenter.'''
</P>
<P>
   Mahomes got through the fifth and sixth, and after Henderson's
two-out single scored Agbayani to give the Mets a 5-4 lead, Mahomes
struck out Renteria to start the seventh. Mahomes walked Drew to
bring McGwire to bat again, and Valentine wasn't going to try his
luck with that matchup twice. Mahomes, who allowed no hits or runs
in three and a third innings, was replaced by the excitable
Wendell.
</P>
<P>
   Wendell's best pitch is his slider, but Piazza, who thinks
Wendell needs to mix up his pitches to be most effective, called
for his fastball. On a 1-2 count, Wendell zipped a pitch past
McGwire as flashbulbs blinked in the gloaming to capture McGwire's
third strikeout of the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm out there, I don't see or hear anything else,''
Wendell said. ``You're subconsciously conscious. When I was done
today, it was a blur. When you're not successful in those
situations, you bang your head on the wall for three days. When
you're successful, it blows by you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
