u i BC-QUAKE-BUILDERS-BOS &LR;      08-21 1089
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUAKE-BUILDERS-BOS </SLUG>
  
 TURKISH BUILDERS CRITICIZED AFTER QUAKE LOSSES
 &HT;    (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALIZA MARCUS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   ISTANBUL _ Turkish building contractors have gone into hiding to
avoid angry survivors of the earthquake that killed more than
12,000 people as engineering experts Saturday accused the
government of not protecting people against shoddy buildings.
</P>
<P>
   The government arrested three builders as Prime Minister Bulent
Ecevit pledged to go after contractors who built that substandard
housing _ among more than 115,000 buildings demolished or rendered
uninhabitable after Tuesday's quake.
</P>
<P>
   But engineering experts demanded that the government investigate
itself instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only the state can stop people from building without proper
plans, from using bad materials. They are the ones to blame and
there must be an investigation that starts with local authorities
and goes all the way to the top,'' said Cemal Gokce, director of
the Building Engineers Association in Istanbul.
</P>
<P>
   ``If all the buildings had been constructed the way they should,
then I think a huge portion would have stayed intact _ we created
this disaster and we must start learning how to live in an
earthquake zone,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The quake hit middle-class and working-class neighborhoods with
almost equal vengeance. Damage stretched through Turkey's
industrial heartland, from Istanbul's outskirts halfway to the
capital, Ankara, and down the coast of the Marmara Sea. Six people
were pulled alive from the rubble Saturday, but authorities fear as
many as 35,000 more missing people have perished.
</P>
<P>
   Rescue workers searching for survivors under the huge slabs of
concrete, stacks of bricks, and twisted metal poles that make up a
building said it did seem that poor construction was to blame for
at least some of the carnage.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you go down a street and the first two buildings are
relatively unscathed, the third has some damage and the fourth is a
pile of rubble _ you have to conclude that the difference is
because of how the fourth building was constructed,'' said Hugh
Parmer, assistant administrator of the US Agency for International
Development's bureau of humanitarian response, which has a rescue
team in Izmit.
</P>
<P>
   Survivors and others have complained that faulty material was
used for some buildings, that authorities did not take action
against clearly substandard housing and that shopowners on ground
floors sometimes cut through supporting walls to increase their
space.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all knew the building was made badly because it used to
shake when trucks drove by, but we did not think it would
collapse,'' said Ali Atalan, 24, whose mother died when their
apartment building in Izmit collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   Turks who saw their homes fall around them, watched their
children die under the wreckage, or heard the screams of friends
trapped beneath the rubble are in no mood to forgive those
responsible for substandard buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Contractor Veli Gocer was one of those builders who went into
hiding, fearful of retribution from angry survivors because it is
known he mixed cement for some buildings with salt water. Salt
water is not supposed to be used because over time the salt eats
into the cement, weakening it dangerously.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody told me to stop what I was doing,'' Gocer was quoted
Saturday as telling Turkish newspapers in telephone calls from his
hiding place. ``I wasn't warned and the state didn't say `hold on
brother, you can't use this' _ later I learned better and started
using different materials,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Police also detained three owners of construction companies in
the western city of Eskisehir on negligence charges.
</P>
<P>
   One building expert said Turkey's building codes related to
protecting against quakes were advanced but the problem was that
contractors ignored the rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't follow procedures because contractors are not
licensed, they don't have any liability insurance, and they don't
understand the complications of the earthquake codes,'' said Ahmet
Cakmak, a professor of civil engineering at Princeton University.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem is that many areas in the hard-hit Izmit
province were built on filled-in lakes or landfill covering the
edges of the Marmara Sea, making them much more susceptible to
earthquake tremors.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are not excellent city planning rules and they
(planners) don't look at the land based on which areas are most
resistant to earthquakes,'' said Cakmak.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, engineers and architects started combing the region,
trying to decide which damaged buildings were safe enough to allow
people to go back home.
</P>
<P>
   But engineering experts who have followed the construction boom
in western Turkish cities _ overflowing with migrants fleeing
poverty and the Kurdish guerrilla war in the eastern part of the
country _ warned that it was not enough to check buildings with
obvious damage.
</P>
<P>
   Quake experts have predicted that another big quake could hit
the same region or Istanbul itself within the next few decades,
raising fears that even buildings that look safe or survived this
disaster may not make it through another one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost every building built in the last 30 years has to be
gone over and checked because many were made without proper
planning or illegally,'' said Gokce, referring to buildings in
Istanbul and the region hit by the quake.
</P>
<P>
   The outcry over building practices comes on top of accusations
that Turkey was woefully unprepared for such a natural disaster
despite the fact that the area hit lies on a known fault line and
for years experts warned of a major earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   Turkish officials say they are doing their best, given the level
of damage, with more than 30,000 people believed buried under the
rubble, hospitals totally overwhelmed and communications, water and
electricity cut in the areas hit hardest.
</P>
<P>
   But people frantically trying to dig through concrete and brick
to get at buried relatives and friends complained that rescue teams
arrived too late to get to many people and they called on the
government to mobilize more groups for a last- minute dig.
</P>
<P>
   ``We managed to save a woman who was pregnant from one building
after I forced the driver of a excavating machine to come to the
place by threatening him with a knife,'' said a 25-year-old man in
the Golcuk who would give only his first name, Seyfi.
</P>
<P>
   ``No help was provided, we didn't see any official rescue
workers until Friday,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
