<HEADER>
A5271 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r p BC-BUSH-DRUGS-TEX     08-21 1137
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-DRUGS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOTERS SEEM TO HAVE HIGHER TOLERANCE FOR FAILINGS OF POLITICIANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RON HUTCHESON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When then-Sen. Al Gore confessed to past marijuana
use as a presidential candidate in 1987, reporters asked Republican
front-runner George Bush if he had ever tried the illegal weed.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' the vice president replied, ``but I'd hate to speak for
my kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the drug issue is roiling another presidential campaign, and
Bush's oldest son, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, is struggling with
questions about cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   But much has changed since Gore became the first presidential
candidate to admit using illegal drugs. Aging baby boomers and the
numbing effect of previous scandals seem to have raised voter
tolerance to new heights.
</P>
<P>
   In New Mexico, Republican Gov. Gary Johnson was elected despite
his admission that he tried both marijuana and cocaine in the
1970s. Minnesota Gov. Jesse Ventura of the Reform Party suffered no
discernible backlash after disclosing in a tell-all autobiography
that he has used marijuana, visited prostitutes and sometimes
forgoes underwear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can remember when Adlai Stevenson's divorce was a problem,''
said Gary Jacobson, a political science professor at the University
of California in San Diego. ``The tolerable kinds of social
behavior for politicians has expanded quite dramatically.''
</P>
<P>
   After rebuffing the question for weeks, Bush answered it
partially last week by saying he had not tried illegal drugs for
the past 25 years. He will not say what might have happened in his
younger years _ before he turned 28 _ and that has led some voters
to draw their own conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   Persistent digging by reporters and political opponents has
failed to produce any evidence of illegal drug use by Bush. The
media frenzy does not seem to have slowed his drive to the
Republican presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   In polls, focus groups and interviews, most voters shrug off the
controversy. If they're disgusted with anyone, they're disgusted
with the news media for refusing to drop the issue.
</P>
<P>
   But, as they did with President Clinton, voters show themselves
to be of two minds. With Clinton, a majority of Americans concluded
he was a poor role model but a good president. In a poll last week
by Fox News, a majority of respondents believed that Bush should
answer the question about drug use but more than two-thirds said
they ultimately didn't care if he had tried cocaine as a young man.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we're young, we all do things. All of us make mistakes,''
said Terry Sawyer, a Bush admirer who showed up to greet the
candidate at a recent campaign stop in Roanoke, Va. ``It's what he
can do for the country now, not what he did as a kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts and political observers cite several reasons for voter
indifference to the subject.
</P>
<P>
   Some theorize that personal flaws are more acceptable because
presidents are no longer viewed as larger-than-life figures.
Revelations of personal misconduct by President Clinton, former
President John Kennedy and other previous White House occupants
have underscored the reality of human frailties.
</P>
<P>
   But the single biggest factor may be the influence of baby
boomers, many of whom are squirming with drug questions from their
children.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest national survey of drug use, nearly a third of
adults over age 35 admitted using illegal drugs at some point in
their lives. Nearly 30 percent confessed to smoking marijuana;
about 10 percent said they had used cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We say we want higher values, but the baby boomers know what
it was like to do drugs back then,'' said Steve Roberts, former
chairman of the Iowa Republican Party. ``It's easy to just condemn,
but the fact is, we have met the enemy and it is us.''
</P>
<P>
   Some family education experts agree with Bush's argument that
spelling out past misconduct sends the wrong message to children.
</P>
<P>
   ``If parents used drugs when they were kids, they don't have to
bring it up, and they don't have to communicate that to their
kids,'' said Sylvia B. Rimm, a pediatrics professor and host of a
National Public Radio program on parenting. ``If kids bring it up,
I think they have to answer honestly. They don't have to give all
the details.''
</P>
<P>
   In making his milestone 1987 drug admission, Gore said he
discussed his experiences with his children shortly before meeting
with reporters. Gore, 51, said he started smoking marijuana with
his wife, Tipper, when they were in college. He said he also used
it when he was in the Army in Vietnam and on a couple of occasions
in the early 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   The question arose when Douglas Ginsburg withdrew his nomination
to the Supreme Court because of the furor surrounding his admission
that he had smoked marijuana with his law school students in
California.
</P>
<P>
   Other politicians who have acknowledged smoking marijuana
include Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt and former House Speaker
Newt Gingrich. Clinton became the butt of countless jokes by saying
that he smoked it, but did not inhale.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1980s, the generational split over drugs led to
friction between the Bush administration and the FBI over
background checks for government workers, according to former White
House counsel C. Boyden Gray. Bush's advisers favored a more
tolerant view because so many applicants had experimented with
drugs in their youths. The FBI backed a hard-line approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over time, I think they realized life had changed,'' Gray
said. ``They were all of a generation that were reaching their
retirement years. As more and more senior FBI members retired, more
and more younger people moved up, and they were more realistic
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say that anything goes. While some jurisdictions
have decriminalized marijuana, the use and sale of cocaine remains
a serious offense. The emergence of the highly addictive crack
derivative has also tarnished cocaine's image in some circles as a
hip, relatively harmless recreational outlet.
</P>
<P>
   Most experts agree that voter attitudes toward Bush could change
dramatically if his acknowledged youthful indiscretions turn out to
be something more serious.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic political consultant Jennifer Laszlo said she was
taken aback when a group of Iowa voters dismissed the cocaine
question as insignificant in a recent focus group.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were a lot more tolerant of cocaine use than I would
have suspected because I'm totally disgusted by cocaine use,
whether it's his or anybody else's,'' said Laszlo, 35. ``But they
had a lot of follow-up questions about how recently he did it and
how much he did it. How recently and how much really seems to
matter.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
