u a BC-MA-SCANDALS-BOS &LR;      08-21 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-SCANDALS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNOR PROMISES ETHICS PUSH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL CROWLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In his first public comments on the most scandalous
week of his term, Governor Paul Cellucci promised Saturday to crack
down on state officials who violate ethical standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to tolerate the misuse of public funds. We're
not going to tolerate the misuse of public office,'' he said.
``When we find that that has happened we will take action, and we
will take action swiftly.''
</P>
<P>
   Returning from a vacation in Florida, a stern-faced Cellucci
sought to downplay the controversies that ousted Massachusetts Port
Authority director Peter Blute, and endangered the job of Economic
Development director Carolyn Boviard.
</P>
<P>
   But he acknowledged that Blute's departure may cost him
politically, as he pushes ahead in his effort to build a new runway
at congested Logan airport. Blute had been leading the Logan
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Losing Peter Blute is not a good thing for our effort to get
this new runway,'' Cellucci said. ``He was doing a very good job on
that effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci returns to a more turbulent political scene than the
one he left a week ago, with investigations under way into
administration officials and his longtime friend Alexander
``Sandy'' Tennant, a veteran state GOP power broker, and headlines
filled with tales of partying and misbehavior in his
administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I obviously wasn't very happy to hear what happened here,''
Cellucci said.
</P>
<P>
   The governor also suggested that Tennant needs ``to turn his
life around.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor, however, defended Boviard, who is now being
questioned about whether she had a romantic relationship with her
top aide, David Shagoury. Shagoury resigned Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Saying he believes Boviard has done ``a very good job'' in her
post, Cellucci noted she is in the middle of a ``rather bitter''
divorce.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci would not comment on whether he believes Boviard had
the affair with Shagoury, as staffers have alleged, or whether she
would be fired if the allegations prove true. Boviard has denied
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are allegations and there are denials,'' Cellucci said.
``We're taking a look at whether there are any other problems
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci is awaiting a report from his chief legal counsel, Len
Lewin, on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Shagoury was forced to resign after allegedly threatening to
retaliate in job reviews against subordinates he believed were
gossiping about him and Boviard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there was a management problem at that agency that has
been taken care of,'' Cellucci said.
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci used harsher words to describe the Tuesday Massport
cruise captured in photographs in the Boston Herald. The newspaper
showed Blute aboard a cabin cruiser with Tennant and several young
women, including one who flashed her breasts for a Herald
photographer.
</P>
<P>
   The cruise was paid for with taxpayer dollars, although Blute
reimbursed Massport after the pictures were published.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the young woman aboard the boat who bared her chest,
Cellucci cautiously replied: ``I don't think that was a very good
thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Cellucci was unforgiving of Tennant, saying ``It's pretty clear
to me that he can't be helpful to me and he can't be helpful to the
Republican Party.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor added that he has not spoken to Tennant since the
cruise, and that he has no plans to do so. But asked whether he
still considers Tennant a close friend, Cellucci hesitantly
replied, ``Sure.''
</P>
<P>
   This spring, Tennant, formerly Cellucci's campaign chairman, was
charged with drunken driving after being found slumped over the
wheel of his car at 5 a.m. on a Brookline street. His trial is
scheduled for next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of us thought his drunk-driving charge would be a
wake-up call, but obviously it wasn't,'' Cellucci said of Tennant.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the turmoil back in Boston, Cellucci said he never
considered returning early from his vacation and he was able to
relax throughout the week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in pretty constant contact with the lieutenant governor
(Jane Swift) and I know she had things well under control,''
Cellucci said. ``So I was able to still enjoy my trip.''
</P>
<P>
   Blute's cruise Tuesday, and revelations of a similar trip last
summer, have prompted Massport to investigate all agency-funded
charter boat trips to determine whether public money was misused.
</P>
<P>
   In another development, the Coast Guard in Boston said the
captain of the Nauticus, the boat rented for Tuesday's trip, was
not certified to charter passengers. The captain, Steve Davis,
could face penalties of up to $5,000 for each day he violated
regulations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
