u a BC-ANTIQUES-SHOW-BOS &LR;      08-21 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-SHOW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S TREASURE OR TRASH ON `ANTIQUES ROADSHOW' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By YVONNE ABRAHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROVIDENCE _ Every one of the 6,500 ``Antiques Roadshow''
devotees who came to the Rhode Island Convention Center ON Saturday
knows this story:
</P>
<P>
   A nice elderly woman from New Jersey buys a little table at a
garage sale for $25, puts her telephone on it and thinks nothing of
it for years. Then the PBS show comes to town, and she wonders what
her find is really worth, so she takes it along.
</P>
<P>
   Appraiser Leigh Keno, who with his twin brother, Leslie, is now
undoubtedly the most famous American furniture expert in the
country, can barely breathe when he sees it.
</P>
<P>
   Keno tells her the mahogany card table, labeled by furniture
makers John and Thomas Seymour, is one of only seven or eight such
pieces known to exist.
</P>
<P>
   Then comes the moment every viewer waits for.
</P>
<P>
   How much is that little table worth? There is a pause, then the
familiar tinkling of bells as the price is flashed across the
bottom of the screen: $250,000.
</P>
<P>
   For a moment, she looks as if she might swoon. So does Keno.
</P>
<P>
   But wait, there's more. Several months later, the table goes to
auction on an especially good day and fetches $490,000.
</P>
<P>
   The nice woman from New Jersey and others like her are the
reason the ``Antiques Roadshow'' is the highest-rated prime-time
PBS program in the country.
</P>
<P>
   She is also the reason all those people showed up at Saturday,
hoping to strike it similarly rich with all manner of tchotchke
snagged at garage sales, inherited from ailing aunts, or dug out
from under piles of junk in the basement.
</P>
<P>
   The show, taping its fourth season, is based on a long-running
English program, and inspires a quasireligious devotion among
audiences and hopeful collectors. Impeccably dressed Chris Jussel,
the presenter, and the appraisers, like the Keno brothers, had
participants in awe Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Unhappy endings are also a part of the show's appeal: Many
viewers will sheepishly admit to drawing as much pleasure from low
valuations as high ones, as long-held family myths are debunked and
prized hand-me-downs are exposed as fakes. But participants
obviously hope for happier outcomes.
</P>
<P>
   They brought cigar store Indians and snakeskin bags, tattered
rugs and Aunt Jemima door-stops. They brought ancient-looking
swords and sad old dolls.
</P>
<P>
   And they waited. Many arrived as early as 5 a.m. Some _ as many
as a hundred, organizers said _ spent the night camping outside the
convention center. Once inside the building, a huge line snaked
around a dozen barriers, and most of the hopeful visitors waited
three hours before getting near the appraisers.
</P>
<P>
   Cheryl Wright, of Rhode Island, brought an elaborate jade, gold,
and ivory Chinese-style box that was intriguing enough to get her a
taped segment on the show. The vast majority of participants don't
make it to the cameras, but receiving free appraisals from experts
who have become as familiar as actors seems payoff enough for most
of them.
</P>
<P>
   Expert Lark E. Mason Jr. of Sotheby's, New York, had never seen
anything like the box. It was made by Edward Farber, a famous maker
of fine-quality desk articles. It was made of 18-carat gold, and
jade and ivory panels taken from a wealthy Chinese 16th century
tomb.
</P>
<P>
   Big find. As much as $125,000.
</P>
<P>
   But while most ``Antiques Roadshow'' hopefuls might jump and
yelp at such a valuation, Wright was not too surprised.
</P>
<P>
   She'd been given the box by a wealthy family friend when she was
10, she said, and he had taken out high insurance on it for her.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the value of the box, this was not the ideal
``Roadshow'' experience, and several members of the production
staff seemed disappointed: the show's allure, after all, depends on
suspense and surprise, the sense that the average viewer, too,
could have a fortune lying around the house and not know it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The show is accessible to everyone,'' said Anne Zeiser,
publicist for WGBH. ``Everybody has a family story, a relic from
the past, an attic or a basement. The show gives you all these
little vignettes, each building up to that moment when you find out
if they've got trash or treasure.''
</P>
<P>
   Rob Van Varick of Rochester, N.Y., hoped his Queen Anne mirror
would be worth a fortune. Van Varick, 20, who arrived at 7:30 a.m.,
knew the history of the mirror backwards, it having been in his
family for a long time. And he had a typewritten account of its
provenance, written in 1899, which said the mirror had once
belonged to 18th century American statesman Jonathan Trumbull, an
ancestor of his.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gotta work myself down. I can't get too excited. I can't get
my hopes up,'' Van Varick said.
</P>
<P>
   While he was waiting, he spotted the Keno brothers working
nearby.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're the best, the Keno brothers,'' he said. ``When they
get excited, they get all giddy, `Oh, I saw this one in line; I saw
you from afar.' ''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Van Varick's mirror, dated at about 1750, was
appraised at about $1,500, since the glass and gilding had been
replaced. But the provenance added another $500 to its value. Van
Varick was disappointed, but not broken. ``It was fun just being
here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And in the end, his mirror had been appraised by the Leslie
Keno.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
