<HEADER>
A5275 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-N.H.-COUNSELOR-SLAYIN     08-21 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-N.H.-COUNSELOR-SLAYING-BOS </SLUG>
  
 FEW CLEAR CLUES IN KILLING OF SOCIAL WORKER
 &HT;    (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLEMENT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   NASHUA, N.H. _ His friends said Daniel Ayer was a troubled man
as he waited for social worker Mark Rowland to make his first visit
to Ayer's home to counsel the family and their developmentally
delayed and hyperactive 5-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   And, police said, Ayer had a rifle.
</P>
<P>
   Ayer, 34, told friends that he was on medical disability from
his job with a Nashua construction firm, that he had been told the
utilities to his apartment would be shut off for nonpayment, and
that he had been served with an eviction notice.
</P>
<P>
   He said he and his wife, Joan, had been battling with state
social service agencies over the care of their only child, Daniel,
disputes that landed them in court where they were prodded to
participate in the Nashua Children's Program.
</P>
<P>
   But no one has yet said why Ayer got into a quarrel outside his
apartment building Friday with Rowland, 36, who worked for the
child care program, and allegedly shot the social worker in the
head.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland, according to the center's executive director, David
Villiotti, met the Ayers in court and his home visit was a critical
component of the program to keep the family together.
</P>
<P>
   Villiotti said that while there was a risk the child could be
removed from the home, ``That wouldn't have been the topic of the
conversation, because our goal was to keep them together.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to make sense out of it,'' Villiotti said of
Rowland's murder. ``We sure can't.''
</P>
<P>
   Authorities did not provide any clarifying information Saturday
as Ayer was arraigned in Nashua District Court on a count of
second-degree murder.
</P>
<P>
   Ayer appeared through a closed-circuit television hookup between
the courthouse and the police station. Ayer's wife, her sister and
brother-in-law, and a friend, Pat Lajoie, were in the courtroom.
Ayer was ordered held without bail pending his next court
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Rowland was shot in the middle of Hanover Street at
about 11 a.m. Friday. Ayer was arrested in neighboring Hudson a few
minutes later, and police said they found a .30-caliber rifle and
ammunition in his car.
</P>
<P>
   Lajoie, her boyfriend, James Trudelle, who is a neighbor of the
Ayers, and a coworker of the slain social worker said they did not
know why Ayer allegedly used a rifle he had inherited from his
father to shoot Rowland.
</P>
<P>
   ``He must have had a lot of anger in him that he did not show,''
said Trudelle. ``It must have boiled to the top and he just
snapped.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ayers constantly told friends that they could not get proper
care for their son, despite a legion of social workers visiting the
apartment where they had taken special precautions to protect him:
kitchen cabinets were locked; every window was locked shut because
Danny had once jumped out of one; and he was usually never left
alone.
</P>
<P>
   Trudelle said the defendant's parents and grandmother died
within the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   He said Ayer rarely drank, never to excess. He would almost
never lose his temper at work, and he kept a collection of guns in
a locker bolted to the floor and ceiling for safety, Trudelle said.
</P>
<P>
   Residents held a prayer service, led by neighbor Carl LeBlanc,
which was attended by Rowland's coworkers and members of the
Manchester Church of Christ, where Rowland was an active member.
Rowland's friends told Ayer's friends that they were praying for
the suspect and his family as strongly as they were for Rowland,
his widow, and their 2-year-old child.
</P>
<P>
   Joan Ayer told friends that welfare officials told her they
could help her financially _ but only if she divorced her husband.
Their 10th anniversary is Friday.
</P>
<P>
   As her husband sat in jail, Joan Ayer sat silently Friday night,
lost in her thoughts. Only occasionally would she speak, friends
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe he did that,'' she said repeatedly. ``I can't
believe he did that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
