<HEADER>
A5281 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-RUN-CHAMPIONSHIPS-NYT     08-21 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-CHAMPIONSHIPS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JONES CELEBRATES, BUT IT'S A VICTORY BY HER HUSBAND  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEVILLE, Spain _ Marion Jones shouted with joy, hugged her
husband and celebrated the first American gold medal of the world
track and field championships with a long line of television
cameras zeroing in on the moment.
</P>
<P>
   She then walked away and let her husband, C.J. Hunter, explain
his victory in the shot-put.
</P>
<P>
   There is no longer just one world champion in the Jones
household, and though Jones could end up with four gold medals when
the nine days of competition here are done, Hunter will be the
first one to hear ``The Star-Spangled Banner'' from the podium in
Seville when he is awarded his medal on Sunday, shortly before
Jones makes her bid to win the women's 100-meter dash.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not about bragging rights,'' Hunter said after his
unexpected success. ``It's a family thing. We'll take the bragging
rights over the other families, but not against each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter and Jones met when Hunter was coaching track and field at
the University of North Carolina and Jones was a star athlete
there. They were married last October, and they honeymooned in
Belize, the nation where Jones' mother was born, swimming with the
dolphins as they dived in the warm waters. Now, they have something
else to savor together this off season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tonight, we'll go back to the hotel; we'll shake hands, I'll
give her a kiss, and that will be it,'' Hunter said. ``We'll
celebrate in October.''
</P>
<P>
   There will also be a celebration in the Dragila residence in
Pocatello, Idaho, after Stacy Dragila became the first women's
world champion outdoors in the pole vault, tying the world record
of 15 feet 1 inch in the process.
</P>
<P>
   The woman whose record Dragila tied, Emma George of Australia,
has been one of the discipline's pioneers, but George, who could do
no better than a tie for 14th Saturday night, has not been as
successful a trailblazer as Dragila in major competitions. In 1997,
Dragila won the first women's indoor world championship in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   Now Dragila, a former heptathlete with dark sunglasses and a
sunny disposition, has done the same outdoors by outlasting a
technically smoother vaulter from Ukraine, Anzhela Balakhonova, the
reigning world champion, in a grueling, highly entertaining duel
that did not end until 11:15 on this warm Saturday evening.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to get over 15 feet coming into this, and I
didn't care how,'' Dragila said.
</P>
<P>
   Dragila already had cleared 15 feet in a competition on the
beach in Santa Barbara, Calif., in June, winning $100,000, but the
International Amateur Athletic Federation did not sanction that
event. She could have won $100,00 more tonight if she had jumped
just a half-inch higher, but after she and Balakhonova both cleared
14 feet 11 inches (4.55 meters), they were not permitted to set the
bar at the record-breaking height of 15-1{, or 4.61 meters.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to respect the progression of heights,'' said Dragila,
who tried and failed three times at 4.65 meters and then settled
happily for the $30,000 first prize.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the first time Hunter, an imposing 30-year-old, has
won a medal at a world championship. In 1997 he won the bronze in
Athens, and in 1995 he won the silver at the world indoor
championships.
</P>
<P>
   But despite his 6-1, 320-pound frame, Hunter has thrown in the
shadow of another strapping American, John Godina, who arrived as
the two-time defending world champion and with the best throw of
the year to his credit.
</P>
<P>
   But Godina looked ill at ease from the start Saturday night,
fouling on five of his six attempts. His one legal throw traveled
66-9\, good enough for seventh place and not nearly good enough to
compete with Hunter's final throw of 71-6, a personal best.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to say what went wrong; everything's spinning right
now,'' said Godina, who will have a chance to right himself in the
discus.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter did not used to spin at all when he put the shot, but he
converted from the glide style once he moved to Colorado after
graduating from Penn State in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday night, after he whirled around the ring in the Estadio
Olimpico and released the shot for the last time, he was grinning
broadly as soon as it left his hand. When it landed, he threw his
head back, thrust both hands skyward and did two bench presses in
the air and then began windmilling his massive arms, the chalk
shining white on his neck under the lights.
</P>
<P>
   After the silver medalist, Oliver-Sven Buder of Germany, and the
bronze medalist, Alexander Bagach, proved incapable of besting
Hunter's final throw, he was soon draping his arms around Jones'
neck. ``She told me she was proud of me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jones already had made Hunter proud of her Saturday morning by
qualifying for Monday's final in the long jump with a leap of 22-4\
and then recording the fastest 100-meter time for women in the
world this season _ 10.76 seconds _ to win her quarterfinal in the
evening.
</P>
<P>
   Not many people saw it _ the stadium was less than half full _
but those who bought tickets witnessed plenty of speed on the new
Mondo track. Before Jones ran, another American, Inger Miller, and
Ekaterini Thanou of Greece had set personal bests by winning their
heats in 10.86 seconds. ``I said, `Hey, why don't I join the
club?''' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   Though she did not manage to beat her personal best of 10.65
seconds or threaten the world record of 10.49, Jones did reassert
her dominance. ``Watch out for a world record,'' she said of Sunday
night's 100 semifinals and finals. ''I'm not saying from me. But
watch the men's sprinters. That track is fast, fast, fast.''
</P>
<P>
   The fastest man in history is the American Maurice Greene.
Saturday night in the quarterfinals he did not come close to his
world record of 9.79 seconds but still managed a very impressive
9.91. ``My coach told me to show them a little bit but don't show
them all of it,'' Greene said. ``I believe I did that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
