<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5290 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-DRUG-KAN &LR;      08-21 1161
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUG-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITNESSES IN CIVELLA CASE PREPARE FOR THEIR OWN TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK MORRIS  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Two men who
helped send the reputed head of the Kansas City mob to prison in a
pharmaceutical fraud scheme now face charges in a similar but
larger case.
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1991, Louie Ferro Jr. and Wilbur Swift served as federal
witnesses against Anthony ``Tony Ripe'' Civella and two other men
who were convicted of buying drugs worth about $1 million at huge
discounts for nursing homes and reselling them at higher prices to
wholesalers.
</P>
<P>
   Federal investigators have called Civella's conviction a
``serious blow'' to the leadership of organized crime in Kansas
City.
</P>
<P>
   Last month Ferro, his father, Louie Ferro Sr., Swift and Kevin
Staley were charged with operating a similar pharmaceutical
diversion scheme that brought them at least $8 million between 1995
and early 1999. All four have pleaded not guilty.
</P>
<P>
   No trial date has been set. As the case evolves, however, it
will spotlight the role that middlemen, such as Ferro and his
partners, play in the complex system that determines how much
Americans pay for prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The crux of the government's case is that the four defendants
defrauded drug manufacturers when they bought discounted
pharmaceuticals meant for nursing homes and then resold them to
wholesalers.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview, the four said they merely used a
legitimate discount offered by manufacturers to deliver cheaper
prescription drugs to wholesale customers.
</P>
<P>
   Ferro Jr. said the government should be more concerned about
allegations of price gouging by manufacturers than with prosecuting
him for helping to hold down the cost of health care.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the matter with discounts if the end user is getting
the same good product?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Whitley, a spokesman for the U.S. attorney's office in
Kansas City, says the safety of patients who depend on those
products is a serious issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Drugs can be stored, and often are stored, in improper
environments, such as excessive heat, cold or humidity,'' Whitley
said. ``It may be a matter of drugs being stored for so long that
they go out of date. Potency and efficacy are serious concerns.''
</P>
<P>
   Once prescription drugs are diverted, regulators cannot track
them, making the recall of defective drugs difficult or impossible,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Whitley said the indictment against the four made no allegation
that anyone became ill from the drugs they sold.
</P>
<P>
   Ferro Jr. said he and his partners met or exceeded industry
standards for handling, shipping and tracking the pharmaceuticals
they handled.
</P>
<P>
   Crossing paths
</P>
<P>
   Ferro Jr., a Kansas City pharmacist, and Swift, a California
drug wholesaler, first met in the coffee shop of a Las Vegas hotel
in the summer of 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Swift was looking for an institutional pharmacy _ a store that
distributes only to nursing homes _ to buy prescription drugs at a
substantial discount and then resell them to a wholesale firm he
co-owned, according to testimony from the Civella trial.
</P>
<P>
   Ferro Jr. appeared to be a prime candidate for the deal. He had
opened such a pharmacy in Kansas City the year before in a
partnership with Civella's son-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   At the Las Vegas meeting, which included other partners in the
Kansas City pharmacy venture, Swift pitched the idea of a
diversion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them that diversion was legally done, and that we would
buy certain merchandise from them, give them a profit, their cost
plus 25 percent,'' Swift testified.
</P>
<P>
   Ferro Jr. testified that he agreed to explore the legality of
the deal. He got his answer later in 1986 after he attended a
pharmacy convention in New Orleans. There, he said, he learned that
agreements with drug manufacturers prevented him from reselling the
drugs on the wholesale market.
</P>
<P>
   When he returned to Kansas City, Ferro Jr. testified, he raised
the issue with another partner in the pharmacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't believe it was kosher,'' Ferro Jr. testified.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of 1986, Ferro Jr. had a falling out with Civella's
son-in-law and later left the nursing-home pharmacy business.
</P>
<P>
   And two years after that, Swift found himself cut out of the
Kansas City diversion by a former business partner.
</P>
<P>
   Their lives then took different paths.
</P>
<P>
   In the summer of 1989, Swift was convicted of 24 counts of wire
fraud in Phoenix for a drug-diversion scheme.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few months after his testimony in the Civella case, Louie
Ferro Jr. decided to run for Congress. At the time, he brushed
aside questions about his testimony.
</P>
<P>
   ``That involved my old partners that I separated from,'' Ferro
Jr. had said. ``I have nothing to hide. Some people may raise
questions, but I don't think it will hurt my campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferro Jr. lost to incumbent Alan Wheat in the Aug. 4, 1992,
primary.
</P>
<P>
   After serving a prison term for fraud, Civella was released in
June 1996. The government has not alleged that Civella or either of
the other men convicted with him were involved in the most recent
pharmaceutical diversion case.
</P>
<P>
   Discount drugs
</P>
<P>
   After Civella's conviction, Ferro Jr. and Swift got into
business.
</P>
<P>
   From May 1995 through January 1999, Swift, the Ferros and Staley
signed agreements that allowed them to buy drugs at a discount as
long as they went to nursing homes only, according to the
indictment. The manufacturers included Bayer, Parke Davis and
Burroughs-Wellcome.
</P>
<P>
   In that time, the group spent at least $420,000 to realize
proceeds of at least $8.4 million from wholesalers in Ohio,
Florida, Kentucky, California, Nevada and Oregon, according to the
indictment.
</P>
<P>
   The Ferros, Swift and Staley said they were still sifting
through the indictment and their own financial records and were
uncertain what that $8.4 million figure represented.
</P>
<P>
   They also declined to discuss the core of the government's case
against them _ that is, that they broke agreements with
manufacturers by sending drugs meant for nursing homes to
wholesalers.
</P>
<P>
   Swift and Ferro Jr. said their testimony in the Civella case
should not be misconstrued. They said they never testified that
they were willing participants in an illegal scheme.
</P>
<P>
   Swift noted that he had been careful in 1991 not to say that any
diversion he had proposed was illegal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't (then), and it isn't (now),'' Swift said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their experience in the Civella case, they said they
could not understand how prosecutors could imagine that they had
committed criminal fraud through their discount pharmaceutical
operation.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is business, not crime, one defense lawyer argued.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our clients have not violated any law and are simply
good businessmen who have worked hard and established themselves in
a business where they've found a method of making money,'' said
Bruce Houdek, who is representing Swift. ``There's no dishonesty at
all.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
