<HEADLINE>
FIRST LADY PLANS NEW CAMPAIGN TACTICS  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hillary Rodham Clinton will inaugurate a new phase of
her exploratory campaign for the U.S. Senate after Labor Day,
breaking from her schedule of listening forums to add other events,
such as street walks and visits to centers for the elderly, the
first lady's associates said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Her associates said the expanded schedule did not mean that Mrs.
Clinton was abandoning her so-called listening forums, which have
been the mainstay of her New York visits this summer.
</P>
<P>
   But they said that her new schedule would include the kind of
less-controlled events that are more typical of full-fledged
campaigns but which have been notably absent from the first lady's
travels to date.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton's listening tours had, as a political device, been
intended to present her as a curious but constant visitor trying to
learn about a state where she has never lived, but one that she
would like to represent in the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The listening events had some degree of spontaneity _ the first
lady's staff did not control the audience _ but as political
events, they tended to be safe.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, Mrs. Clinton discussed an issue, such as health care
or child care, of particular concern to women voters, who are
likely to be key to this election.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady's friends described her Saturday as enjoying the
listening events and being satisfied with their political result.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
