<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: HOLDING A HOUSE HOSTAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., N.J., Conn.)  (js) 
 By JAY ROMANO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It may seem outrageous, but it is possible for someone you had
no contractual relationship with _ indeed, someone you have never
even met _ to file a lien on your property that would make it
impossible for you to sell your house, mortgage it or refinance an
existing mortgage on it.
</P>
<P>
   The document is called a mechanic's lien and it could set you
back thousands of dollars in legal fees to get the party filing the
document off your back.
</P>
<P>
   ``A mechanic's lien carries with it very substantial power,''
said Gerald Zisholtz, a real estate lawyer in Mineola, N.Y. ``It's
like a bank mortgage, and an unfriendly one at that.''
</P>
<P>
   Zisholtz explained that a mechanic's lien is an encumbrance
against a property that can be filed by just about anyone who has
provided services or materials at the property. And as long as the
lien is on the property, he said, the owner is essentially held
hostage by the person who filed it.
</P>
<P>
   What action to take is the immediate problem. The homeowner may
already have paid his general contractor, but have no way to know
whether the subcontractor who has filed the mechanic's lien was
paid by the general contractor. If the homeowner has a record of
having paid the general contractor in full, that will constitute an
absolute defense in a legal proceeding between the subcontractor
and the home owner.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, the homeowner is well-advised to consult a lawyer,
because one way or another, the homeowner must get the lien
removed. One option may be for the property owner to pay the
subcontractor the amount of the lien, and then deduct that amount
from future payments due the general contractor. Another
possibility, usable when the lien is filed by the general
contractor, would be for the property owner to post a bond for the
amount of the lien, and then resolve the issue of who owes whom
through litigation.
</P>
<P>
   One common way homeowners end up on the wrong end of a
mechanic's lien, he said, occurs when they enter into a contract
for a major home-improvement project. In most cases, Zisholtz said,
the general contractor will then ``sub out'' portions of the job _
plumbing and electrical work, for example _ to subcontractors. The
general contractor and subcontractors will then purchase supplies
and materials.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, Zisholtz said, the relationship between the
general contractor and the subcontractors and suppliers is not
obvious to the homeowner because the homeowner only deals with _
and is under contract to make payments to _ the general contractor.
It is the general contractor's responsibility, then, to make
payments to subcontractors and suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   On occasion, however, a general contractor will fail to make
those payments. And when that happens, Zisholtz said, the law gives
subcontractors and suppliers the right to file a mechanic's lien
against the property for the value of the services or supplies.
</P>
<P>
   But why should an owner be forced to pay a bill to a
subcontractor with whom he has no contractual relationship?
</P>
<P>
   ``Because the lien law charges the owner with a responsibility
to pay a subcontractor whose labor and materials are being used to
enhance the value of the owner's property,'' Zisholtz said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Under current law, he said, a contractor, subcontractor or
supplier has a limited amount of time in which to file a mechanic's
lien. For one-family houses, he said, the lien must be filed within
four months after the work was performed or material was delivered
to the job. For other properties the lien must be filed within
eight months.
</P>
<P>
   Zisholtz said a mechanic's lien automatically expires after one
year unless it is renewed. Moreover, he said, the person filing the
lien must notify the property owner within 30 days after filing and
must file proof of that notification within within 35 days after
filing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't dot your i's and cross your t's, the lien may
fail,'' Zisholtz said, adding that the best defense to a mechanic's
lien is having made payment in full to the general contractor or to
the person who has filed the lien.
</P>
<P>
   If the property owner does not have an adequate defense against
a properly filed valid lien, the law gives the person who filed the
lien the right to start a foreclosure action against the property.
</P>
<P>
   In New Jersey, the rules governing mechanic's liens are somewhat
different from those in New York. Richard M. Baron, a Hackensack
lawyer who helped draft New Jersey's lien law, said that while
contractors, subcontractors and suppliers can file liens for the
same general reasons that liens can be filed in New York, the
procedure for doing so is different.
</P>
<P>
   Baron said that mechanic's liens _ or construction liens, as
they are referred to in New Jersey _ can only be filed when there
is a written contract between a homeowner and a contractor. In New
York, he said, liens can be filed even when the agreement between a
contractor and a homeowner is oral.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he said, liens in New Jersey must be filed within 90
days of completion of the work or delivery of material to the
property. For residential properties, he said, the filing of the
lien must be preceded by the delivery of a special form to the
owner bearing the amount of the claim. The contractor must also ask
the homeowner to submit the matter to arbitration or to another
form of dispute resolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose of that is to get the homeowner and the claimant
together to see if they can sort out the dispute without ending up
with an encumbrance on the property,'' Baron said.
</P>
<P>
   If arbitration takes place, he said, the contractor can only
file a lien in accordance with the arbitrator's decision. If the
homeowner ignores the demand for arbitration, the contractor must
still petition the arbitrator for a decision allowing the
contractor to file the lien. In such cases, Baron said, the
arbitrator will generally permit a lien for the full amount
requested by the contractor.
</P>
<P>
   Another difference between New York and New Jersey, Baron said,
is that while New York liens can be renewed every year, New Jersey
construction liens automatically expire if the contractor has not
started a foreclosure action within one year of the filing of the
lien.
</P>
<P>
   In Connecticut, the laws on mechanic's liens are essentially a
blend of New York and New Jersey laws.
</P>
<P>
   William Selsberg, a Stamford real estate lawyer, said that as in
New Jersey, contractors in Connecticut must file their liens within
90 days of performing work or delivering supplies to the property.
Moreover, he said, such liens automatically expire one year after
filing. At the same time, however, there is no requirement in
Connecticut that there be a written contract for a contractor to
file a mechanic's lien, and no requirement that the contractor
first make a demand for payment or arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   Homeowners should make sure they do whatever is necessary to
protect themselves, Selsberg said. For example, he said, if a lien
has been filed by a subcontractor, a property owner should
discontinue payments to the general contractor until the
subcontractor's lien has been resolved. And if the time period for
the filing of the lien has expired, he said, the homeowner should
make sure he or she doesn't inadvertently reopen it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do not let a contractor back into the house if the period for
filing has expired,'' he said. ``Unscrupulous contractors will
always find some sham reason to go back and do additional work just
to start a new 90-day period running.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
