<SLUG> BC-FBC-CSUN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GILMORE PUTS ON GOOD SHOW IN NORTHRIDGE SCRIMMAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ He's a running back who transferred to Cal State
Northridge after three years at a DivisionI football program. He's
not that tall but he carries a wide load. And he's wearing No.6.
</P>
<P>
   DeJuan Gilmore, a senior who came to CSUN from Washington State,
isn't Melvin Blue, even though he's wearing Blue's number from
1998. He did put on a good display of speed and power in Saturday's
scrimmage at North Campus Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Gilmore broke off a 40-yard run on his first carry and also
muscled into the end zone from 1 yard later in the scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   ``When your first run is a long run,'' Gilmore said, ``that
gives you a lot of confidence for the rest of the day.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilmore, who is listed at 5-foot-8 and 204 pounds, had a strong
day despite not being in shape. He's carrying what looks like 15-20
extra pounds, and Gilmore has actually slimmed down from the start
of fall camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little chubby, but my legs are still strong,'' he said.
``I try to run hard all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Matadors are counting on Gilmore to complement fullback
Jaumal Bradley, a senior first-team All-Big Sky Conference
selection last year. That's a role Gilmore is happy to fill; he
isn't making any promises of a 3,000-yard season like the cocky
Blue did last year.
</P>
<P>
   Blue led an anemic CSUN rushing attack with only 476 yards.
Bradley, who rushed for 374 last season, reported to fall practice
leaner and faster than last year. After sitting out most of the
week with the flu, Bradley was on the field for 20 plays Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``All my blocks were crisp,'' Bradley said, adding he ran out of
gas on his last carry, which he fumbled. ``I didn't have anything
to finish the run, no pop.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Kearin, CSUN's interim head coach, was enthusiastic about
the combination of Gilmore and Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ran the ball really well,'' he said. ``DeJuan had a big
day. We have two physically superior running backs.''
</P>
<P>
   Wham, bam, boom: Wide receiver Terrence Jones, a senior transfer
from Fresno State, scored the first of the offense's four
touchdowns Saturday when he took a 10-yard pass from quarterback
Marcus Brady and sprinted 50 yards down the sideline, past a
shocked defense.
</P>
<P>
   But Jones (5-11, 180) made an impression with three crushing
downfield blocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got a big statement to make,'' Jones said. ``If I have to
block the whole game ... I'll do whatever the coach asks me to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   The flip side: Two negatives from the scrimmage: An injury to
redshirt freshman Isaac Gardner and several holding penalties.
</P>
<P>
   Gardner separated his shoulder while trying to tackle Gilmore
during the third possession. The seriousness of the injury isn't
known.
</P>
<P>
   Kearin wasn't pleased with the penalties.
</P>
<P>
   ``We held way too much, on both sides of the ball,'' Kearin
said. ``I was hoping the referees would be sticklers about it and
they were.''
</P>
<P>
   Taking a break: CSUN gets today off and resumes two-a-days
Monday morning. The coaching staff hopes to have a depth chart
completed by Monday, and the season opener is Sept. 4 at home
against Western Oregon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
