<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 22:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5456 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     08-21 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DO POETIC SOULS LURK BEHIND THESE MINDS?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It appears that as much as we've overrated Raul
Mondesi the ballplayer, we've underrated Mondesi the essayist.
</P>
<P>
   I refer to a curious footnote to the outfielder's recent obscene
diatribe against the Dodgers' manager and general manager _ the
four-sentence apology issued in his name the next day by the front
office.
</P>
<P>
   For an athlete, Mondesi displayed surprising polish in his
session at the typewriter, batting out a statement of uncommon
succinctness and grace.
</P>
<P>
   A minor grammatical lapse (he wrote ``importantly'' when
``important'' would have sufficed) was overshadowed by the easy
sophistication of the sentence that followed (``In what has been a
frustrating season, I let my emotions get the best of me'').
Mondesi, though little-schooled in the art of the English language,
showed a facility for Anglo-American idiom when he thanked fans who
``have stood behind me.''
</P>
<P>
   It must be concluded that Mondesi is a demon on deadline, seeing
that the statement had to be completed in time to be passed out to
Dodgers beat writers in Montreal in the hour or so between the end
of that afternoon's game and the team's departure for the airport.
</P>
<P>
   It is fair, of course, to speculate that he enjoyed the benefits
of a collaborator in the project. Maybe one of the Dodgers' college
products, Paul LoDuca or Trenidad Hubbard, helped with the actual
typing. Perhaps a member of the coaching staff, a Glenn Hoffman or
a Claude Osteen, performed the proofreading chores.
</P>
<P>
   Possibly someone other than Mondesi _ Devon White? Craig
Counsell? Jose Vizcaino? _ ghost-wrote a rough draft and Raul
imposed his style through aggressive editing later on.
</P>
<P>
   I hope the cynics are wrong when they suggest the apology was in
fact composed by Dodgers management and merely attributed to
Mondesi.
</P>
<P>
   It's my experience that putting words on paper often causes the
writer to learn more than the reader. The page is a mirror of the
mind. It forces the writer to confront the holes in his logic and
his soul. Mondesi needed the therapy.
</P>
<P>
   Many others in the world of sports could benefit from sitting
down at a typewriter, a word processor or a yellow legal pad and
writing a heartfelt apology. Based on the success of Mondesi's
literary debut, we can imagine the results if they did.
</P>
<P>
   Dear San Diego fans,
</P>
<P>
   If only a surgeon could stitch a broken spirit as surely as a
torn shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   I stand before you an aimless vessel of misspent passion, crying
out for a guiding light.
</P>
<P>
   After my latest misdemeanor, in which a harmless heckler was
forced to bear the verbal brunt of my self-induced frustration, I
would not blame this forgiving town if it cast aside all hope for
my redemption.
</P>
<P>
   I pray you do not abandon me, but instead accompany me on a
dusty journey to adulthood. Have faith that one sunny day you will
proudly say, ``I knew him when.'' &QL; 
A last thought: How fleeting is youth, how elusive maturity. &QL; 
Sincerely &QL; 
Ryan Leaf &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dear golf fans,
</P>
<P>
   Among our sport's endearing oddities: Many touring professionals
are multimillionaires, and individual earnings determine the season
standings, yet golfers are generally spared the ``greedy'' label
applied to other athletes. Ours is seen as a gentlemen's game
played for the love of it.
</P>
<P>
   We tarnished that cherished reputation by suggesting we should
be paid _ or our favorite charities should be paid _ when we
represent the United States in an international match. For this we
are profoundly sorry. &QL; 
With renewed patriotism, &QL; 
The U.S. Ryder Cup team &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dear Detroit fans,
</P>
<P>
   Once I clutched a football to my ribs, but now I tote the dead
weight of regret.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing my retirement last month, I was thinking only of
my own selfish desires. I realize now that the frustration of
playing for a losing franchise and the physical pain associated
with football are trivial compared to the aching knowledge one let
down one's teammates and public.
</P>
<P>
   I know now that putting off my decision until the eve of
training camp left the Lions without a running back or time to make
alternative plans. If the Lions lose again in '99, this time I am
to blame.
</P>
<P>
   Once I clutched a football to my ribs, only to fumble it on
immortality's goal line. &QL; 
Begging forgiveness, &QL; 
Barry Sanders &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To our physically challenged friends,
</P>
<P>
   It was an honor to get to know some of you during the
controversy that followed our indefensible misuse of the so-called
handicapped-parking placards. In many ways that count, you are
bigger, stronger, more complete people than we.
</P>
<P>
   Thank you for furthering our educations. &QL; 
Best wishes, &QL; 
The UCLA Eleven &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dear CSUN football fans,
</P>
<P>
   On the day I was fired as head football coach, I questioned the
competence and integrity of Cal State Northridge administrators.
This was unfair of me.
</P>
<P>
   I was unable then _ and am unable still _ to support my vague
accusations with facts. Until or unless I do, the administrators
deserve no disrespect and I deserve no leniency in the court of
public opinion.
</P>
<P>
   In what had been a frustrating time, I let my emotions get the
best of me. &QL; 
Yours truly, &QL; 
Ron Ponciano &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-99 2237EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990821.0225 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-21 22:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5457 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-GULF-HURRICANCE-HNS &LR;      08-21 1305
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GULF-HURRICANCE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
POWERFUL HURRICANE HEADS TOWARD TEXAS COAST
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
By JAMES PINKERTON &QL; 
and EDWARD HEGSTROM &QL;
</P>
<P>
   c. 1999 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH PADRE ISLAND _ Hurricane Bret churned north toward to the
Texas coast Saturday, packing winds of 135 miles per hour and
threatening to become one of the strongest storms ever to reach the
region.
</P>
<P>
   Though the tempest remained offshore about 165 miles southeast
of here, it continued to move north at about 14 miles per hour,
instead of drifting west as originally predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, residents of this low coastal island fled the storm's
wrath amid wind gusts and rain squalls.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of shrimp boats streamed past the granite jetties of the
Brazos Santiago Pass to escape roiling gulf waters, and the only
causeway off this resort island was backed up with residents towing
smaller boats, vacation trailers and their belongings from Bret's
path.
</P>
<P>
   Late Saturday, officials extended a hurricane watch all the way
to Freeport, south of Houston. A hurricane warning was in effect
from Port O'Connor to the Mexican border.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now it looks like Corpus Christi is going to be the
major threatened area,'' said Matt Moreland, a meteorologist with
the National Weather Service's Houston/Galveston office. But
Moreland added that it ``still looks unlikely'' that the storm
could reach as far north as Galveston and Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is now a very serious, dangerous storm,'' added Moreland.
If Bret were to strike land at its current strength, ``it would be
along the lines of Carla or Andrew.''
</P>
<P>
   Carla ravaged Texas in 1961, and Andrew hit Miami in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Alicia, the most recent storm to hit the greater Houston area,
was listed as a category 3 storm when it hit in 1983.
</P>
<P>
   There is still the possibility that Bret could diminish before
hitting land, but officials said they consider that unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, it looks like it will make land as a Category 4
storm,'' said Moreland.
</P>
<P>
   The National Hurricane Center warns that Bret also could soak
coastal areas with 8 to 10 inches of rain _ or even more, depending
on the speed and the motion of the hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   With its powerful winds, Bret was upgraded late Saturday to a
category 4 storm on a scale of 1 to 5. Only 17 category 4
hurricanes have touched land in the United States over the last
century, and virtually all of them did catastrophic damage.
</P>
<P>
   The strong possibility remains that the storm could still turn
west, striking this southern tip of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   And all along the Rio Grande Valley, from Brownsville to
Mission, residents prepared for the storm by emptying grocery
stores, lumber yards, and hardware stores of emergency supplies,
and stood in long lines at water kiosks to lay in supplies in case
power is lost. Others, afraid their low-lying homes would not stand
the expected flooding, fled inland in a hastily-organized
evacuation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It caught us with our pants down, is what it did,'' said Matt
Moreau, owner of Pico Ace Hardware on South Padre Island as he
ordered employees to cover cash registers with garbage bags before
closing. The owner of the only lumber yard on the island said he
was out of plywood by 10:30 Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Panic has set in and everybody cleaned me out of plywood,
flashlights and hurricane materials and now we're battening down
the hatches and I'm getting out,'' said Moreau. ``I still have five
hours of boarding up on my house in Port Isabel, so I'm getting
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Cameron County Judge Gilberto Hinojosa arranged for
residents in flood-prone areas to leave the county after Red Cross
officials decided not to open any emergency shelters in the county.
Instead, buses from local school districts transported evacuees
inland to shelters in neighboring Hidalgo County.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going a 100 miles a hour, I'm trying to get my people out
of the county because it's going to be bad,'' predicted the county
judge, who said National Weather Service officials told him to
expect a direct hit later on today.
</P>
<P>
   ``It poses a severe threat,'' the judge said. ``We're looking at
conceivably the worst natural disaster Cameron County has had since
hurricane Beulah and when that happened, I was a freshman in high
school at Mission High. It's been a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   And as Hurricane Bret strengthened Saturday afternoon and
evening, island officials told residents it was time to get out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're ordering everyone to leave, I'd rather just be safe than
sorry,'' said town mayor Ed Cyganiewicz.``I'm not sure what it's
going to do, but they're still predicting it will have a drastic
effect on the island.''
</P>
<P>
   The causeway linking the island would be closed by 8 a.m., and
water and electric power shut off, the major said.
</P>
<P>
   Late summer guests at island hotels cleared out early, adding to
an orderly exodus from South Padre Island that by noon had cars
backed up to the middle of the causeway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ninety percent of the people have left the island, and most of
the homes are boarded up. People are taking it very seriously, but
there is no sense of panic,'' Cyganiewicz said.
</P>
<P>
   In Valley cities not directly along the coast, including
Harlingen, a number of residents boarded up homes on the seaward
side of their lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, we've lived through several of them, hurricanes Beulah
and Eric, and we've done pretty good so far but we're not taking
any chances,'' said Victor V. Garcia, as he nailed plywood over the
windows of his woodframe home at 1401 E. Taylor. He added: ``We'll
be ready if it does hit us directly and hopefully this old house
will be able to sustain what the hurricane brings.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia and his wife, Arminda, had gassed up both cars, hauled in
extra drinking water and bought enough groceries to feed themselves
and the three grand children who live with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it hits, it's going to be a bad one because of the strength
it has,'' Arminda Garcia said. ``The kids are a little scared.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Valley natives expressed optimism Bret would mimic
Hurricane Allen, a deadly 1980 storm which roared across the
Caribbean Sea and into the Gulf on a collision course with the
Valley. But the storm stalled offshore of Brownsville, lost
considerable strength, and went inland farther north.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully we won't get it, but we have to be prepared. You
never know about hurricanes,'' commented Tadeo Cano, who was
waiting in a long line to purchase drinking water. ``They may stop
and go in another direction.
</P>
<P>
   South Padre Island officials, noting that most of the
construction is relatively new, did not anticipate ``mass
destruction of buildings.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll survive. We've planned for a long time and I think we're
ready,'' said mayor Cyganiewicz.
</P>
<P>
   The American Red Cross has already opened a shelter in Pharr,
near the Mexican border. The shelter has space for 4,000 people.
Three other shelters are also on standby, according to Margaret
O'Brien-Molina, head of communications for the Red Cross' Houston
office. Ten disaster specialists from the Houston office of the
American Red Cross took off for McAllen Saturday, prepared to help
with evacuations, shelter and other possible emergency needs.
Additional personnel and three food trucks are expected to head
south today.
</P>
<P>
   The trucks, each with a capability to provide a small meal to
2,000 people, have not yet received a specific destination.
</P>
<P>
   ``They will go where they are needed,'' said O'Brien-Molina.
</P>
<P>
   Unpredictable as hurricanes can be, O'Brien-Molina said the Red
Cross has begun planning for the remote possibility that the
hurricane might reach as far north as Galveston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was here for Alicia,'' she said, referring to the Hrricane
that hit in 1983. ``I don't even want to think about another.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-21-99 2253EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990821.0226 </DOCNO>
