<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-NL-CORRECTION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHILLING OUT FOR SEASON?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Fixing fifth graph, indicating Rockies GM Gebhard resigned
Friday) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Curt Schilling is eligible to come off the
disabled list Monday, but it is not out of the question he could be
finished for the season, especially after the Philadelphia Phillies
dropped nine of 12 to fall out of the wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   There are several theories why Schilling broke down when the
Phillies needed him most, but overwork tops the list. During the
past four seasons, Schilling, who had major shoulder surgery in
1995, has thrown 38 complete games, including five straight in May.
That is 14 more than anyone else in baseball. (Randy Johnson is
next with 24).
</P>
<P>
   During the past three years, he has thrown 10,722 pitches. No
other pitcher is within 500 pitches of that total.
</P>
<P>
   When he recorded back-to-back 300-strikeout seasons in 1997 and
1998, Schilling pitched 523 innings. No one else pitched 500.
</P>
<P>
   Out of a job: Published reports said Colorado Rockies GM Bob
Gebhard would be fired last Monday. He ended up resigning Friday.
The strange thing was the story first came out Monday in the Denver
Post when former Rockies manager Don Baylor was in town as batting
coach with Atlanta. Baylor was fired last fall after owner Jerry
McMorris had to decide between the manager and the GM. Gebhard
stayed, but was gone this week. ``He called the shots,'' Baylor
said. ``I've taken my fall.'' Baylor is expected to surface next
season in either Anaheim or Baltimore. And it comes at a time when
baseball is under fire for not hiring more minorities. Only two of
11 minority managers hired ever got a second chance. ``If that's
racist, I don't know,'' Baylor said. ``The hiring practices haven't
been very good lately.''
</P>
<P>
   Going out on top: Left-hander Brian Anderson, who Arizona was
ready to trade this spring, was 5-1, 5.02 in 15 starts while taking
Todd Stottlemyre's spot in the rotation. Tuesday, Anderson pitched
his second career shutout, a 4-0 three-hitter against the Cubs, in
what likely will be his last start of the season. He will be used
in long relief as the D'backs stay with 12 pitchers and will step
in if any trouble develops with Stottlemyre, who returned Friday.
``All I could do was pitch today,'' Anderson said after the
victory. ``Everybody knew this was my last start. I can do the
math. I just wanted to go out and give it my best effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Clutch: Javy Lopez's season-ending knee surgery has robbed
Atlanta's lineup of one of the club's best clutch hitters. Lopez's
absence has been felt most in the late innings with the game on the
line. The Braves' .262 average with runners in scoring position is
only 11th-best in the league. With men in scoring position and two
outs, their average is .234, ranking them 15th among 16 teams.
Lopez's average was .296 with runners in scoring position and an
astounding .333 with runners in scoring position and two outs. His
replacement, Eddie Perez, is hitting .184 with runners in scoring
position and .091 with runners in scoring position and two outs.
</P>
<P>
   Muscle man: A year ago at this time, Dale Sveum was warming up
the pitchers in the bullpen for the New York Yankees, having been
released by the team a few weeks earlier. Wednesday, the
35-year-old utility player batted cleanup and started at first base
for Pittsburgh. Sveum not only hit his first two homers of the
season, he became the second player in franchise history to homer
from each side of the plate in the same game. The only other
Pirates player to do it is Bobby Bonilla, who did it twice. Sveum,
who played for the Pirates in 1996-97, signed a minor-league
contract with the team in May. He was called up July 24 but entered
the game batting just .172.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
