<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARCH-DAVIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEENA DAVIS' BID FOR THE OLYMPICS FALLS SHORT  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLOOMFIELD, N.J. _ As an Oscar award-winning actress, Geena
Davis knew that someday her secret passion for archery would be
exposed. But in her first two years of competition, the news media
throng never came, and Davis began to treasure the thought that
maybe she would be allowed to compete as the rest of America's
archers do: in peace, in quiet and in anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   But that notion ended Saturday when news media members from more
than 50 outlets worldwide converged on a wet and dreary Brookdale
Park to watch Davis shoot arrows in the semifinals of the U.S.
Olympic Trials. Joining the dozens of local media members were
reporters from the British Broadcasting Company, the London Times,
RTL television in Germany and a newspaper in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   The 60 male and female archers, who, despite being the nation's
best in their field, are accustomed to performing before
single-digit crowds and had not experienced such a media frenzy.
And neither had Davis, who, despite her renown as an actress, was
not ready for such attention as an athlete.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was ill prepared for this onslaught,'' Davis said after
seven hours of competition. ``It was like being at a premiere,
which I'm used to. I mean, that doesn't make me nervous anymore.
But to do a sport with this kind of attention was kind of
unsettling. And also, one wants to do well at the Olympic Trials,
so there was a level of stress.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis, who won an Oscar for best supporting actress in the 1988
film ``The Accidental Tourist,'' laughed and smiled as she spoke.
Despite her anxiety about being in the spotlight, she admitted to
being pleased with her performance.
</P>
<P>
   Her 24th place finish in the field of 28 women was not enough to
get her into Sunday's second round, but it was nevertheless
exceptional for someone who, after becoming enthralled with the
sport while watching the 1996 Olympics, began shooting for the
first time in the spring of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's come farther in two years than most people would in five
or six years,'' said Janet Barrs, a fellow competitor from Salt
Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Scavotto, a 17-year-old soon-to-be senior at Enfield High
School in Connecticut, ended the day in first place with 1,287
points, 205 more than Davis. Jessica Carlson, 22, was second with
1,279 points, and Denise Parker was third with 1,255.
</P>
<P>
   The top three men's finishers were the two-time world champion
Vic Wunderle (1,335 points), the 1996 two-time gold medalist Justin
Huish (1,378) and the two-time Olympian Butch Johnson (1,312). The
top 16 finishers in each division will continue on in the
round-robin competition.
</P>
<P>
   While Davis views the serenity that surrounds most archery
events as a nice and welcomed respite from the raucous world of
Hollywood, her counterparts would rather have a little publicity.
So they appreciated the media coverage and also the roughly 50 fans
who showed up _ many because of Davis _ to watch in the pouring
rain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like when people come out to see me shoot,'' Scavotto said.
``I think it's great that the media is here. Archery doesn't get
much publicity and I think it's great that Geena is bringing more
popularity to the sport.''
</P>
<P>
   Dereck Chiu, Ketaki Chakracarti and Jennifer Lee, all recent
graduates of Bloomfield High School, were among the spectators who
took in their first archery event Saturday because of Davis. Huge
fans of Davis', particularly of her performance as a female
baseball player in ``A League of Their Own,'' they braved the
inclement weather to get a peek at her.
</P>
<P>
   Davis does not claim to be very athletic. She competed in only
track and field in high school, and said that it is easy to look
like a sportsman in Hollywood. But archery is as much a mental
challenge as it is a physical one, and it is the cerebral demands
of the sport that Davis finds most enjoyable.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's the challenge of trying to perfect something that
you're doing over and over again,'' said Davis, who like the rest
of the competitors shot 144 arrows Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Since becoming a student of her coach, Dan Rabska, more than two
years ago, Davis has trained six days a week, five hours a day. She
lifts weights, mainly focusing on the legs for stability when
aiming at the target, and jogs for stamina.
</P>
<P>
   For the mental aspects of the competition, she practices
visualization techniques for 20 to 30 minutes every day. In
addition to envisioning herself hitting the bull's eye, Davis also
tries to visualize ignoring any archers or reporters who may be in
the vicinity. Of course, she came up short Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very nervous,'' Davis said. ``It was incredibly
challenging and not something I could prepare for. I tried to
visualize what it would be like, but ...
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been wonderful that for two years, I've been able to
pursue this in my own little bubble. It's just been my private
thing that I've been doing and was able to work on in a fishbowl.
It's been really fun.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
