<HEADLINE>
BENNETT SHARPENS GAME, SPARKLES IN SCRIMMAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Junior quarterback Drew Bennett spent much of the
week throwing floaters, but he had his game arm Saturday in a
90-minute scrimmage at Spaulding Field dominated by the defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had more to think about than throwing spirals, and I think
that took my mind off it,'' said Bennett, who completed 4 of 5
passes for 50 yards and directed the only scoring drive. ``I
worried about throwing it hard, rather than how it looks.''
</P>
<P>
   Freshman quarterback Cory Paus completed 5 of 9 passes for 55
yards. Sophomore Scott McEwan was 2 of 6 for 45 yards, and freshman
Ryan McCann, who suffered a concussion, completed 2 of 4 passes for
9 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett and Paus are expected to survive this weekend's
quarterback cuts and spend two weeks competing for the starting
job.
</P>
<P>
   ``The scrimmage was part of the whole (eight) days,'' UCLA coach
Bob Toledo said. ``We've been evaluating them through training
camp, and this was another part of the evaluation process.''
</P>
<P>
   Making the cuts: Toledo and offensive coordinator Al Borges will
gather in the coaches' room this morning and spend the day
evaluating each quarterback's performance in 14 practices.
</P>
<P>
   They'll consider composure under pressure, frequency of scoring
drives, ability to read blitzes, playmaking and grasp of the
offense. But the most important factor will be completion
percentage, since UCLA's passing game is based on short- and
middle-distance throws.
</P>
<P>
   Borges has tracked every pass thrown against both the first- and
second-team defenses. He has a statistical analysis of each
quarterback in one-on-one drills (receiver-against-cornerback),
seven-on-seven situations (no linemen) and the scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everytime you involve more players in a drill, the evaluation
becomes more important,'' Borges said. ``Seven-on-seven tests
decision-making, and 11-on-11 is really important. It counts double
the others.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday, Toledo will meet with the quarterbacks and announce the
finalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'll be able to sleep tonight,'' Bennett said, ``and
not say I wish I had done better.''
</P>
<P>
   Scrimmage notes: The standout performers were tailback DeShaun
Foster, who scored the lone touchdown, receiver Brian Poli-Dixon
and three freshmen: cornerback Ricky Manning and linebackers Asi
Faoa and Marcus Reese.
</P>
<P>
   Receiver Danny Farmer (ankle) and safety Jason Stephens (knee)
suffered mild sprains and may miss a few days. Otherwise, the
Bruins survived the first week of training camp with no significant
injuries to their top players.
</P>
<P>
   Gaining ground: Sophomore Devon Reese, a walk-on from Palmdale,
is contending for the fifth spot in the receiver rotation behind
Poli-Dixon, Farmer, Brad Melsby and Freddie Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reese blocks well, he catches well, and he's on a lot of
special teams,'' Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   It's a subtle but significant development. Toledo wants to
redshirt Jon Dubravac, who played sparingly last year, but he can't
do it unless someone emerges as a reliable No. 5 receiver. Reese's
competition is Ryan Wilkins and Saugus' Cody Joyce, who is out with
an infected foot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
