<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTROYAL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROYALS LOSE AGAIN TO DEVIL RAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DICK KAEGEL  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ Sometimes Royals manager Tony Muser's
post-game ruminations seem like replays. And he knows it only too
well. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There he was after Saturday night's 8-2 loss to the Tampa Bay
Devil Rays repeating himself again. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We've said it before,'' Muser said. ``Walks are the worst
enemy for a baseball team. Errors and walks are giveaways that get
you in trouble.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His starting pitcher, Jay Witasick, was the god of giveaways as
35,769 fans gathered at Tropicana Field. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the first inning, Witasick made an error that helped the
Devil Rays score three unearned runs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the second inning, he walked two batters with two outs and
then gave up a three-run homer to Fred McGriff. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The score was 6-0, and Witasick was done. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a quick night,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It sure was. The game was over, but the last seven innings were
played anyway, out of deference to Abner Doubleday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the Royals were still numb after losing Friday night on
three walks and a hit batter by reliever Scott Service. Losing
without the other team putting the ball in play can do that. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It affects you emotionally, but it's something we've had a lot
of practice at. Let's put it that way,'' Muser said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been able to overcome some pretty tough losses.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not on this night, during which a Florida thunderstorm shook the
dome. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Royals' hitting continued its free fall. Run production is
down to a relative dribble in this high-scoring season. They've
scored more than five runs just twice in the last 14 games. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Devil Rays right-hander Dave Eiland rocked them to sleep for
five innings before successive hits by Rey Sanchez, Mike Sweeney
and Jermaine Dye and a ground-out gave them their only two runs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Witasick immediately got into trouble, although the Devil Rays
didn't get the ball out of the infield when they loaded the bases
in the first. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two singles were stopped by shortstop Sanchez, and then
McGriff's one-out tap toward the mound was missed by Witasick. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It took two small bounces, and I was waiting for the third,
and it just stuck to the turf,'' Witasick said. ``It just went
right under my glove.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Joe Randa snared John Flaherty's grounder and got
a force-out at the plate. But Paul Sorrento got a two-run single on
a grounder that took a nasty hop past second baseman Jed Hansen. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I almost got it in my teeth,'' Hansen said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jose Guillen followed with an RBI single for a 3-0 lead. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Witasick had two outs in the second when he walked Dave Martinez
and Jose Canseco. With an 0-2 count on McGriff, he threw a
curveball. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It was off-speed and something that fluttered high in the
strike zone,'' Muser said. ``Maybe a ball but very whackable. And
McGriff whacked it.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two little-used bullpen residents finished the game. Chris
Fussell gave up one run in four innings, and Mac Suzuki allowed one
run in two innings. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Royals beat up on the expansion Devil Rays last season,
winning eight of 11 games. But they are only 2-7 against them this
year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Witasick is 0-2 in three starts against Tampa Bay with a 10.48
ERA. And this time he lasted just two innings. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're missing the strike zone in and out and up and
down, you're not going to last long,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
