<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-PIRATES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON BEATS PIRATES, 4-2 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ His fastball hisses like the snake on his cap. His
slider breaks across the plate at the last second and can cause
hitters' knees to quiver and go out of joint.
</P>
<P>
   On an ``off'' day, well, Diamondbacks left-hander Randy Johnson
still is better than most pitchers in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson admitted he was not at the top of his gameSaturday
night, yet still managed to keep the Pittsburgh Pirates under
control as Arizona recorded a 4-2 victory at Three Rivers Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   He pitched his 10th complete game of the season, scattering six
hits, walking one and striking out eight and raised his record to
13-8. Pirates first baseman Kevin Young hit two solo homers off
him, but he came back to strike Young out the next two times.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona (71-52) maintained its 7{-game lead over San Francisco
in the National League West Division. The Giants won their second
straight over the Brewers in Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Randy did what good pitchers do when they don'thave their
overpowering stuff _ he PITCHED,'' said Diamondbackspitching coach
Mark Connor. ``He's given up two runs or less in hislast 12 starts
D that's incredible. I've never had anybody likehim.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Johnson: ``I didn't have some of my beststuff, but I feel
like I put in a good day's work. I got some quick outs _ they would
swing at the first couple of pitches _ and that helped. I didn't go
deep in the count too many times. I got some ground balls, andgot
good defense behind me.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the second efficient start in a row for Johnson. He threw
107 pitches in eight innings when he beatthe Chicago Cubs on Monday
night and followed that up with 113 Saturdaynight.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fewer pitches I throw now, the more fresh I'll be later in
the season,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And the closer he getsto a complete game, the better for the
bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``As theseason wore on, the bullpen has gotten stronger, and a
big reason for thatis because guys like Randy take their games
deeper (longer),'' said Diamondbacks Manager Buck Showalter.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson did not strike out abatter until the third inning _ his
mound opponent, left-hander Jimmy Anderson _ but got the Big K when
he needed it. He needs eight to reachthe 300 mark for the season
and should get that in his next start on Thursday against the
Florida Marlins in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Entering Saturday's game, he had fanned 10 batters or more in a
game six straight times and 19 this season.
</P>
<P>
   He struck out Young for the final out of the sixth, got
pinch-hitter Dale Sveum (a Diamondback during the spring who played
briefly for Triple-A Tucson) to begin the eighth and got Young and
former Arizona State shortstop Mike Benjamin in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't have his good stuff, but he knew it. He's
abattler,'' said catcher Damian Miller. ``He was flying open a
fewtimes on his delivery, so I reminded him of that, and that he
was losinghis concentration a couple of times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Complete games aresort of important to him, but strikeouts . .
. I don't think he reallycares. If he strikes out 15 and loses,
he's probably a bitter humanbeing, but if he strikes out six or
seven and wins . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd much rather throw 114 pitches and strikeout five or six
and win than throw 145 pitches and strike out 10 andlose,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Miller said that most of the game, Johnson was inthe 94-95 mph
range, ``but when it counted, like in the ninth, he wascloser to 97
and that nasty slider was there.''
</P>
<P>
   TheDiamondbacks scored once in each of the first three innings.
Luis Gonzalezdrove in Tony Womack with a single in the first, Jay
Bell drove in Steve Finley with an infield hit in the second, and
Matt Williams scored in the third when Pirates second baseman
Abraham Nunez let a sharp grounder by Finley go through his legs
for an error.
</P>
<P>
   Young, meanwhile, kept Pittsburgh (61-62) close with his 18th
and 19th homers.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks tacked on a big insurance run in the seventh
when Greg Colbrunn drew a two-out walk and scored on a double by
Bernard Gilkey. Pirates left fielder John Wehner moved to his left
toward the gap in left-center and appeared to hesitate on to
whether to dive for the ball or let it bounce. He did both and the
ball got by him. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
